<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECTION (Tehran, Iran) _ The confident mood of the
reformers who seem headed for victory in Iran's parliamentary
elections was on full show Sunday at the home of perhaps the most
outspoken clerical advocate of change and democracy, Abdullah
Nouri. Early tallies and various prognoses indicated that reformers
and moderates who could be expected to back President Mohammad
Khatami will have a significant, probably even dominant, place in
the new 290-seat parliament. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   MILOSEVIC-CRACKDOWN (Prague, Czech Republic) _ The government of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic _ its support sliding in an
election year _ has sharply intensified attacks on Serbia's
democratic opposition and the media, calling them traitors and
using a draconian press law to intimidate and impoverish
independent publications. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-IMF (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ A new Brazilian government
plan to spend more than $22 billion on social programs in the next
decade has led to a squabble with the International Monetary Fund,
which argues the money should be used to reduce Brazil's
indebtedness rather than to fight poverty. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LAUNDERING (Jerusalem) _ Almost uniquely among developed
democracies, Israel has not made money laundering a crime, though
it is now taking steps in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-TRAIL (Bangkok, Thailand) _ The government of Vietnam
has announced that it plans to turn the faint remnants of the Ho
Chi Minh Trail into a highway, linking the north and the south for
peaceful commerce as it once did for wartime supply and transport.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FATIGUE (Saku, Japan) _ When the Japanese government
announced this week that one-third of the working age population
was suffering from chronic fatigue, few stress-haunted denizens of
Tokyo could have been taken aback. What is far more surprising is
that quiet little towns like these are being hit every bit as hard
by a poorly understood condition that leaves many of its victims
incapacitated for months or years on end. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLA-HOMESTEAD-REBUILD (Homestead, Fla.) _ Homestead has still
not reclaimed its old self. Andrew chased out much of the white
middle class, obliterated an Air Force base that poured more than
$400 million a year into the area's economy and reduced houses,
trailer parks and 3,000 acres of lime groves to a horizon of
sticks. Still, in the rubble of Hurricane Andrew, an entirely
different Homestead has begun to bloom, a transformed community
that says much about the changes that are sweeping small towns
across this state and much of the South. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN-GENERAL (Fort Hood, Texas) _ Soldiers on this sprawling
post in central Texas snap to salute when Maj. Gen. Rick J. Hillier
strides by. He is, after all, deputy commander of the Army's 3rd
Corps and its 57,000 troops. But there is something unusual about
this lanky officer that gives soldiers pause. First there is his
clipped accent, which sounds even stranger down here in Texas. And
then there is his uniform, his forest-green beret and the two maple
leaves he wears instead of a general's stars. Hillier, second in
charge of one of the Army's four corps, a senior officer overseeing
the operations of three Army divisions, is a Canadian. By Steven
Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICH-VOTERS (Roseville, Mich.) _ With time, money, political
momentum and the Republican machine working against him, John M.
McCain is trying to corral an unlikely coalition of moderate
suburban Republicans and poor urban Democrats, along with feisty
blue-collar independents. But showing the confidence of a
frontrunner whose believes his core of support is secure, George W.
Bush signaled that he would compete for some of the same voters. By
James Bennett
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BACKGROUND (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ When Sen. John McCain of
Arizona describes the people who shaped his life, he invariably
dwells on the influence of his father and grandfather, both
distinguished Navy admirals and larger-than-life figures. Less
widely known are the roles played by two other powerful men in
launching the Republican presidential aspirant's political career.
By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT10,11,12,25) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SC-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT (Charleston, S.C.) _ Talking to conservative
Christians who helped swing the South Carolina primary to George W.
Bush. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT28) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS-ASSESS (Charleston, S.C.) _ A closer look at what was
on South Carolina voters' minds. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS-ADS (Undated) _ How the negativity of the ads by both
candidates influenced the election. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-FINANCES (Washington) _ A look at the financial status of
the McCain and Bush campaigns. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WATTS-PROFILE _ Rep. J.C. Watts is the only black Republican in
Congress. He is also the communicator-in-chief for his party in the
House, and a rising national conservative star. But three weeks
ago, Watts nearly called it quits, frustrated with his job and its
strains on his family back in Oklahoma. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OILPRICES (Washington) _ For the past year, even as the price of
oil tripled to $30 a barrel from a record low of $10, policy
makers, economists and many in the oil industry itself hewed
closely to the same line: Oil doesn't matter much anymore.
Technology, which depends much less on energy than manufacturing
does, now drives economic growth. Such thinking was, and to a
certain extent remains, conventional wisdom. But it has taken only
a few weeks of $2 a gallon home heating oil, $20 airline ticket
surcharges, and $75 to gas up Ford Expeditions to make people
wonder if oil is really so irrelevant. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TALKS (Undated) _ As the court proceedings in the
Microsoft trial are scheduled to resume on Tuesday, a look at where
things stand in the settlement talks that Judge Richard Posner has
been holding with both sides in Chicago. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: The
construction industry is the latest business in which many
e-commerce companies are eager to lay a foundation. By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT1,20) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TALENT-AGENTS-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ A new agreement with the
Screen Actors Guild would give talent agents greatly expanded power
in Hollywood. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT9) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REPORTER-MEDIA (Columbia, S.C.) _ On the road with a
television reporter who works for many masters _ NBC, MSNBC, and
MSNBC.com. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORK-TRAFFIC (Undated) _ The Industry View column: As
Internet traffic becomes as crucial to everyday commerce as the
working world's daily road and rail commute, when will network
traffic reports become a drive-time news staple alongside highway
traffic and weather reports? By Susan Stellin.
</P>
<P>
   EAZEL-LINUX (San Francisco) _ Three former Apple Computer
employees who were part of the original Macintosh development team
have set up a new company, Eazel, which intends to create a
Mac-like interface for using the Linux software operating system.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BIZ-MEDIA (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Thanks in part to a
boom in German high-technology stocks and a revolution in attitudes
toward investing, Germany has become a battleground for new
business publications. On Monday the Pearson Group, producer of
Britain's Financial Times, will start a German version of its
salmon-colored business daily with the Hamburg magazine publisher
Gruner &AMP; Jahr, which is owned by Bertelsmann. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-PAPERS-MEDIA (Toronto) _ What's behind the Thompson
newspaper sale. By Timothy Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MAGS-MEDIA (Undated) _ The Advocate buys Out magazine. By
Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ The Fox broadcasting network created an
unexpected television phenomenon last week by marrying off a man
who said he was a multimillionaire to one of 50 female contestants
vying to be his wife. But even as Fox executives basked in the
publicity from the ratings-rich ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'', they were faced with questions _ and not just
about the propriety of having a woman agree to marry a man she had
seen for about a minute. They had to explain how the groom _ a
comedian named Rick Rockwell with a penchant for stunts (he once
told jokes for 30 straight hours in an attempt to make the Guinness
record book) _ could be taken seriously as a wealthy man in need of
a wif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-LAWSUIT (Undated) _ In the art world Herbert Black is
known as a man who loves art and antiques, and loathes the auction
houses where he buys and sells them. Suddenly he has a lot of
company. Black, a copper trader from Montreal, is suing the two
major art auction houses, Sotheby's and Christie's. He and other
disgruntled customers contend that they were overcharged because of
collusion by the two rival auction houses, and they are basing
their suits in a criminal antitrust investigation being conducted
by the Justice Department. The fallout is likely to be not just
embarrassing but also expensive for Sotheby's and Christie's, which
could end up paying their irate clients tens of millions of
dollars. By Leslie Eaton and Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER (London) _ London's historic Royal Court Theater
opens after a lengthy renovation. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT18,19) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-COMMISSIONS (Undated) _ Taken aback by the disclosure
that some museums, like dealers, request a commission when art they
are exhibiting is sold, museums around the country scrambled last
week to plead innocence, profess ignorance, or say that they had
stopped doing it. Only one of some two dozen museums surveyed _ the
Walker Art Center in Minneapolis, which is widely known for
exhibiting the work of new artists _ admitted to the practice. By
Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   THINKERS-CONVENE (New York) _ Innovative thinkers convene at the
Hammerstein Ballroom. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VANGUARD-JAZZ (New York) _ The Village Vanguard marks 65 years
as a temple of jazz. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
