   `Anytime you lose one, you need to win one, and I think we need
to win one now,'' said state Sen. Joe Schwarz, R-Battle Creek, one
of McCain's state chairmen. ``I expect the stops to be pulled out
here on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recent polls show that Michigan is up for grabs. A
``Detroit Free Press'' survey conducted just before the South
Carolina primary had McCain clinging to a two-point lead over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush arrived here from the Palmetto State riding a wave of
momentum, and benefits from the presence of a large paid staff and
healthy advertising campaign. McCain has mostly had to rely on free
media and an army of 2,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to carry Michigan,'' Bush told reporters before
ducking into services at the Central Wesleyan Church in Holland,
Mich. ``I feel confident of that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush has anything to overcome, it could be the trail of
personal ties he left behind in South Carolina, where he was
criticized for visiting the Bob Jones University, a school that has
a reputation for its anti-Catholic bias and race-based policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Rep. Peter King, a New York Republican, defected from
Bush's campaign and threw his support to McCain, in part because of
Bush's decision to deliver a speech at the South Carolina
university.
</P>
<P>
   Bush grew testy in response to questions about the reasons for
King's defection, noting to reporters at one point, ``My little
brother Jeb is Catholic.'' &UR; Roman
 &UR; Catholics are the largest denomination in
 &UR; Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   With McCain expected to win his home state of Arizona, most eyes
are on Michigan and its rich payoff of 57 delegates. If McCain
loses again, even his supporters concede it will be difficult to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt it's critical, but I think he's going to
win,'' Schwarz said. ``Demographically, this is a good state for
McCain. It's the first state that's a real slice of life. It's the
first state that has a lot of caucasian ethnics and it's the home
of the Reagan Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Reagan Democrats have been the target of an advertisement
paid for by Jeffrey Fieger, the lawyer for assisted suicide
advocate Dr. Jack Kevorkian. Fieger also was the 1998 Democratic
candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Fieger urges Democrats to come out and vote against
Michigan Gov. John Engler, a Bush supporter, and Bush himself,
calling them ``dumb and dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has disavowed the ad, but Bush nevertheless
sought to use it as evidence that Democrats are trying to
infiltrate the GOP election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing I can do about that except this,'' Bush told
about 300 supporters at Detroit's Lawrence Technical School. ``We
can rally our friends and neighbors. We can rally our kinds of
folks to go to the polls to say to Kevorkian's lawyer, `You're not
going to get to pick who the nominee of the Republican Party
is'.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
