<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLETT FINALLY WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And you thought Gilligan would never get off his
island.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett, as famous for his crumpled hat as for his 11-year
PGA Tour winless streak, broke through on try No. 266 Sunday,
finishing with a 4-under-par 67 for a 12-under total of 272 and a
one-stroke victory over Jesper Parnevik in the Nissan Ope n at
Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' said Triplett, who fought off
rain, playing partner Parnevik and the glare from Parnevik's pink
pants to outlast the tour's tightest-bunched final-round field in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the event's remaining 71 players were within
reach of third-round leader David Sutherland at the start of
Sunday's play. Seven of them held or shared the lead - including s
3-4 finishers Robin Freeman (68-274) and Russ Cochran (69-275)
before Triplett took charge with birdies midway through his round.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Armour III, Bob Tway, Brandel Chamblee, Craig Spence, and
Sutherland also had their turns at the top during the morning, and
the tournament remained a wide-open competition until Triplett
birdies holes 9 and 10 to forge a three-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   He never trailed again but had to survive his own brief
breakdown follow ing a rainbreak, then needed to outlast a hard
charge by Parnevik, whose closing 22-foot birdie putt forced
Triplett to make a 4-foot par-saver to avoid a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring good nature of the popular Triplett, 37, left
Parnevik a bit conflicted as he watched his opponent attempt a putt
that - if missed - would keep the Swede in contention for the
tournament's $555,000 first-place check.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was standing over that putt, I was hoping he would
make it,'' said Parnevik, laughing. ``But inside I was shouting,
`No! You want to be in a playoff.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the nicest guys on tour and I'm really happy for
him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett was happy for his play throughout a final round in
which some of the tour's most-celebrated players struggled with the
weather and with greens that remained bumpy from early and
late-week rain.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods,'' who entered the tournament with six wins in his
past seven starts, closed with a 72 to finish 279 and tie for 18th.
David Duval, ranked No. 3 in the world, shot 74 for a 281 that tied
him for 31st. Defending Nissan champion Ernie Els, a two-time U.S.
Open winner, had a final-round 76 and finished next to last at 288.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those closer to the lead entering the final round fared
little better, including Sutherland, who closed 72 to finish 280
and tie for 25t h. Armour was 71 for 276 and a share of fifth,
Chamblee shot 72-277 to tie first-round leader J.T. Hayes (71).
</P>
<P>
   Triplett, meanwhile, emerged a mudder and a closer, impressing
Parnevik, whose back-nine charge included three birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddie kept saying, `Doesn't this guy know he's never won?'
'' Parnevik said. ``He was peppering every pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the one for the biggest his biggest putt of the day,
the last one on 18, when Triplett first had to convince himself
that Parnevik would make his much-more-difficult 22-footer for
birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(The par putt) was an inside left read and I knew the only
thing that could hurt me would be a bad stroke,'' Triplett said.
``So I made sure I made a good stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that, he made a good comeback from a 12th hole bogey
that resul ted from brief lack of focus following the rainbreak.
</P>
<P>
   That bogey reduced Triplett's once-three-stroke lead to one
stroke ahead of Cochran and Freeman, but Triplett bounced right
back to birdie two holes later, then held off the challenge from
Parnevik as Freeman and Cochran started to run out of holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't give myself very any birdie opportunities,''
said Freeman, who was near the lead throughout the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett had enough birdies, barely, totaling six to offset a
bogey on each nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well all day,'' Triplett said, ``but I knew it would
be
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland, like Triplett searching for his first victory, wound
up disappointed he couldn't make a better showing with what he
called a great opportunity:
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted terribly the first 12 holes,'' said Sutherland, who
was celebrating his 34th birthday. ``I must have had three or four
3-putts. That sort of took the fun out of it... but I sure had a
good seat for a hell of a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland admitted he might have learned something about
competing in the final round but added, ``I would have rather
learned about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something Triplett now knows about, although he worried
about it while trying not to think ahead while slogging up the 18th
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a playoff,'' he said. ``I've never really
been in the lead or this close to the lead that late in the day and
it kept gnawi ng at me''
</P>
<P>
   The secret to his Sunday success?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is staying out of your own way,'' Triplett said,
``and I did a good job of that today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
