<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA500-BOS &LR;      02-21 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM EFFORT HELPS JARRETT WIN DAYTONA 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A gentle cascade of confetti and imitation
dollar bills fell upon Dale Jarrett, crew chief Todd Parrott, car
owner Robert Yates, and their entire crew as they stood in Victory
Lane at Daytona International Speedway and basked in their total
team victory in Sunday's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Now this was a Happy Hour celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a departure from the glum scene only 24 hours
before when Jarrett drove his badly limping car into the garage
area after a four-car mishap with 10 minutes remaining in Saturday
afternoon's Happy Hour session, the last practice before NASCAR's
crown jewel event.
</P>
<P>
   The car Jarrett had driven to the pole position and to victories
in the Bud Shootout and the 25-lap qualifier sat in the garage,
whimpering with a wrinkled nose, a dinged left front corner of the
hood, and dented front and rear bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   But Parrott rallied his troops _ summoning three fabricators
from the team's shop in Charlotte, N.C., to repair the nose _ and
began working feverishly in the garage that night to smooth out the
body work until NASCAR officials chased them out at 10:30 p.m.
While Jarrett slept soundly in his motorcoach in the infield, the
crew returned to the garage at 4:45 the next morning and began
delicate repairs to the nose, the most critical part of the car's
aerodynamics, which took six hours to complete. According to
Parrott's calculations, 15-20 people did 12 hours worth of repairs
to 35 percent to 40 percent of the car's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had the people that could put it back together,''
Parrott said. ``The big thing for me was, were there any demons in
there that I missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he promised Jarrett his No. 88 Ford Quality Care Taurus
would drive like new when they rolled it to the starting line at 11
a.m., Parrott wasn't certain of that until ``(Jarrett) took the
lead and sat there for a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was eating at my stomach and I was getting ready to get
sick, because he hadn't said anything to me over the radio,''
Parrott admitted. ``So, finally, I had to ask him and when he said
everything was fine, I knew we'd be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the defending NASCAR Winston Cup champion who led three
times for 89 laps, went to the front for the third and final time
when he made a strong move to the low line to pass Johnny Benson on
a restart after the race's fifth caution. Benson, who was 10 miles
away from winning his first Winston Cup race, muttered ``damn it''
over his radio when he got hung out in the draft by Jarrett and
fell back in the pack to finish 12th.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Spencer slammed into the wall exiting Turn 4 to
induce the race's sixth and final yellow on the next lap, Jarrett's
third career Daytona 500 triumph was sealed. He earned a record
$2,277,975 payday, which included a $1 million Winston No Bull 5
bonus that also made an instant millionaire of Melissa Brown, a
42-year-old data entry operator from Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The range of emotion in about a 24-hour period has been pretty
incredible,'' said Jarrett, who became the fourth driver to win
three or more Daytona 500s. ``Everything had gone so smoothly for
us since we got here about 10 days ago and then (Saturday)
afternoon, in making our last run, getting involved in that little
accident and bending the car up . . . just knowing the time and
effort that not only was put forth but that it actually takes to
make on these cars fast here looked to be taken right out of our
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parrott refused to let this race slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dale came into the garage, I could just see it in his
eyes that he was all torn up about it,'' Parrott said. ``I could
see all the adrenaline and all the momentum we had built up
starting to go away from him, and I didn't want to see that happen,
so I did everything I could to make sure that it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, as a result, wound up leading a conga line of five
Fords across the finish line, including runner-up Jeff Burton,
third-place Bill Elliott, fourth-place Rusty Wallace, and
fifth-place Mark Martin, who was irked at Jarrett for apparently
reneging on a late-race deal they had made to work together. Martin
was hung out high on Turn 2 of Lap 187 and was shuffled back in the
lead pack from second to sixth when Jarrett went low to protect
from losing track position to Burton and Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lied to,'' said Martin, who led once for 65 laps. ``I
just asked to have a chance and today we had a chance. I'd rather
have tried to win and lost than not tried. I could have sat there.
I did get lied to, but it was a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett openly apologized to Martin afterward in his
celebration, saying it was his only regret of the day. ``I didn't
lie to Mark Martin,'' Jarrett countered. ``I know that he felt like
that and there's nothing I can say that's going to change his mind.
If I were in the same position I'd feel the same way, probably;
when I looked up in the mirror and saw the 99 (Burton) and he had
the 94 (Elliott) behind him, I knew I was getting ready to lose my
position.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jarrett came across the finish and took the checkered under
caution, Martin sped up and pulled alongside the winner. Asked if
Martin offered his congratulations or shook his fist, Jarrett
chuckled. ``When Mark pulled up beside me he didn't shake his fist
and he didn't give me the finger,'' Jarrett said. ``He just threw
his hands up like, `What happened?' and I totally understand that.
I would've been the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was going to tarnish Jarrett's victory on this day.
Spare him the grief. After all he and his team had been through in
the previous 24 hours, they were deserving of a little happiness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
