<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-TEDWILLIAMS-BOS &LR;      02-21 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS STILL THE WORD IN BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 WILLIAMS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERNANDO, Fla. _ One baseball player left here saying, ``Man,
the whole thing gave me the chills.'' The player had sat under a
huge tent for hours, listening to testimonials. The words had
inspired him, as if he were in church being moved by a sermon.
Which, technically, he was.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference was that this was a Sunday afternoon
baseball revival. On one side of a stage you saw Carlton Fisk,
George Brett, Wade Boggs, Robin Yount, Al Kaline, and Jim Lonborg.
Across from them you saw Gaylord Perry, Buck O'Neil, Monte Irvin,
Johnny Pesky, Dom DiMaggio, and Bob Feller. In the middle was the
leader of the congregation, (Rev.) Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can understand why the witness to the good news, Red Sox
first baseman Brian Daubach, had the chills.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be formal, you can say this was a ceremony to
honor the players who were added to Williams's Hitters Hall of
Fame. Fisk, Boggs, Lonborg, and Daubach were among the honorees.
Truth is, this was more pilgrimage than ceremony. It was a long and
pleasant baseball bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   After Daubach and Florida's Preston Wilson were honored as
Williams's Rookies of the Year, Daubach took a seat next to
Williams. The young man asked the older one, ``What's the story
with the red seat (in right field at Fenway Park)?'' Williams
smiled and said, ``Aw, that's nothin'. I hit a lot of balls farther
than that one; that was a curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole afternoon was like that. Everyone had a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Lonborg explained the magic of 1967 to Daubach by pointing out
that the Sox had a strong finish to '66. ``So everyone was feeling
good in the offseason,'' Lonborg, now a dentist, said. ``That makes
a big difference. You can take that momentum and carry it to the
next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach listened and nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lasorda, the perfect choice for master of ceremonies, was
talking _ to anyone who wanted to listen _ about media absurdities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue now is the length of the games,'' he said. ``Do
you think the average family of five is keeping track of how long
the games are? The only people who care about that are the writers.
You know why? They want to finish early so they can have more time
to drink!''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Brett would say that Williams's .406 is nearly
untouchable. Robin Roberts laughed about the time Williams, so
angry that Roberts got him out, spit at the pitcher. ``If I had
known he was going to do that,'' Roberts said, ``I would have given
him a pitch right down the middle.'' O'Neil, who played in the
Negro Leagues with the Kansas City Monarchs, recalled a beautiful
moment in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in Kansas City, we could always hear the best jazz,'' he
said. ``The musicians would come in and jam for hours and hours.
One night, a young man walked in and started playing. Everybody
said, `Who is that?' The kid had a unique sound. You know who it
was? The great Charlie Parker. He was just a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   I would be willing to bet (friendly, of course) that you could
bring the most historically ignorant major leaguer here and he
would not only be humbled, he would be curious about those who
contributed before him. I don't mean for that to be taken in a
mawkish, weren't-those-the-good-days way. It's just that any
profession runs a little better when the current employees
understand its history.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who is only 26, may have had the most accurate line of
the day. As he accepted his award, the outfielder looked at the
Hall of Famers accompanying him and said, ``These people are truly
the geniuses of what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   A 19-year-old catcher from Charlestown, N.H., understood that in
'67. Fisk was in Ocala, Fla., a minor leaguer trying to get better.
He picked up a bat, positioned his hands and began to swing. He
paused when he heard Williams's mortified voice. Ted didn't like
the way the young catcher was holding the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez!'' he screamed at Fisk, while showing him the proper
positioning. ``And then,'' Fisk said, ``he told me to go off to the
side and start swinging on some tires.'' Fisk swung on the tires
until his hands were raw, but The Kid had made his point: You have
to be scientific when you hit. Williams not only did that, he wrote
a book about it. Fisk said he watched him bring the book, ``The
Science of Hitting,'' to life in '67. Williams had already retired
by then. He was helping Sports Illustrated do a story on hitting
by, well, illustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk stood behind him and watched him hit to the left side of
the infield. ``He was saying, `I could have gotten a hit there any
time I wanted,' '' Fisk said with a laugh. And then he watched him
hit to the right. Next, it was time for him to assault a fence in
right. The retired hitter cursed himself the whole time, telling
himself he could do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the greatest ambassador that baseball has today,''
Lasorda said of Williams. When Lasorda said that, Williams began
gesturing at Lasorda, saying that the former Dodgers manager
deserved that title. ``He is baseball from head to toe,'' Williams
said of Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost time to leave the revival tent. But before
leaving, Williams pointed to a covered field nearby. He said Little
Leaguers will be playing there soon, and that he hopes a few of
them will one day join his Hall of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
