<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BECK-BOS &LR;      02-21 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECK'S FASTBALL HAS SOME ACCELERATION 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BECK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ So this is why Jimy Williams and Joe Kerrigan
never could reach Rod Beck during the offseason: He was in the
garage.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox didn't know this, but Beck is a major gearhead. With
his brother-in-law, Sandy Neyer, Beck has formed a drag racing team
back home in Arizona that takes its name _ Nine's Mine Motorsports
LLC _ directly from Beck's principal mode of making a living, as a
closer. He owns a 1993 Corvette with two $50,000 engines that can
cover a quarter-mile track in 6.3 seconds, at speeds approximating
220 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine's Mine, like the ninth inning's mine,'' said Beck, who
enters this season with 260 saves, ranking him sixth among active
pitchers. ``And that's LLC, in case anybody wants to sue me.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck estimates he has invested $300,000 in the enterprise. He
entered the car in four races last year, and plans to run it on the
West Coast ProMod Association circuit this spring. The first race,
he said, will be in three weeks in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Neyer does the driving. Beck sent both Neyer and his
crew chief to school to master these cars, which are the types that
require parachutes as braking mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll drive when I retire,'' Beck said, ``The biggest thrill
for me is buying the car and building and rebuilding the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastest I've ever gone?'' He laughed. ``I don't want to
say, because I'm still under contract. Probably 160. Most of my
experience has come in illegal street racing. I got started in this
during the strike in '94. I was sitting around with nothing to do,
and had a '69 (Chevy) Nova sitting in my garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't into cars in high school. I was into baseball. My
brother Rick was the car nut. But I had some fun tinkering with the
Nova, and six years later, here I am. I always told my brother that
one day I'd have a car that could beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in years, the ninth inning has not been
promised to Beck, who had a career-low 10 saves last season, one in
which he had surgery to remove bone chips from his elbow in May and
was traded from the Cubs to the Sox at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   The first time he walked out of the Sox bullpen in Fenway Park,
on the same day he flew in from San Diego, Beck got a save. He also
pitched a heroic four innings in an epic, 13-inning win in
Cleveland in September. But the enduring memory he left Sox fans
with came in Game 1 of the ALCS, when Bernie Williams of the
Yankees hit a massive home run off Beck in the bottom of the 10th
to send the Sox to a crushing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Beck refuses to blame his elbow for his late-season
ineffectiveness, which left the Red Sox sufficiently alarmed to
declare Derek Lowe the closer entering this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame nothing on my arm,'' he said. ``I don't make
excuses. If you put the ball where you want it, you're going to get
a hitter out. You saw Pedro (Martinez) against Cleveland. He was
hurt, but he changed speeds and location and was just as
dominating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get excited and want to get a guy out so fast,
you don't take the proper steps to get there. I wanted to bust
(Williams) in so bad, but I flew open and the ball tailed back over
the plate. And who says he wasn't looking there, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Beck says he has been working out since Thanksgiving at the
Cubs' complex in Arizona and that his elbow feels as good as it has
``since high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the same guy who saved 48 games for the Giants in
'93,'' said Beck, who will be 32 this August. ``I don't know if I
can light up the clock (speed gun) the way I did back then, but
this is as good a health I've been in for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to extend my elbow to the point I can now
for years and years. In that respect, I feel pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Sox intend to use Beck to set up Lowe, and as a
closer when Lowe has pitched two innings the night before. Does
Beck believe he has a chance to change Williams's mind about his
role?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to,'' he said, ``but I'm not going to create a
controversy over it. The best man's going to win. If he's better
for the job, fine. I have a firm belief that once you make a
decision, stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beck acknowledged that the Red Sox might be stronger if he
can close, which would leave the Sox able to capitalize on Lowe's
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can give you starts, too,'' Beck said. ``He's one of those
pitchers who can do anything you ask him to, at any point in the
ballgame. There aren't too many guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he wants to see how Beck throws before he makes
any decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's let Beck pitch,'' he said Sunday. ``He's almost a year
recovered from his operation. We know he has the mentality (of a
closer). All you have to do is look at his numbers. But will he be
able to get back to that degree? I don't know. Physically, I don't
know. But looking at him, you can see he's already been trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck already has met his Seoul brother, Korean reliever Sang
Lee, whose hair rivals Beck's in length. ``But he got it cut,''
Beck said. ``When I saw pictures of him, it was down to here.''
</P>
<P>
   He put his hand between his shoulder blades.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe I'll borrow his orange dye.''
</P>
<P>
   And given Lee's fender bender on the way to work Saturday, maybe
Beck could offer him a ride, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
