<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENT FIRES UP BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ As if Bruins coach Pat Burns
hadn't been through enough during this disappointing season. The
hits just keep coming. A couple of weeks ago, he was criticized by
owner Jeremy Jacobs. Sunday, it came from former Bruin and current
Channel 38 broadcaster Phil Esposito.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's Boston Herald, columnist Jim Baker wrote that
Esposito believes Burns may be trying to get himself fired. It was
a small item, but it evoked a titanic reaction from Burns following
the club's workout at GM Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later it's got to stop,'' said Burns. ``Now they're
saying I'm trying to get fired. I called (Esposito) and left him a
message. He said something, too, on Friday that I didn't let the
players be themselves or something. That's all right _ there you're
doing an (analysis). If you want to analyze that, that's fine. I
can disagree with it, which I do. But to say I'm trying to get
myself fired, that's BS. Call me anything you want but that's
calling me a crook. I'm not a crook and I'm not dishonest. I'm out
here every single day trying to win hockey games, certainly not to
get fired. I'm still a young guy who has a coaching career ahead of
me. Why would I do something stupid like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he realizes he's not immune from criticism and he
doesn't mind when shots are taken _ until they cross a certain
line. He believes Esposito went way over the line that separates
analysis from character assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can question my coaching abilities, that's fine; you can
question the way I look, that's fine; but to question my
credibility when I come to work every day, that I won't take,''
said Burns. ``I don't want to get into Phil's past and I'm sure he
doesn't want me to. He's trying to say I'm trying to get myself
fired so I can sit home? That's the biggest line of crap I've ever
heard in my life. To say I'm a crook? People who know me know
better than that. You're questioning the whole integrity of myself
and the whole integrity of the game. That's (expletive)
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barring a significant improvement overnight, it's possible Ray
Bourque might be sidelined Monday night when the Bruins take on the
Canucks. Bourque, who suffered a whiplash-type muscle strain in his
neck last week against Toronto, practiced Sunday but said he's
still having trouble turning his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty stiff,'' he said. ``It was a long flight and
hopefully another day will help. We're going to work on it and
hopefully it will feel better. If I can't (turn), you can't move
quick or see. I wouldn't want to be in that position. You can't do
certain things because you can't move. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had planned to arrive here Saturday. But weather
conditions grounded their charter flight and they were forced to
wait a day, arriving Sunday instead. The pilot of the originally
scheduled flight felt the runway at Hanscom was too slick to
attempt a takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making that call,'' said Burns. ``I can control the
four-by-four but I can't control the wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burns said it was a disappointing development since he
had hoped to give his club the edge by arriving early, especially
since the Canucks were playing in Ottawa Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good plan,'' said Burns. ``But like everything else .
. . We were going to come out here (Saturday) and have a good
practice and have another one here (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they arrived late for their scheduled workout Sunday
and ended up begging for a half-hour of ice time from a group of
kids who were there to skate. In exchange, the kids were invited to
watch practice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe will get the start for Boston. Rob Tallas,
who is still bothered by a fractured left ring finger suffered
against Toronto, is slowly making progress. He went through the
workout with Dafoe and goalie John Grahame. Burns said he isn't
sure how the goalie game plan will go this week with four games in
six nights. It's possible Grahame will see some action, but Burns
said it depends on how Dafoe fares Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
