<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-PIT     02-21 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEARS HEADS BC CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-PITTSBURGH-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ A smile flashed across Adriana Spears's face when
she was called for her third foul with 6:33 left to play. Not that
she was happy to have committed the foul, she was happy that she
had done her job.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston College freshman hit layups, pulled down rebounds,
and drew fouls in possibly the best game of her young career as the
19th-ranked Eagles defeated the Pittsburgh Panthers, 66-52, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Spears wasn't the high scorer, she played a
career-high 25 minutes, scored a career-high 11 points, grabbed 6
rebounds, handed out 3 assists, and made 2 blocks. So you had to
excuse the 6-foot-1-inch forward for that smile when she picked up
her third personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really went out there and sparked us, especially in the
second half, not just with her play, but emotionally, the way she
was going after the ball,'' said senior point guard Cal Bouchard,
the game's high scorer with 20 points. Bouchard was 3 for 4 from
3-point range and 5 for 5 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles (21-6 overall, 10-3 Big East) were slow getting to
Pittsburgh this weekend after their flight from Boston was
canceled, and Saturday's game had to be pushed back a day. BC flew
late Saturday night instead and arrived at Fitzgerald Field House
Sunday to face the Panthers (14-10, 5-8) before 441.
</P>
<P>
   BC marched out to a 10-4 lead, highlighted by three straight
field goals by Jamie Cournoyer (15 points). But then the Eagles
went cold as Pittsburgh went on a 6-0 run sparked by a 3-pointer by
freshman guard Brooke Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   A jumper by Bouchard gave the Eagles the lead at 12-10, but
Pittsburgh responded a minute later with a basket by freshman Mandy
Wittenmyer to tie the game. A rebound basket by Spears followed by
a Bouchard 3-pointer gave the Eagles their biggest lead of the half
at 17-12. But the Panthers clawed back and pulled ahead, 25-23,
with 2:37 to go in the half.
</P>
<P>
   A Celeste Barkley free throw opened up a 3-point lead for
Pittsburgh, but BC answered with a Kim Mackie free throw, a jumper
by Bouchard, and a layup by Spears to close the half in front,
28-26.
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese said she wasn't really surprised by the
first-half struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just weren't focused at first; it took us a while
to settle down,'' she said. ``We had to come out and play with more
emotion, more intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   So she switched from a man-to-man defense to a zone, which
seemed to befuddle the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles started to pull away after a 3-pointer by Bouchard
made it 35-28. Pittsburgh came back to within 1, but BC followed
with a 10-0 run to widen the lead to 45-34 with 12:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Pittsburgh came the rest of the way was 8 as the
Panthers shot just 38 percent from the floor and hit just one free
throw after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half we looked staggered,'' said Pittsburgh coach
Traci Waites. ``They found our weakness and exploited it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Monique Toney, who hit three 3-pointers, was the Panthers'
high scorer with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Spears just shrugged when asked if playing more than half the
game felt different than logging minutes in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I know what I'm supposed to do,'' she said. ``Get the
offensive boards, bang around, box them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bouchard: ``We have different people who can step up on
different nights, and this was definitely her night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
