<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SAIL-AMERICA'SCUP-BOS     02-21 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIWIS' WIN: FIRST IN A SERIES? 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ In the calm after the storm, two stories
were told on this dozing waterfront. Two stories of the same race.
</P>
<P>
   The postrace cacophony created by thousands of boat horns and
fans at Viaduct Basin Saturday night sounded as if the coronation
of the 30th Cup winner was at hand, though it was just one race in
the best-of-nine series.
</P>
<P>
   And with a lay day Sunday, all there was for race fans to chew
on was the opener, and the different versions of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   According to the skipper of Prada, Francesco de Angelis, the
first race showed only that New Zealand won the first race,
although that was the minority view.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand beat Prada by 1 minute 17 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As de Angelis and his tactician, Torben Grael, told it, Saturday
was clearly a ``no passing lane day.'' Actually, there was one
passing lane on the first leg. But as the big black bow of the
Kiwis came at them at 9.5 knots on starboard tack, the Italians
decided not to cross the Kiwis to take the favored right side of
the course. They probably could and should have.
</P>
<P>
   It happened during a tacking duel that began about 20 minutes
into the race. Prada was riding on the left side of the New Zealand
boat, and as the two tacked to cross once, then twice, Luna Rossa
seemed to have enough space to cross New Zealand's bow, something
it would have done, perhaps, against any other opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Grael, ``The second cross was the best one for us, but
still it would have been very scary to cross them, especially
against those very experienced guys. It was early in the race and
we shouldn't risk a cross like that. We tacked to leeward and we
lost after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The match-racing textbook backs Grael's call not to cross. Early
in a big money race, the risk of fouling out was just too great.
Only in retrospect did it become clear that that was the only
moment the Italians could have taken control of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The textbook also says the lead boat in a race between equals
should be able to extend its lead because of its ability to control
tactics and pick shifts.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand did extend its lead in every leg but one, Leg 4, the
second run. It was there that Prada sailed a lower, faster line to
take 38 seconds out of the Kiwi lead, narrowing the margin to 25
seconds at the mark _ the only leg New Zealand has lost in all 36
it has sailed in America's Cup match races since May 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand side of the story comes down to this simple
belief: The Kiwis' innovative International America's Cup Class
yacht, much different from the challenger norm, is more than fast
enough to beat Prada, 5-0. A few would give the Italians one or two
wins because of days of fluky shifts.
</P>
<P>
   No one innovation has been credited for the ``leap ahead'' that
Kiwi designer Laurie Davidson predicted weeks ago. Was it the
knuckle bow that, despite its ugliness, gives the Kiwis more
waterline?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the ``millennium rig,'' a bendy mast supported by just
three, rather than five, sets of spreaders for less drag? Or the
upwind detachment of the top-mast backstay, again making for less
drag?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the new super lightweight form-fitting sailing suits
make the Kiwis sleeker, or maybe their electronic communication
system, allowing skipper Russell Coutts to talk into the ear of his
foredeck crew a noisy 75 feet away, helps clarify the moves on
Black Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any or all of that makes the Kiwis the 5-0 Cup killers
their backers now proclaim them to be remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that this remote South Pacific nation of 3 1/2
million has sea water in its veins. In splendid isolation, New
Zealand has matched and perhaps trumped the best the rest of the
world has to offer from design offices in wealthy capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Winning) was not easy,'' said Kiwi mainsheet trimmer Warwick
Fleury, who became a team spokesman when Coutts and tactician Brad
Butterworth decided to avoid the postrace news conference. ``Races
like that in those conditions come down to whoever gets a jump.
Once a boat gets ahead, it is able to extend, especially upwind. If
Prada had been able to squeak across (in Leg 1) then it may have
been a different result.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the only part of the Kiwi line the sailors of the
red-striped bullet Luna Rossa were happy to hear. During the
anxious wait Sunday until Monday's second race, it was about the
only hope they had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
