<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3221 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SPURS-HNS     02-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SPURS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Rudy Tomjanovich searched for words and answers. He could not find
them. His eyes seemed to search the room, the hallways. He waited
silently, patiently forming words carefully but unhappily.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, with the Rockets' 113-111 overtime defeat to the Spurs
on Sunday still painfully churning in his stomach, he forced out a
few sentences like bitter spit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of effort put into the game,'' he said before
pausing to collect himself again, ``and I just didn't feel we got a
fair break. That's about all I've got to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about what he considered unfair, Tomjanovich said again,
``That's all I have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich never specifically mentioned the officials or even
individual plays that had him and most of the 16,285 in Compaq
Center in an uproar. It was all he could do to speak of Hakeem
Olajuwon's ``phenomenal'' return to the starting lineup, Kenny
Thomas' brilliant defensive effort on Tim Duncan, or Steve Francis'
51-minute marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're trying to make me feel better ,'' he said of what
got the Rockets into overtime, unable to finish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had come back from their Friday-night whipping in
San Antonio to give the defending world champions all they could
handle. But they could hardly say a word about what they had done
right or what finally went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the last game, the comment I gave was that this game was
going to be different; it was going to be a war,'' Spurs coach
Gregg Popovich said. ``I was right. The Rockets were great, the
fans were great, and we were thrilled to come away with a
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets scored more points against the Spurs than anyone had
all season. They held Duncan in check most of the night, and after
he got rolling to his NBA Finals standards, they shut him down
again. Olajuwon had his best performance since November, scoring 21
points, grabbing nine rebounds and blocking four shots. The Rockets
led by eight in the fourth quarter. They led by a field goal with
90 seconds left in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   They did virtually everything they would have included on a
pre-game checklist and still were beaten. And like so many victims
of the Spurs' find-a-way way, they were lost when trying to
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game we should win,'' Olajuwon said. ``There's not
an excuse for losing this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets took a 107-105 overtime lead when Francis split
Duncan and David Robinson on a drive with 3:13 left. But with the
game on the line, the Spurs typically applied the defensive clamps.
It took the Rockets three minutes to score again.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets hit the overtime wall, Avery Johnson tied the
score with a jumper with 1:17 left. Duncan made a pair of free
throws with 35.5 seconds left for a 109-107 San Antonio lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets set up Francis to create on a drive, and he said he
saw an uncovered Kenny Thomas. But Duncan slapped away Francis'
pass on the baseline. Terry Porter picked up the loose ball, and
his two free throws gave the Spurs a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody was open,'' Francis said. ``I just couldn't hit him.
He was wide-open, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon scored on a spin to the basket with 12.6 seconds left.
But by then the Rockets had to foul, and Mario Elie made a pair of
free throws with 10.9 seconds left to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had reason to believe they should have taken the
victory much earlier. The Spurs led by 10 in the first quarter and
by five with three minutes left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets led by 13 in the second half and by eight in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Rockets took their eight-point fourth quarter lead,
the Spurs put the ball and game in Duncan's hands and let him carry
them. He scored the next seven points and set up four more. After
scoring just eight points through three quarters, he led the Spurs
with 25.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final three minutes of regulation, Thomas threw
himself at that speeding train and stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had given the Spurs a 103-98 lead with a spin move. But
Thomas then harassed him into a turnover. He immediately drew a
foul on Duncan inside, and with a contact lens missing, he made one
free throw to cut the deficit to 103-101.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was fouled but missed both free throws. The Spurs
grabbed the rebound and went back to Duncan as a matter of course,
but Thomas stopped him again. Thomas so completely cut off every
Duncan option that the All-Star Game's co-Most Valuable Player held
the ball too long in the lane and was called for three seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets isolated Cuttino Mobley on the right side, and he
quickly beat Porter off the dribble to nail a 14-footer and tie the
game with 6.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was more than enough time for the Spurs to get
the ball to Duncan. He made his move and went up from 14 feet, but
this time Olajuwon rushed over to help and swatted the shot safely
away with 2.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets set up a final play to shoot for the win, but the
Spurs cut off every option the Rockets had planned, forcing the
inbounds pass to Olajuwon. His hurried 18-footer missed, sending
the game to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the moment the Rockets bemoaned most. It barely
made the list. And as they searched for answers, about the best
they found was Tomjanovich's lament, ``You can always make one more
play.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have done it. But that fact did not make it any
easier to take.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
