<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     02-21 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE FINALLY HAS THAT WINNING FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The whisper of a wintry wind over nervous silence.
A four-foot putt rattling into a cup. The sudden shrill roar of a
smallish Sunday gallery. A fist thrust as high in the gray sky as a
limber man of 6-foot-3 can reach.
</P>
<P>
   And then an unusually joyous congratulatory handshake from a
beaten opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett had always tried to imagine the sights, sounds and
feelings he experienced late on the final afternoon of the Nissan
Open at Riviera Country Club. He had tried for so long to imagine
the moment when he'd finally win a PGA tournament that he had begun
to believe it might never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   And now here it was.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Cathi, had always kidded him about not having a fist
pump like Tiger Woods', and now here he was with his right arm in
the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger says he doesn't plan his fist pumps, they just kind of
happen, and now I know what he means,'' Triplett said a few minutes
later. ``You've got a lot of emotion built up, and at the end it's
got to come out. I just hoped it would come out the right way. I
hoped I wouldn't faint.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Triplett, a genial Washington state native with
graying sandy hair and kind blue eyes, had merely been a happy and,
by most measures, successful member of the PGA Tour. He had earned
$4,270,878 in 10 seasons, a record for a player who had never
actually won a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   With that money, he had provided for his family of four, and he
had paid his dues plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   He had spent three years in the 1980s playing in Asia, Australia
and Canada. He had put in his time on ``the miniest mini-tours,''
testing himself in events named the Hagen Oaks Pro Scratch and the
Winnemucca Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm halfway around the world playing for $18,000 for first
(place). Getting sick, riding on the buses two hours each way to
the golf course,'' he said of the Asian tour, which left him with
stories so good, he can't tell them in polite company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid you in cash _ `whip-out,' right after the end. You
like driving the back roads with $17,000 in American hundred-dollar
bills in your back pocket? In a taxi? And the (driver) doesn't
speak a word of English? `Take me to the Black Angus.' `Yeah,
right.' Two hours later, where is it?''
</P>
<P>
   The rain in which most of Sunday's round was played was growing
stronger as Triplett spoke, beating on the roof of the Riviera
press room like a snare drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Taiwan it rained 13 out of 14 days, and we played every
day,'' he said. ``This is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering where his career began made what happened Sunday
``so sweet for me,'' Triplett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played at every level. Except the buy.com Tour (formerly the
Nike Tour). They didn't have that when I started, that's how old I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   At 37, Triplett is a veteran of 266 PGA Tour events. Saturday,
after finishing the third round tied for second, a stroke behind
David Sutherland, he remarked that after that many failures, it was
hard to imagine (begin ital)this(end ital) might be the week.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, people would ask, ``How many years you
been out here?'' They didn't have to add, ``without winning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say four, five ... six ... seven ...,'' Triplett said.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, it dawned on him that this 0-fer was
dragging on. The realization came when he made a tournament cut for
the 150th time, earning the qualifying exemption known officially
as ``Veteran Member.''
</P>
<P>
   A second-place finisher five times in his decade of play, he
couldn't remember going to the final nine holes in the lead before
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But on a day when seven men held or shared the lead at some
point, and when the Woods threat came uncoiled early, Triplett
opened a three-shot lead when he birdied the par-4 ninth hole. By
the time he ambled to the final holes, he was two ahead of Jesper
Parnevik and wondering how he would respond to the pressure.
Triplett hadn't won even a non-PGA Tour event since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would get rocky coming in, knew I'd be fighting it,
and I was,'' he said of the nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik was watching him and found him ``very calm, very
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his familiar floppy white hat, Triplett wore a soft,
closed- mouthed smile. He looked at the crowd, savored the
long-awaited moment.
</P>
<P>
   He even managed a smile when Parnevik holed a 22-foot birdie
putt at 18, forcing Triplett to sink his downhill 4-footer to win
without a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, knowing Triplett's story, knowing him as ``a very
humble guy (who) never ticks anybody off,'' found himself kind of
rooting for his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Triplett is the kind of guy who already considered
himself a success, win or no win, because of his family. The kind
of guy who said: ``I can't wait to get home (to Scottsdale, Ariz.)
and see them. But I would have felt that way if I'd shot an 82.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he also admitted, ``It's not as good a career if you
don't win a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The green fell silent. Triplett smacked the putt straight into
the back of the hole. The gallery, shrunk by the exodus that
followed Tiger's round, saluted with shouts and applause. Triplett
threw that hand in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik shook it happily.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody handed Triplett a check for ... how much was it? he
asked later.
</P>
<P>
   So that's what winning is like. He'll have to do it more often. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 0141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
