<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-TIGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE DRAMA FOR TIGER FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the charge that never came, the great rally
that wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful still followed, no matter the elements, waiting for
the dramatic finish they were certain awaited.
</P>
<P>
   Only Tiger Woods never did make a move. Never did get close
enough at the Riviera Country Club on Sunday to make the leaders
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his past eight tournaments, Woods never
developed as a real factor. Instead of a charge, there was only a
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had conditioned his faithful to expect drama, to
anticipate a final surge towards the top of the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   But the only movement was so uncharacteristic it was almost
unrecognizable. He started the day six under, three strokes back of
leader David Sutherland. He birdied No.3, and his afternoon had
peaked.
</P>
<P>
   He bogied seven, eight and nine, and was out.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who had won six consecutive tournaments before
finishing second last week, had tumbled out of contention at the
Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad round,'' Woods said. ``I didn't really have
it going this entire week. If I had putted a little bit better, I'd
have been right there for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't have everything, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, there you have it. Not even Mr. Nike can have everything.
On a sometimes windy, rainy and cold afternoon, Woods made like a
mortal.
</P>
<P>
   He began the day with promise. Despite not playing at his best
in the first three rounds, no one was running away with the
tournament and Woods lurked nervously near.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit frustrating, but given the way I played
this week, I really should not have been where I was today,'' Woods
said. ``I should have been a little worse. I still hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods played in a snappy red Nike vest, over a black Nike polo
shirt and wore a black Nike cap. When the rains fell, he donned a
black Nike nylon jacket that matched his black Nike nylon pants.
Fighting a little cold, he frequently went to a hankie, where
surprisingly, no small swoosh mark was identified. Opportunities
still await.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped a 12-foot putt for the birdie on No.3, to fall seven
shots under. Putting had been a tricky problem for Woods on the
thick poa annua greens throughout the tournament. Putts kept
ringing around the cup and spinning out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those weeks where I hit so many good putts that
lipped out,'' Woods said.``A perfect example is the last hole. A
perfect putt that looks dead center from 2 feet out, all of a
sudden it dies and lips out.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' tournament hopes started to die on the seventh. He hit a
poor drive, that left him in the rough and needing to send his
second shot over a pair of trees. It landed in the rough 20 feet to
the right of the green. His wedge shot flew past the cup and onto
the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Woods slammed his club to the turf, his only display of emotion
on the day.
</P>
<P>
   After bogeying seven, he did the same on eight when he missed a
simple 2-foot putt. On No. 9, he went over the green, chipped 12
feet past the cup and left with his third consecutive bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kirk Triplett birdied four of his first nine holes
and was taking control.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was falling from condition for the first time since last
August when he tied for 37th at the Sprint International.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't manage another birdie until the 13th hole, where he
had double-bogeyed the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another good putt,'' he said. ``I'll be honest with
you, it hits a huge piece of poa 10 feet out it hopped straight
left. I thought I would miss it left, and then it hops back to the
right and now I think I'm going to miss it on the right edge, then
about 6 inches it dives har d left and back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's potluck out there on those greens right now. They're
really bumpy. There's so much moisture in the greens, the poa is
just growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods knew he was disappearing, and several times gambled and
used his driver when others were playing safe with irons, but it
never paid dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Woods finished one over, seven shots back of Triplett. For a
change, the day ended without the Woods charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
