<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-MELUSKEY-H     02-21 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MELUSKEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ It was great to be Mitch Meluskey last spring.
Catcher Brad Ausmus had been traded by the Astros to Detroit to
create a roster spot for Meluskey, who spent most of the spring
answering questions about how it felt to be considered a Rookie of
the Year candidate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expectations were high, and pressure was great, but nothing ever
materialized, thanks to a shoulder injury that limited Meluskey's
rookie season to 10 games. There is nothing fun or easy about
starting over, which he no doubt will find out over the next
several weeks of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey is no longer a lock to make the team. In fact, he
entered spring training as the No. 3 catcher _ in the mind of
manager Larry Dierker _ on a team that likely will carry only two
players at that position.
</P>
<P>
   Having signed a two-year, $2.4 million contract and with seven
years of big-league experience, Tony Eusebio is a lock for one of
the positions. Paul Bako, who was recalled from Class AAA New
Orleans and hit .256 after Meluskey's injury, is out of options,
meaning he would have to clear waivers _ an unlikely possibility _
before the Astros could send him to the minors. Thus, Bako has an
inside track to the other spot.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave Meluskey? Fighting an uphill battle and
needing to do some serious eye-opening to make the opening-day
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it looks like Eusebio and Bako, because Mitch has
options,'' Dierker said. ``But Mitch can't be ignored. He's in a
position to force his way onto the team. Mitch understands the
situation, and I think he's more relaxed this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the pressure is off this spring. Last year, he was
the subject of a great deal of attention. He had a lot of people
from the media interviewing him, and that was the first time he had
ever faced anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spring it seems like the pressure is off because he's not
the fair-haired boy, the Rookie of the Year candidate or anything
like that. He's just another guy trying to win a job.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appears the deck is somewhat stacked against
the 26-year-old Meluskey. However, he doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel at a disadvantage at all,'' said Meluskey, who
declared his shoulder a non-issue. ``I guess I'm still kind of one
of their guys. I don't know if my (value) went down because I got
hurt last year. I really am not too worried about it. There could
still be moves. If I just go out and play my game, everything will
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the possibility of opening the season at Class
AAA New Orleans, where Meluskey hasn't played since 1998?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very, very, very, unbelievably, terribly
disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bako knew the feeling last spring. He outhit Meluskey .333 to
.222 and doubled Meluskey's production in home runs and RBIs, yet
he still began the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I kind of felt like I was the odd guy out and that I
was really going to have to open some eyes to make the team,'' Bako
said. ``I thought I did that, but I was still the odd guy out. This
year I feel that, hopefully, I have a better crack at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Eusebio is the only catcher in the mix who is
totally secure. Throughout his career, Eusebio has outlasted
several catchers acquired to take his job.
</P>
<P>
   His patience was rewarded this offseason with the first
multiyear contract of his career. Despite a fragile set of knees,
Eusebio started 83 games behind the plate in 1999 and hit .272 with
33 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to get a two-year contract for the last two
or three years,'' Eusebio said. ``I guess now was the time. I've
been with the organization a long time, and I've appreciated
everything they've done for me, but I feel like I was entitled to
that contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few teams interested in me _ the Yankees and St.
Louis _ but I've been with the Astros all of my life, and I wanted
to make a deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the key questions regarding the Astros going into last
season was whether the team would suffer a defensive drop-off at
catcher after Ausmus was traded. Ausmus, nicknamed ``The Officer''
because of his penchant for controlling traffic on the basepaths,
is one of the top defensive catchers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be wasted worry. Astros catchers threw out 31
percent of the runners who attempted to steal against them,
fifth-best in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can produce more runs than we did last year, but as
far as throwing out runners and helping the pitchers out, I think
we did a pretty good job,'' Bako said. ``Our pitching was good _ if
not great _ all year, and I'd like to think (the catchers) had
something to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to keeping baserunners honest, the Astros' catchers
also contributed to the pitching staff's 3.83 earned run average,
which ranked third in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker no doubt would take a repeat of that kind of work from
his duo behind the plate. It's just a matter of which catchers will
form the tandem.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
