<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-21 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Upon entering the clubhouse at the Astros' spring
training home for the first time, Octavio Dotel got the good news
he had been assigned a locker stall right next door to an old
friend.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the friend is Jose Lima, and that means if
Dotel wants to get in a single word, he's almost got to make a
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Jose,'' said Dotel. ``I've known him from playing
together for several years in the Dominican Republic. He's always
talking, always going, and that's all right with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been here in the Astros organization for a while, and I
will be listening to him to find out what I need to do to fit in
with this team and what I need to do to grow and become the kind of
pitcher that he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Call the class Lima 101, and if the 24-year-old Dotel, who came
with Roger Cedeno from New York in the Mike Hampton trade, is
willing to sit in the front row and learn the ropes from Professor
Merengue and the coaching staff, that will be fine with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   For in Dotel, the Astros' brass see similarities to Lima that
are more than just a common native land. Both have live arms. Both
have plenty of competitive fire. But what has enabled Lima to
advance over the past two seasons to a level where he could record
16 and 21 wins respectively is that he came to a greater
understanding of what it means to be a pitcher rather than just a
battler and a thrower.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it worked for Jose, then I can see that what they might
want me to do can work,'' said Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in his first major-league season, Dotel posted an 8-3
record in 19 starts for the Mets and was 7-1 after the All-Star
break. He possesses a 92-94-mph fastball that was rated the best in
the Class AAA International League in 1998, and his hard curveball
gives him two overpowering pitches. He showed flashes of
brilliance, striking out a batter per inning and holding opposing
hitters to a .226 average.
</P>
<P>
   But Dotel also walked 49 batters in 85 innings, gave up 12 home
runs and at times got himself into trouble by falling behind in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen of him, he's got a great off-speed
pitch,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker. ``But he does not have
great control, and yet he's still been able to win games. That
tells you he's a fighter. But to improve, to really be more than a
fighter, to be a dominant pitcher, you've got to learn some of the
basic philosophies. You've got to learn to pitch, not just
overpower or see every batter as a personal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Astros would be happy if Dotel could emulate
Lima and learn that getting a batter to hit a ground ball to
shortstop or second base by using just a couple of pitches is
better than fighting through eight or nine pitches to get a
strikeout. And they want him to work on developing a changeup.
</P>
<P>
   The learning process, according to pitching coach Vern Ruhle,
involves a great deal more than just constant preaching. It is
breaking down the elements to give a pitcher several focal points
every time he throws the ball, much like a golfer has a swing
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's a real interesting topic for a fan,'' Ruhle
said. ``But what I'm talking about is getting a guy to focus on the
mitt, to think about his stride, to be aware of the location of his
shoulder and his elbow on every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea isn't to make them all identical. Guys have different
styles, from Lima to Shane Reynolds to Scott Elarton. What you're
trying to do is to get them to kind of be their own coach out there
on the mound, to be able to check what they're doing, to know if
what they're doing is the right thing, even if the result isn't
always positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, a guy can pitch a two- or three-hitter for eight
innings, make one bad pitch in the ninth to give up a homer, and he
gets a loss next to his name. You get down. The clubhouse is quiet.
But you have to be able to look back at the outing and say that
what you did was right and stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't take it personally and go back out in your next start
trying to mow every batter down.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken Lima a few years of Ruhle's influence to understand
the concept fully, and the hope is that he can now help pass the
message along to Dotel a little more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They traded Mike Hampton, the best pitcher they had, to get
me,'' Dotel said. ``That makes me feel good and tells me what they
think of me. I thought I had a good first year in New York. But if
they have a way to make me better, no problem. I'll listen.''
</P>
<P>
   To Dierker, to Ruhle, to Lima monologues from the next locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to have a teammate, a friend, be able to say,
`Hey, I went through this,''' said Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   For Professor Merengue, then, class is in session.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
