r s BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN     02-21 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' SEESAW WON'T STOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON -- Kings coach Andy Murray didn't have much of an
appetite a little after midnight Sunday morning as he sat picking
at a hamburger in the team's Buffalo hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In 24 hours the Kings had gone from the emotional peak of
beating the mighty Detroit Red Wings to a 4-1 loss against the
struggling Sabres. This was heartburn NHL style.
</P>
<P>
   On one restaurant TV was a replay of his game against the Sabres
that ended a five-game winning streak and made King Vladimir
Tsyplakov -- with one goal and two assists -- a hero in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Another TV was playing the late game between Calgary and
Edmonton, two teams seemingly headed in opposite directions in the
Western Conference but both critical to the Kings playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't rule anything out,'' Murray warned after slumping
Calgary jumped out to a 2-0 lead. ``The only thing that you can
predict is the unpredictability.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton, which hosts the Kings tonight, had entered the weekend
series with Calgary leading the Northwest Division. The Flames were
winless in their previous 10 games. On a five-game trip, they lost
them all by one goal, including three in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton had a seven-point lead over Calgary in the Western
Conference and more importantly in the bitter battle between the
two small market clubs in the province of Alberta. The Oilers
seemed to be pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Calgary won the first game 4-2, but the Flames early
lead in Saturday's game evaporated with 35 seconds left in
regulation on a goal by Todd Marchant. The crowd in Edmonton went
wild, but even before the noise died down, Marc Savard scored a
minute into overtime and the Flames had swept.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary now is only three points behind Edmonton, which has been
bumped by Colorado in the Northwest and now hold the eighth and
final playoff spot in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (28-23-7) are sixth, one point ahead of San Jose. The
Sharks host the Kings on Saturday and there is not telling where
all this will be by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a shame that it turned out the way it did for us,''
Oilers forward Bill Guerin said after the second game. ``These are
going to be tough points to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the same about his team's performance Saturday night
Buffalo. The Sabres had scored most than two goals just once in its
previous 13 games. But after the Kings took a 1-0 lead in the first
period on Ziggy Palffy's 23rd goal, the Sabres former MVP
goaltender Dominik Hasek shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think they were going to score a lot of goals
against us,'' Luc Robitaille said. ``But we know anytime you go up
against Hasek, it's going to be a tough night.''
</P>
<P>
   No one had a tougher than Robitaille, who had chance to give the
Kings the lead early in the second, but his backhander hit the
post. A second chance in front of Hasek also failed later in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever seen Luc miss those shots,'' Murray
said. ``In this league, you just never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
