<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREZ-PRIZE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST NEXT ON PRIMARY JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Once the presidential circus wraps things up in
Michigan, attention will turn west and north over the next two
weeks for the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' primaries, with California
the biggest prize of all.
</P>
<P>
   California and New York _ along with 13 other states and
territories _ hold primaries and caucuses March 7 that will almost
certainly determine the major parties' presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``California could become the make-or-break state,'' said Kam
Kuwata, who is managing the campaign of Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., and is not involved in any of the presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, have had the luxury since the New Hampshire
primary of being able to crisscross the nation without worrying
about any other elections leading up to Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the leading Republican candidates _ Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain _ have both been helped and hurt
by the glare of public scrutiny as they have battled fiercely in
South Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even with those efforts, all four have begun the
traditional California campaign, with the start of television
commercials that are expected to cost $1.5 million a week at their
peak.
</P>
<P>
   Recent independent polls show Gore and Bush with large leads in
the state, but McCain has been moving up, particularly among
independents and crossover Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   All the campaigns are planning to have their candidates in the
state during the coming two weeks, although specific details are up
in the air as each adjusts to his needs in shoring up efforts
around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Bush campaign has only a firm commitment from
the candidate to be in Los Angeles on Wednesday, with discussions
of other events in the first week of March.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has declined an invitation to debate McCain on March 2 in
Los Angeles, but is looking at other offers, spokeswoman Margita
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had seven different invitations and there will be a
California debate,'' Thompson said. ``We think we continue to have
strength in California and it will carry through to March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the effort is expected to be targeted to Republican
areas of the state, such as Orange County and the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley also are expected to vary their campaigns with
trips across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley recently completed a four-day campaign swing in
California, while Gore was in the state three days.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expected to return toward the end of the month,
wrapping appearances around their March 1 debate in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Confusing the California election this year is that voters can
cast a ballot for any candidate, regardless of political party.
However, only the votes of registered party members will be counted
to determine the delegates that will go to the national conventions
this summer to select the parties' nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of confusion is that the GOP has a
winner-take-all system, while Democratic delegates are assigned
proportionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think California will be watched as the bellwether of the
election,'' Kuwata said. ``While there will be a lot of attention
paid to the overall results, it will be Republicans electing a
Republican and Democrats electing a Democrat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
