<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TAP WINNING FORMULA, BEAT AVALANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Colorado Avalanche saw its crowd turn against the
team midway through Sunday's game. Boos cascading down from
everywhere, the Avs' five shots probably a big reason why.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we like to hear,'' Dallas Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of the Stars' theme song, to go along with their
philosophy of score early (which winger Scott Thornton did), don't
allow anything but dump-and-chase after (which they mostly didn't)
and get big saves from goalie Ed Belfour when needed (which they
did).
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and win a game that many will criticize as boring,
which the Stars also did, 2-1 against Colorado on Sunday at the
Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very entertaining, I'm sure for the fans,'' Stars
center Mike Modano said. ``It's not very exciting for people
watching on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily the way they want to play or would play if
they were healthy. But it's the way they've had to play because
they aren't. The story is the same as Game 4, Game 34 and Game 57,
just change the names on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Stars played without Jamie Langenbrunner (neck), Joe
Nieuwendyk (shoulder), Jere Lehtinen (ankle), Brian Skrudland
(chest) and Shawn Chambers (knee), but the team still sits atop the
Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what is really good for us is we've kept pace with the
rest of the NHL,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We've done it
mostly with `D.' ... We've struggled offensively all year, but
we've been great defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   They were again Sunday. They allowed the Avalanche four shots in
the first period, six in the second. And in the third period, when
Colorado unleashed a 14-shot barrage, Belfour turned them away. He
would've had his fourth shutout had it not been for Avs winger Alex
Tanguay's power-play goal with 10.7 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing worse is one second or a half,'' Belfour said.
``They got a whack at it in front and then another whack, and it
went in.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get the shutout. He did get the redemption for what he
considered a bad performance in Friday's 4-3 loss to Phoenix. That,
coupled with a chance to prevent Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy from
moving to second on the all-time regular-season win list, provided
Belfour with plenty of motivation.
</P>
<P>
   But Roy didn't dress because of a groin injury, and aside from a
couple of minutes, Belfour was never really challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas Stars hockey at its best,'' Matvichuk said.
</P>
<P>
   The goals were provided by Thornton, his first since being
traded to the Stars on Jan. 22, and Modano, his 10th goal in the
past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to finally get that first one out of the way,''
said Thornton, who attributes his increased scoring chances to
playing on a line with Brett Hull. ``He's been feeding me in the
last two games. I've got a lot of opportunities. I knew one was
going to go in sooner or later. That's what I kept telling him.
Odds are I'll score one of these days so keep passing it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's goal, which came at 10:50 of the first period, was
important because it let the Stars settle into their defensive
style. Modano's goal, which came at 11:44 of the third period, was
significant because it kept one of their most consistent offensive
threats hot, which is important because they can't seem to score
more than two goals a game. And while Modano admits the
zero-to-no-risk style might not be very exciting for the TV
audience, not to mention Sunday's Avalanche crowd, he certainly
isn't apologizing.
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado defenseman Aaron Miller said there where ``times
where the fans were falling asleep,'' it's exactly what the Stars
want to hear. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
