<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER SEES CAUSE FOR ALARM (CLOCK)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ From now until the end of the season, Dallas Stars
winger Jamie Langenbrunner will use the alarm clock test to see if
he's OK to play.
</P>
<P>
   If he wakes up and the herniated disc in his neck feels good
enough for him to play, he will. If it doesn't, he won't. Sunday,
he didn't. He missed his second consecutive game, but a myelogram
taken last week revealed that the disc is getting better and the
injury is an irritated nerve root.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the frustrating part,'' Langenbrunner said, ``because
you have to give it time, and time is not necessarily something we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   He missed 11 games in January and February with a disc injury,
but Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said the test showed that had
healed. Langenbrunner said he isn't considering surgery, which had
been mentioned as an option, but will probably have to put up with
the day-to-day status for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he expects Langenbrunner to play
Monday against Nashville. JUST IN CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Stars decided to dress seven defensemen and 11 forwards
Sunday, instead of the usual six and 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars weren't sure if captain Derian Hatcher, who was
playing in his second game after missing nine weeks with a
lacerated calf, would be able to play the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't afford for Derian to hit the wall and have us go
down to five guys against this group,'' Hitchcock said. ``In
talking with Derian, this is a tough time for him. The first game
he played on emotion. He's still a step-and-half or two steps
behind where he wants to be, and we felt we had to protect
ourselves.'' Hatcher played 20 minutes Sunday, third among the
Stars' defensemen. EXTRA, EXTRA
</P>
<P>
   Maybe nobody felt the bite of the decision to play a forward
short more than center Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   He was the forward getting double shifted.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up playing 25:14, more than any other Stars player and
only four seconds less than Colorado's Sandis Ozolinsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough place to do that with this altitude,'' Modano
said. ``You have to be smart about it. ... Sometimes, if I got out
there a little too long, I'd be sucking wind hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't effect him too much, though, as he scored a goal in
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we had a day off (Saturday),'' Ken Hitchcock joked.
DEFENDING THE CUP
</P>
<P>
   The Stars haven't had the best luck with travel this season.
</P>
<P>
   They've been flying by the seat of their pants to get planes
ever since the company they charter their flights with went
bankrupt earlier in the season. They're plane from Dallas to Denver
was late Saturday. They're plane from Denver to Nashville was late
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be like in (the movie) ``Major League,'' when they get
that bad plane with propellers,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor
joked.
</P>
<P>
   Or the other end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   When their charter plane got stuck in the Northeast because of
weather Saturday, the charter company sent presidential hopeful
George W. Bush's plane to take the team to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Stars notice a difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's late like the rest of them,'' Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
