<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3340 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX     02-21 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: What Bush Lost in South Carolina
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush's big win in South Carolina revived his candidacy
but at the cost of the inclusive campaign that had been the high
promise of his early run for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   One of the appeals of the Bush candidacy to defeat-fatigued
Republicans and to the general electorate alike had been the
governor's proven ability in Texas to draw Hispanic and even some
African-American voters to a party estranged from both.
</P>
<P>
   But to pull South Carolina out, Bush, like a troubled machine
defaulting to its zero setting, lapsed to the race hustle GOP
presidential nominees have frequently resorted to since Richard
Nixon's so-called ``southern strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reintroduced himself to South Carolina, post New Hampshire,
with a much-ballyhooed speech at Bob Jones University, a racist
school that into the bargain also harbors sometimes a virulent
anti-Catholicism. Atop his waffling on the state's Confederate
battle flag issue, the meaning was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was following in what has become a disturbing tradition
among Republican presidential aspirants.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon co-opted Alabama Gov. George Wallace's white-backlash
politics by, among other mimicking positions, opposing the busing
that was the only means for desegregation in many school districts.
Nixon skipped Wallace's overt racial demagoguery, but the message
got through.
</P>
<P>
   To kick off his successful presidential candidacy, Ronald
Reagan, who had opposed every civil rights law in its time, went to
a Mississippi county infamous for Klan activity, where three civil
rights workers had been murdered, and declared for states' rights.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush was elected president behind the TV-ad specter of
recidivist convict Willie Horton, an implied charge that hapless
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis would turn violent black men
loose on nice white people.
</P>
<P>
   The only failed GOP presidential campaigns since Nixon have been
ones that didn't work the race angle _ Gerald Ford's, Bush's second
and Bob Dole's.
</P>
<P>
   (At least George W. shunned invitations to denounce immigration
and, for the record, John McCain wasn't exactly clean. He took a
dive on the flag issue, too, and one of his top advisers edits a
magazine, Southern Partisan, that trades in Old South stereotypes,
Confederacy nostalgia and faux scholarship of the sort that argues
slavery was mainly a happy bond between benign masters and
grateful, uh, workers.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this connects to dubious performances in recent
Republican Congresses. The GOP Senate has rejected black and
Hispanic judicial nominees at twice the rate of whites. And the
House leadership recently passed over a bipartisan task force's
preferred candidate for chaplain, a Catholic priest_ he would have
been the first _ for still another Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Bush at first seemed to understand that national leadership
these days requires a broader embrace. He will have a difficult
time after South Carolina seeming anything better than merely
unctuous in such claims.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 0935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
