<HEADLINE>
ATTN. EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe offers a look at the latest in developments
for the automotive consumer, including information on new
technology and gadgets that are improving the operation and safety
of motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-SHOPPING (Undated) _ These are heady times to be a seller
of cars. They are selling in record numbers. But they are also
heady times to be buyers of cars. That is because today's vehicles
are more exciting, more dependable, safer and more imaginatively
designed than ever. By Royal Ford. 1675 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-SMALL (Undated) _ Looking for a car that's big enough for
family and friends but won't break the budget? This is your year.
By Jerry Morris. 945 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-WAIT (Undated) _ While some models being shown now are
brand new and offer innovative features, others are redesigns of
existing models with better features. By Jerry Morris. 1150 worsd.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-GADGETS (Boston) _ More and more gadgets, especially
navigation devices, are showing up on vehicles. By Jerry Morris.
1420 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-USED (East Providence, R.I.) _ Here's something to keep in
mind when you're checking out the new cars. While your mind is on
what you'd like to drive out of the lot, the used car manager is
more interested in the wheels you'll be leaving behind. By Bill
Griffith. 1260 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-LOOKING (Undated) _ It hits me every year at this time. Do
I need a new car? Not really. So why look? Because that's me. By
Bill Griffith. 1360 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-NOTES (Undated) _ Buick has a tiger by the tail; Buick's
new SUV; Ford Ranger has two mini-doors. By Bill Griffith. 1070
words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the  &UR; Lifestyle  &LR; (l) and  &UR; Financial  &LR; (f)
category codes.
</P>
