<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-LOOKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAR BUFF SIZES UP THE 2000 MODELS, Z TO A 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens every February.
</P>
<P>
   The roads are sloppy, the cars are filthy.
</P>
<P>
   You brush against a fender in the parking lot and your coat is
covered with road grime.
</P>
<P>
   You open your car's door, cringe at the accumulated salt and
sand on the mats, and wonder if you'll ever get it truly clean when
spring finally arrives.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the New Car Genie sneaks out of some crevice in your
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't hurt just to look. You don't have to buy a new car.
Maybe you'll walk through the showrooms, see all the shiny new cars
and walk back outside and this car will look like a carriage
instead of a pumpkin,'' says the little voice.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   It hits me every year at this time. Do I need a new car? Not
really. I'm driving a 1997 model that runs well, performs well, has
low mileage and hasn't had to be repaired once other than regularly
scheduled maintenance. So why look?
</P>
<P>
   Because that's me.
</P>
<P>
   My kids are grown up. I don't have extravagant tastes. And I
really enjoy driving a nice car. And looking is fun. If that makes
me a voyeur of Voyagers, so be it. It doesn't cost a whole lot and
provides me with days of entertainment. From A (as-in-Acura) to V
(as-in-Volvo), you show me the dealership, and there's something
inside I'd like to see and drive. What follows is by no means a
list of the best-selling or most popular cars, just the one model
I'd look at first at each dealership.
</P>
<P>
   We could take this from the top, but I was in the military and
had a drill sergeant who always ran the alphabet in reverse, so,
even though it isn't Veterans Day, let's work backwards in his
memory.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO _ Our eyes are on the 40 series. The S (sedan) and V
(wagon) models are ``entry-level'' Volvos. Our auto friends from
Sweden see what Camry and Accord have done and want a piece of that
mid-price marketplace. Of course, summer is coming (eventually), so
we'll take a peek at the C70 convertible on our way out.
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN _ The Beetle is hard to overlook, as is the
Cabriolet. But the well-optioned Passat, with a V6 and great
handling, is what we'll checkout. It might be the one to put some
sizzle back in your driving.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA _ You already know about the Camry, Avalon, Tundra and
RAV4, don't you? This month, we want to see the new Celica. It's
not a Supra, but this car looks promising. Besides, I have to see
if there's enough headroom to sit in it with a sunroof. And, are
you ready for a six-speed manual transmission?
</P>
<P>
   SUZUKI _ A much-begrimed Grand Vitara SUV with a V6 marched me
up two hills covered by 6 inches of unplowed snow and ice to my
house in the middle of January's biggest storm. It isn't generally
rated at the top of its class, but it earned a place in my heart.
I'd like to look at one that's showroom clean.
</P>
<P>
   SUBARU _ One of my favorite stops. On this trip, we want to
check out the Outback Limited Sedan. It looks like a nice mid-sized
sedan, but under the sheet metal is the all-wheel drive that will
take you any place you reasonably want to go. A vastly
underappreciated vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   SATURN _ We owe it to ourselves to check out the new mid-size L
series. The question is simple: Do you get enough car for what you
save in price? The answer may be yes.
</P>
<P>
   SAAB _ Gotta see the hot rods. The 9-3 Viggen and the 9-5 Aero.
You want torque? They've got torque.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC _ A friend-of-a-friend came home with a new Bonneville
SSEI. It's big, a bit pricey, but I wanted to beg for the keys.
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE _ I get the shakes every time I walk into a store where
there isn't anything for sale under $40,000. But isn't that Boxster
about the neatest thing you see on the road?
</P>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH _ Daniels LeSaffre Motors in Melrose always was a
regular stop. Plymouth's nameplate is on the way out, but we'll
still drop in to see the Chryslers.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE _ The marque always has stood for class, and we're
going to check out the entry-level Alero. On the road, they never
fail to catch my eye. This is a chance to see one up close. The
Aurora has always been a favorite, but a new design is coming by
summer.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN _ How can a company that makes such great cars (and which
sell so well in New England) have such financial problems
elsewhere? The new Maxima is worth a look, but we're going to check
out the updated Altima and see if it's a hidden jewel.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI _ Get me to an Eclipse. It's no longer just a kids'
car. The turbo will be missed, but this is a great design with a
solid V6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   MERCURY _ Let's test-drive a no-longer-ovalized Sable. I
apparently was one of the few who wasn't bothered by the
Taurus/Sable Oval Era. The Sable's adjustable pedals are a bit of
future shock.
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES _ The sticker shakes are back. So let's go right to the
top and check out the $85,000 CL500. The absolute state of the art,
top of the line. Besides, if you grip the wheel tightly enough, the
shakes go away.
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA _ I want to revisit the Protege ES, one of those cars that
always has felt ``right.'' A great blend of price, economy, and
performance.
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN _ A Lincoln with a 5-speed manual? This I've got to see.
</P>
<P>
   LEXUS _ Risking another case of the shakes, I've always wanted
to drive a GS 300 or GS 400.
</P>
<P>
   LAND ROVER _ What the heck. Let's drive the Range Rover _ at
nearly $60,000, it's as unique in its own way as a Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   KIA _ The Sportage is a low-budget SUV with sensational looks
covering an economy vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   JEEP _ A good time to revisit the Cherokee, in many ways the
father of all SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   JAGUAR _ I'm almost afraid to stop here (Mrs. G loves Jags). But
the new S-type is to love.
</P>
<P>
   IZUZU _ Remember those Amigo ads last year? They left a lasting
impression.
</P>
<P>
   INFINITI _ The new I30 is on my list for its looks. It probably
will stay there for its performance.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI _ A must stop. The funky Tiburon is a low-cost sports
car. I love it, even though it's built for short- to medium-sized
folks (and I don't qualify for those categories).
</P>
<P>
   HONDA _ I want to check out both the hybrid gas-electric Insight
and S2000, but, even if they're not in stock, revisiting the Accord
is always worth a stop.
</P>
<P>
   GMC _ Time to think big. I once owned (and loved) a Suburban.
Now the GMC version is the Yukon XL. (Does that mean extra long?)
</P>
<P>
   FORD _ This is truck and SUV city, but our tour is aiming
smaller _ at the new Focus. Small money, small car, and we want to
check out the package. With everyone else buying big, sometimes
it's nice to look in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   DODGE _ The Caravan and Grand Caravan. Even without kids in the
family, these remain prime people-movers. A young couple of our
acquaintance just bought a bright red one for weekend excursions
and mountain-bike transporting.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO _ The Lanos. At under $9,000, it's a basic car _ and it's
got to be checked out.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER _ Great designs across the board, but we're headed for
the 300M and hopefully a road test.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET _ People are buying Malibus and liking them. It's a
good month to check out what the excitement is about.
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC _ The new DeVille DTS. Technology meets luxury meets
big sedan.
</P>
<P>
   BUICK _ Have to see how the Park Avenue compares to the
Cadillacs.
</P>
<P>
   BMW _ The X5, BMW's all-new SUV, is expensive ($49,400). They've
managed to make it look _ and perform _ like a pure BMW. How? Don't
question. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   AUDI _ The A4 Quattro. A great blend of value and performance
with either the 1.8-turbocharged, 4-cylinder or 2.8-liter V6
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ACURA _ This trip winds up with a car I'd buy _ the 3.2 TL.
Another car that does everything right. At $28,000 (with only a
Navigation system as an option), it's a great value to boot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1049EST &QL; 
