<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-GADGETS-BOS &LR;      02-21 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-GADGETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATE AND TELECOMMUNICATE FROM THE COMFORT OF YOUR CAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ I'm driving an Acura RL with a dash mounted navigation
system. From Chatham, I program it to go to Boston, or more
precisely to The Boston Globe, and it does so flawlessly, always
keeping me informed as to how much further I have to travel and any
turns I must make . . . that is, until I decide to get off I-93 one
exit earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the woman's voice that gives the directions senses that
I am about to do it my way, and get off at Exit 14 instead of Exit
15. Suddenly the voice announces ``Stay on 93.'' I don't, and
instead of reprimanding me, the system suddenly recalculates the
route, noting I am already on Morrissey Boulevard and takes me
right to the front door of the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation systems are showing up on more and more vehicles, but
such toys are expensive _ around $2,000 _ and while I like them and
find they can be useful, they're still not ready for prime time
driving. In cities like Boston, they can get you around, but you
must know the territory. Yes, the Globe is in Boston but I had to
program it for Dorchester, the section of the city where the
building is located. This navigation system doesn't know all of the
streets. For Chatham, I programmed it to start from a house near
where I live and it did give me the option to head to the town
hall. When I head to Woonsocket, R.I., it knows the street where
I'm going, but no house numbers. Heading to Uxbridge, it knew where
the town center was, but not where the house we were heading to was
located.
</P>
<P>
   One nifty device is OnStar. Of course, you have to buy a GM
vehicle to get one. Onstar, which is linked to a cell phone, also
uses global navigation to assist you, but here you have a real
person who can not only locate where you are, but help you if you
get lost or are in an accident. Better still, if you should be in
an accident and the air bags deploy, the system automatically seeks
help. GM is smartly packaging it with many models, but you'll still
have to pay a monthly service charge. Call it insurance. It's also
good in helping you find hotels, restaurants, gas stations, and
other places.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz offers StarTAC, the first fully integrated digital
cellular phone system in a car. Among its features are a
multi-function dashboard and steering wheel control, allowing
drivers to keep their hands on the wheel and eyes on the road;
integrated radio system that mutes the sound while on the phone and
can also pause the CD or cassette player, and voice recognition
capabilities. It is also portable so it can go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes has also expanded the use of its TeleAid system to most
of its models. The system, like OnStar, provides both convenience
and emergency information at the touch of a button. It uses Global
Positioning to aid in locating the vehicle, should you become lost
or in an accident. TeleAid also provides drivers with a real person
to help them with vehicle questions.
</P>
<P>
   Voice recognition controls are an option on the new Jaquar
S-Type. The driver can just speak to use the cell phone, control
the temperature or the navigation system of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's new Seville has a radio that also offers e-mail,
stock quotes, and traffic information. Should a traffic alert
occur, the radio will broadcast it even if the CD is playing. If
you don't know where to find traffic information on the dial, the
radio will do it at the touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   If having Internet access while driving is in your plans,
perhaps you should hold off for a while. Ford, GM and
DaimlerChrysler are all working to put e-mail availability in
vehicles. Ford and GM are working on voice recognition systems
that, when you say ``get e-mail'' or ``read e-mail,'' will deliver.
DaimlerChrysler plans a ``bring your own laptop'' approach and is
designing a system that includes a small screen, microphone and
cellular phone modem in its vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision technology is another Cadillac feature that is
found on the new DeVille. With the system, potential safety hazards
out of range of the car's headlights, are illuminated on the
windshield in front of the driver. The system not only allows the
driver to see three to five times farther than the range of their
low-beam headlights, but also helps reduce the glare of oncoming
headlights.
</P>
<P>
   The new Volvo S40 comes with an optional front-seat laptop
computer table. The very safety conscientious Volvo posts a warning
that the table should only be used when the car is parked.
</P>
<P>
   Already available on General Motors and other minivans are
entertainment systems allowing the gang in the back to watch
videos, play Nintendo or listen to their own music.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort is also being upgraded. Many models now offer dual-zone
climate controls to keep both the driver and front-seat passenger
comfortable. The Jeep Grand Cherokee Limited goes one step farther
by using an infrared sensor to detect the skin temperature of the
riders in the front seat to keep them at precisely the right level
programmed into the system.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up in the 2001 Lexus LS 430 will be a system that allows
rear passengers to also select their own temperature setting. And,
the 2001 DamilerChrysler minivans will offer three separate
temperature zones, one for each row of seats.
</P>
<P>
   Heated front seats are found in many makes, but a few, including
Saab and the Cadillac Catera, also offer rear passengers heated
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Seats are key to driving safety, if you're not comfortable
seated behind the wheel, you could tire easily. If your vehicle is
used by others, getting one with power seats that can be set for
each individual driver is a handy feature. Many vehicles offer
lumbar supports that certainly could help your back on a long
drive. Cadillac even has a seat that gives a massage as you drive.
</P>
<P>
   Saab has an extra option ventilated seat for those hot sticky
days, and its also heated for colder times..
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Navigator has a climate-controlled seat as an
option. The seat has a fan that directs ambient air to two ceramic
thermoelectric devices located in the seat's back and cushions,
which then release or absorb heat, depending on the flow of
electric current to them. The warm or cool air is directed through
perforations in the seat upholstery. There are five different
heating and cooling settings.
</P>
<P>
   Other niceties being found on 2000 models include the storage
bin found on the roof of the Nissan Xterra. It is self draining so
you can throw those muddy hiking boots up there. The Xterra has lot
of other neat storage ideas, including an inside bike rack. The
Ford Taurus and Mercury Stable have trunk hooks to hang those
plastic grocery bags, no more loose cans rolling around in the
trunk. The Pontiac Bonneville SSEi comes with an emergency package
with rain suit, first-aid kit, gloves, light, and an air hose to
pump air into low tires.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon, has a smart gauge to read the fuel supply. No more
guessing how much is left in the tank, the gauge continuously reads
the fuel-tank float level every six seconds, comparing it with
stored historical data to calculate a ``real-time'' reading for the
gauge to give a more accurate assessment of the fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
   Some cars come with automatic gauges to read the tire pressure,
warning the driver if a tire has low pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz now has a sensor in the oil pump that analyzes oil
for impurities such as water, fuel, and metal. It sends its
information to the car's Flexible Service system which then decides
when to flag the driver. With this, Mercedes says, some drivers may
only have to change their oil every 20,000 miles. Not bad, but
better still is Mercede's free maintenance during its
four-year/50,000-mile warranty. That cuts ownership costs even
more.
</P>
<P>
   With the price of gasoline skyrocketing these days, Cadillac is
giving buyers of its high-performance Northstar V-8 engine equipped
vehicles a bonus _ it now runs on regular gasoline instead of the
high-priced 93 octane. Even Cadillac owners can appreciate the
savings of 20 to 30 cents or more a gallon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
