<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to car-wreck TV
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Some television shows possess the simple
hypnotic drawing power of a bad car wreck. People see something
horrible happening to other people and yet they can't look away.
Even people who possess good intentions, love for humanity and
average decency cannot fail to slow down and point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' is car-wreck
television.
</P>
<P>
   About 22 million people dropped the remote to see this
high-stakes ``Dating Game.'' A third of all women under 35 who were
watching television that night watched the nuptials. The show's Web
site
</P>
<P>
   crashed under the traffic from women who want to be on the next
installment. (Or maybe the Web site just crashed because Web sites
do that all the time. Publicists used to say their switchboards
``lighted up like a Christmas tree,'' but that's yesterday's
viewer-response cliche.)
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the show is summed up in the title. About 50
women were considered for the wife job. The multimillionaire,
without the aid of a human resources department, pared their number
to 10, then five. The winner, a nurse from California _ who
presumably had failed to find an anesthesiologist to marry the
old-fashioned way _ was awarded the prize of getting married on
</P>
<P>
   national television.
</P>
<P>
   It was a true ``Truman Show'' moment, when real life, palpable
greed, show biz and media blend in one metal-twisting pile up. But
will this story really conclude with a Vegas minister and closing
credits?
</P>
<P>
   One might hope, but be real. This is a cultural phenomenon. As I
write this, the tabloids have airlifted reporters around the world
to pick up where this story left off. If the happy couple have
their act together _ something I would in no way presume _ they
already have retained an agent. Book and movie rights and maybe a
product endorsement or two should be tied up before they set foot
in the honeymoon suite. Those whom television game-show producers
have joined together, let no man sunder from royalties.
</P>
<P>
   But the happy couple also needs time. It takes most couples some
time together before they get a sense of whether their life
partnership is going to be a situation comedy, a gripping family
drama, a hokey soap opera, a dark mystery in which everyone is a
suspect, or just another blues number played late at night from a
plywood stage in a dark and smoky barroom.
</P>
<P>
   If things don't work out, the couple might go before a TV judge
and let the television audience interactively divide their
properties. A Web site poll could decide who drives away in the BMW
and who gets to keep the set of Dale Earnhardt coffee mugs.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the beginning of a whole media-convergent life. A
Web site could record their domestic life with a 24-hour Web-cam.
Their ghost-written book could give a heartwarming account of their
secrets for a successful marriage. Then, after the book tour and
paperback editions run their course, they would be followed by a
dark tell-all account of lives gone horribly wrong. After rehab,
there's a career in motivational speaking to encourage people to
get their lives together, too.
</P>
<P>
   Should something unfortunate happen along the way, the funeral
could be pay-for-view and Judge Judy could do the probate.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, imitators have already whipped out their cell phones
and are packaging deals for cheap knock-offs that lack the dignity
and class of the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Zeroaire Who is Living with His Momma and
Leaves his Laundry on the Floor'' could be produced for a fraction
of the cost. It would be like Jerry Springer, only legally binding.
Have your people call my people.
</P>
<P>
   I would offer my own services for ``Who Wants to Marry a
Divorced Hundredaire with Two Smart-Mouthed Teen-aged Kids and an
Ugly Dog'' but the Web site taking offers crashed under the
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there is such a thing as car-wreck TV too gruesome to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Is marriage a game show? Should poor ratings be legally
recognized grounds for divorce? In the brave new world of media
convergence, these questions must be answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire'' is only an early
symptom of what's ahead. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
