<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0222-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Does civil disobedience equal good citizenship?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Don't you occasionally wonder what some folks
are usingfor walking-around sense? And aren't you particularly
annoyed when it's those very same folks who are making decisions
that affect all the rest of us who weren't invited to be on the
committee?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's state board of education has been meeting in Columbus to
review a list of what educators believe high school seniors need to
know in order to pass a 12th-grade proficiency test. Proposed
questions in the citizenship section of this test would require
students to ``illustrate how the evolution of democratic principles
(e.g., civil rights widening franchise) can occur through civil
disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Civil disobedience'' is defined as a ``refusal to obey
governmental demands or commands, especially as a nonviolent and
usually collective means of forcing concessions from the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   And the problem is: One board member, a conservative writer and
lecturer from a Dayton suburb, has nixed any question about civil
disobedience on the test because the words in themselves are, as
she reads them,
</P>
<P>
   ``inflammatory language.''
</P>
<P>
   Right away, I'm thinking if that's the case then we probably
ought to deep-six the Ten Commandments too; they're loaded with
inflammatory language. All that killing and coveting. My oh my.
</P>
<P>
   Then I'm reminded of a faded photograph of my grandmother, chin
set and petticoat hanging down below her hem, marching down the
street with a bunch of other matrons, demanding that women be
allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Civil disobedience? You betcha!
</P>
<P>
   The board member, obviously on a _ Duh _ roll, asks two
questions: `` Civil disobedience is now regarded as good
citizenship?'' and, ``Are we trying to promote civil
disobedience?''
</P>
<P>
   Good grief.
</P>
<P>
   The answers are simple. Yes. No.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Civil disobedience is occurring when a bunch of folks
exercise their legal right to gather and non-violently protest
drinking fountains that come in pairs labeled: White Only, and
Colored Only, and buses that demand equal fares but admonish:
Colored Seat from Rear.
</P>
<P>
   Civil disobedience is what kick-started this country into
existence. If some of our ancestors hadn't seen fit to protest
taxation without representation, we'd still be rolled back on our
complacent haunches, sending part of our
</P>
<P>
   paychecks to England to keep the Queen in silly hats.
</P>
<P>
   And no. Although I'm not privy to a copy of the proposed
proficiency questions, I'd bet my new shoes that not one of them
urges teens to get out there and bust up a storefront as a
prerequisite for graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The esteemed board member is obviously confusing civil
disobedience with criminal acts, and although it may be a little
obscure to her, most 12th-graders will figure it out _ no sweat.
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell's ``1984'' remains the most terrifying book I have
ever read. I hated teaching it to high schoolers _ but I did. They
had to know what happens to a society that gives over its will to
the government in exchange for the
</P>
<P>
   guarantee of a mindless existence. They had to experience the
feeling of being a cipher where ``Big Brother'' watched their every
move. They had to learn the fate of independent thinkers in such a
world.
</P>
<P>
   The board member, not to be dissuaded by her colleagues, insists
that civil disobedience is ``...the antithesis of our way of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it a rest, lady. Anyone who ever paid attention in history
class knows that civil disobedience, in its true sense, is the very
basis of our government and if it hadn't been for my grandmother
and her civil disobedience, you'd
</P>
<P>
   still be in the suburbs dusting figurines.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
