<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOOSEXY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sex-drenched imagery is recipe for shattered lives
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Sunday's Waco Tribune-Herald.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Is Britney Spears too sexy too soon?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The question is asked on the cover of the Feb. 14 People
magazine. The answer is self-evident in the work and wardrobe _
like a V-neck down to the belly button at the American Music Awards
_ of the just-now-18-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Spears has it all _ a voice, a personality, a spark. She can
sing like a bird, dance like Solid Gold. She's a nice person from
every indication. She's also a legal Why advise her on how
to comport herself?
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that someone can come to realize and address
influences that commonly cause misery.
</P>
<P>
   She would be a wonderful role model to have except for clothes
that send many parents into conniption and chosen lyrics that would
make a peep-show barker blush.
</P>
<P>
   At this point someone asks the Charles Barkley question: Me a
role model? For better of worse, Britney Spears is. It could be for
better.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we want it or not, young people are watching, are
modeling.
</P>
<P>
   There's absolutely no reason to single out Spears as the root of
any evil. She's just a symptom of times that seem to take many
youngsters on a fast lane to disaster. Particularly one worries
about little girls growing up with the feeling that sexy is of the
essence.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's on television or in the checkout line, where curvy,
low-cut cover girls pose with chests that might as well advertise,
``This place for rent,'' little girls are bombarded by a particular
conditioning. We shudder to think how the little boys are being
conditioned, but we can guess.
</P>
<P>
   Children grow up soon enough. It can be tragic when they fall
under the command of physical maturity that arrives before
emotional maturity does. That's why teen pregnancy and sexually
transmitted diseases are such major problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even parents who exercise the utmost discretion find their
efforts thwarted repeatedly during so-called family movies, during
off-the-wall TV teasers and whatever visual cues await at the
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Just the way of the world? Maybe. But it doesn't mean we have to
drink it all in without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears didn't ask to be the focal point of such a
debate, but she's it. And she could be an ally for the better.
She's got the smarts, the talent and, we think, the good heart to
say, ``Whoops, we've been overselling sexiness,'' and make the
world a better place by example. Whatever she does, little girls
and boys will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-ANNOY22-COX     02-21 0171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ANNOY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home intercoms make you want to scream
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We're all for improving family communications,
but sticking a home intercom system in every bedroom and paging the
family down for dinner wins our annoying gadget of the week award.
</P>
<P>
   Eschewing traditional foot-stair movement in favor of calling
people in your own house is not only lazy, it's usually accompanied
by a squawking burst of feedback caused by having the intercom
units placed too closely together. For centuries, families have
been held together by one common denominator that crosses all
racial, cultural and generational lines: really loud yelling. If
you want the kids to come downstairs for dinner, bang on the wall
and yell their names at high decibels.
</P>
<P>
   Inter-home primal-scream therapy has kept us sane for this long.
Don't let technology take away your right to scream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
