<HEADER>
A3389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-REPORT0222-C0X     02-21 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT0222-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't despair if you haven't seen the movie or read the book
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We are supposedly a nation too busy for anything but
work. Banks have become ATMs. Grocery stores stick prepared dinners
up front so workers can grab something quickly on the way home. Gas
stations let you pay at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   That's nice. But it's just toying with efficiency, really. If we
indeed are a harried nation, we should get serious about it.
</P>
<P>
   Movies, for example. Who has time to sit in the dark for two
hours? Why not get a nice summary so you can nod knowingly when the
latest trendy, independent film that sweeps the nation is talked
about at work?
</P>
<P>
   A Web site is here to help.
</P>
<P>
   www.rinkworks.com/movieaminute/ can trim the fat from your
leisure time; it will boil that latest plot down to a digestible
few sentences.
</P>
<P>
   As the promotional copy on the front of the Web site reads:
``Let's face it. There's a lot of movies out there and very little
time to watch them in. ... We've taken several classic and
contemporary movies and extracted the important stuff, cutting out
all the filler. (You'd be surprised how much filler there is
sometimes.) With our ultra-condensed versions of your favorite
films, you can experience whole movies in just one minute!''
</P>
<P>
   A movie such as last summer's ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a
horror flick about three people getting lost in the woods then
dying, was shot with a hand-held camera. It became infamous for
sending viewers speed-walking out of the theater, queasy from
motion sickness. The Web site reduces it to three tolerable
components:
</P>
<P>
   Actors: A twig! I'm scared!
</P>
<P>
   Audience: Get me some Dramamine.
</P>
<P>
   Actors: Thump.
</P>
<P>
   The end.
</P>
<P>
   More interested in the classics? How about ``It's a Wonderful
Life?'' The 1946 Frank Capra film is a holiday season staple. But
with shopping and wrapping and party-going, who has time to let
Jimmy Stewart figure out the meaning of life? The Web site helps by
reducing the story to the important points:
</P>
<P>
   James Stewart: I'm useless.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Travers: Don't say that. The happiness of the entire
universe depends on your existence.
</P>
<P>
   James Stewart: Hooray!
</P>
<P>
   The end.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``When Harry Met Sally,'' a film about two people
who annoy each other while falling in friendship before finally
falling in love.
</P>
<P>
   Sally: I hate you.
</P>
<P>
   Harry: That's your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sally: I think I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Harry: I might love you.
</P>
<P>
   Sally: I hate you.
</P>
<P>
   Harry: Please don't.
</P>
<P>
   Sally: I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Harry: I love you, too.
</P>
<P>
   The end.
</P>
<P>
   The idea works well for books, too. The folks at Rinkworks.com
reduce tedious and time-consuming classic literature and bedtime
stories to something to be enjoyed in a matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cat in the Hat,'' a Dr. Seuss classic about two kids and a
mischievous cat, has lots of rhyming words that can trip up a
reader. Thanks to the Web site, the essential elements are
presented rhyme-free.
ly and Me: We're bored.
</P>
<P>
   (The Cat in the Hat shows up and wrecks the entire house. He
cleans it up just before Mom gets home.)
</P>
<P>
   Sally and Me: Let us never speak of boredom again.
</P>
<P>
   The end.
</P>
<P>
   Adult stories fit the format as well. Already a short book,
Ernest Hemingway's ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' a story about an
old man's struggle to haul in a big fish, is reduced to a three
tight, symbolism-free sentences: An old man catches a fish that's
too big for his boat. The fish gets eaten by sharks. Then he goes
home and dies.
</P>
<P>
   Or take ``Moby Dick,'' another story of one man's (Captain Ahab)
obsession with a large fish. It's required reading for most
schoolkids. But with ESPN and MTV and Ricki Lake and Sega, who has
time?
</P>
<P>
   Ishmael: Call me Ishmael.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ahab: Crew, we will seek the white whale and kill it,
because I am insane.
</P>
<P>
   Crew: Alas, your destructive obsession will be our undoing.
</P>
<P>
   (They almost find the white whale. Then they almost find the
white whale. Then they find it.)
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ahab: I stab at thee. I stab at thee.
</P>
<P>
   (Everybody dies except Ishmael, although this is no surprise,
because it was foreshadowed CONTINUALLY from the BEGINNING.)
</P>
<P>
   The end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
