r l BC-TECHNOBUDDY22-COX     02-21 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inquiring minds eagerly cater to that box on the desk
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was once a time when I was a computer hobbyist.
My first computer came as a box of parts to be assembled _ an old
Altair that was as worthless as my most shiftless relative. But the
idea wasn't to use the computer to do work. Instead, it was enough
that rows of red lights flashed on its panel and there were toggle
switches to throw.
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, computers became more common and even
occasionally useful. By the time I was working as an advertising
copywriter, I wrote such masterpieces as ``Free Gift Inside'' using
a Macintosh computer. It was almost reliable and even encouraged my
laziness with cryptic error messages such as: ``Work session too
long, please quit.'' When that message appeared, I eagerly obeyed,
heading for the Mexican restaurant on the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone has a computer. And most of us are eager to do
right by them. We subscribe to computer magazines, watch computer
shows on television, buy books that openly call us dummies.
</P>
<P>
   We seem almost desperate to be well thought of by that box on
our desk.
</P>
<P>
   I often get e-mails from readers who worry about the darnedest
things, agonizing over questions that frankly don't much matter as
far as the health of the computer. But since the questions do
matter greatly as far as the mental health of the readers, let's
look at some useless computer questions. I'll tell you my own
answer to these subjective questions, but keep the good news in
mind. It really doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Should I turn off my computer or leave it on all the time? Turn
it on when you begin using it for the day and leave it on. When it
is time to go to sleep or leave for an extended period, turn it
off. It's true turning a computer on and off isn't good for a
computer, but the damage is slight and gradual. Turning it off when
you are away for extended periods protects the computer from big _
and much more harmful _ surges that happen when the power comes
back on.
</P>
<P>
   Which is better, an AMD or an Intel processor chip? I prefer the
Intel chip. But the AMD chip, especially its new Athlon, is an
excellent chip. It outperforms the Intel chip in many benchmark
tests. Both chips perform the same functions in much the same way.
But Intel is the standard, and most software is written
specifically for it. I doubt you'd ever have trouble with the
Athlon and _ if you prefer it _ that's fine. No big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Should I buy a Macintosh or a Windows PC? I use both and am
comforted by the fact neither is used to provide the computing
power for a heart/lung machine. If you use one or the other at
work, buy the same kind for use at home. If you don't use a
computer at work and don't have a personal preference, buy the kind
your most computer-savvy friend owns. That way, when you have
trouble _ and you will _ you'll know someone who can help.
</P>
<P>
   How powerful a computer do I need? Most computers for sale these
days are plenty powerful enough for word processing, e-mail and the
Web. If you play games, get the most powerful computer you can
afford. Games demand more from a computer than almost any other
task.
</P>
<P>
   Should I buy a brand-name computer, or is it OK to buy an
off-brand? The guts of a well-made off-brand computer (note the
well-made) are identical to the guts of a well-made brand-name
computer. What you are often paying for (besides the obvious markup
to pay for the advertising and marketing that created that brand
name) is the assurance of good technical support and customer
service. If you feel comfortable judging the merits of the parts
used in the off-brand computer and don't feel you need a lot of
hand-holding, it's safe to save the money. If you want hand-holding
and the assurance that comes with a brand name, buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Now you are free to worry about more important things, like how
you're going to pay for that new computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
