<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sites for Black History Month
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ Encyclopaedia Britannica: This collection from the
Encyclopaedia Britannica includes audio clips of Gwendolyn Brooks
reading one of her poems and Malcolm X talking about civil rights,
and links to 15 other sites, including the Amistad Research Center
and the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for Afro-American Research at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   blackhistory.eb.com/index2.html
</P>
<P>
   _ The African-American Mosaic: This is one of several resources
on black history at the Library of Congress. (Another is the
African-American Odyssey, at lcweb2.loc.gov/ammem/aaohtml.)
Highlights in Mosaic include photographs and historic documents
that help tell of events like the colonialization of Liberia by
free blacks in the early 1800s and the founding of places like
Nicodemus, Kan., one of the towns established by blacks after the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   lcweb.loc.gov/exhibits/african/intro.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Africana.com: This Web site's producers include the editors of
Microsoft's Encarta Africana, Harvard professors Henry Louis Gates
Jr. and Kwame Anthony Appiah. It is a full-fledged Web site _ with
chat rooms, news and the like _ and includes content from the
encyclopedia; it is not sponsored by Microsoft. It has a great
directory of links, and you can browse by subject and find anything
from the history of the Works Progress Administration to voodoo to
Charlie Parker to great sports figures. www.africana.com
</P>
<P>
   _ African-American women: Entering this site is like pulling
back the cover on an old family album: sepia-tone photographs
appear on a screen that looks like faded parchment. It's a great
place to appreciate the nuances and complicated language that was
used in the 19th century.
scriptorium.lib.duke.edu/collections/african-american
</P>
<P>
   -women.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Mathematicians of the African diaspora: Created by Scott
Williams, a mathematics professor at the University of Buffalo,
this site includes profiles of notable contemporary black
mathematicians, as well as a historical look at mathematics in
Africa. www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/mad0.html
</P>
<P>
   _ History challenge: This site is comprised of 11 profiles of
prominent 19th century black Americans. You can take three levels
of multiple-choice quizzes. The site doesn't simply tell you which
answers you got wrong and give you the correct answer; it tells you
where on the site you can read to discover the correct answer.
www.brightmoments.com/blackhistory
</P>
<P>
   _ Gale Group: This selection of about 80 short biographies for
children is on the Web site of the Gale Group reference publishing
company. The subjects include contemporary celebrities, like
Veronica Webb and Lauryn Hill, as well as the usual historic
subjects, like Frederick Douglass; offbeat figures, like the
science fiction writer Samuel Delaney; and people in the news, like
Louis Farrakhan. The site also has a link to a timeline of black
history, a quiz and links to 12 other black history and culture
sites. www.gale.com/schools/resrcs/blkhstry/bios.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ American slave narratives: In the mid-1930s, thousands of
former slaves were interviewed under the auspices of the WPA. This
Web site includes text and audio clips from 13 of them.
xroads.virginia.edu/(tilde)hyper/wpa/wpahome.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Afro-American history: While this site may not be as lacquered
as some of the others, it highlights interesting links. Click on
Black History Month and you will be led to early black communities
in Nova Scotia, for example, and books by black Canadians. Whether
you are interested in the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry or
a historical resource on the Gullah culture, this site can guide
you. www.aawc.com/aah.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Gateway to History: Created by the State Department's
International Information Programs, this has links to
bibliographies, archival and research sites, presidential speeches
and full-text versions of government reports, and articles on
topics like the Amistad revolt, the civil rights movement and
President Clinton's ``National Conversation on Race.'' A link is
also provided to the Association for the Study of Afro-American
Life and History.
</P>
<P>
   www.usia.gov/usa/blackhis
</P>
<P>
   POTPOURRI
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet investing _ after-hours trading: With all the
after-hours trading hoohah, one question remains unasked (until
now): When do these people sleep? For insomniac Wall Streeters,
there are links to brokers, extended-hours quotes and suggested
readings. www.internetinvesting.com/afterhours.htm
</P>
<P>
   _The Linux Show: Whether you're looking for news about the Linux
operating system or analysis of the tech industry and how it
affects the company, this site offers the most up-to-date
information. www.thelinuxshow.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Execu-Net: How hot is the market for your executive talent?
Execu-Net's Demand Index provides user-friendly charts for a
variety of executive functions. www.execunet.com/talentdemand.cfm
</P>
<P>
   _ Mortgage search: Let the AllMortgage search engine unleash its
software spiders to comb the Web for all sorts of info related to
home mortgages. Searchable by state. www.allmortgagesearch.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet tutorial: When it comes to answers about the Web,
this newbie tutorial from the University of California at Berkeley
starts with the basics (What is the Internet?), moving quickly to
the practical (How do I get connected to the Internet?). Text-heavy
but useful.
www.lib.berkeley.edu/TeachingLib/Guides/Internet/FindInfo.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Auction Prime: If you're spending so much time bidding at
online auctions that you need an electronic butler to keep track of
your transactions, maybe you ought to ease back on the throttle.
That said, Auction Prime offers auction management software to
track online sales that might interest you. www.auctionprime.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Master Developers: Developing a Web page can be a lonely,
frustrating task for those who don't do it for a living. This new
service offers tutorials, Web resources and interviews with
accomplished Web developers from sites including Google.com,
Harvard.edu, VW.com, SlashDot.org and Computing.net.
www.masterdevelopers.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Free agent: So you can't feel like Bret Favre on a football
field. But you can in the workplace. by becoming a ``free agent''
consultant, free-lancer or independent contractor. This site offers
a few suggestions about how to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   www.freeagent.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Bio-Jobs: Whether you're looking to cure the common cold or
just hold the beaker of the man or woman who will, Bio-Jobs offers
information and listings on biotechnology positions across the
country. www.bio-jobs.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Star stock: Stock market games are all the rage. This fantasy
game lets users ``buy'' and ``sell'' shares in their favorite TV
and movie stars, musicians, politicians and other celebrities.
While you're there, check out news about the stars.
</P>
<P>
   www.starstock.com/starstock
</P>
<P>
   _ Investor chat: This site provides free chat rooms, message
boards, e-mail and stock research for individual investors.
Subscribe to investing newsletters, visit the online bookstore,
why, there's even a list of recommended feature films about
investing! Talk about educational!
www.investorschat.com/?clicktrade &QC; 143249
</P>
<P>
   _ Best cowboy: Need some cattle rounded up? Some horses shod?
Best Cowboy Enterprises, an Idaho company, stands ready to provide
``professional cowboy services for the Northwest U.S.'' Services
range from ``cattle and horse marketing'' to something called
``cowboy day work.'' www.bestcowboy.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
