</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the Oscar Jr. goes to...
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Tom Hanks, Tom Cruise and Bruce Willis. Hollywood's
hottest leading man is a 13 1/2-inch tall, gold-plated guy named
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   He's an Academy Award. Since 1927, the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences _ a group of more than 6,000 movie industry
people _ has given him to the year's best movies, actors and
actresses, among other categories. ``Oscar'' is actually his
nickname. It was given by Bette Davis, one of the most popular
stars in the history of movies. Supposedly, she thought the skinny,
bald statue looked like her husband!
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars almost always go to grown-up actors and serious,
grown-up movies. But this year might be different _ a kid is in the
running to win an award! He's 11-year-old Haley Joel Osment. He's
nominated in the Best Supporting Actor category for his part in
``The Sixth Sense,'' a very scary movie. (Maybe some of our older
readers saw it _ it's rated PG-13.)
</P>
<P>
   If you were giving out Oscars, what would be your choices? Would
``Stuart Little'' be best movie? Would you give a best actor Oscar
to Jake Lloyd, who played Anakin Skywalker in ``Star Wars: Episode
1 _ The Phantom Menace?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth year we've asked Georgia kids to award
``Oscar Juniors'' to the movies they liked the most. This year,
we've thought up a few new categories: Who was the coolest cartoon
hero of 1999? What was the scariest scene? Who was the silliest
grown-up?
</P>
<P>
   We've included a list of nominations here. It's easy to vote _
you can even do it over the phone or on your computer. Just call
404-222-2062 and follow the instructions. Or you can log on to
www.ajc.com and follow the directions there. You can even mark your
choices on this page and mail it to us at Oscar Jrs., P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The deadline to vote is 5 p.m. Feb. 28.
We'll award the Oscar Juniors on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   THE BALLOT BOX
</P>
