<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From slave to entrepreneur _ Atlanta's first black millionaire
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alonzo Herndon is one of the greatest success stories
in the history of Atlanta. He started life as a slave, but grew up
to become a wealthy businessman _ the city's first African-American
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Herndon was born in 1858 on a plantation near Social Circle, 40
miles east of Atlanta. The Civil War soon broke out and all the
slaves were freed. Herndon's mother decided to stay in the area and
keep doing farm work. Her son didn't like farm work. He wanted more
out of life.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 20, Herndon left home with $11 in his pocket and
started walking toward Atlanta. ``I knew my mother would never
consent to my leaving the farm,'' he later wrote, ``so I took my
little hand trunk on my shoulder and stole silently away in the
darkness of night.''
</P>
<P>
   Herndon found a job as a barber's apprentice and learned how to
cut hair. He worked in several shops around downtown Atlanta.
Customers liked him and followed him wherever he took his clippers.
In 1902, he opened his own establishment on Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   Herndon's was one of the biggest and fanciest barbershops in the
United States. There were 25 chairs sitting atop marble floors and
mirrors down both walls. You could get a shave, a shower and a
massage. The owner's name was etched in gold letters above the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Herndon used his earnings to launch a new company that sold
insurance to African-Americans. He built the Atlanta Life Insurance
Co. into one of the largest black-owned businesses in the South. He
became a rich man.
</P>
<P>
   The Herndon family erected a mansion near what is now the
Atlanta University Center and filled it with fine furniture. They
hosted music and drama recitals. They traveled to Europe and
brought back beautiful art. At a time when many white people
believed their race was superior, the Herndons were living proof
that people of color could be as cultured as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Herndon died in 1927, but his legacy lives on. He gave
much of his fortune to the Herndon Foundation, an organization that
grants money to good causes. His company, Atlanta Life, remains a
thriving business. Herndon Stadium, the Herndon Homes housing
project and Herndon Elementary are all named for him.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to learn about Alonzo Herndon is the Herndon Home
museum, near the Atlanta University Center. Herndon and his wife,
Adrienne, a teacher at the university, designed and built the house
in 1910. Their only child, Norris, lived there until his death in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the mural paintings on the living room walls. They
depict Herndon's life, starting with a scene of young Alonzo
standing in a field with a hoe in his hand. Herndon was proud of
where he came from, proud of his success, proud of his race.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
