r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX     02-21 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceAUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Charles Schulz's family?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jane Bayles
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Schulz's family in care of United Features
Syndicate, 200 Madison Ave., New York, N.Y. 10016
</P>
<P>
   Q: I used to buy extra-long double bed sheets from the Sears
catalog, but that is discontinued. I really need to find some place
to buy these _ mine are thin as paper. _ J. Linton
</P>
<P>
   A: Order extra-long double sheets from Tall Paul's Tall Mall
(OK, he's into rhyme) at (802) 223-4915. Owner Paul Hartmann is
6-foot-11 himself. The Vermont retailer also stocks extra-long king
or queen sheets as well as Adirondack chairs with deep seats and
higher backs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This past week I saw a novelty dispenser I wish to obtain.
Dilbert is sitting at a computer console, tie askew and all.M&AMP;M
candies are loaded into the rear of the screen. It appeared that as
the mouse was touched, M&AMP;Ms were dispensed. Can you help? _ Sammy
H. Claiborne
</P>
<P>
   A: The Dilbert M&AMP;M dispenser ($14.99 plus shipping and handling
and tax) is available online at www.umstore.com or by phone at
(888) 221-3397 (item number 12058). Chocolate and a smile will help
you through any workday.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We watched the ``MacGyver'' series, also the ``Equalizer''
series, now discontinued. May we please have the ages of both men,
and what they are doing now? Any other info on both men would be
appreciated! _Betty Taylor
</P>
<P>
   A: Good taste in television heroes. Richard Dean Anderson, Angus
MacGyver from 1985-1992, just turned 50. He performed as a mime,
played in bands and played hockey before he turned to acting.
Anderson has a daughter with current girlfriend, Apryl Prose. His
most recent project was 1997's ``Stargate SG-1.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Equalizer,'' played by Edward Woodward (not his real name
or his name in the series), was born in Croydon, Surrey, England,
and is rapidly approaching 70. (Great accent!) His most recent
project was starring in television's ``C15: The New Professionals''
(1998). He has three children, Tim, Pete and Sarah, with his wife,
Michele Dotrice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a wooden cabinet that contains books, encyclopedias,
maps, photos and a lot of paper. Every time I open it, I smell
mildew. How can I get rid of the mold and smell without having to
discard the books? _ Olga Salas
</P>
<P>
   A: Wood cabinets are not the best place to store such items.
Take all the books and papers out and wipe the cabinet down with a
weak bleach solution (nine parts water, one part bleach). The books
need circulating air to prevent mold and mildew. Take the books
outside and wipe them off with a soft cloth or vacuum them. When
the cabinet is dry, reshelve the books and see if you have
forestalled the mildew. If not, consider removing the cabinet
doors. That's the advice of Christine Wiseman at SoliNET,
Southeastern Library Network. Need to read more? Get a free copy of
``Attack of the Giant Spore'' from Solinet by calling (800)
999-8558 or write 1438 W. Peachtree Road, Suite 200, Atlanta, Ga.
30309.
</P>
<P>
   One more paper storage tip: Place ``micro chamber'' paper from
Conservation Resources International at (800) 634-6932 between maps
and so on to protect paper from moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you please settle something for me and hubby? How do
the lawyer TV shows work? When someone loses a lawsuit, does the
person who loses pay or does the show pay? Just curious since there
are so many on now, and I watch them all.
</P>
<P>
   _Pat D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Two of the entertaining judgment shows (``Judge Judy'' and
``Judge Joe Brown'') confirmed the judgment amount is paid by the
show. A spokesperson for Brown's show says both parties receive a
$100 fee for being on the show in addition to travel expenses. Not
a bad deal _ if you don't mind airing a grievance in front of
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last time my husband and I did not get in the census. How do
I get my name entered into the census along with my husband and any
other family members? _Mary Anderson
</P>
<P>
   A: Census day is April 1. According to officials, wait until
your neighbors receive forms in mid-March (everyone should receive
bar-coded census forms). As a last resort, ``be counted'' sites
will be set up where you can pick up blank forms (locations to be
announced).
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Need motivation to not clean a room? Ace Hardware's America's
Messiest Room Contest. Grand prize? A room makeover by a
professional and organizing supplies worth up to $5,000 and a
$5,000 Ace gift certificate. Your messy room could catch the eye of
disheveled contest judge and broadcaster John Madden. Send a messy
room photo (child or adult bedroom, garage, kitchen, basement,
attic, home office, workroom, playroom, closet or dorm room) and a
brief (25 words maximum) explanation of how getting the room
organized will help in dealing with the new millennium. Entries
must be postmarked by than Feb. 29 and mailed to America's Messiest
Room Contest, 625 N. Michigan Ave., Suite 2400, Chicago, Ill.
60611. Check www.acehardware.com for details.
</P>
<P>
   4 DIGITS AREN'T ENOUGH ZIP FOR YOUR MAIL
</P>
<P>
   Q: How specific an area is defined by the last four digits in a
nine-digit ZIP code? If the digits of a residential address were
added to the first nine, would this be sufficient for use as an
address or a return address? Think of all the time this would save
to come up with questions like this for you! _John Nemetz
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope. Barbara Pokorny, U.S. Postal Service spokeswoman, notes
the ``plus 4'' designation is not necessarily unique to your
residence. It could be one side of a street or a bank of mail
boxes. Several residences in your area may share this code.
Remember, a carrier reads the address and the ZIP code. ``Plus 4''
along with your house number would not provide enough information
to deliver or return your mail.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
