<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-KUDZU-STUDENT22-COX     02-21 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUDZU-STUDENT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGIA TEENAGER FINDS HIS OWN WAY TO KILL KUDZU
 &HT;    720&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government scientists who say they have isolated a
fungus that destroys kudzu may have competition from an unexpected
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For a science fair project, an 18-year-old Georgia high school
student has identified another kudzu-killing fungus and developed a
way to use it against the vine that has enveloped so much of the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Farris, a senior at Houston County High School, in Warner
Robins, has won numerous honors for his work with a kudzu-attacking
fungus called ``Colletotrichum gloeosporioides.''
</P>
<P>
   He was among a small group of teen scientists invited to present
the results of their research at the annual meeting here last week
of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, who has participated in science fair competitions since
seventh grade, noticed a patch of kudzu on growing beside
Interstate 75 three years ago, and it got him thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea came to me that if I could find a naturally occurring
pathogen on kudzu, I might use it as a biological control of the
weed,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Mrs. Katie Farris, was driving the car as they
passed the kudzu patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, 'Momma, I'm going to try to find a way to control
kudzu,' `` Katie Farris recalled. ``And I said, 'Oh, Jeremy, how
can you possibly even think of such a thing.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The thought of controlling kudzu would have struck just about
anyone in Georgia, even Jeremy Farris's mother, as blue-sky
fantasy. Since it was introduced into the United States in the late
1800s, kudzu has spread over an estimated 7 million acres, from
Florida to New York to Texas. Infestations are particularly heavy
in Alabama, Georgia and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Agriculture researchers recently announced
they had identified a different fungus that kills virtually 100
percent of kudzu vines when applied to them in high concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, the older of the two sons of Jerry and Katie Farris,
does not claim such a high ``kill rate'' for the Colletotrichum
organism.
</P>
<P>
   However, he believes it is potentially an effective control for
the weed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Farris said she and her husband, Jerry Farris, a vocational
rehabilitation counselor at the Veterans Administration Medical
Center in Dublin, Ga., were not surprised when Jeremy threw himself
into a search for a natural enemy of kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He amazes us,'' she said. ``When he sets a goal for himself,
he's driven. He's very goal-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Unaware that the USDA scientists also were looking for a way to
control kudzu, Farris began searching through patches of the vine
for signs of anything that might be attacking it.
</P>
<P>
   He isolated several types of fungus from small, seemingly
insignificant spots on kudzu leaves. He grew the various fungi in a
laboratory and applied each to kudzu vines in a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used something that is called 'Koch's postulate,''' he
explained. ``That means that if you grow an organism in the
laboratory and inoculate it onto a plant, then re-isolate it from
the damaged plant, logically it is the organism you placed on the
plant and it is pathogenic to the host.''
</P>
<P>
   This process led him to the Colletotrichum fungus, which causes
kudzu to develop lesions on leaves and stems.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate problem lay in the fact that the fungus also
attacks peaches, pecans and apples, Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   Farris developed a special laboratory culture containing
ground-up kudzu leaves and used it to grow the fungus. He applied
each laboratory crop to kudzu vines, re-isolated it and grew it
again in the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Over many generations, the fungus appeared to develop an
increased virulence against the vine and a reduced appetite for
fruit and nut trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It causes the leaves of kudzu to be covered with brown (dying)
areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of Charles Reilly, a plant pathologist at an
agricultural research laboratory in Byron, Ga., Farris determined
that his fungus is a ``stress pathogen'' for kudzu, meaning it
attacks plants that have already been stressed by drought or some
other adverse circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he said, he worked out a system under which a dilute
herbicide mixture is used to stress the plants, followed by an
application of fungus spores.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Farris is an Eagle Scout and captain of his school cross-country
team (''Regional champions this year,'' he said.) He is on the
school mathematics and academic teams.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to enter Georgia Tech in Atlanta later this year and is
applying for scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Houston County High School chemistry teacher Laura Byrd
describes Farris as ``a very interesting kid, a typical American
boy, very laid-back and friendly, not the kind of kid you would
look at and say he was a nerd or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you get him talking about his project, he turns into a
different person,'' Byrd added. ``He is extremely knowledgeable
about this fungus of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton G. Sutherlin, a teacher at Warner Robins Middle School,
has known Farris for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught this kid in the seventh grade and continue to work
with him and encourage him,'' Sutherlin said. ``It is not often
that a teacher gets the honor and privilege and satisfaction of
watching a flower bloom. Man, what a rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
