u f BC-AUTOS-SHOPPING-BOS &LR;      02-21 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-SHOPPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADY TIMES FOR BUYERS AND SELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is that time of year again.
</P>
<P>
   We flock to showrooms and honor (in New England, at least) dead
presidents by kicking tires (though these days be careful because,
with low-profile tires all the rage, there's not much rubber
between rim and ground), checking out seats, sound systems, and
dashboards, slamming doors to see if they are solid, and generally
dreaming summer dreams in the dead of winter.
</P>
<P>
   It is a time of sales in the auto industry _ sales being taken
two ways, one being actions the auto dealers hope to make, the
other being perceived deals on this year's crop of cars, SUVs,
pickup trucks, and myriad amalgams of all three that have become
the rage.
</P>
<P>
   These are heady times to be a seller of cars. They are selling
in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also heady times to be buyers of cars. That is
because today's vehicles are more exciting, more dependable, safer
(when driven properly), and more imaginatively designed than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Very good autos can be purchased for $12,000 (not a lot of money
in today's auto market); superb sedans can be found for $18,000 to
$25,000; mid-luxury cars that are finer than any true luxury car
built 10 years ago can be found in the mid-30s to mid-40s; and the
high-end luxury cars, $50,000 to upwards of $80,000 come with a
sportiness aimed at appealing to young, suddenly wealthy drivers
even as they continue to appeal to the older driver who has longed,
and saved, for years for such a car.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks are cars are SUVs. Convertibles are making a big
comeback, mostly as sports cars. Power is a seller, but so too will
be ``green'' cars such as the hybrids offered by Honda and Toyota,
autos that combine electric and gasoline motors and drive like your
everyday auto. Their big selling point? They recharge their own
batteries while rolling, so there is no need to plug them in when
batteries run low.
</P>
<P>
   Because manufacturers have learned to ``share'' platforms within
their model lines, they save money that allows them to offer
wonderful, relatively limited creations that might never see the
light of day if they had to be developed from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Chrysler can bring out its PT Cruiser, part
panel-truck, part gangster car. It's why Ford can offer a four-door
pickup truck on the platform of its F150 pickup. The possibilities
seem endless. So what to do?
</P>
<P>
   Here, in several categories, are the cars I've already driven,
or am particularly looking forward to driving, in the year ahead.
When you shop, ask yourself a few questions: What will I use this
car for most of the time? Is there some exciting and esoteric use
that I am paying thousands extra to obtain but which I'll seldom
utilize? And, particularly in the low- and mid-luxury ranges, is
one car is really $5,000 or $10,000 better than another. Many are
not. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trucks &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --If you are a truck fan _ a big truck fan _ drive a Toyota
Tundra. You will be amazed at its smooth ride, its powerful and
amazingly quiet engine. It comes with four doors and seating for
five. It's got a decent size bed. It's got Toyota longevity and
reliability written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   --Chevrolet Silverado. It, too, has a four-door model available
and seats six comfortably. It comes with four engine options _ from
a 200-horsepower V6 to 300-h.p. V8 _ and an Autotrac system that
sends power to the front wheels (on four-wheel drive models) when
extra grab is needed up there.
</P>
<P>
   --Dodge Dakota. Smaller sibling to the Ram, but available with
four doors, seating for six (there's a pattern developing in pickup
trucks here) and a range of engines, though I doubt many 120 h.p.
V4s will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   --Ford SuperCrew. Need I say it: four doors, lots of room, lots
of power. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUVs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, a word of warning here. Don't buy one of these for your
kids because you think they'll be safer in one. If you do buy an
SUV, special driving lessons for young drivers is in order. I am a
fan of Sport Utility Vehicles _ in the right hands. You cannot
drive them as if they are cars. You cannot drive fast the way you
can in a car, nor can you do sudden stops and quick lane changes at
higher speeds as you can in a car. You can haul lots of people and
gear, go places cars can't go, and make them an important part of
your traveling life _ if you are careful. Thankfully, auto
manufacturers are starting to catch onto the inherent dangers that
come when bad or inexperienced drivers get behind the wheel of an
SUV and are responding with automatic driver assist systems, better
suspensions, and wonderful yaw control systems. Some good SUVS
include:
</P>
<P>
   --Honda CR-V. Marginally a true SUV, but a great rig for bad
weather with its all-wheel drive, good suspension, and stability.
Don't plan on going off-road in one, but even most true SUVs never
get there.
</P>
<P>
   --Nissan Xterra. The least expensive true SUV you'll find, if a
dealer isn't gouging because of its popularity. A throwback to the
days when SUVs were tough, spartan, actually did go off-road, and
were affordable. If a dealer asks you to pay well over $20,000 for
one, walk away.
</P>
<P>
   --BMW X5. Perhaps the finest SUV on the market today. It's a
high-performance car on the road; a beast off the road. It is
stable, corners in a way others do not, and has all the feel of
luxury of a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   --Subaru Forester. Another marginal SUV, but wonderful on ice
and snow, quiet, reliable, and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   --Land Rover Discovery. A real SUV in swank clothing. Wonderful
suspension, roomy interior, good in mud, snow, forest, and field. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minivans &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minivans are a market in flux, to some extent. Who needs a
minivan when you can haul the kids, the lumber, the groceries, the
loam for the lawn, all in a four-door pickup truck that rides like
a car? But there are some good ones and they will sell:
</P>
<P>
   --Ford Windstar. Smooth, powerful, sliding doors on both sides
(de rigeur, I'd say) and it has some of the best crash-test results
of any minivan ever.
</P>
<P>
   --Honda Odyssey. Bigger than ever _ and that means a lot of
space inside _ and right up there with the Chrysler products. Dual
sliding doors and a third seat that disappears (Voila!) into the
floor for good cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   --Mazda MPV. Thankfully, it's been redesigned with front-wheel
drive and that's a smart move. It also has two sliders, a
disappearing seat like the Odyssey, but is just a bit smaller
overall.
</P>
<P>
   --Chrysler Town &AMP; Country, Dodge Caravans. Without these, we'd
not have the others. They're big, powerful, and roomy. Did I
mention dual sliders? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sedans &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is where we urge you to shop carefully, folks. They come
small, medium or large, from low-cost to high-cost. When you're
shopping for a sedan, try out lots of them; many are good, many are
good deals, and many are not worth the extra cash that makes them
more expensive than comparable models, even in their own line.
</P>
<P>
   --Nissan Maxima. It's scheduled for a redesign over the next
couple of years, but its 222-h.p. V6 is one of the finest engines
on the market and its price _ the low $20s _ is appealing because
it is as good as many cars costing $8,000 to $10,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   --Lincoln LS. A sporty, European-feel, American luxury sedan.
The Lincoln LS is a breakthrough and if you're looking at foreign
sport sedans, drive one of these, too.
</P>
<P>
   --Chrysler 300M. American 1950s raw power meets 2000 world-
class styling.
</P>
<P>
   --Ford Focus. Another breakthrough car. At $12,500 to start, it
comes in hatchback, four-door, and wagon models. Smooth,
surprisingly roomy, and a real treat at this price.
</P>
<P>
   --Toyota Camry. Simply, it's the Model T of this age.
Affordable, dependable, reliable. For the masses.
</P>
<P>
   --Chevrolet Monte Carlo. It has great sporty looks with a
performance package to make you feel like you, too, are on the
NASCAR circuit.
</P>
<P>
   --Volkswagen Passat. Soon to come equipped with all-wheel drive.
Smooth, zippy, comfortable, and reliable. Need two cars? Pair this
one up with a Jetta in your garage.
</P>
<P>
   --Any BMW, Saab, Volvo, Mercedes, Acura, Audi or Lexus. In this
pack, it's all a matter of want and wallet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Station Wagons &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're making a comeback. Some favorites:
</P>
<P>
   --Saab 9-5. It's not big, but roomy enough. Powerful, quiet,
wonderful in snow and ice, and hey, I love that glove compartment
that chills drinks to 42 degrees using the car's air conditioning
system.
</P>
<P>
   --Volvo wagons. The 40 series at around $25,000 with a
turbocharged four-cylinder is a fine car; the Cross Country may be
the best all-around New England car you could buy.
</P>
<P>
   --BMW 5401. Rugged, fast, smooth, quiet. What would you expect? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sports cars &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roadsters are the rage with more and more ragtops appearing
every day. In this market, you can go wild with desire, wilder with
your wallet. A few favorites:
</P>
<P>
   --Honda S2000. I drove this one to Pennsylvania and the Pocono
racetrack. Redlines at 9 grand. Fast, six speeds, snappy as a
rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   --Porsche Carrera 4. Probably the finest car I have ever driven.
So subtle, yet so powerful. Its driver assist system, when on,
won't let you make the car fishtail.
</P>
<P>
   --Acura NSX. Another pricey option. Aluminum, horsepower, you
can feel every pebble in the road. The most fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   --Mazda Miata. Without this car, we wouldn't be writing about
the comeback of the sports car. Definitely a car for the
afficianado.
</P>
<P>
   --Audi TT coupe and convertible. Not the easiest car to get
into, but once you are wearing it, it's like you're driving inside
a computer game.
</P>
<P>
   --BMW Z3. Snappy, corners like it's on rails, odd appearance
grows on you until you love it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
