<HEADLINE>
ARE NEW MODELS WORTH THE WAIT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long gone are the days when all the vehicle manufacturers
introduced all their new models in the fall. Now it's a year-round
happening. Gone, too, are the days when manufacturers kept new
models under wraps until introduction day. You don't need to look
at spy photos of new models (as happened a few decades ago); now
the manufacturers are putting them out in full view to look at,
marvel about, and think about, long before they are available in
the showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   While some models being shown now are brand new and offer
innovative features, others are redesigns of existing models with
better features.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking to buy, in the case of the DaimlerChrysler
minivans, for example, you might want to hold off until the new
2001 models are available.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring Oldsmobile introduced its 2001 Aurora at the New
York Auto Show. ``The all-new Aurora has everything consumers
demand from a premiere luxury sedan,'' says John Gatt, brand
manager for the Aurora. ``We've improved on everything that defines
the Aurora's heritage _ exhilarating power and performance, precise
ride and handling, and an overall presence that is incredibly
distinctive.'' Unlike the first Aurora introduced in 1994, the new
model will offer a choice of two engines, a V-8 and a V-6.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac has been showing its EVOQ a lot. But this
405-horsepower, $80,000 sports vehicle won't be available until
2003. In this case, Cadillac is working on its image and wants
younger buyers to think Cadillac when they head to the showrooms.
While some of the present styling of Cadillac models still say
older buyer, under the sheet metal is some pretty impressive
performance and innovations.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler PT Cruiser is another vehicle that's been on view
since last spring. Now its actually going on sale in March. Is it a
sedan, minivan, or truck? Chrysler says it's a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Rover is a long-established name in Great Britain, but hasn't
been sold in the States for quite some time. Now BMW (which owns
Rover) confirms the Mini is heading our way. Rumor has it showing
up in fall 2001, and may be sold in BMW showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Acura, which did not offer a CL coupe this year, will have an
all-new model, the 2001 Acura 3.2 CL. This one is based on the
Acura TL sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen is adding its 4Motion, all-wheel-drive to its Passat
sedans and wagons, a feature VW hasn't offered in more than 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus will bring out the LS 430 to replace its flagship LS 400.
The new model, coming in the fall, will be packed with safety
innovations and comfort. Its amenities are almost mind boggling: a
climate-control system that senses if more sunlight is hitting one
side of the car than the other, and adjusts the cooling system
accordingly; a driver's seat with dual lumbar controls; and options
that include air suspension, navigation system, front seats with
separate heating and cooling elements, power adjustable rear seats
with heat and massage, rear air conditioning and more.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is already showing off its 2001 minivans. Even
though the company leads the field when it comes to minivans, it is
taking no chances on losing sales to other makers. So it's out to
prove that there's no minivan to consider other than a Chrysler or
Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   The new minvans look a lot like this year's models but just
consider the changes: power sliding doors at last, but not like
those on GM models, these can be closed manually; an optional power
liftgate in back that opens and closes electrically, an industry
first; quieter, more powerful engines; stronger bodies; and more
inside features, such as a console that can be moved from the front
to the second row of seating, more cargo room, a cargo organizer to
handle grocery bags, and other items. And the company is retooling
just about everything for better fit and more durability.
</P>
<P>
   If you're into trucks or SUVs, look what's coming:
</P>
<P>
   The Isuzu VX-02 is scheduled to be in showrooms sometime late
this year or early next year. Isuzu takes its futuristic VehiCROSS
one step better by chopping off the top for that open air look. In
addition, the VehiCross has a powerful 215-horsepower V6 engine and
an active control switch on the dash that lets you choose from
off-road to highway driving.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is giving its Frontier a tougher looking exterior to set
it apart from other makes; otherwise mechanically it is the same.
It will come in two and four-door versions, extended cab and
four-wheel drive versions.
</P>
<P>
   GM will offer new pickups with four full-sized doors as well as
heavy-duty versions of Chevrolet Silverado and the GM Sierra
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 77 years, Buick is introducing a truck
(SUV) that will offer the cargo capabilities of a truck and the
easy ride of a sedan. The Buick Rendezvous will sell for around
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac is coming out with the Aztek, a sport utility clearly
aimed at the young at heart. This 2001 model is expected in
showrooms this summer and will be offered in both front-drive and
all-wheel-drive models.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is entering into the full-sized sport utility world with
the Sequoia, based on the Tundra pickup platform. The Sequoia is
almost identical in size to the Ford Expedition. Interestingly, the
Sequoia will be priced less than the smaller Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which has purchased Hummer, now says it will
offer a smaller version of this vehicle in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is coming out with a few new models. Among them is the Ford
Explorer Sport Trac that will offer seating for five, four doors,
and a short cargo bed that can be extended with a flip-out cage.
Another is the Ford Escape, a small SUV and the sixth in the
company's line. Ford is aiming this July model at those with an
``active lifestyle.'' Among its features is a slide out roof rack
that goes into the rear hatch for mountain bikes or skis.
</P>
<P>
   Other SUVs being introduced at this year's Detroit Auto Show
include the Hyundai Santa Fe, a redesigned Mitsubishi Montero, and
the new, small Daewoo Korando, that will be among the lowest priced
SUVs in America.
</P>
<P>
   And Acura, which did not offer an SUV this year, has previewed
its MD-X which will replace the SLX that was built by Isuzu. The
MD-X will share its platform with the Honda Odyssey minivan and
have an independent rear suspension. It goes on sale in the fall
and is aimed right at the Lexus RX300.
</P>
<P>
   With models like this in the pipeline, it almost makes you want
to wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
