<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      02-21 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA STANCE ON ARMS STYMIES LEADERS OF BRITAIN, IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ On Wednesday afternoon, Feb. 16, as Sinn Fein leaders
Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness huddled with the prime ministers
of Britain and Ireland trying to find a way out of the impasse that
imperils the Northern Ireland peace process, one aide to Tony Blair
suggested that maybe it was time for the IRA and the British to
talk directly.
</P>
<P>
   The process had ground to a halt because the Irish Republican
Army refuses to say if or when it will disarm, and because the
Ulster Unionists refuse to share power with Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing, as long as the IRA keeps its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   According to some who were in the room, McGuinness, Sinn Fein's
chief negotiator, who was once the IRA's chief of staff, closed his
eyes and shook his head. The IRA, he said, would not talk to the
British about disarming ``in a million years.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of two nations were left trying to figure a way out
of a Catch-22. After the power-sharing government was suspended
last week, the IRA said it would not even discuss disarming until
the government is restored. And the unionists say they won't allow
the government to be restored until the IRA begins to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA considers itself an undefeated army, and undefeated
armies don't discuss turning in weapons with an enemy it fought to
a stalemate. That would be a surrender.
</P>
<P>
   And, the IRA and Sinn Fein point out, the IRA was not a
signatory to the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, the compromise that
created the political institutions that are supposed to transform
Northern Ireland into a peaceful, democratic society after 30 years
of the Troubles. That agreement said the IRA and pro-British
loyalist paramilitary groups should disarm by May, but purposely
left open the date that the process would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leaders are technically correct in saying there was no
violation of the agreement to justify last week's decision by
British Secretary of State Peter Mandelson to restore direct rule
from London after just 72 days of local government.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a political reality in the deliberately vague
wording of the Good Friday Agreement. And the political reality is
that everyone involved in the peace process _ not just the
Protestant unionists and the British government but moderate
Catholic nationalists from Northern Ireland and the Irish
government _ expect the IRA, at the very least, to commit itself to
disarming by a specific date. Everyone, that is, except
republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They consider disarmament a red herring meant only to humiliate
the IRA and delay addressing the grievances that are at the root of
the conflict, such as discrimination against Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinn Fein says it is responsible only for the 18 percent
of the population that votes for it, the reality is that everyone
else considers it the political wing of the IRA. It may be that
Adams and McGuinness, despite their best efforts, cannot deliver
IRA disarmament, but the peace process has rested on the premise
that they could.
</P>
<P>
   And while the IRA is not a signatory to the Good Friday
Agreement, it has benefited from it. Most of the 400 IRA prisoners
held at the time it was signed have been released. By July, all of
them are supposed to be. The 13,000-member Royal Ulster
Constabulary, which is more than 90 percent Protestant and which
republicans see as the military wing of unionism, upholding a
system that has treated them like second-class citizens, is being
reformed.
</P>
<P>
   Most crucially, the agreement, with the support of both
governments, enshrines the principle that if a majority of Northern
Ireland ever chooses to merge with the Irish Republic, Britain
would accept that decision. The IRA's holy grail, a united Ireland,
is achievable by democratic means.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRA is undoubtedly worried about a bloody split in its
own ranks if it begins to disarm, its refusal to budge on weapons
also serves a tactical purpose. Republicans have been arguing that
they might make an offer on disarming in return for a scaling down
of the British military presence.
</P>
<P>
   But while British and Irish senior security officials privately
acknowledge they are more concerned about the IRA using its weapons
than merely holding them _ reasoning it could rearm itself or use
fertilizer bombs _ they also believe the threat from dissident
republicans and loyalists remains too great to scale down just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has repeatedly said that republicans are committed to
disarming, and see it as essential to the success of the peace
process. The difference, Adams and other Sinn Fein leaders say, is
that it has to be done voluntarily, without deadlines set by the
unionists or the British.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble's threat to resign
as leader of the power-sharing government that led Mandelson to
suspend the assembly instead. In an interview, Mandelson insisted
he had no alternative, and that Trimble's resignation would have
led to a collapse that would have made it harder to restore local
government, and virtually ensured that Trimble's moderate
leadership team would be replaced with hard-liners who do not want
to share power with nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   But Mandelson's decision to back the unionists led republicans,
and even some moderates, to claim that Britain had caved in again
into a unionist veto.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, republicans and unionists wield what amounts to veto
power. Either side can halt the peace process whenever it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Blair, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, and, by
trans-Atlantic telephone, President Clinton are trying to bring
leverage on both sides, but mainly on republicans, to find a way
around the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   A senior US official here said ``nothing is off the table,''
including the cutting back on what has been the unfettered access
to the United States by Sinn Fein officials. Such a sanction,
however, would mean little to the IRA, and would actually bolster
IRA hard-liners who oppose the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been wary of being seen to take sides, White
House officials acknowledge the president had expected more out of
the IRA than the last-minute, conditional pledge to eventually put
its weapons ``beyond use,'' which failed to forestall the
suspension of the power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments hope cooler heads will prevail
in the next two or three weeks. But Mandelson said the drift cannot
continue indefinitely, because dissidents are likely to step in to
fill the vacuum with violence.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that's the only thing Peter Mandelson and Gerry
Adams agree on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
