<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3430 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-BOS &LR;      02-21 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIDER'S NO HITLER, IF THAT IS ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KLAGENFURT, Austria _ Joerg Haider, the man who has been
described by some as the next Hitler, presides over a remote
province here that has about as many people as Worcester and,
leaving aside the surrounding snow-capped peaks, even looks
something like it.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office, here in this unexceptional city
surrounded by exceptional mountains, his collar open, the
50-year-old Haider looks more like the provincial governor he is
than the monster some warn he could become.
</P>
<P>
   And if one listens carefully, and then considers Haider's views
in the bigger context of world affairs, it raises the question of
whether his demonization has been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   As he rattles off the policies of his far-right Freedom Party,
Haider's anti-immigration stance sounds as if it could be lifted
from Pat Buchanan, or any politician whose constituency includes
the border with Mexico. His complaints of an unelected European
Commission dictating to member states about areas once the domain
of national sovereignty sound exactly like those voiced by
Euroskeptics in the eminently respectable British Conservative
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Haider sounds like many other conservatives and even,
when he talks about giving more money to stay-at-home mothers or
expounds on his opposition to the death penalty, like some
liberals.
</P>
<P>
   This is the next Hitler? Hitler exploited a postwar depression
in Europe's biggest country, where millions who were out of work or
needed someone to blame for their problems willingly followed his
fascist regime into an attempt at world domination and genocide of
European Jewry.
</P>
<P>
   Austria is a democratic country of 8 million people, with one of
the smallest unaligned armies in Europe. The country's unemployment
rate, at 4.2 percent, is the third-lowest in Europe, and it is one
of the most affluent countries in Europe. The retirement age is 57,
and people are complaining the government wants to raise it to 59.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Haider has cynically blamed foreigners for
Austria's woes, and has repeatedly played down the evils of the
Third Reich, portraying ordinary Nazis as misguided but basically
honorable people whose only real sin was to bet on the wrong horse.
But then, given that Haider's parents were among those ordinary
Austrians who enthusiastically joined the Nazis, it seems no
surprise that he will not denounce them. How many politicians
would?
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking things about the Haider phenomenon is
how many Jews in Austria distinguish between his xenophobia and his
alleged fascism _ finding him guilty of the first, but not the
second. Simon Wiesenthal, the illustrious Nazi hunter from Vienna,
insists that Haider is neither a fascist nor an anti-Semite.
Instead, he sees a right-wing populist who tells people what they
want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Georg Haber, the courtly manager of Vienna's Jewish Museum,
recently found himself in the awkward position of telling Israelis
that their fears about Haider were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was visiting my daughter in Tel Aviv, where she lives, and I
was arguing with people all over the place,'' Haber explained,
shaking his head at the thought as he nursed a coffee in the
museum's quiet cafe. ``In Israel, I had to say it's not as
dangerous as it seems. But I learned to be more sensitive. I
understand the outrage, especially among Holocaust survivors and
their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, nearly all of Austria's Jewish population has
lived in Vienna. There were 185,000 Jews in Vienna before the Nazis
annexed a willing Austria in 1938. Most fled, but some 60,000 died
in Nazi concentration camps. Today, there are just 12,000 Jews in
Vienna. The refusal of most Austrian Jews to compare Haider to
Hitler, says Haber, is because they know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling Haider a Nazi is not only inaccurate, it cheapens what
being a Nazi means,'' Haber said. ``I am very concerned about
Haider's antipathy toward foreigners. Having black hair and a
mustache here, you have problems. But this is not just a problem
with Haider. It's a problem in Austria as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even the Social Democrats, the liberals who ruled in
coalition with the mainstream conservative People's Party for much
of the last half-century, got tough on immigration in recent years.
Party spokesmen sheepishly explain the main motivation was to
prevent Haider from gaining power by exploiting public fears about
foreigners taking jobs and upsetting Austria's relatively stable
society.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Haider's followers are more worrying than he is. Thomas
Prinzhorn, whom Haider proposed for the new Cabinet, last year
claimed the previous government gave immigrants free hormone
injections ``to increase their fertility.'' Austrian President
Thomas Klestil, who figuratively held his nose when he approved the
new coalition government, refused to approve Prinzhorn's
appointment. Another one of Haider's aides whom Klestil refused to
approve for the Cabinet was behind last year's Freedom Party
campaign posters that warned of ``over-foreignization,'' a phrase
popularized by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Freedom Party houses some virulent racists, it
is hard to find any difference, in substance, between what they are
saying about immigrants and what most right-wing parties now in
opposition throughout most of Europe are saying.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-foreigner sentiment is common. People in polite circles in
London, Paris, and Dublin dismiss most immigrants as freeloaders
who are responsible for increases in crime and taxes. Compared to
Austria, there has been more violence directed at foreigners in
several other European countries, including in some that have
denounced the rise of the Freedom Party and advocated sanctions by
the European Union against Haider.
</P>
<P>
   While European leaders who have canceled bilateral meetings with
the Austrian government say they have a moral duty to ostracize
Austria, there is also self-interest. Haider's party could
single-handedly veto the first batch of Eastern European countries
up for EU membership, three of which border Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Austria, nearly 10 percent of whose population is foreign-born,
has the third-highest proportion of immigrants in Europe and fears
being swamped with workers from neighboring Hungary, Slovenia, and
the Czech Republic. But open borders are part of the price of EU
membership, which Austrians knew when 66 percent of them voted to
join the EU in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The international outcry over Haider has bolstered his
popularity at home _ including among people who didn't vote for
him, but who object to what they view as interference from the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most disturbing is that Haider's party could become so
popular, and xenophobia so socially acceptable, when Austria is
enjoying a period of prosperity and low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens,'' asks Walter Famler, who edits and publishes
the literary magazine Wesennpest, ``when things get bad here?''
</P>
<P>
   While it is unlikely to ever get as bad as when Hitler rose to
power, there is another Austrian politician Famler recalls when the
question of Haider's rise to power is considered.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the last century, a populist Vienna mayor named
Karl Lueger blamed foreigners for everything wrong in Austria. Like
Haider, Lueger was charismatic and a good orator. Unlike Haider, he
never apologized for his insensitive remarks, nor felt the
constraining force of world opinion, nor had to worry about
sanctions from his European neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Under Lueger, Vienna's enlightened society, famed for its cafes,
opera, and civility gave way to a place where racism was openly
spouted and tolerated. Within 10 years of Lueger's election, a
young Adolf Hitler came to Vienna and began airing his theories on
Aryan superiority at the Cafe Sperl. An aspiring artist, Hitler was
rejected from Vienna's Academy of Fine Arts, but the oratory skills
he acquired at Vienna's cafes served him well when he moved to
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haider is not Hitler, but more like Karl Lueger,'' says
Famler.
</P>
<P>
   More historically accurate, perhaps, but Famler acknowledged
that even that comparison is not terribly reassuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
