<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-21 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-GOVERNMENT RHETORIC TURNS PERSONAL IN NEVADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has written about public lands issues
for over a decade and is known for his insight to these issues. His
e-mail address is levendos(at)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Forest Supervisor Gloria Flora of the Humboldt-Toiyabe
National Forest resigned late November not only to get the U.S.
Forest Service's attention to the climate of hostility and
harassment surrounding Forest Service employees in the Elko area of
Nevada, but also to make the public aware.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, she said, ``I also wanted the public
in Nevada to pay particular attention to how some of their citizens
were behaving, including how some of their elected officials were
behaving.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Forest Service report on the situation, USFS
employees were refused service at restaurants and gas stations.
Their wives and children were cursed and verbally abused in
schools, at school bus stops, and in grocery stores. A bulldozer
operator at a mining operation tried to run down one USFS employee.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials, including members of Congress, were
bad-mouthing the Forest Service and its employees.
</P>
<P>
   The local newspaper, Elko Daily Free Press, added fuel to the
fire. One of its editorials defined ``fed bashing'' as ``roughly
standing up for the rights of the citizens.'' Another editorial
called Forest Service employees ``thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems to have been forgotten in the bombast is that USFS
employees were only following federal laws passed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Flora paid a high price for alerting top officials of the Forest
Service and the public about the seriousness of the situation. She
ended 22 years of service in the Forest Service with her
resignation. There's no going back.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter of resignation, Flora addressed the climate of
hostility in the Elko area: ``People in rural communities who do
respect the law and accept responsibility for complying with it are
often rebuked or ridiculed. They are compared to collaborators with
the Vichy government in Nazi-controlled France! People who support
the federal government or conservation of natural resources ask
that they not be identified for fear of retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Flora is optimistic about what her resignation has set into
motion. It has begun a dialogue among leaders in Elko and
discussions in the media.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service conducted an inquiry among its employees
working in the Humboldt-Toiyabe National Forest and issued a
report. And on Feb.
</P>
<P>
   18, U.S. Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck arrived in Elko to
talk to USFS employees and community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Flora commented on the antagonism between some elected leaders
in the West and the federal agencies that manage public lands:
``This issue is very critical, not just as a situation in Nevada.
We see pieces and parts of this kind of uncivil rhetoric and the
threats, and these thinly veiled threats of armed insurrection and
all these ultra-right wing kinds of attitudes. I think people need
to examine them and say how do these attitudes assist in solving
the dilemmas that we have facing us on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is room for everyone's opinion, but I don't think that
people's opinion, even if they are very far to the left or very far
to the right, should be expressed in such a way that it precludes
others from expressing theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   She agreed with the USFS report that blames some of the problems
on the Forest Service itself. When the Humboldt and Toiyabe
national forests were put under one administration and Flora made
the forest supervisor, there were fewer USFS employees left in
smaller communities and in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed in public lands management _ expectations of
public lands have changed, budgets have been cut, employee numbers
have been reduced, workloads have increased, and much of the work
isn't in the field as it once was. People now want information so
that data collection and organization is a major part of the work
USFS employees do. Yet most of the public still wants to see the
forest ranger in the field.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pivotal issues in the Elko-Forest Service conflict
has been the Forest Service closing the mile-and-a-half Jarbidge
South Canyon Road, which leads to a trail head. Dirt from the road
silts up a stream of bull trout, which can kill off the fish.
</P>
<P>
   The county claims it's the county's road. Elko County Manager
George Boucher said, ``The road brought on the dissension,'' but
that other Forest Service policy decisions caused the community's
irate responses and finally a breakdown of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Elko City Manager Linda Ritter said the anti-government
sentiment among some of the people in the county comes from
frustration with the Forest Service. She thinks Flora's resignation
over the climate of hostility ``blew the entire issue out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck flew to Nevada to try to bridge the rift between the
Forest Service and the people of Elko County. He held separate
meetings to talk to his employees and then to talk to community
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Feb. 19, Dombeck said he thinks the conflict
over the closure of South Canyon Road contributed to the climate of
hostility, but blames the origins of the hostility on ``some of the
challenges that have occurred over the last several decades on the
authority of federal management of lands.''
</P>
<P>
   He clarified: ``I think you're really seeing cumulative effects
of a long history of concern and, to be realistic, when you have a
large proportion of a state like Nevada in federal ownership, the
stakes are high. The various sides care very deeply about these
issues.'' Approximately 83 percent of Nevada is federal public
land.
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck's meeting with community and state officials leads him
to believe that ``there's a real willingness on their part of
wanting to move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck admitted that Flora's resignation brought attention to
the issues involved: ``My number one concern as I met with my
employees is, of course, employee safety. We absolutely cannot put
employees in unsafe situations whether it's a fire line and
employees fighting a wild fire or in anything we do. The report
verified that safety isn't the issue, it's how people feel. And, as
I said to the employees, that it's important to me that not only
they be safe but that they feel valued because they are proud of
what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service's report on the problems in Elko County
documents some of the hostile pressure brought to bear on USFS
employees. One employee said that when driving in a Forest Service
vehicle in northeast Nevada, ``I often feel like a `sitting duck,'
a target.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone working for a business were the victim of the kind of
harassment that targeted Forest Service employees in Elko County,
that person could file and win a lawsuit against that business.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-government rhetoric is an old tradition in the United
States and criticism of government practices has an honored place
in that tradition _ but when people are attacked instead of
government policies and decisions, then the rhetoric has taken a
wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to eliminate the personal attacks on Forest Service or
other federal land management personnel who are doing their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH-BOS     02-21 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET RALLIES BESPEAK ANGER AT US FOR ISRAEL STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ The US Embassy compound here has the feel of a crusader
castle. It is perched on a rocky outcropping with a winding entry
that leads up to a bunkered complex ringed by massive stone walls,
gun turrets, and steel barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Officials inside this fortress are anticipating more
demonstrations this week reflecting the rising anger in Beirut
against what many here see as an unjust US policy that supports
Israel even when it hits civilian targets in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, who see the hand of Hezbollah in promoting the
demonstrations, say the anger nevertheless is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just got sick and tired of American support for
Israeli aggression,'' said Fouad Faris, 19, a college student who
describes himself as apolitical but who joined last week's
protests. ``Look at America hiding behind all this barbed wire, and
all these walls. If they had a fair policy, they wouldn't have to
do all this,'' Faris said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment notwithstanding, the security here is a holdover
from the 1980s, when Americans in Lebanon were the targets of
kidnappings and Hezbollah-orchestrated bombings and sniper attacks
that killed more than 260 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the seafront American Embassy, just 800 yards from the
new embassy, was destroyed by a bomb that killed 63 people,
including 17 Americans. Another bomb attack destroyed a barracks
near the airport, killing 239 US military personnel, including 218
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the shells of some of these buildings are visible from
the embassy compound, which has retreated to a more strategic
hilltop overlooking the sea. Noticeably absent are any Marines at
the guard posts. Instead, the embassy staffs Lebanese security
guards clad in black Kevlar vests and wielding M-16 machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the image of a diplomatic mission under siege, a
cluster of offices in small trailers is sealed in sheet metal, and
the central building is outfitted with steel-mesh cages to protect
windows from rocks and Molotov cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials, meanwhile, say they do not feel any danger
from the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that the protests are against US policy, and
analysts point out that the rhetoric and slogans being shouted
should not be confused with anti-American sentiment. Indeed, just
down the street from the protests is a commercial boulevard of
American commerce: a massive Burger King, a brand new Kentucky
Fried Chicken, and other American chains and outlets with glittery
window displays.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, one demonstrator holding a placard that read ``Death
to Israel, Death to America'' was wearing a Chicago Bulls hat
turned backward. Another young man in the crowd pressing against
the police line was wearing a ``South Carolina'' sweatshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of protesters also rallied in front of CNN's offices _
a unique expression of outrage against the global news channel and
what Lebanese perceive as a pro-Israeli bias in its coverage. One
mocking placard read: ``Q&AMP;A: Where is the other side of the
story?''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's airstrikes on Lebanon this month, in which three power
stations were destroyed and 20 civilians wounded, were in
retaliation for Hezbollah attacks on its soldiers in southern
Lebanon. The guerrillas have killed seven Israeli soldiers in a
series of attacks since Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Observers here say the recent demonstrations are significant,
largely because they seem to be uniting Lebanon with Hezbollah in a
way that it never has been.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, when Israel retaliated for Hezbollah's shelling of
northern Israel by targeting civilian infrastructure and killing
five Lebanese civilians, there were no such demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was a backlash against Hezbollah, which was seen by
many Lebanese as contributing to the cycle of violence.
</P>
<P>
   But not this time. Now, the Lebanese believe Hezbollah hit
legitimate military targets when it killed Israeli soldiers who are
occupying southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time Hezbollah played its cards very well,'' one diplomat
in the region put it.
</P>
<P>
   In the US compound ringed by concertina wire, Anne O'Leary, a
spokeswoman for the embassy, said the demonstrations ruined the
visit of an orchestra from Keene, N.H., which was performing a
series of concerts as a sign of American solidarity with the
Lebanese people.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the day after Israeli airstrikes near Beirut,
hundreds of student protesters swarmed the concert at American
University in Beirut and heckled US Ambassador David Satterfield by
chanting ``shame, shame'' throughout the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Another concert scheduled for Thursday was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concerts were to be a symbol of our confidence in their
country and its stability, and were much appreciated by many
Lebanese,'' O'Leary said. ``It was ironic that the events instead
became a magnet for student protesters who overshadowed the good
they intended to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nizar Hamzi, a political scientist at American University, and
an expert on Hezbollah, says the ``anger in the street is
legitimate, and real.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sees the demonstrations as an effort by the Islamic
guerrillas to shore up public support, especially among students,
as the group's political leadership faces an uncertain future if
Israel pulls its forces out of the occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, more than 10,000 people were in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are gathering in the street because they have found
rare common ground,'' said Charles Adwan, a researcher at the
Lebanese Center for Policy Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not only Hezbollah, this was Christian students,
Sunni students, a mix of student political parties; there were
those who support Syrian presence in Lebanon and those who
adamantly oppose it. There was the whole spectrum of Lebanese
voices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is legitimate anger,'' he said, ``and America would do
well to listen to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
