<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE CAMPS STRAIN TANZANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KASULO, Tanzania _ Every morning, Daniel Kyiyuga walks six miles
over rolling hills to check the banana groves and corn fields of
his farm. The crops, the only source of his income, often bear
signs of looting from the night before.
</P>
<P>
   It is the price he pays for living so close to the sprawling
refugee camps along Tanzania's western border with Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be happy if the refugees went home,'' Kyiyuga said,
sitting on the stoop of the mud-brick house he rents in this
roadside village, his toddler son nestled in his lap. ``If I stay
on the farm, armed bandits can come and kill my family.''
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, ethnic violence in Rwanda and Burundi has sent
hundreds of thousands of people fleeing into seven camps stretched
along the Tanzanian frontier. At the height of the influx, shortly
after the 1994 genocide that left 800,000 ethnic Tutsi dead in
Rwanda, the two camps near here swelled with 500,000 refugees,
dwarfing the local population.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees attract foreign aid organizations, which bring in
money for roads, water systems, and schools. Fifteen miles down the
road in Ngara, the main town in northwestern Tanzania, business is
booming. They also represent cheap labor for the surrounding towns
and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But the displaced also pose security and environmental problems.
They cut down forests for firewood, hunt the wildlife for meat, and
attract armed rebels looking for food, shelter, and new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Rwandans were repatriated in 1996. There are now
about 310,000 refugees in all the camps, 100,000 in the two near
Kasulo, according to the Ngara field office of the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees. Of those, only about 5,000 are
Rwandans, some of whom are believed to be tied to the Hutu
extremist groups that carried out the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanzanian police require cars to ride with armed escorts
along the stretches of road between the camps and the border.
Locals fear for their lives. Night watchmen patrol Kasulo with a
large drum to signal the villagers in case of an attack by thieves.
</P>
<P>
   As Nelson Mandela, the former South African president, convenes
peace talks on Burundi's civil war in Arusha, Tanzania, regional
security experts worry that heightening rhetoric about ethnic
hatred among warring parties in the region could spark a new mass
exodus into Tanzania. Already, as many as 200 people arrive at the
two camps here each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of specific concern is the ongoing and growing tension between
Burundi and Tanzania over the fact that the Burundian refugee camps
just across the border in northwestern Tanzania are being actively
used by Burundian rebels to recruit as well as allegedly train and
store arms _ on an ongoing basis _ to launch large-scale attacks in
southern and southwestern Burundi,'' Jan van Eck, a consultant to
the Arusha talks from the Center for Conflict Resolution in Cape
Town, wrote in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR confirms the presence of Rwandan Hutu rebels in the areas
around Kasulo.
</P>
<P>
   Security issues aside, the refugees make life hard on the locals
in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Burigi Game Park's rear boundary is only about four miles from
the two camps. During the peak of the Rwandan influx, the park's
animal populations were vastly depleted, according to Leonce
Batandana, an environmentalist at the Relief to Development
Society, a UN-affiliated organization in Ngara.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam has measured declines in the underground water table due
to usage in the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Alabyoma, a resident of Kasulo, worries about how she'll
cook her beans and corn. ``Before the refugees came, we could find
plenty of firewood nearby,'' she said. ``Now we have to walk miles
to find enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
