<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTH ROCK SHINES ON `BLOODFLOWERS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (``Bloodflowers''; The Cure; Elektra/Fiction) 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 20 albums and 20 years, the King of Mope, Cure singer
Robert Smith, has finally found his niche. Turns out it wasn't too
far from where he began. His band's latest, ``Bloodflowers,'' finds
Smith doing what he does best: whining poetically, and sometimes
jubilantly, about the ills of the world, so that the rest of us
don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   The Cure actually has been two bands during its career. It began
with the prancing guitars of ``Boys Don't Cry,'' but has recently
been wrapped in drawn-out suicide notes like 1992's ``From the Edge
of the Deep Green Sea.'' After spending the '80s as a decadent punk
band turned alternative rock icon, the group wallowed through the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Cure once again is recognizable as the band that
created ``Lovecats'' and ``Let's Go To Bed.'' Smith is the band
now, and his wailing Halloween howl has always been the constant.
On ``Bloodflowers,'' the second part of its winning combo _ warped
guitar lines and ``Phantom of the Opera'' imagery _ have returned.
</P>
<P>
   Lost like Austin Powers' mojo since 1987's ``Kiss Me, Kiss Me,
Kiss Me'' album, the group spent the '90s trying to get the balance
back. The result was sonic lithium on ``Wish'' and insincere joy on
the aptly titled ``Wild Mood Swings.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Bloodflowers,'' Smith has finally stopped trying to
please anybody but himself. ``Out of This World'' and ``Watching Me
Fall'' are long, winding, guitar-shearing Goth tales featuring
Smith climbing over it all like he hasn't done since ``The Hanging
Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the ``Birds Always Fly'' is a beautiful cousin to ``In
Between Days.'' Distinct multiple guitar voices couple with
sustained one-chord piano breaks. Most beautifully horrifying is
``Maybe Someday,'' which finds the Cure once again fitting
complicated horror into a shiny pop-rock box.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Smith and the Cure are doing again what they once did
so well, pushing alternative rock forward and nay-saying those who
swear the genre is dead.
</P>
<P>
   It's not. ``Bloodflowers'' proves that. It's the band's best
since 1985's ``The Head on the Door.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
