<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-AFFLECK-INTERVIE     02-21 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFLECK-INTERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLECT GETS BIGGEST ROLE YET IN `REINDEER GAMES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Actors often look bigger onscreen than in the flesh,
but Ben Affleck has got it backward. He's a sizable guy, 6-foot-3,
and broad-shouldered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that and his all-American handsomeness, the first
impression when he walks in the room is that of the proverbial
``regular guy,'' a well-grounded, likable 27-year-old who wouldn't
stand out in a crowd unless you'd seen him in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go to the bookstore. Sometimes you can wear a hat and,
by your carriage and demeanor (not be noticed),'' says Affleck, who
on this day is dressed casually in a gray crew-neck sweater layered
over a white T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   So Affleck may be playing against type in a bit role as a
stock-market scam recruiter in ``Boiler Room,'' which just opened,
but he is well-cast as a regular guy in ``Reindeer Games,'' opening
Friday. Well, as regular as any other guy just getting out of
prison after serving five years for car theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games'' is an unpretentious little thriller from
renowned director John Frankenheimer (``The Manchurian Candidate,''
``The Fixer,'' ``Ronin''). It's a modern version of the old film
noir B-movie in which some poor chump ends up in a tight spot,
where everything he does right goes wrong and leads him deeper and
deeper into trouble. That's what happens to Rudy, Affleck's
character. ``Reindeer Games'' has more slippery twists and turns
than an oiled Slinky.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck's co-stars are Charlize Theron (``The Cider House
Rules'') and Gary Sinise (``George Wallace'' and the upcoming
``Mission to Mars'').
</P>
<P>
   They are eager to confirm Affleck's reputation as a fun-loving,
easygoing guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's a great guy,'' Sinise says. ``He's funny, he's charming,
he's got a very natural behavioral thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an easy guy to be around. I like him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Theron was even more flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Ben,'' she says. ``Ben makes work so easy. It's his
spirit that shows up to work that makes the job so much easier. If
you only have that and nothing else, it's such a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds so impossible, but I swear, there was not one day he
showed up for work in a bad mood. You'd walk into the makeup and
hair trailer and he wanted to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   After numerous roles in mostly unseen movies and a few
successful independents, such as ``Dazed and Confused,'' Affleck
hit the jackpot with ``Good Will Hunting,'' a film he and pal Matt
Damon wrote together. Damon took the lead role and won the glory,
but Affleck got noticed as his onscreen buddy. By the time they won
an Oscar for their screenplay _ looking like naughty Boy Scouts in
their tuxedos and Cheshire grins, with their mothers as dates _
they were both launched toward stardom.
</P>
<P>
   In the two fast years since ``Good Will Hunting,'' Affleck has
made up for the many years when he was eager for any role by doing
11 movies, including ``Armageddon,'' ``Shakespeare in Love,''
``Forces of Nature,'' ``Dogma'' (for pal Kevin Smith) and ``Boiler
Room.'' He also has a role in ``Daddy'' and ``Them,'' an upcoming
film written and directed by Billy Bob Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   His salary has gone from next to nothing (for Smith films such
as ``Mallrats'' and ``Chasing Amy'') to a reported $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah, he also dated Gwyneth Paltrow, with whom he worked
on ``Shakespeare in Love,'' though according to both, that has gone
from romance to affectionate buddy status.
</P>
<P>
   But Clarence Williams III, Affleck's co-star in ``Reindeer
Games,'' told reporters that Paltrow was a frequent visitor to the
film's remote Canadian location, where she spent a lot of time
holding hands with Affleck. And Affleck and Paltrow will be
reunited onscreen this summer in ``Bounce,'' a romantic drama.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck has been on a personal rocket as hot as the one he rode
in ``Armageddon,'' but he's tried not to let it affect him. It
hasn't always been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strange thing happens where you have no success in your
life whatsoever, and then you get some,'' he says. ``It's thrilling
and exciting and ... you get scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really. All of a sudden, you have something to lose, you know
what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck, who never runs short of words, says he's getting it in
hand now.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has settled down a little bit, thank you very much. It
was a little bit crazy for a while, and now I'm sort of settling
in. Not so prone to be freaked out by highs and lows and different
things that happen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He may be enjoying himself, but Rudy sure isn't having any fun
in ``Reindeer Games.'' Though he gets to spend most of the story
traipsing around the countryside with Theron, ideas of romance soon
get sidetracked in the maze that is the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was filmed in northern British Columbia, near Prince
George, which Affleck calls ``the furthest north civilized city of
western civilization.'' The actors spent a lot of time cold and
miserable, especially in a scene in which Affleck and Theron fall
through the frozen surface of a lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games'' is the first time Affleck has been in the
position of carrying a big-budget major film as the star. (In
``Forces of Nature,'' Sandra Bullock was the big name.) He admits
that he felt a little trepidation about the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, sure,'' he says. ``The way I came into this business was
with people who were, like, near to my age and near to my
experience and near to my level of experience. It's not like
working with an icon of cinema (Frankenheimer), where you naturally
defer to that person's experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy may be just smart enough to keep his head above icy waters,
but not smart enough to keep himself from sinking deeperire
of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he's a little thick,'' Affleck says of Rudy. ``One of
the things I loved about this character was that they don't make
movies with this kind of protagonist any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This character is like these tough-luck '60s film-noir
protagonists who always struggled and never had a sense of what
they were doing. Like (Jack) Nicholson's character, getting beaten
up and getting his nose cut open in `Chinatown.' He's always behind
the curve of what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more interesting to me, to watch a guy who is a little
confused and suffering a little more, than somebody you know is
going to win and figure everything out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games'' is, at $34 million, the most expensive movie
ever financed by Miramax (through its Dimension logo), which is no
surprise since, in addition to Affleck's salary, Theron, Sinise and
Frankenheimer don't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   It won't go down as a classic on any of their resumes, but
Affleck is confident it will do well with audiences looking for a
little escapism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, films noir were B-movies. They weren't high
drama. They were popcorn entertainment. We've sort of gotten away
from that. Movies that were fun and didn't try to take themselves
too seriously. Escapist entertainment that was still sort of
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck also wants to continue not taking himself too seriously.
He kept going back to his respect for director Frankenheimer, both
as a filmmaker and an example of how to survive in the movie
business by focusing on work, not the publicity or fame that comes
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to surrender yourself to the process and act of
doing the stuff, because (otherwise) you can drive yourself
crazy,'' Affleck says. ``That was a good lesson to learn. In
keeping with that I've been able to find some normalcy and settle
into my life and focus on the things that are important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1156EST &QL; 
