<HEADER>
A3453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-EXECUTION-TEXAS-2TAKE     02-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-TEXAS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-DEATH ACTIVISTS JOIN WOMAN IN HER PLEA TO BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the scheduled execution of Betty Lou Beets
looming less than a week away, anti-death penalty activists have
stepped up the pressure on Gov. George W. Bush to halt the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International, the Texas Catholic Conference and a host
of family violence groups have called on Bush and the Texas Board
of Pardons and Paroles to spare Beets' life.
</P>
<P>
   Once a strawberry-blonde who hustled beer in a tavern near Gun
Barrel City, Beets today is 62, gray-haired with deep furrows in a
face that reflects a hard life. The ninth-grade drop-out is
scheduled for execution Thursday for the 1983 murder of former
Dallas firefighter Jimmy Don Beets, her fifth husband. Prosecutors
contend he was killed in an attempt to cash in on a $110,000
pension and life insurance package.
</P>
<P>
   Beets pleaded her case to Bush through a television interview
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking you to let me live,'' she said, her voice cracking
with emotion in a broadcast on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
``I'm asking for mercy. And I'm asking for that compassion and I'm
praying you will allow it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would make no decision until the parole board makes
its recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no unilateral right to stop an execution,'' he said.
``Secondly, all facts of a case need to be considered. And the
thing I consider is whether or not a jury has heard all the facts
and whether or not the person is guilty of the crime committed and
whether or not the person has had full access to the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   If her death sentence is carried out, Beets will be the second
woman put to death in Texas under modern capital punishment
statutes. She would also be the oldest along with another
62-year-old inmate executed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Beets was indicted but never tried in the slaying of her fourth
husband, Doyle Wayne Barker, a construction worker who disappeared
in 1981. She pleaded guilty in 1972 to shooting her second husband,
Billy Y. Lane, who survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe all life is sacred, even the life of a person who
has committed a heinous crime,'' said Richard Daley, executive
director of the Texas Catholic conference. The conference is the
public policy arm of the Catholic Bishops Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can protect society from these people without killing
them,'' Daley added.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic bishops are asking Bush not only to spare Beets' life,
but to issue a moratorium on all executions until the state can be
assured that no innocent person is sent to the execution chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has said the Texas Constitution does not empower
him to halt all executions, Daley and other abolitionists argue
that he could encourage the 18-member Board of Pardons and Paroles
to halt executions on an individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   They have drawn strength from Illinois Gov. George Ryan, also a
Republican, who last month called a halt to executions after a
college journalism class study revealed that 17 men were sent to
death row for crimes they did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Texas leads the nation in the number of executions carried out
in modern times, with 205 men and one woman put to death since the
state resumed executions in 1982. Of those, 119 have been carried
out while Bush has been in office, although most of those
executions were cases that had been wending their way through the
courts long before Bush was elected.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Texas Council on Family Violence, the
National Coalition Against Domestic Violence and Amnesty
International also have urged Bush to grant Beets a commutation of
sentence, alleging she has endured ``repeated sexual, physical and
emotional abuse ... throughout her life'' and ``severe and repeated
beatings'' by Jimmy Don Beets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush must ensure that Texas does not commit the final act
of violence against this woman,'' said Shelia Dauer, director of
Amnesty International's Women's Human Rights Program.
</P>
<P>
   Adds &UR;  &LR; Juley Fulcher, of the National Council Against domestic
Violence, ``It will be a terrible miscarriage of justice if Texas
executes this battered woman without hearing her story.''
</P>
<P>
   Beets' story of abuse, however, is a relatively recent one. In
several letters to the Houston Chronicle and an extensive interview
dating back to 1989, Beets never once mentioned having been
battered by any of her husbands, raped repeatedly or abused as a
child, as her clemency petition now contends.
</P>
<P>
   At her trial, one of Beets' daughters mentioned abuse in
passing, testifying that her mother claimed she had shot husband
No. 4 because she was tired of being beat and wanted him out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Baggett, the warden at the Mountain View Unit in
Gatesville, where death-sentenced women are housed, said the
battered wife claims are new _ as are the tears she has shed in
numerous media interviews in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Baggett has worked at the unit for most of the past 11 years,
becoming well-acquainted with Beets, and she said it has been only
recently that she has heard the grandmother talk about being a
battered wife.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beets' advocates suggest that her failure to mention repeated
episodes of abuse are typical of battered women who try to keep the
abuse secret out of fear, shame and humiliation. They also fault
her trial attorney for failing to present any mitigating evidence
on Beets' behalf at trial.
</P>
<P>
   But James Donald Beets, the son of her victim, says his father
never abused his former stepmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy was not an abuser,'' he said. ``My daddy can't stand
up and defend himself. ... For the first year after they were
married, she went around town telling everybody my daddy was the
best thing that ever happened to her.''
</P>
<P>
   And James Beets said all anyone need do to discover the true
Betty Lou Beets is to ``look into her cold, black eyes. They might
be blue, but look deep into her soul. They're black.''
</P>
<P>
   He accuses Beets of ``abusing the system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's hollering `abused grandma' and all that,'' James Beets
said. ``But what about my daddy? My kids have never known their
granddaddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of five, grandmother of nine and great-grandmother of
six, Beets is a former barmaid who once was charged with public
lewdness during an audition as a topless dancer. She was reared in
North Carolina in a sharecropper's shack, married the first time at
15, and was a grandmother by the time she was 36.
</P>
<P>
   Since her conviction, two of Beets' daughters have done jail and
prison time on prostitution and drug charges. Shirley Furgala
Branson is serving a one-year sentence for possession of a
controlled substance and has served jail time on three different
prostitution charges. She is housed in a prison across the street
from her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Another daughter, Phyllis Ann Coleman of Balch Springs, has a
string of at least six prostitution convictions and served time in
the Texas Department of Criminal Justice on possession of heroin
charges before she was discharged in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Beets was convicted of capital murder in the death of Jimmy Don
Beets, who was shot multiple times in the back of the head. Beets
reported her husband missing in 1983, and authorities initially
thought he had drowned in a boating accident on Cedar Creek Lake,
near the couple's trailer home in Gun Barrel City.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Henderson County authorities, acting on an
anonymous tip and armed with a search warrant, discovered the
missing man's body in a shallow grave beneath a wishing-well flower
bed.
</P>
<P>
   They made an unexpected find as well: the body of Barker, her
fourth husband, buried in a shallow grave under a patio at the rear
of the home. He had been reported missing in 1981 and he, too, had
been shot several times in the back of the head. Beets was indicted
in Barker's death, but was never tried for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of Jimmy Don Beets' killing, Betty Beets had moved
an ex-con who had done time for theft and killing his wife, into
her home, prison and court records show.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, Beets, who in recent days has said she wants to be
remembered as a loving family matriarch, accused her daughter,
Shirley Stegner Furgala, then 24, of killing Barker, and her son
Robert F. ``Robbie'' Branson II, then 18, of killing Jimmy Don
Beets.
</P>
<P>
   Both children testified for the state, saying their mother had
shot both men and that they had helped bury the bodies _ the exact
opposite of Beets' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Her appeals lawyers have argued that Beets did not receive
adequate representation at trial, calling her trial lawyer a
``corrupt trial attorney ... who sold her out for his own profits''
when he demanded book rights to her story in payment for
representing her.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals initially overturned the
case, saying the state's murder-for-hire statute applied only in
cases involving hired killers and not in cases where the
remuneration involved pension or insurance benefits. The court
changed its mind on rehearing, though, and reinstated the
conviction. Trying her for murder for remuneration was the only way
the state could get a death sentence under Texas law at that the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Beets' case, though, prompted the Legislature to rewrite the
murder-for-hire definition to include situations like hers.
</P>
<P>
   Then a federal judge overturned her conviction, saying not only
was her attorney's book deal unethical but he should have withdrawn
from the case so he could testify on her behalf. The attorney, E.
Ray Anderson, has said that Beets did not know about the pension or
life insurance until he told her she could collect those benefits.
The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned that judge's
ruling and reimposed the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   James Beets said he will be on hand Thursday to witness the
execution, although he said he is not relishing the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgive her with all my heart, I really do,'' he said.``And
I ask God to forgive her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
