</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-SLUMS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU'S WELFARE PROGRAMS KEEP PEASANTS LOYAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLA EL SALVADOR, Peru _ Nearly every neighborhood in this
sprawling slum has a concrete basketball court, a child-care center
and a soup kitchen that ladles out 30-cent meals.
</P>
<P>
   To remind residents of the man most responsible for these
improvements, huge white letters spelling the name of President
Alberto Fujimori's political movement emblazon the hillside
overlooking Villa El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fujimori has all of our support,'' said Irene Saez, 64, who
works at a center that distributes state food. ``I don't think any
other government would do as much for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Government programs, which hand out nearly $300 million in food
annually, aggressively target some of the most wretched pockets of
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The largess has resulted in widespread support for Fujimori
among the poor, who make up half of Peru's population of 24 million
people, and, according to analysts, could propel the president to
victory in April 9 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics describe the war on poverty as a crude patronage
system designed to ensure election-day loyalty to Fujimori, who is
running for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of public works, land giveaways and
direct aid,'' said Guillermo Loli of the Lima polling firm Apoyo.
``It's a very effective way to buy votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the anti-poverty program has made some strides, critics
also contend that it has addicted the population to handouts.
</P>
<P>
   The government's effort is evident in Villa El Salvador, a slum
on the southern edge of the capital of Lima that was founded by
squatters 30 years ago and now is home to 300,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, Isabel Mena, 35, has volunteered at a
state-sponsored soup kitchen. In exchange for peeling potatoes and
shucking corn, she receives free food for her family of five.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchens were set up in the late 1980s amid food shortages
and economic chaos. The program expanded under Fujimori, who was
first elected in 1990, and became a permanent part of the
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for the poor people who really need the help, such as
single mothers and abandoned children,'' Mena said. ``If it weren't
for the kitchens, we would be in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Mena would prefer a paying job and complains that unemployment
is the biggest problem in Villa El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   But she credits Fujimori for taming hyperinflation and for
crushing the Shining Path guerrilla movement, which killed hundreds
of people in Villa El Salvador in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, she wonders whether a different president
would eliminate her soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   As election day nears, many observers claim that the Fujimori
administration has capitalized on such fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's daily lives are very linked to the survival of this
government, or at least that's how they perceive it,'' said Diego
Garcia-Sayan of the Andean Commission of Jurists, a legal aid group
in Lima. ``It's not that they are pro- or anti-Fujimori. But they
are receiving something concrete, and they fear that they could
lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a critical report released this month, the Washington Office
on Latin America noted that 42.5 percent of all Peruvian households
receive food aid. The think tank warned that the government is
manipulating this lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offering or threatening to withdraw food aid in exchange for
political support appears to have become a common tool of the
Fujimori government,'' the report said. ``While previous
governments also engaged in such practices, never before has the
phenomenon been so widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Chavez, a legislator aligned with Fujimori, insists that
results _ not threats _ are the reason that poor people will vote
for the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a government makes good on its promises, it will
naturally have the advantage'' in elections, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another resource at the government's disposal is land.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, thousands of squatters have taken over private
property in Villa El Salvador. Though army troops later forced them
to move, Fujimori promised that all homeless people in urban areas
would be eligible for plots of vacant land.
</P>
<P>
   ``This experience will be repeated throughout the country, and
the delivery of land will be free,'' Fujimori said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Federico Salas promptly accused the
government of violating electoral laws by handing out public
property during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that after 10 years in power and just weeks
before the election, (the government) has just now become concerned
about the lack of housing in Peru,'' Salas said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such controversies, development experts say that
Fujimori has had some success in reducing misery. Between 1991 and
1997, the number of Peruvians living in poverty decreased from 57.4
percent to 50.7 percent, according to the Lima research center
Cuanto.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the Washington Office on Latin America, food
distribution programs are a dubious way to fight poverty. That's
because they do nothing to increase the ability of people to buy or
grow food for themselves. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``If this were the United States, we would say that President
Fujimori has reduced poverty by putting people on welfare,'' the
group said in its report.
</P>
<P>
   The effort also creates dependency, according to Gloria Tejada,
of the international aid group Caritas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It conditions people to avoid doing things for themselves,''
she said. ``It's a policy that has people holding out their
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez, the pro-Fujimori legislator, said emergency food
programs are necessary to combat cases of extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they suggest as an alternative?'' she asked. ``That
the people die of hunger?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
