u i BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-HNS &LR;      02-21 1584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI WANTS THIRD TERM IN OFFICE, LEGAL OR NOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over the n in Castaneda) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ He took on Maoist terrorists and won. He
resurrected a dying economy. And over the years, he has racked up
higher poll ratings than any other Peruvian head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet President Alberto Fujimori, who is the overwhelming favorite
to win the April 9 election, has come under intense criticism for
his heavy-handed maneuvers to hang onto his job.
</P>
<P>
   International monitors say that, without major changes by the
government, a free and fair vote may be almost impossible because
of harassment of candidates, unbalanced media coverage and a surge
in public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts argue that Fujimori, who took office in 1990 and
was re-elected five years later, should not be allowed on the
ballot. That's because a constitutional provision bans sitting
presidents from serving three consecutive five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``His main concern is staying in power, and he's going to get
there by hook or by crook,'' said Hernando de Soto, a former
economic adviser to Fujimori. ``He's got the media controlled. He's
bullied his main opponents. In a way, you could say he's got it
pretty well rigged.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, observers from the Atlanta-based Carter Center seemed
to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori enjoys so many advantages, they said, that conditions
for a fair election have not yet been established. They urged the
government to ``act swiftly to restore public confidence in the
electoral process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even on a level playing field, opposition candidates would
be in for a dogfight.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10 years in office, Fujimori, the son of Japanese
immigrants, has received higher job-approval ratings than any other
Peruvian president, according to Guillermo Loli of the Lima polling
firm Apoyo. A January survey put Fujimori's popularity rating at 58
percent.
</P>
<P>
   When first sworn in as president a decade ago, Fujimori took
over a nation reeling from hyperinflation, food shortages and
attacks by Shining Path, a hard-line Maoist guerrilla organization.
</P>
<P>
   His authoritarian tendencies were evident almost from the start.
He once suggested that ``perhaps an emperor would be good for
Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing an obstructionist Congress in 1992, Fujimori ordered
tanks into the streets. He closed Congress and the courts and
declared one-man rule. The moves, though condemned abroad, were
popular at home.
</P>
<P>
   The government then decimated Shining Path by capturing its
supreme leader, Abimael Guzman. A radical program of reforms opened
Peru to foreign investment, leading to the highest economic growth
rate in Latin America in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic institutions were eventually restored, and Fujimori
easily won re-election in 1995 with 64 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's second term, however, has been marred by what critics
call a systematic drive to concentrate power in his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent report by the Washington Office on Latin
America think tank, the Fujimori government has erased meaningful
checks and balances by gutting the Supreme Court, harassing the
press and giving exceptional power to the state intelligence
service. A rubber-stamp Congress has approved most of the
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past decade in Peru has witnessed the steady dismantling
of the basic institutional structures of democratic governance,''
the think tank's report said. ``Peru represents a new form of
`hybrid authoritarianism' where the formal trappings of democracy
are maintained but are often neutralized.''
</P>
<P>
   In a new book, ``The Fujimori File,'' author Sally Bowen calls
Peru's current government ``one of the most sinister, durable and
effective power machines to emerge in Latin America in recent
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's most controversial move during his second term has
been his insistence on running again.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 constitution allows sitting presidents to stand for
re-election just once. In 1996, however, Congress passed a law that
``reinterprets'' the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The provision says, in effect, that because Fujimori was
originally elected under the old charter, his first term does not
apply toward the re-election ban, making him eligible to run in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Civic organizations gathered enough signatures to hold a
national referendum on the matter, but the vote was blocked by
Congress. Fujimori launched his re-election campaign Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole electoral process starts out with a factory defect,
which is the Fujimori candidacy,'' said Jorge Santistevan de
Noriega, who heads the Office of the People's Defender, a
government ombudsman group in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Alberto Bustamante argues, however, that strong
leaders such as Margaret Thatcher of Britain, Felipe Gonzalez of
Spain and Helmut Kohl of Germany all stayed in power for more than
10 years. He insists that no viable successor to Fujimori has
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread to imagine Peru in 2000 in the hands of any of those
who have appeared at the moment as alternatives,'' he told Peru
Monitor magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the nation's economy has stagnated in the past three
years, and many Peruvians long for change. Last week, police and
soldiers used tear gas to break up hundreds of rock-throwing
protesters who tried to storm the National Palace to denounce
Fujimori's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, however, has made a series of blunders. For
instance, instead of uniting behind one or two figures, eight
opposition candidates have entered the race. None appears to have
caught on with the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Polls give Fujimori a comfortable lead over his nearest rivals _
Lima Mayor Alberto Andrade and Luis Castaneda Lossio, the former
head of the social security institute. If no one receives more than
50 percent of the vote on April 9, a runoff between the two top
finishers will be in June.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition ``hasn't broken out with a message that resonates
with the public,'' said a U.S. Embassy official in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't vote on rule-of-law issues,'' the official said.
``They vote on your record of success, and Fujimori has a strong
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say, however, that it's been nearly impossible for
opposition candidates to take their case to the public.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Carter Center report, television stations have
been ``openly hostile and biased'' toward opposition candidates,
denying them regular access and, in some cases, refusing to accept
their campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   The report pointed out that the Peruvian government is the
single largest buyer of TV and radio ad time. Most television
stations have outstanding tax debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the tacit threat of calling in these debts or
withdrawing a major source of advertising income that acts as a
disincentive for media corporations to sell spots to opposition
candidates,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Fujimori has received far more TV coverage than his
rivals, according to Transparencia, a Lima-based electoral
monitoring group. In November, for example, stories on the
president made up 80 percent of TV campaign coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidate Andrade said the dirty war in the press has
paid off for Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, polls showed that 70 percent of Peruvians opposed
re-election. But the media campaign has been so strong and our
image has been so blackened that the only option voters see is
Fujimori,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few newspapers cover the opposition, but most Peruvians read
tabloids that are overwhelmingly pro-government.
</P>
<P>
   Laura de Cordoba, who lives in a Lima slum and gets her news
from television, had trouble naming any of the opposition
candidates. ``We don't know what they would do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Chavez, a pro-Fujimori legislator, said that the
president gets more coverage simply because of his office. ``It's
not like he's a small-town mayor. There are always 20 or 30
reporters trailing him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition also has faced mysterious power outages
during their rallies as well as counter-demonstrations by Fujimori
supporters. One candidate was targeted by Peru's tax agency for an
aggressive audit within two weeks of entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Fujimori has capitalized on his incumbency by
inaugurating bridges, schools and health clinics across the
country. Last week, he even promised free land for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Santistevan, the human rights ombudsman, said that with the help
of outside observers, there is still time to improve conditions and
mount fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the international community wants to help, they must come
now and make their judgments and try to influence events,'' he
said. ``Most of the time, they just come for election day. But we
are asking for observation in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has denounced Fujimori's
anti-democratic measures. But because he has fully cooperated with
U.S. counter-drug policies, many analysts believe that Washington
would not object to a third term for Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the civil war in nearby Colombia, last month's coup in
Ecuador and the election of a former coup-plotter as president of
Venezuela, Peru can seem like an island of stability, said Diego
Garcia-Sayan of the Andean Commission of Jurists.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside, Peru is seen as a factor of equilibrium in
an area that would otherwise be complete chaos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
