<HEADLINE>
WILL DEATH PENALTY'S FOES STOP AT NOTHING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bleeding hearts are at it again.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-capital punishment crowd has now gone to bat for Texas
Death Row inmate Betty Lou Beets, 62, who has a date with the
executioner Thursday for the crime of shooting her fifth husband in
his sleep and then burying him in the front yard. Her fourth
husband also turned up shot to death and buried in a shallow grave
not far from where No. 5 was buried.
</P>
<P>
   She shot at least one other husband, although that mate survived
the two bullets she put in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Beets is sometimes referred to as the ``Black Widow'' due to her
penchant for murdering spouses rather than disposing of them
through the more conventional means of divorce.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about some kindly grandma who accidentally
dropped some cyanide into granddaddy's oatmeal. This woman is a
cold-blooded killer.
</P>
<P>
   But the death penalty opponents insist that the state of Texas
should spare Beets' life rather than administer the lethal
injection that she so richly deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose there could ever be a murderer so vicious, so
vile, so irredeemable that these people would be unable or
unwilling to summon up a hysterical outbreak of weeping and
teeth-gnashing over his or her impending demise?
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough when the pro-killer forces invent some phony
argument in support of the idea that the killer is innocent,
claiming that 10 eyewitnesses were hallucinating or wearing dirty
contact lenses or perhaps fingered the defendant because he
reminded them of the schoolyard bully who used to steal their lunch
money.
</P>
<P>
   But what's really insulting _ to the killer's victims, to the
public and to the cause of justice _ is when the evidence of guilt
is unassailable and the bleeding hearts resort to conjuring up some
outrageous rationale for nullifying the death sentence even as they
concede that the killer is the killer.
</P>
<P>
   You know. Karla Faye Tucker was a born-again Christian. Larry
Keith Robison was mentally incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Lou Beets was a victim of wife abuse.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. That's why the death penalty opponents are saying we
should cancel Betty Lou's appointment with the needle. Her
husband(s) abused her.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a question: Did she kill the fifth husband in retaliation
for abuse that he inflicted or because she was abused by husband
No. 4? And was husband No. 4 subjected to multiple gunshot wounds
in the head because he treated Beets badly or because she was still
mad at that other husband, the one who had the audacity to survive
those bullets she fired into his back?
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're willing to buy into the idea that spouse abuse is
a justification for murder, Beets hasn't produced a shred of
evidence that she was abused by Jimmy Don Beets, whose slaying
earned her the death penalty. Her lawyer, in fact, was interviewed
on Court TV the other day and all but admitted that the murder
victim never laid a hand on the alleged abuse victim.
</P>
<P>
   The killer, meanwhile, has been sobbing and whining for the
benefit of anyone who gets near her with a camera or a notebook in
a disgustingly transparent campaign to generate public sympathy. At
least Karla Faye admitted her guilt and showed some dignity during
that farewell round of interviews shortly before her execution.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Texas is that the Lone Star State has a
tough-minded governor who understands the value of capital
punishment and won't be buffaloed by nonsense such as abuse-excuse
pleas on behalf of Beets or the recent unfounded demands for a
moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Gov. George Ryan might have valid reasons for ordering
a moratorium in his state. Gov. George W. Bush says no such action
is needed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have had full access to the courts,''
Bush said in response to a question by CNN's Larry King during last
week's presidential debate in South Carolina. ``There's no doubt in
my mind that each person who's been executed in our state was
guilty of the crime committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Say goodnight, Betty Lou.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
