<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-21 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 27)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WOMAN: An Intimate Biography &LR;  By Natalie Angier. Anchor, $15. A
Pulitzer Prize-winning science writer for The New York Times
conducts a rapturous tour of the female body and its intricate
workings, drawing on evolutionary theory, science, literature,
medicine and history. ```Woman' is a tour de force, a wonderful,
entertaining and informative book,'' Abraham Verghese wrote in The
New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST INTO UPPER EAST: Plain Tales From New York and New Delhi &LR; 
By Ruth Prawer Jhabvala. Counterpoint, $14. These stories by a
connoisseur of divided souls, written over the last 20 years or so
and set in gilded Manhattan co-ops and expensive Indian villas,
focus on rootless characters whose inner longings are at odds with
their protective coloration. In 1998 the reviewer Deborah Mason
called the author ``a spellbinding urban fabulist'' and said ``each
story reveals Jhabvala's mastery of the form.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; OUT OF INDIA: Selected Stories &LR; 
($14), a collection of Jhabvala's early tales that explore the
domestic lives of middle-class Indians and the spiritual yearning
of Westerners who flock to often-bogus ashrams. In 1986 in The New
York Times Book Review, Rumer Godden said the stories display ``her
hallmark of balance, subtlety, wry humor and beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FORTRESS AMERICA: The American Military and the Consequences of
Peace &LR;  By William Greider. PublicAffairs, $10. A journalist
searches for the ``peace dividend'' that was supposed to follow the
Cold War, and discovers instead a bloated military establishment
dedicated to building an increasingly chaotic and obsolescent
arsenal. This ``is the kind of book that leaves a reader agitated
and indignant, and should by all rights ignite an urgent national
debate,'' James B. Stewart wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSE OF SAND AND FOG &LR;  By Andre Dubus III. Vintage
Contemporaries, $14. In this tale of good people gone crazy, three
characters collide in Pacific suburbia: an Iranian immigrant, a
California woman who loses her home to him in an auction, and a
deputy sheriff who comes between them. In 1999 the reviewer Bill
Sharp admired the novel's ``highly visual, descriptive language.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE: Superstrings, Hidden Dimensions, and the
Quest for the Ultimate Theory &LR;  By Brian Greene. Vintage, $15. A
Columbia professor makes a case for string theory, which posits a
universe with 10 curled-up dimensions and melds quantum mechanics
with the general theory of relativity. ``In the great tradition of
physicists writing for the masses, `The Elegant Universe' sets a
standard that will be hard to beat,'' George Johnson wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEONS, BLACK HOLES, AND QUANTUM FOAM: A Life in Physics &LR; , by
John Archibald Wheeler with Kenneth Ford (Norton, $14.95), is an
account of the Princeton physicist's long career (he worked on the
Manhattan Project) and highly regarded theoretical work on atomic
nuclei and gravitation (he coined the term ``black hole'').
``Difficult concepts that defy common sense come briskly to life,''
Michael Riordan wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXTREMITIES: Stories &LR;  By Kathe Koja. Four Walls Eight Windows,
$13.95. In these unsettling tales, a survivor of a plane crash
changes into a bird and a woman transforms herself into a plant to
remain near her boyfriend. ``Koja's provocative story lines and
evocative prose combine reality with invention, the supernatural
with the everyday,'' Christopher Atamian wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WISCONSIN DEATH TRIP &LR;  By Michael Lesy. University of New
Mexico, $29.95. This 1973 chronicle of a rural Wisconsin town
ravaged by depression, madness and epidemic disease at the turn of
the century combines many haunting old photographs with local
newspaper accounts. ``The result is an impressive example of the
poetry of history,'' William H. Gass wrote. ``This original work
makes us deeply feel one form that misery has taken.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALLAN STEIN &LR;  By Matthew Stadler. Grove, $12. A young teacher
visits Paris in search of information about Gertrude Stein's nephew
and becomes obsessed with a 15-year-old boy. ``Stadler demonstrates
that he is among the handful of first-rate young American
novelists, one with a wide reach and a quirky, elegant pen,''
Edmund White wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WITH OSSIE AND RUBY: In This Life Together &LR;  By Ossie Davis and
Ruby Dee. Quill/Morrow, $14. The actors reflect on their
childhoods, the black experience in American theater and the many
social causes they have championed during their more than 50 years
together. In 1998 the reviewer Victor Navasky called this ``a
conversation studded with anecdotes ... and also some inspiration,
wisdom and gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MISTRESS &LR;  By Philippe Tapon. Plume, $12.95. Emile Bastien
is a French doctor living comfortably with his mistress in
Nazi-occupied Paris until his affair, his family and his livelihood
are threatened by betrayal and perilous wartime allegiances. Last
year the reviewer Liam Callanan called this ``a fine, wicked'' and
``altogether enjoyable'' novel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
