<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5861 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-SECURITY-REV     02-21 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SECURITY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICING THE INTERNET: ANYONE BUT GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDS: Replace double parentheses (( )) with single brackets) 
(bl) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The attacks on eBay, Yahoo, Etrade and other big Web sites
earlier this month showed the Internet to be surprisingly
vulnerable to a few laptop-toting cyber-vandals. This is a pressing
public concern, surely, as the nation increasingly comes to rely
for commerce and everyday communication on this chaotic, global
computer network.
</P>
<P>
   But when President Clinton met last Tuesday with more than two
dozen representatives of the Internet community, a big role for
government was not on the agenda. The president asked what could or
should the government do. Not a lot, the Internet elite told him.
The group's message: It's an industry issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in that room was asking the government to fix this
problem,'' said Nicholas Donofrio, senior vice president for
technology at IBM, who attended the meeting in the Cabinet Room of
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering epitomized the main thrust of government policy in
the Internet arena. Government, the theory goes, should offer a
forum and be a cooperative partner, so as to facilitate the rapid
rise of Internet commerce. That stance was set in a July 1997
policy document on e-commerce written by Ira Magaziner, a senior
White House policy adviser at the time. His document extolled the
``breakneck speed of change in the technology'' and stated,
``Government attempts to regulate ((the Internet)) are likely to be
outmoded by the time they are finally enacted.''
</P>
<P>
   The hands-off approach, however, will be challenged more and
more as the Internet moves rapidly into the mainstream. For just as
the Net creates new forms of commerce, it also opens a door to new
forms of crime. And the malicious hackers who recently brought down
the big commercial Web sites by jamming them with a flood of bits _
a tactic known as denial-of-service attacks _ are but one example.
</P>
<P>
   Online con artists are doing a booming business. In a report to
the Justice Department in January, the National Consumers League
warned, ``The Internet has become the new frontier of fraud.'' The
Federal Trade Commission, for example, reports an alarming surge in
consumer complaints of fraud on Internet auction sites, to more
than 10,000 last year from about 100 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yet combating such crimes seems to be among the easier Internet
issues to handle. Cracking down will require some new tools, new
skills and new forms of cooperation among federal and state
agencies. The FBI, Justice Department and FTC are increasing their
computer crime and Internet fraud squads. But the issue appears to
be mainly one of enforcement, not the need for new laws or
policies. The problem seems manageable, even familiar in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   Other new technologies, from cars to credit cards, have prompted
dire warnings that they would bring a flood of crime. In the early
1900s, the automobile was seen as an ideal means for bank robbers
and murderers to flee before police could catch them. Criminals did
use them, but police got their own cars and motorcycles, cars were
licensed and federal agents were allowed to pursue suspects across
state lines. Later, credit cards were seen as a license for fraud.
And, indeed, credit card fraud exceeds $1 billion a year. But law
enforcement authorities and industry have kept it a manageable cost
of doing business, amounting to roughly 9 cents for every $100 of
goods purchased by credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The thornier policy issues raised by the Internet concern
privacy and antitrust matters. On privacy, the United States has so
far adopted a self-regulatory approach, letting the online industry
set its own policies for collecting personal data on computer users
who visit Web sites _ and for informing users of those policies and
how they can opt out. The FTC is monitoring the industry's efforts,
saying that self-regulation, if effective, is more flexible and
thus preferable to direct government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates and other critics say self regulation
gives too much power to Internet companies and too little to
consumers. The danger, they warn, is that increasingly
sophisticated software will soon allow marketers to track a user's
every mouse click and then match that information with demographic
databases to establish online profiles of individuals. Those
profiles could, in theory, be used to determine not only what
online marketing pitches people see, but also potentially what job
and education opportunities people are offered.
</P>
<P>
   The industry says such concerns are overstated. But the FTC
recently began investigating how medical Web sites handle personal
information. And last week, DoubleClick, the Internet's leading
advertising placement company, reported that the FTC was
investigating how the company collected and used personal data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the profiling technology disturbing _ this notion of
checking on consumer viewing habits without them knowing it _
especially if that information is then merged with other databases
so they can be identified,'' said Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the
FTC.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy issue is so sensitive that Robert Litan, an
economist at the Brookings Institution, recommends ``minimalist''
privacy legislation to engender consumer trust and ensure the rapid
development of E-commerce. The effect, he says, would be similar to
legislation in the 1970s limiting a person's liability to $50 if
his credit card is lost and used fraudulently, which eased consumer
worries about credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the more innovative views of government's role in the
Internet era comes from Lawrence Lessig, an antitrust scholar and
the author of ``Code and Other Laws of Cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessig argues that the headlong commercialization of the
Internet threatens its decentralization and openness _ the
technological ``architecture,'' as he puts it _ that has made
wide-open innovation, competition and free expression essential
features of the Internet. That core architecture, he explains, is a
network that has open access and public software standards so that
anyone can communicate over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig sees the efforts of cable television operators, who are
beginning to offer high-speed Internet service, to deny competing
Internet services access to their cable network as one such threat
to the openness of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government should be pro-active early on to make sure the
architecture of the Internet remains open,'' Lessig said. ``If you
get the architecture right, the regulation takes care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But other experts are skeptical of the need for much government
involvement, all the more so of the pre-emptive variety advocated
by Lessig. The answer they offer is to let markets work _ the
Internet being first and foremost an extremely efficient market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there a role for government and that policy must be
informed by the new technology,'' said Carl Shapiro, an economist
at the University of California at Berkeley. ``But the fact is the
technology is enabling an enormous amount of new competition and
breaking down barriers. The Internet is off and running, and for
the most part the government should stay out of its way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
