<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAM-MILITANTS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LEBANON AND IRAN, A TIME OF TESTING FOR ISLAMIC ZEALOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABATIYE, Lebanon _ A group of hard-eyed men from Hezbollah, the
Party of God, were driving an American correspondent down a narrow
road outside this village in southern Lebanon last week when the
visitor pointed through the open car window toward an Israeli
fortification high on a rocky hill to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Something on the hill was glinting in the blinding sunshine. It
was probably an Israeli soldier's binoculars, and the reaction of
the Hezbollah fighters was quick and angry. ``In the name of Allah,
don't point!'' the driver said, turning the car and racing back
toward the village. ``If you point, the Israelis will think you're
aiming at them, and they'll hit us with their 155-millimeters.''
</P>
<P>
   The reproach was a hard lesson, but it was nothing compared with
the cold fury of the Hezbollah men a little later while driving
past billboards showing the supreme icons of Hezbollah's brand of
Shiite Muslim fundamentalism _ Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who led
Iran's Islamic revolution in 1979, and his successor as the Islamic
Republic's supreme religious leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
Blundering again, the reporter asked where were the images of
Iran's president, Mohammed Khatami, an Islamic reformer whose calls
for greater democracy and human rights have electrified his country
and crystalized the battle between reformers and conservatives that
culminated in the Iranian parliamentary election held Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This time the driver slowed, looked back at his questioner with
something approaching contempt, then fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   Among militant Shiites in Lebanon, apparently, Khatami is a
nonperson, somebody who merits only scowls. Later, much the same
reaction was evident in Hezbollah's heavily guarded sanctuaries in
the southern suburbs of Beirut, where Hezbollah leaders are
preparing to face up to their own day of reckoning. That will be
the moment in July when Israeli troops complete their promised
withdrawal from Lebanon and leave Hezbollah to make a historic
choice between the militant Islamic policies of its past and
mounting pressure for more pragmatism _ particularly if Lebanon's
neighbor and protector Syria resumes seeking peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of holding high the banner of Islamic
fundamentalism, the conservative mullahs of Iran and their
counterparts in the leadership of Lebanon's Hezbollah have arrived,
more or less simultaneously, at their respective political
Rubicons, the point at which their cause will either adjust or
wither. Partly this is a matter of coincidence, of political
timetables in Iran and Lebanon that have their separate logics. But
there are common factors, too, as there have been since the first
stirrings of Shiite clerical insurgency in the two countries more
than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching any broad conclusions about the tide of affairs in the
Islamic world is fraught with hazard, considering that there are
more than 50 Muslim nations, comprising more than a billion people,
vastly different cultures in Africa, the Middle East and Asia, and
a deep theological and political schism between the world's 800
million Sunni Muslims and 200 million Shiites. But some trends are
too compelling to ignore; the events now unfolding in Iran and
Lebanon, suggesting a broader movement toward political realism in
the Shiite world, are among them.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Sunni-Shiite schism, tracing back to the dynastic
rupture that followed the death of the Muslim Prophet Mohammed in
632 A.D., it would take an intrepid chronicler to suggest that
something still broader may be stirring across all of Islam _ a
slow, even crab-like move away from the militancy that seemed like
a rising tide at the onset of the 1990s. After all, Osama Bin
Laden, the heir to a Saudi Arabian fortune who is the world's
most-wanted terrorist leader, is still at large in Afghanistan,
with cells of armed supporters spread widely through the Middle
East, North Africa and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Other forms of Islamic militancy continue to lurk, on the
fringes of power or underground, in dozens of countries _
Indonesia, Pakistan, Egypt, Sudan, Algeria among them. Some experts
think the world has yet to see the high tide of Sunni
fundamentalism, an equivalent of the Shiite revolution in Iran in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, what seems inescapable is that the men who
kick-started the wave of Islamic militancy in the modern world, the
Shiite clerics of Iran and Lebanon, have their backs to the wall,
even if few hard-line mullahs in either country seem ready to fly
the white flag just yet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, where huge numbers of voters turned out for
parliamentary elections last week, the results will take days to
compile and it is possible that reformers, divided among themselves
and deprived of some of their best candidates by pre-election
screeners loyal to Khamenei, may have to settle for something less
than outright victory.
</P>
<P>
   And in Lebanon, a surface appraisal would suggest that
Hezbollah, after 15 years of battling Israeli troops, is on the
verge of its brightest moment yet, the unilateral Israeli pullout
promised by Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But in Lebanon, as in Iran, the longer-run trends seem to lie
against the militants. With Israel's troops gone, the Islamic group
will be deprived of its most powerful card, and Lebanon's 3.5
million people will be left to weigh whether they want to give the
group more political power than it already has with its minority
bloc in the Lebanese parliament. Every sign says that they do not.
In recent times, Hezbollah has even been rewriting history,
pretending it had nothing to do with the brutal terrorism it
sponsored in the 1980s, and playing down its commitment to an
Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in Iran, the long run seems to strongly favor the
pragmatists, if only because of demographics. The young constitute
a great bulge in Iran's population _ people under 25 who are too
young to remember the revolution or to have fought against Iraq or
to do anything today but chafe at the social restrictions Khomeini
imposed as the price of liberation from the rule of Shah Mohammed
Reza Pahlavi. Those young are a formidable, and growing, base of
support for the forces of reform.
</P>
<P>
   If the pragmatic trends hold, it will be an ironic comeuppance
for the Shiite fundamentalists, who once viewed the Iran-Lebanon
axis as the basis for building an eventual Islamic superstate. Only
in Lebanon, it seems, do many people remember that it was here, in
the 1960s, that Musa al-Sadr, an Iranian-born Shiite cleric,
pioneered the populist form of Shiite political awakening that
found its ultimate expression in the Islamic revolution in Iran.
Revered by Shiite moderates and revolutionaries alike, he
disappeared on a trip to Libya in 1978, the apparent victim of a
plot by the Libyan leader Moammar el-Gadhafi, a Sunni Muslim who,
most Lebanese Shiites suppose, did not favor the rise of Shiite
fundamentalist power in the heart of the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months after Sadr's luggage turned up off a
Tripoli-Rome flight without Sadr, Khomeini was on a flight from
Paris to Tehran, where he declared the Islamic state that turned
Iran upside down. Within a few years, the militant Lebanese Shiites
who felt orphaned by Sadr's disappearance were empowered again when
Khomeini sent 5,000 Iranian revolutionary guards to Lebanon's Bekaa
valley, where they armed, trained and indoctrinated the Hezbollah
force that went to war against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in both countries, the hard-line clerics are faced with
evanescent dreams. About the only solace for them may be that their
Shiite faith has rested from the start on a cult of dispossession,
betrayal and defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Shiites believe that Sunnis usurped the rightful
inheritance of Ali, the Prophet Mohammed's son-in-law and the
Shiites' first imam, so now the hard-liners may come to believe
that their enemies on earth have wrested from them the Islamic
state that, according to the militants, was the millennarian
promise vouchsafed them by the Prophet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
