<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GORE-BUDDHISTS-REVIEW     02-21 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUDDHISTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUND-RAISING SCANDAL SHRINKS TO A SHADOW OF ITSELF _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the same federal courthouse where Kenneth
Starr's grand jury met, Maria Hsia, an obscure California
immigration consultant, sits silently at the defense table dressed
in a neat yellow sweater set and black skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia is the only figure embroiled in the 1996 Democratic
fund-raising scandal to face a full trial so far. Other party
fund-raisers, like John Huang and Yah Lin Trie, have pleaded guilty
to charges growing out of the scandal, and Pauline Kanchanalak,
another fairly obscure figure, is awaiting trial. But no senior
Democratic National Committee officials were ever charged. In a
much criticized decision, Attorney General Janet Reno decided
against appointing an independent counsel to investigate the fund
raising of either President Clinton or Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So, after four years of congressional hearings and federal
criminal investigation, it could all boil down to Hsia. In an
interesting piece of legal symmetry, Hsia's lawyer, Nancy Luque,
also represented Julie Hiatt Steele, a tangential figure in the
Monica Lewinsky investigation, who was the only person to face
criminal charges in the White House sex and lies scandal. (After a
jury deadlocked, Steele was not convicted).
</P>
<P>
   Hsia is charged with engaging in an illicit scheme to reimburse
Democratic contributors, including donations connected to the
now-infamous luncheon held at the Hsi Lai Temple in Hacienda
Heights, Calif., which was attended by Gore. Hsia has pleaded not
guilty. The vice president has said he had no knowledge of the
$55,000 in illicit contributions to the Democratic Party collected
from donors at the temple.
</P>
<P>
   But the temple fund-raiser shadows Gore, particularly as he
campaigns for the March 7 primary in California. Sen. John McCain
has savagely mocked Gore's varying statements about the event
(initially the vice president denied knowing it was a fund-raiser).
On the Democratic side, former Sen. Bill Bradley has warned that
the fund-raising scandal is an unremovable stain on Gore's record.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom last week, it was clear the Hsia trial could
provide Republicans with fodder for attack ads against Gore. Among
the exhibits was a videotape of Gore making his entrance at the Hsi
Lai temple on April 29, 1996, and then giving a speech surrounded
by enthusiastic worshippers in robes. The judge presiding over the
case noted that members of Congress, presumably Republicans, had
already called for copies, while Luque argued against releasing the
tape. ``My concern is that I can just see it played because the
vice president is campaigning on March 7 in California,'' she said.
(On Friday, the judge decided to keep the tape under wraps until a
verdict is reached.)
</P>
<P>
   There are no media throngs filling the grass and concrete area
in front of the courthouse known as ``the beach'' during the Monica
Lewinsky spectacle. The Hsia case involves far less sensational
testimony, including complicated federal election laws, party
allocation formulas and four-year-old allegations of fund-raising
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   That is how the Gore campaign would like it to remain. But the
video isn't the only trial exhibit that could cause Gore problems.
Luque also introduced into evidence a color photograph of Hsia and
a broadly smiling Gore, with longer and much bushier hair, during a
trip they made to Taiwan in 1989. It was during that trip, arranged
by Hsia and Huang, that Gore first met the temple's leader,
Venerable Master Hsing Yun.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia is charged with providing Huang and others with checks
signed by monks, nuns and other straw donors who were reimbursed
for their donations by the temple and other illegal sources.
</P>
<P>
   The marquee witness last week was Huang, who testified that he
knew nothing of the reimbursement. Huang occasionally shot a sad
glance toward Hsia, who was once his good friend and political
comrade. In the late 1980s, they helped organize the Pacific
Leadership Council in order to gain more clout for Asian-Americans
in California. To achieve that goal, Huang explained, they started
raising money for Democratic Senate candidates, including Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Huang's testimony certainly exposed some of the dark side of
fund-raising. He made it clear that both he and Hsia were under
intense pressure from the party to bring in money. He said that
fund-raising events featuring Gore were expected to generate
$200,000 and that the temple event had fallen far short of that
amount. He said he called Hsia after the luncheon and urged her to
help him reach his goal of taking at least $100,000 back to
Washington with him. He said he knew this meant she would return to
the temple for more money and when he met her there later, she
handed him an envelope with checks totaling $100,000. Among the
checks were those from the monks and nuns who were later illegally
reimbursed by the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Backus, a spokesman for the Democratic National Committee,
said the party was unaware of the reimbursement scheme or of any
illegal fund raising by Huang, who pleaded guilty to a single
conspiracy charge last August. The committee returned all the money
raised at the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Huang said he needed dignitaries from Washington to draw donors
to events in California. He had wanted Gore to attend two events, a
fund-raising luncheon at a Los Angeles restaurant and a visit to
the temple that would not involve soliciting donations. But Huang
was told Gore would only have time for one stop, and so the two
events were collapsed into one. ``Everything was on a tight
schedule,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, his testimony was helpful to Gore and Hsia. The
fact that the two events were hurriedly combined and the temple
visit was not originally scheduled as a fund-raiser may help
explain why the vice president at first described it as a
``community outreach'' luncheon. And Luque said that Gore did not
give a fund-raising speech at the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia's trial has renewed criticism from Asian-American political
activists that relatively small fry like Huang and Hsia have been
singled out for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But Hsia has had kind words for Gore. In an interview last year,
she said: ``I've met dozens of politicians. The others come saying,
`Money, money.' By comparison, he is a more genuine person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
