<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-PROSTITUTION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS LOVE FOR MONEY, RIGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By LAURA MANSNERUS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many Americans so repelled by ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' that they watched it in astonishing numbers,
Scott Shuger, a columnist for Slate, came away with questions. He
wrote: ``How is this show, with its explicit cash and property
prizes for the woman, not prostitution?''
</P>
<P>
   The question may have been rhetorical, of course. No one said
anything about a sexual quid-pro-quo on the Fox special aired from
Las Vegas last week, and it ended in a wedding ceremony minutes
after Rick Rockwell, described as a real estate investor and
motivational speaker, chose Darva Conger, a nurse, from a field of
50 women who competed to marry a man they had never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arrangement struck some as akin to prostitution or
soliciting prostitution, both crimes under Nevada statutes. After
all, a woman was promising sex to a stranger in expectation of some
of his assets, and prostitution is defined by law as ``engaging in
sexual conduct for a fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the crime of pandering, in which a third party
``induces, persuades, encourages, inveigles, entices or compels a
person to engage in prostitution.'' Fox did inveigle, and it
offered the winner an Isuzu Trooper and a $35,000 diamond ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas authorities are not on the case. ``I don't watch
television,'' said J. Charles Thompson, the deputy district
attorney, although he said the show sounded like something his wife
had mentioned because her beautician was talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the marriage would nullify a possible prostitution
charge, he replied: ``It's often the case that people have sex and
then get married, but you can do it the other way. We don't mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like something that's going to be big on our
list to prosecute,'' Thompson continued. His office's top
priorities are murder, robbery and rape, he said, though there is
the occasional prostitution arrest. ``If you're hanging on a street
corner with your thumb out saying you'll do certain things for 20
bucks,'' he said, ``we have vice cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve George, a spokesman for the state attorney general's
office, said of Fox's contest, ``They're not selling sex,'' though
he quickly added, ``It may be an end product.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox assured viewers that the entire production was legal. And it
arranged for all 50 contestants to sign a prenuptial agreement
protecting Rockwell's assets, just in case things don't work out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
