unable to keep up with the fast horse of mere information.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) And so we grow bored. But boredom isn't all
bad. In ``Boredom and the Religious Imagination'' (University Press
of Virginia, 1999) Michael L. Raposa, a religion professor at
Lehigh University, argues that it can be a catalyst to religious
insight: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced that there is a great deal to be learned from the
