<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-UNIVERSE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-21 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY CHECK: A SMALL STEP FOR MAN, A GIANT LEAP OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who grew up in the 1950s and '60s, mesmerized by the
predictions in Life magazine or The Saturday Evening Post of
exploring the solar system and establishing colonies on the Moon
and Mars, it might have been a little depressing to gaze half a
century ahead to what counts as a big space story in the year 2000:
the visit of an unmanned craft _ with not even a dog or a monkey
inside _ to a lifeless asteroid barely beyond Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The simple probe called the Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous met
up with Eros, a 21-mile-long, potato-shaped space rock named, for
some reason, after the Greek god of love, on Valentine's Day.
Adding to the sappy coincidences, the craft's camera spotted a
confluence of shadows on the asteroid that looked like a big heart
_ ``a valentine from Eros,'' mission director Robert Farquhar
called it.
</P>
<P>
   But as mundane as the voyage may have seemed, there was no need
to strain for a good sound bite. Any success, of course, would be
encouraging after last year's disappointing near misses by the Mars
Climate Orbiter and Mars Polar Lander. There was much more, though,
to NASA's accomplishment. In a day when a steady stream of exotic
scientific speculations overwhelms the public imagination _ tiny
superstrings vibrating in a 10-dimensional universe, invisible
parallel worlds, wormholes tunneling through space and time _ a
comfortable satisfaction can be taken from a modest technological
triumph like NEAR.
</P>
<P>
   The closest most people will get to science's more ethereal
wonders is through animations on TV science shows or planetarium
megascreens. At the new Rose Center for Earth and Space at the
American Museum of Natural History in New York, which opened this
weekend, visitors can take a visual tour of the galaxy and beyond,
finally plunging through a black hole, emerging unscathed onto West
81st Street.
</P>
<P>
   With so many things about the universe that can only be
simulated or imagined, there was something wonderfully direct about
the four-year asteroid mission that reached its destination last
week. The NASA scientists reminded us that for all we don't know
about the universe, when it comes to the basics, earthlings have it
down cold: Put the equations for the trajectory to an asteroid into
a computer, plot a three-year course, whip the spacecraft around
the Earth to give it a gravity boost _ and when you miss your tiny
target the first time, follow it for another year around the Sun
before carefully moving in for final contact.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:33 a.m. Eastern Standard Earth Time, NEAR came within
striking distance (203 miles) of Eros. It fired its thrusters for
57 seconds, slowing itself just enough (about 30 feet a second) to
be gently pulled, as planned, into the asteroid's field of gravity.
There it became the first artificial satellite to orbit one of
these flying rocks. All this precise maneuvering took place 160
million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   With their digital observer in place, the scientists began
downloading photos of the barren terrain, posting them one by one
on the NASA Web site (www.nasa.gov). Planetary scientists prepared
for a yearlong study of the asteroid's geology, seeking clues to
the formation of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   If this wouldn't make much of a ``Star Trek'' episode, it is
only because viewers have become so spoiled. Whether they glean the
details from the latest issue of Scientific American or from the
newest Michael Crichton novel, legions of popular science fans have
become accustomed to increasingly fantastic revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month at a meeting in Atlanta of the American Astronomical
Society, scientists described how the orbiting Chandra X-Ray
Observatory remotely took the temperature of a black hole at the
core of the neighboring Andromeda galaxy, as though it were
possible to insert a thermometer, deftly removing it just before it
was swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, physicists meeting at a conference in
Pasadena, Calif., discussed the latest twists in what used to be
called superstring theory. It now goes by the name M theory, with
the M sometimes said to stand for ``magic,'' ``mystery'' or
``mother of all theories.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving an idea of just how fast the theoretical forefront is
moving, Stephen Hawking hailed what he called ``the most exciting
idea in the last 12 months.'' Speaking with his voice synthesizer,
five-second pauses separating each sentence, he explored some of
the consequences of a recent suggestion that this universe is a
four-dimensional membrane floating inside a five-dimensional
universe.
</P>
<P>
   The last reason to reject a hypothesis is because it defies
narrow conceptions of common sense. The curved space-time of
Einstein's general theory of relativity and the paradoxical
predictions of quantum mechanics have proved to be powerfully
precise tools for explaining what is going on in the world. Trying
to merge these two theories into a single picture of creation has
yielded an explosion of perplexing new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing there is a growing appetite for this stuff _ and the
weirder the better _ some physicists have taken their case directly
to the public. In his recent book ``Life of the Cosmos,'' Lee
Smolin, a physicist at Pennsylvania State University, argues that
our universe is but one among many in a ``multiverse'' _ a kind of
cosmic ecosystem in which universes compete in a Darwinian struggle
to reproduce. (The baby universes are spawned through black holes _
cosmic wombs.)
</P>
<P>
   In the latest addition to this genre, ``The End of Time,'' a
British physicist named Julian Barbour lays out an elaborate theory
in which time turns out to be an illusion. Every instant past and
future coexists in an eternal present he calls Platonia _ a
hypothesis put forth earlier by the American theorist Kurt Vonnegut
(see ``Slaughterhouse Five'').
</P>
<P>
   With theories getting wilder and wilder, real physics and
fictional physics _ call it phiction _ have become mashed into a
new folklore. When writers for ``Star Trek'' need to bring back a
dead character or reverse a pivotal event, they can simply invoke a
space-time distortion or declare that what seemed so persuasive was
just a simulation on the holodeck. (In the old series ``Dallas,''
resurrecting the beloved Bobby required tweaking the script so that
his tragic death turned out to be somebody's dream.)
</P>
<P>
   When causality appears so mushy, tragedy becomes impossible. If
a story's essential turning point _ what Aristotle called
peripeteia _ can be undone at will, the drama starts to leak away.
Whether the entertainment comes from science or science fiction, an
old-fashioned narrative sometimes comes as a relief. That's what we
got from NEAR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
