<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to the Onetime Fire Wall State
</P>
<P>
   A few days before Saturday's South Carolina primary, a
Reuters/Zogby poll of Republicans, Democrats and independents
showed Gov. George W. Bush with 42.7 percent and Sen. John McCain
with 42 percent. And this was supposed to have been Bush's fire
wall state _ the one he would win in a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's been a nasty firefight, the sort that Lee Atwater,
that son of bare-knuckle Palmetto politics, would have loved.
</P>
<P>
   After the dull ``No, you first'' courtliness of New Hampshire,
South Carolina brought the invigorating ugliness of ``push
polling,'' in which Bush campaign callers, posing as unbiased
pollsters, did their best to trash McCain.
</P>
<P>
   This primary also highlighted the increasingly independent South
Carolina electorate. Transplanted business people, part of the
state's growing connection to the global economy, upwardly mobile
suburbanites and retirees on the coast have made politics here more
cosmopolitan and less predictable. The big question all week was
how many Democrats and independents might weigh in on McCain's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right remains influential, but uncertainly so.
Both these traits could be seen in Gary L. Bauer's endorsement of
McCain. On the one hand, McCain was assumed to benefit; on the
other hand, no one was sure how much; and on the third hand, it was
duly noted that Bauer had endorsed a candidate who hasn't pledged
to outlaw abortion or to hew to other issues dear to the religious
right.
</P>
<P>
   All the energy and anxiety engendered by this fluctuating
environment were on display last week in a shrill televised debate
ineffectually moderated by Larry King. The spectacle of a McCain
smiling a tight smile to mask his famous anger and an agitated Bush
sputtering in indignation _ both far less articulate than Keyes _
was compelling enough to make one forget that a couple of testy
Democrats, with no primary until next month, were also campaigning
somewhere or another.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Bush, who has already spent a mind-boggling $52
million, will soon have to ask his backers for more money.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Man Who Created the Kid In Us All
</P>
<P>
   Charles M. Schulz, the creator of the comic strip ``Peanuts,''
died Saturday night, Feb. 12, just hours before his last comic ran.
He was 77. The strip was 50.
</P>
<P>
   From the day the strip was first published, Oct. 2, 1950, the
lives of the comic and its creator were entwined. Schulz once said,
``This is my excuse for existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the humor of ``Peanuts'' was gentle, it was dark, too.
``All the loves in the strip are unrequited,'' Schulz once said,
``all the baseball games are lost, all the test scores are D
minuses; the Great Pumpkin never comes; and the football is always
pulled away.''
</P>
<P>
   What accounted for the pull of ``Peanuts''? Umberto Eco, the
novelist and semiotician, who wrote the introduction to the first
``Peanuts'' book translated into Italian, thought it captured
modern neurosis. Schulz's wife, Jeannie, said the characters were
parts of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Schulz said, he woke up in the middle of the night
thinking about Charlie Brown, Snoopy, Lucy and Linus and exclaimed:
``Good grief! Who are all these little people? Must I live with
them for the rest of my life?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was yes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH BOXER
</P>
<P>
   A Series of Tornadoes Rip Through Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Residents of southwest Georgia awoke to the sound of wind and
snapping pines, and most had little chance to escape the deadliest
tornadoes to strike the state in more than 50 years. The twisters
killed 18 people, injured more than 100 and destroyed 258 houses,
causing an estimated $20 million in property losses.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   Arms and the IRA
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who shut down the government
of Northern Ireland , continued to keep it shut over disagreements
on how the Irish Republican Army should disarm its arsenal of
weapons, despite demands from Gerry Adams, the president of Sinn
Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army, that the
government be restored. Adams' demands were met by counter demands
from Blair, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, and Ulster Unionist
leader David Trimble that the IRA first return to disarmament
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine Again
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in 10 months, students from Columbine High
School were shot to death. The bodies of two sophomores, Nicholas
Kunselman, 15, and Stephanie Hart, 16, were found behind a counter
in a Littleton, Colo., sandwich shop, just blocks from the school
where two students killed 13 people, and then themselves, last
April. Authorities, who said little about the latest shootings,
interviewed scores of people in the area, hoping to learn whether
robbery or something else was the motive.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL JANOFSKY
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian Investigation
</P>
<P>
   After a two-week verbal standoff, Indonesia's President
Abdurrahman Wahid removed Wiranto, his most prominent general, from
his cabinet pending the outcome of an investigation of his
involvement in atrocities in East Timor. Despite fears of violence
or a military coup, the general went quietly, accepting his
suspension with a smile and stating his obedience to civilian
authority.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   Another World
</P>
<P>
   The universe is expanding at an increasing rate, and the reason
may be a force from another universe. Dr. Andreas Albrecht, a
cosmologist at the University of California in Davis, and his
colleague, Constantinos Skordis, have published a paper showing
that a ubiquitous energy named quintessence could inflate the known
universe like a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quintessence is a very ghostly thing,'' said Nima
Arkani-Hamed, who with his colleagues has presented evidence of how
it might function within the 10 dimensions predicted by superstring
theory, which suggests that all matter is made from small vibrating
strings.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   The Lonelier Crowd
</P>
<P>
   Americans are forsaking face-to-face relationships in favor of
Web surfing and e-mail, according to a nationwide survey by the
Institute for the Quantitative Study of Society. The survey, which
is based on 4,113 telephone interviews, suggests that the Web is
also cutting into time once spent watching television and reading
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Internet defenders responded that the Web enabled people
separated by time or space to stay in close contact and gave new
independence to the aged and infirm. Still, said the study's
principal investigator, Norman Nie, a Stanford political scientist,
``When you spend your time on the Internet, you never hear a human
voice and you never get a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   The People's Choice
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, who has held office since
1980, was given a humiliating vote of no confidence when voters
rejected his proposed new constitution. With the economy in a
shambles, citizens, urban ones in particular, showed no inclination
to strengthen the man many blame for soaring inflation, rising
unemployment and a litany of other ills. A new opposition party
smells blood, and parliamentary elections in April promise to be
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HENRI E. CAUVIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
