</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD IRA WITHDRAWALS BE DELAYED UNTIL THE LAST POSSIBLE DATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I will be 70 1/2 this year and my wife will be 66. I am
fully retired. As you know, one is required to start taking minimum
withdrawals from IRAs the year after he reaches 70 1/2, so for me
that year will be 2001. This means I have only a few months to
position my IRA so as to be most advantageous to me at the time I
must start my required minimum distribution. Would it be advisable
to begin the required minimum distribution from my IRAs this year
rather than having to take two distributions during the first year
if I wait until tax year 2001 to begin the withdrawals? How should
I reallocate my IRA holdings at this time? I have income from the
military, Social Security for myself and my wife, and income other
investments, so I do not need the IRA withdrawals for living
expenses. Therefore, I will take only the minimum withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   G. L. Seal Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. If your goal is to remove money from your IRA as slowly as
possible, you would be better off taking your first mandatory
minimum withdrawal this year rather next year, when you would have
to take two withdrawals, one for the year in which you turned 70
1/2 and another for tax year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math. Your joint and life expectancy is determined by
the ages of yourself and your beneficiary on your birthdays in the
tax year in question.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if you turn 70 1/2 before June 30, you would calculate the
life expectancy using your wife's age of 66 and your age of 71.
Using the IRS life expectancy tables, you would get a life
expectancy of 22.2 years, and divide the IRA balance by 22.2.
</P>
<P>
   If the balance were the same as it currently is, that would
require a withdrawal of $19,690. (If you turn 70 1/2 after June 30,
the calculation would be based on ages of 70 and 66, the divisor
would be 22.5, and the mandatory minimum withdrawal would be only
$19,427.)
</P>
<P>
   In the next tax year, your divisor would fall to 21.7 or 21.3,
again depending on where your birthdate falls. Thus, you would face
withdrawals of $20,144 or $20,522, basing the calculations on the
same theoretical balance. The upshot is that for the two tax years,
your withdrawals would total $39,571 or $40,212.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the effect if you waited until tax year 2001 to
take the withdrawals. If you were age 71 at the end of that year,
the divisor would be 21.7 and you would take two withdrawals of
$20,144, or a total of $40,288. If you were 72 at the end of tax
year 2001, you would face two withdrawals of $20,522 each, for a
total of $41,044.
</P>
<P>
   There is another way that taking your first withdrawal this year
might benefit you. This is that if you wait until tax year 2001 to
take the double withdrawal, the addition of more than $40,000 to
your taxable income might push you into a higher tax bracket, thus
leaving you not only with heavier withdrawals from the IRA, but a
higher tax bill as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for reallocating your IRA portfolio now that you have entered
the age when you must face withdrawals, I see no reason to make a
change. As I break it down, your current IRA portfolio is 31
percent each in stocks and in bond funds, and 38 percent in CDs and
money market funds. (I have divided the assets of a balanced fund
to make that calculation.)
</P>
<P>
   If you like that allocation, which is a fairly typical one for a
person your age, you can simply take the withdrawals
proportionately from each portfolio segment, or take them so as to
realign the portfolio however you like. But if I were doing it, I
would take the actual yields from the bond portfolio and the
CD/money market segments, which I estimate at a little more than
$18,000, and sell only enough of the stock fund shares as you need
to make up the remainder of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be retiring in about three years. I will need income
for the rest of my life, which I plan to draw from a $150,000 bond
portfolio. My investments now consist of about 80 percent in stocks
and stock funds and the rest in bonds or cash. I am leaning toward
the idea of establishing the bond portfolio in the taxable accounts
and leaving the IRA almost fully invested in stocks and stock funds
for growth. This is based on my assumption that the tax
consequences would be the same whether I withdrew dividends from
the IRA or from the nondeferred account _ that is, both taxed as
ordinary income. Is there a fault in my thinking? Also, where is
there a good source of information on IRA withdrawals on the Web?
</P>
<P>
   J.W., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you have worked out the right plan, but the tax
consequences would not be the same if you used the alternative
approach. If you follow your plan, you will have $200,000 in the
IRA, all in stocks. You won't be required to take anything from
that account, and therefore won't have any tax liability, until
after age 70 1/2. You would then have $150,000 in bonds and
$250,000 in stocks in your taxable accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that your bond portfolio yields an average 6.5
percent and that the distributions _ income and capital gains
distributions from funds _ averaged 4 percent. You would thus have
taxable income of $9,600 from the bond holdings and $10,000 from
your stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The latter figure is a hard one to estimate, particularly if the
majority of the holdings in the taxable accounts is mutual funds
rather than common stocks; a funds pattern of capital gains
distribution can be quite irregular, and sometimes have little
relationship to the short-term performance of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   But look what would happen if you built the bond fund in the IRA
and took the yield from there: You would have the same $9,600 in
taxable income from the IRA withdrawals, but you would also have
$16,000 in taxable income from the taxable accounts, meaning you
would have taxable income of $25,600 rather than $19,600.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal way to build the portfolio is to have your bonds in
the taxable account, and to arrange the taxable stock positions so
that they are dominated by common stocks with the lowest dividends,
and by funds that have historically been fairly tax efficient, such
as index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Your IRA would then be the ideal repository for your stocks with
high payout levels, such as utilities, and funds that traditionally
deliver large capital gains distributions.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy would reduce the short-term tax effects, but of
course the taxman will ultimately get his due, because not drawing
from the IRA should mean that it will grow steadily during the
dozen or so years after retirement and before you need to take
minimum mandatory withdrawals, and the higher the balance at that
time, the higher the withdrawals will be.
</P>
<P>
   So at that point you could adopt a reverse strategy _ selling
the taxable bond positions and replacing them with common stocks
and tax-efficient funds, and swapping some of the tax-deferred
stock holdings for a bond portfolio in the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am in my first year working as a court reporter and am
already concerned about self-employment taxation. Can you recommend
a ``For Dummies'' book?
</P>
<P>
   C.B., Chattanooga, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, there is a book called ``Taxes for Dummies: 2000
Edition'' by Donald J. Silverman and Eric Tyson, but I haven't read
it so I can't provide an evaluation. My tax bible is ``J. K.
Lasser's Your Income Tax,'' revised for each tax year. It resembles
a Manhattan telephone book, and there's no question that some parts
of it are fairly tough sledding.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than faulting the book, I lay the blame for the
complexity on the tax code itself. (Lines from Ezra Pound come to
mind: ``I won't say it wasn't hard going / Over roads twisted like
sheep's guts.)
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, if the dummy is computer-literate, using one of
the computer programs to generate your tax return is probably the
easiest approach. The programs pose a long sequence of questions,
you supply the answers, and you just follow the instructions until
you come to the crushing reality of Line 68 of Form 1040, the one
highlighted Amount You Owe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money musings: Here's a classic quotation for tax time from
Judge Learned Hand, one of the nation's greatest jurists never to
sit on the US Supreme Court, written in 1934: ``Anyone may so
arrange his affairs that his taxes shall be as low as possible; he
is not bound to choose that pattern which will best pay the
Treasury; there is not even a patriotic duty to increase one's
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3551 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONLINE-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      02-21 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE OVER DAY TRADERS: T-BILL BUYERS USE THE NET, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet isn't just for day traders, tech-stock mavens, or
others who want in on the excitement of the stock market. It's also
for individual investors who want to buy something as conservative
as US Treasury securities and savings bonds.
</P>
<P>
   At two Web sites, www.treasurydirect.gov and
www.publicdebt.treas.gov, you can make a direct purchase of
Treasury securities online _ once you have mailed in a paper
application to establish a TreasuryDirect account.
</P>
<P>
   At a third site, www.savingsbonds.gov, parents, aunts and
uncles, and grandparents can buy that perennially popular gift for
young children _ the US savings bond _ with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, with Treasuries or savings bonds, investors are
helping to fund the $5.7 trillion US debt.
</P>
<P>
   The government doesn't give financial advice, but there are
advantages to Treasuries worth mentioning, said Larry Grey, manager
of TreasuryDirect for the Federal Reserve Bank in Boston: ``One is,
they're not subject to state taxes. The second one is, they're
guaranteed by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Internet, the TreasuryDirect program let
individuals buy Treasury bills, notes, and bonds directly from the
overnment, without a broker or commission. It usually involved a
trip to a Federal Reserve Bank or the use of a cashier's or
certified check.
</P>
<P>
   Now, once your TreasuryDirect account is open and the government
has bank-account debit information, you can order directly on the
Internet. Account holders can also make a purchase by calling
800-943-6864.
</P>
<P>
   Online ordering is just one of the latest additions to
TreasuryDirect. ``One of the things the Treasury is doing is trying
to make it so customers can be self-sufficient,'' Grey said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can still get an application by mail. Call (617)
973-3811 and leave your name and address. Later, you can mail in a
purchase order.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury has gotten rid of the walk-up windows at Federal
Reserve Banks, though.
</P>
<P>
   Technology also makes it easier to reinvest and sell Treasuries
and to pay the $25 fee due annually on accounts with balances over
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites provide plenty of information about Treasuries _
including auction dates, interest rates, and minimum investment
amounts _ plus downloadable applications and a history of the
public debt.
</P>
<P>
   Rules for buying Treasuries can be somewhat complicated, so
check the sites carefully. Some basics:
</P>
<P>
   --Treasury bills, or T-bills, are short-term obligations that
mature in one year or less and are sold at a discount from face
value, paying interest at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an auction of three-month T-bills resulted in a 5.682
percent interest rate; six-month T-bills had a 6.032 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   --The terms of Treasury notes range from more than a year to 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   --Bonds are issued with a term of more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   --Both Treasury notes and bonds pay set interest rates, with
payments made twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation-indexed versions of Treasury notes and bonds
adjust the principal based on the Consumer Price Index and pay
interest twice a year based on that adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum investment for all forms of Treasury securities is
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   US savings bonds are even easier to buy online than Treasuries.
You don't need to open an account first.
</P>
<P>
   Simply go to savingsbonds.gov and click the ``Savings Bond
Connection'' link. You an then shop for everything from a $50
Series I savings bond to a $1,000 face-value Series EE bond and pay
online with MasterCard or Visa.
</P>
<P>
   The site also lets users print out a gift certificate.A savings
bond calculator helps you figure out what a bond is worth today;
other tools help you to calculate everything from the tax
advantages of savings bonds to the growth you can expect from the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet sites of interest for prospective buyers of
Treasuries:
</P>
<P>
   --bondsonline.com
</P>
<P>
   --bondvu.com
</P>
<P>
   --investinginbonds.com
</P>
