<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      02-21 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE STARTER MUST STINT MIGHTILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We have made little preparation for retirement. Our mortgage
payment is $950 a month, with $650 coming from the rental unit,
leaving us with just $300 to pay. We have made a committment to
start investing $400 a month. I know we should start an IRA, but
which one? And how much should we put in? Should we invest the
$15,000 (savings) in a mutual fund, and if so, which one? My
feeling is to be a little aggressive, so I guess my question is
where should we invest to make up for lost time?
</P>
<P>
   G.J., Fallbrook, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'll start with the really bad news: The rate at which you
propose to invest isn't nearly enough to get you very far. Saving
6.4 percent of your income might have been satisfactory 20 years
ago, but at this stage you're going to have to stint on yourselves
mightily. Unless you have the prospect of a fat pension, I can't
really propose anything more than taking a very hard look at your
budget and determining how you can make dramatic cuts _ enough to
double or triple that $400 a month in savings.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, if you add $400 a month to your current $9,000 in
investments, you would amass $103,377 over the course of 10 years _
assuming average portfolio returns of 10 percent. Why didn't I plug
in 12 percent, since you're willing to invest aggressively? Simply
because I don't think you can afford the risk of aggressive
investments, which could backfire and put you even deeper into the
hole. My byword for people who need to make up for years of playing
the grasshopper is to save aggressively, but invest conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   Now, how to start? I would not advise putting all of your
$15,000 savings into mutual funds. But if you feel that your
overall financial security _ particularly job security _ is strong
enough so that $11,000 would be an ample emergency reserve, you
could put $4,000 into traditional IRAs. Do so by April 15 and you
will be able to deduct that $4,000 on your 1999 federal tax return.
(Entitling you to a tax refund. If that's the case, I suggest that
you invest the refund _ in addition to whatever regular savings
program you have adopted.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, I suggest you embark upon a program of fully funding
each of your IRA accounts for tax year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If you are beginning in February, you could add $182 a month to
each IRA, cutting the payment to $180 for December. (You are
subject to penalties if you add more than $2,000 a year to an IRA.)
In 2001, you could drop the IRA contributions to $166 a month,
adding $8 to one of the payments so that you will again be
precisely on target.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are unwilling to go beyond the $400 monthly savings
you proposed, fully funding the IRAs will account only for $4,000
of your proposed $4,800 in annual savings. I suggest you put the
remaining money in a bank account until you accumulate enough to
open a taxable fund account. You can open IRAs with initial
investments in the $500 to $1,000 range, but the minimum for
taxable accounts if often $2,500 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for what funds to use: Save aggressively and invest
conservatively. I suggest you begin with the Vanguard Index 500
fund for your IRAs, which seeks to track the Standard and Poors 500
Index. Then, consider Vanguard Balanced Index as the eventual
target for your additional savings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I have newborn twins and expect to pay a
significant portion of their college expenses and to pay off our
mortgage before retirement. Our mortgage has a $183,000 balance,
with 29 years remaining. We add an extra $100 a month to our $1,465
payment. Other than a $350 monthly auto loan, we have no other
debt. It's likely I will not work full time for the next two or
three years, reducing our combined salaries from $165,000 to a
minimum of $75,000. Our rate of savings would be greatly reduced.
We will cut back on 401(k) contributions, mortgage prepayments, and
contributions to taxable savings, but will contribute to the Roth
IRAs and college savings. Is this sensible? Stock funds are 70
percent of our assets; we'd prefer at least 90 percent but feel we
need some cash handy. We fear the large-cap segment of our
portfolio is too high. Should we build up the small-cap portion
quickly? Do we have too many funds? What about our prospects for
having a mortgage-free retirement at age 60?
</P>
<P>
   K.P., Southington, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. With the short-term slowdown in your earnings and savings,
it's hard to predict fairly precisely where you'll be in 27 years.
But I did run a calculation based on the current assets and the
pre-interruption contributions, figuring that future salary
increases _ plus savings increases during later years _ should make
up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Based on expectations of 10 percent average annual portfolio
returns, I came up with an eventual accumulation of $5,766,443 _
another way of saying youd be in fat city. That calculation was
based on a projection of your 401(k)s, IRAs, and taxable accounts
only, leaving your emergency savings and the college account to the
side.
</P>
<P>
   Too many funds? Well, you have a lot, but they are solid
offerings. The only effect of having so many is a certain amount of
duplication, particularly in the large-cap arena. If there is a
small- or mid-cap offering in the 401(k) account in which you hold
the Vanguard Total Bond Market position, I'd suggest a swap there.
If the tax consequences are not onerous, you might also swap Janus
Worldwide for Janus Overseas, thus getting a pure foreign stock
play rather than one mitigated by about a third of the portfolio in
North American markets.
</P>
<P>
   And you could invest so as to achieve greater portfolio
diversification. This would probably give you even more funds, but
you seem to have an eye for good ones.
</P>
<P>
   As for the college savings, Roth IRAs and reduced contributions
to the 401(k) and taxable savings:
</P>
<P>
   First off, it's eminently sensible to invest in your twins
early. (I've trod the two-at-a-time path, and it's an exhausting
one). It's equally sensible to focus on the shorter-term goal
(college costs) and in the uninterrupted progress in building that
tax-free Roth account, which will provide you with valuable
flexibility in your retirement when you will need to manage the
withdrawals from the very large projected accumulation in the
401(k).
</P>
<P>
   It seems pretty clear that people who have saved so well by age
33 will certainly have the discipline to pick up the ball again
after a few years' interruption.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money musings: Maybe it's the choppy markets, but lately I've
had queries about whether I provide individual advice for a fee.
The answer is no. I'm a journalist, not a financial adviser. To
work for fees would violate the canons of journalism _ and the law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
