<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOLLAR COIN? WE HAVE ENOUGH CHANGE ALREADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Mint is wasting its time and coinage trying to convince
Americans they need a shiny new gold dollar. Americans need more
change in their pockets the way Noah needed rain.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the new issue bearing the likeness of Sacagawea, Lewis
and Clark's Shoshone guide, isn't a lovely keepsake. But carry it
around? Make room for it on the dresser? Get real.
</P>
<P>
   The dresser is loaded. So are the candy dishes, jelly jars, and
wine carafes. The kitchen drawers rattle with it. The car grows it
under the seats. The change purse is fat with it and weighs down
the shoulder bag. The pocket seams rip from it. And the plastic
coin sorter that was supposed to help get the stuff organized,
rolled, and into the bank is overflowing onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a $40 million promotional campaign, scheduled to start
next month, can make us eager to cram more jingly into our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as replacing four quarters,'' says Jim Benfield,
executive director of the Coin Coalition in Washington, cheerleader
for the new dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar won't replace the quarters _ it will be in
addition to the quarters and the rest of clinking mess that gets on
people's nerves in check-out lines _ especially when the person up
front has to fish pennies out of a coat lining or drops them down a
grate.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet is to be the person up front who mistakes the subway
tokens for nickels and who forgets how to count because everyone is
staring hard and starting to cough.
</P>
<P>
   Chump change, that's what coins are.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how they make a person feel, no matter how shiny, or
how convenient they're supposed to be at the bus stop or the
vending machine. More of them can never be convenient _ only
redundant.
</P>
<P>
   The new dollar is also likely to be expensive and fattening. The
Mint says so, right in its promotional materials, which contain a
page of testimonials from a gleeful vending industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Buckholz, president of Goodman Vending in Reading, Pa.,
says the dollar coin will ``increase profitability by reducing
service calls, encouraging impulse sales, and allowing us to sell
higher-priced items.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes that the upside for consumers is learning about
Sacagawea's journey with Lewis and Clark and treasuring ``the
coin's exceptional aesthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Chump change once again, for the consumer is seen as easily
distracted from the nub of the matter, which is that 80-cent drinks
will probably go up to a buck as soon as the dollar coin slot can
be installed in a machine.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mint weren't trying so hard to push its new issue, a
person might be a little more willing to give it a try. But money
that begins circulating in Cheerio's boxes and Wal-Mart and Sam's
Club stores has all the allure of a deodorant sample.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint, which plans to have 200 million Sacagaweas in
circulation by March 1, is working overtime to avoid another fiasco
like the Susan B. Anthony dollar, which even the Mint's director,
Philip Diehl, calls ``the Edsel of American coinage.'' Not only did
that one run afoul of the public's inherent resistance to coins,
but it looked so much like a quarter that it doubled the tension in
check-out lines.
</P>
<P>
   The gold Sacagawea isn't as bad, but it isn't that good either.
It's barely bigger than a quarter and can still cause confusion in
the dark recesses of a bulging change purse when the pressure is on
to count fast.
</P>
<P>
   Benfield, at the Coin Coalition, and many of the group's members
hope that the dollar coin, which is said to be sturdy enough to
circulate for 30 years, will replace the fragile dollar bill, which
has a life span of only 18 months. But Benfield knows that logic
has little to do with people and their money and that they don't
like the government messing with their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any more personal than that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Coin proponents cheer the wisdom of Canada for ditching the
paper dollar in 1989, after Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
introduced a coin with the alluring loon on its face.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone calls it the ``looney.'' And the two-dollar coin,
introduced in 1996, is a ``tooney.''
</P>
<P>
   Figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
