<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-YORKER-BOS &LR;      02-21 1716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-YORKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE AUTHORS VIEW THE NEW YORKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ABOUT TOWN: THE NEW YORKER AND THE WORLD IT MADE 
By Ben Yagoda. Scribner. 
431 pp. $27.50. 
 
GONE: THE LAST DAYS OF TE NEW YORKER 
By Renata Adler. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 252 pp. $25. 
 
 
SOME TIMES IN AMERICA AND A LIFE IN A YEAR AT THE NEW YORKER 
By Alexander Chancellor. Carroll &AMP; Graf. 309 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two decades ago, fire alarms went off in the offices of The New
Yorker, then located at 25 West 43d St. Firefighters rushed to the
scene: false alarm. Meanwhile, a group of writers huddled outside
their 18th-floor warrens. A fireman idly asked what kind of company
they worked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``A magazine,'' one staffer replied. ``Actually, it's The New
Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Yorker!'' the fireman exclaimed. ``Geez,'' he said,
glancing around at the shabby accommodations. ``What's a classy
magazine like that doing in a dump like this?''
</P>
<P>
   You won't find that anecdote in any of the new books published
to coincide with The New Yorker's 75th anniversary. But the story
would almost surely serve as parable for one of the following: the
deep and longstanding disconnect at the magazine between appearance
and reality; the insecurity that drove staffers to cry ``fire!''
(metaphorically, at least) to get the attention of then-editor
William Shawn, the Unabomber of West 43d Street; the contrast
between 1930s-style bohemian chic (good) and 1990s-style Conde Nast
glitz (bad); or even the wistful notion that the entire enterprise
should have burned down when it had the chance years ago, with
Shawn laid out in his woolen suit on a pyre of unpublished
manuscripts, to spare everyone the pain of watching the magazine
wither and rot from within.
</P>
<P>
   Well. Alarms aside, there are a few things that can be safely
said about The New Yorker, past and present. One is that its inner
workings have inspired more curiosity among outsiders _ and more
perfervid memoir-writing _ than any other periodical of its time,
and not by accident, either. Another is that the magazine is not
dead, notwithstanding Renata Adler's hyperbolic obituary notice; in
fact, under incumbent editor David Remnick, it may be healthier
than at any time since Shawn's inglorious departure in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A third is that the Reign of Shawn is of infinitely greater
interest to literary archeologists than the Reign of Tina Brown,
the anti-Shawn, which ended in 1998. (Footnote: Whereas the names
of founding editor Harold Ross and Shawn never appeared in the
magazine before their deaths, Brown never missed an opportunity to
buzz her own moniker into print. Perhaps this accounts for the
discrepancy in third-party interest.) A fourth is that the
magazine's high command tinkered with the editorial formula many
times before Queen Tina took over, and will presumably continue to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, what do the rash of current books about The New
Yorker add to our understanding of the place? What do they say
about the methods and motives of their respective authors:
scholarly and critical analysis, personal score-settling, making a
quick buck, or what? Do we need to know anything more about Ross's
unpolished genius, or Shawn's druidic ways? About ``The Years with
Ross'' (James Thurber's quirky memoir) or The Affair with Ross
(Shawn's hush-hush tryst with Lillian R.)? To recontextualize a
line from Adler's jihad of a book, ``Is this pathology, or the wave
of the future?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Ben Yagoda's exhaustively researched and highly
entertaining history, the answer is: Quite a lot can be learned,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   Yagoda, a journalism professor, is the first institutional
biographer to make extensive use of archival materials donated to
the New York Public Library in 1991 _ including thousands of pages
of interoffice correspondence, the unaccessed e-mail of its era.
His re-creation of the magazine's beginnings and its golden years
(along with some less-then-golden ones) is everything the other
books demonstrably are not, namely: balanced, nuanced, informative,
and fair-minded.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout Yagoda's narrative, which basically ends
with the Shawn years, are nifty portraits of such New Yorker
stalwarts as Thurber, E. B. White, J. D. Salinger, John Cheever,
Saul Steinberg, and Truman Capote, a lineup that reminds us of the
all-star talent The New Yorker has put on the field over the
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Yagoda is particularly strong on the early days, when New York
City was becoming the world capital of hip sophistication and The
New Yorker was ``the only cocktail party in town.'' Uninterested in
highbrow culture, founder Ross, a rough-edged Midwesterner and
former newspaperman, conceived the magazine as a comic journal that
would, as he put it, ``hate bunk'' and ``contain some josh and some
news value.'' Almost from the outset, writes Yagoda, the place was
a mass of contradictions: ``a pure accident from start to finish,''
to quote another memorable Rossism, a multiplicity of tics and
talents that consistently defied definition.
</P>
<P>
   In its infancy, as Yagoda notes, the magazine's most successful
component was its art. Yet as the roster of early contributors
(John O'Hara, Dorothy Parker, Wolcott Gibbs, S. J. Perelman, Edmund
Wilson) expanded, so did The New Yorker's cultural significance.
The magazine grew from a showcase for cutting-edge humor and
criticism into a forum (under Shawn) for some of the century's
finest journalism (John Hershey's ``Hiroshima,'' Capote's ``In Cold
Blood'') and best short fiction (Cheever, John Updike, Ann
Beattie), then to a mouthpiece for contrarian political views
(Jonathan Schell on Vietnam and Watergate), and finally into a
repository for the best from across the print-media spectrum, from
Steinberg's illustrations and Pauline Kael's film reviews to the
writing of Ian Frazier, Calvin Trillin, and John McPhee.
</P>
<P>
   As a business, The New Yorker was not only immediately
successful but astonishingly so, growing in circulation from 14,000
to 156,000 between 1925 and 1940. In defiance of its elitist image,
it flourished during the Depression. By 1952, its circulation had
reached 370,000, even as the magazine itself was beginning to
stultify. It was then, writes Yagoda, that Shawn _ ``a poet with a
pencil,'' in one acolyte's view _ shook up the formula again,
publishing writers like James Baldwin and Hanna Arendt. By the
mid-'60s, Shawn's personal foibles were so legendary (the
polyphobia, the corn flakes lunches at the Algonquin) and his
editorial system so idiosyncratic (the endless queries, the layers
of fact-checking, the unexplained last-minute substitutions) that
when Tom Wolfe mockingly profiled him in New York magazine it all
sounded so improbable it almost had to have contained a kernel of
truth.
</P>
<P>
   What of the casualties, then? Joseph Mitchell, perhaps the most
gifted nonfiction writer in Shawn's stable, published nothing for
30 years. The magazine would have none of the so-called New
Journalism, nor much in the way of experimental fiction or poetry.
Rejectees included Styron, Pynchon, Roth, and Flannery O'Connor.
Long fact pieces were often too long and too fact-laden. There were
libel lawsuits and succession struggles, palace intrigue made even
spookier by Shawn's passive-aggressive management style and code of
omerta.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn came to run the enterprise, writes Yagoda, ``the way
Algerian terrorist cells were organized in the Battle of Algiers _
no one knew who anybody else was or what anybody else was doing.''
In the end Shawn himself was the most conspicuous casualty,
standing on his ship's main deck after being harpooned by owner S.
I. Newhouse and exhorting the crew to ``love'' him back to power. A
shout of ``fire'' would have been the apter rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   As for two new memoirs _ one by Adler, a staff writer from 1963
to 1989, one by Alexander Chancellor, a Britisher who edited the
Talk of the Town under Brown from 1992-93 _ one might rightfully
ask, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   (Full disclosure: My late father, E. J. Kahn Jr., a New Yorker
staff writer from 1937 to 1994, suffers some unkind _ and in one
instance, untrue _ cuts by Adler in her book. My late
father-in-law, Robert Shaplen, who covered Southeast Asia for the
magazine, fares considerably better. All I can say in my father's
case is that he's in good company and that like Kael and Roger
Angell, he'll survive.)
</P>
<P>
   Adler's book has gotten the lion's share of critical attention,
most of it negative. Leaving aside her purportedly loving portrait
of Shawn, which manages to out-Wolfe Wolfe in wading into the
waters of dysfunction, Adler goes from nit-picking other memoirists
(Lillian Ross, Ved Mehta) to making sweeping statements about
colleagues' actions and motives, backed by little evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Other books about Shawn and The New Yorker ``do not seem right
to me,'' writes Adler, who published virtually nothing in the
magazine after she skewered Kael in another journal (to Shawn's
great displeasure). At one point Adler refers to the ``ethic of
silence'' that developed under Shawn, the feeling among some New
Yorker writers that it was ``morally wrong to write.'' Amazingly,
the magazine kept coming out, week after week, without Adler in it.
As it continues to do today, despite Adler's obituary.
</P>
<P>
   The line on Chancellor's slight but reasonably entertaining
memoir involves: many, many dry martinis consumed; endless
welcoming dinners and goodbye parties hosted by titans of the
social and journalistic establishment; an account of how he hired
Jeffrey Toobin to be a Talk writer (good) and how he kept defying
Brown's wishes not to write about cow murders (bad); a rehash of a
Columbia Journalism School panel on British journalists that
Chancellor failed to attend; his on-again, off-again closeness to
Tina; and, what a marvelous time he had spending oodles of Newhouse
money that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My observations of New York were poignantly unoriginal,''
Chancellor writes of his first attempts to wring a book out of his
year in Manhattan. Faced with the prospect of having to return his
advance, apparently, Chancellor bravely soldiered on. To return to
Ross for a moment, the results are long on josh and short on news
value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
