<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PAROLE-BOS &LR;      02-21 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PAROLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON BEYOND WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ON PAROLE 
By Akira Yoshimura. Translated, from the Japanese, by Stephen
Snyder. Harcourt Brace. 
244 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born in 1927, Akira Yoshimura is an acclaimed Japanese writer
who has written 20 novels, only two of which have been translated
into English. The first, ``Shipwrecks,'' was published here in 1996
to a good deal of critical regard, for its hauntingly careful style
was eclipsed only by the mounting horror of the story it told. ``On
Parole'' possesses a similar titrated intensity, measured in
half-teaspoons and building to a nearly unbearable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the obvious joy of reading the literature of another
culture is the education one receives in the greater world; less
manifest but just as valuable are the mirrored refractions we
witness about our own lives. Both of Yoshimura's English
translations depend upon deeply rooted Japanese traditions for
their stories: upon the dominion of family, the self-control of the
individual, the sometimes agonizing strain of trying to live up to
societal codes. Set in a poor, isolated fishing village on the
Japanese coast, ``Shipwrecks'' told the terrible story of what
befalls a populace that depends on looting for its own survival;
the novel's gothic consequences suggested a complex portrait of
human loss _ of the potential tragedy in doing the wrong things for
the right reasons. This intricacy of purpose also governs ``On
Parole,'' which opens with a man waking up to his first day of
freedom after serving 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a narrative that consistently remains compassionate but
detached, we see the world through Shiro Kikutani's eyes, and it is
not an easy place in which to wake. Formerly a high school teacher
in a village a few hours from Tokyo, Kikutani received an
indefinite sentence for what is first described as ``the incident''
_ a crime that will become clear only after Kikutani himself has
been thoroughly introduced. A quiet man of modest decorum, he was a
model prisoner who passed most of his sentence proofreading for the
prison's print shop. The last few years of his incarceration were
spent awaiting the parole board's decision on his release _ a
torturous process in which he was told nothing, presumably because
that silence would help him come to terms with his crime.
Kikutani's loneliness in his concrete cell was so thorough that he
once captured a housefly, then clipped its wings, in order to have
something alive to keep him company.
</P>
<P>
   athos of this incident has to compete, of course, with its
inherent ghastliness, and that mix pretty much suggests Kikutani's
own life story. The ``incident,'' we learn soon enough, was the
murder of his wife _ a woman he loved and found in the arms of
someone else, at which point he took a fish-scaling knife to them
both. Condemned by his family and village, he leaves prison under
the guidance of a kind parole officer, Kiyoura, and spends the
first few months of his new life in a halfway house on the
outskirts of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The nebulous quality of Kikutani's freedom is apparent from the
moment he attempts to cope with a radically different world. The
society he left 15 years ago now seems a futuristic madhouse of
freeways, department stores, and hugely inflated prices _ even a
shopping trip to purchase an alarm clock is fraught with
apprehension and despair. More inescapable are Kikutani's internal
strictures, the ones that must have served him well during his
crime and punishment both. Walking the Tokyo streets with another
newly paroled man, he strides in the military lockstep he learned
in prison; at the end of his day, he sits in his room on his mat,
feet tucked under his knees, waiting for the hours to pass. He
finds a job shoveling excrement on a chicken farm outside the city,
and each day he dresses in his only suit for the commute, carrying
his work clothes along with his lunch. He discovers the ominously
transformative pleasures of sake. With his new savings, he buys a
heater and a small television; finally, having more to choose from
in the outside world than a mere housefly, he purchases a tank and
a few fish.
</P>
<P>
   All these journeys of discovery unfold with a finely wrought
tension touched by poignance; one feels for Kikutani and his
agonies but also shudders at the ways in which he avoids them,
sensing what the payback must be for that evasion. For this is a
man who, prudish and judgmental about his own sexual desires, feels
no remorse for his crime _ a loving husband who, faced with an
adulterous wife, went after her with the precision of ``a carpenter
driving nails in just the right places.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems extraordinary about ``On Parole'' is the finely
modulated way in which Kikutani's character unfolds. Throughout the
novel, he remains partly sympathetic and mildly unknowable, when it
would have been an easier task to make him unsympathetic and
revealed. His love for and dependence upon the two men who help him
_ Kiyoura, then Takebayashi, who takes over as parole officer _
reveal both the emotional complexity of the man and his vast
psychic need. And the manner in which a courtship is foisted upon
him _ a woman for a bunch of fish, Kiyoura tells him, is ``not a
bad trade'' _ suggests the societal misogyny that must have made it
a bit more tempting for Kikutani to drive those nails home.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``On Parole,'' one is reminded that the literary premise
of the prison of self is hardly a Western concept. Kikutani has
miles to go in search of the peace that sake and psychic repression
promised but didn't deliver; and no matter what path he takes, he
finds that ``his past was still coiled tightly about his heart.''
The crimson blur of fury that awaits him hasn't softened with the
years, in or out of prison. If penitence doesn't really work in
alleviating rage, then neither, as it turns out, does murder.
</P>
<P>
   This is quite a terrible story, not least because, in Kikutani's
world, mercy can be a dangerous thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
