<HEADLINE>
GOING ALONG FOR THE JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the central conceit of ``Wit,'' Vivian Bearing describes the
similarity of her life to that of the overbearing doctor treating
her for ovarian cancer: ``So. The young doctor, like the senior
scholar, prefers research to humanity. At the same time, the senior
scholar, in her pathetic state as a simpering victim, wishes the
young doctor would take more interest in personal contact.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Bearing's wry acknowledgement that she has learned her
lesson, that a life of the mind _ as satisfying as it might be _
needs to be balanced by a life of the heart and soul. For the
professor, it will provide only small comfort given the advanced
stage of her cancer. For the audience, though, it is not too late.
``Wit,'' like the fairy tale that runs through it, is ``a little
allegory of the soul,'' as one character puts it. And one of the
reasons that audiences have taken Margaret Edson's play so much to
heart is the reenactment of the archetypal life lesson, the journey
of discovery and transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a cursory knowledge of mythology, or of the late
Joseph Campbell, knows that such journeys are central to art of all
cultures. They are also an area in which the theater, for all its
contemporary troubles, still has a huge edge over movies and
television, an edge it would fritter away at its own peril. These
journeys take any number of forms, but a live performance takes the
audience along communally and spiritually. As Judith Light, who
plays Bearing in Boston after an extremely successful run in New
York, said in a Globe interview, the professor's epiphany about
what she had been missing in the poetry of John Donne ``is as good
as any sermon you will hear in any church.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey in ``Violet'' is a much simpler one. Jeanine Tesori
and Brian Crawley's musical is a contemporary recasting of ``The
Wonderful Wizard of Oz.'' In Salman Rushdie's BFI Film Classics
essay about the movie version, he talks about the tension between
the two dreams of returning to one's roots and escaping from them,
with ``Over the Rainbow'' symbolizing the greater power of the
latter: ``In its most potent, emotional moment, this is unarguably
a film about the joys of going away, of leaving the greyness and
entering the colour.''
</P>
<P>
   There may not be any songs in ``Violet'' with the power of that
Harold Arlen-E. Y. Harburg song, but Tesori's skillful use of other
musical idioms, such as gospel and country music, makes ``Violet''
a rewarding journey in its own right. Violet's face was disfigured
by the blade flying off her father's ax, and she's yearning for a
contemporary version of the wizard, a televangelist, to give her
``Gene Tierney eyes, Judy Garland's chin,'' and body parts from
other actresses.
</P>
<P>
   Her journey takes the form of a bus ride with two soldiers, one
black, the other white, from the Blue Ridge Mountains through
Tennessee and Arkansas to Oklahoma. In the rich SpeakEasy Stage
Company production at the Boston Center for the Arts that just
finished its run, the audience went along for the ride and even
wound up in church with Violet. Tesori and Crawley cleverly use
gospel music both to subvert the literal Messianic purpose of
gospel and to substitute a more metaphorical, romantic conception
of deliverance and redemption. The evangelist will be an empty
wizard, too, and Violet's epiphany will come from a more secular
source leading her to the light. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Emotions multiplied &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the nature of that epiphany, the two actors who played
Violet in her 20s and her teens, Bridget Beirne and Kristina
Bjornstad, made it easy for the audience to identify with Violet's
transformation. As Light says, it's as good as any sermon even if
the revelation isn't ultimately earth-shaking. Whenever the two
actresses were onstage together, the theatrical effect was like
nothing in any other art form, as time is encapsulated into an
eerie stillness and emotions are multiplied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet'' made use of a particular device that's also on
display in Diane Samuels's ``Kindertransport'' at the New Repertory
Theatre production in Newton _ having the same character appear
simultaneously as both adult and child. Eva Schlesinger survived
the Holocaust because her mother put the 9-year-old German girl
(played by Emily Dubner) on a train to England. She was taken in by
a kindly English woman, but yearns for her parents to join her.
Most of the dialogue takes place in an attic (shades of another
Holocaust play) where, almost simultaneously, we see Eva as an
adult (Nancy Carroll) struggling for a decent relationship with her
daughter as well as struggling with her own depression, or
repression.
</P>
<P>
   Because we constantly see her as a fearful and traumatized
child, it is impossible not to feel things for her that she can no
longer feel for herself. Her odyssey has been a journey away from
herself. We won't say whether she goes through a transformation,
but the harm of hiding from one's past is almost unbearably
wrenching for the audience. Samuels can be heavy-handed at times
and is certainly no Shakespeare, but the effect of watching Eva's
identity crisis unfold is the same as when classical tragedy hits
home.
</P>
<P>
   Many modernist artists, of course, reject the whole notion of
such transformations as sentimental romanticism. In the American
Repertory Theatre's fine production of ``Full Circle,'' Charles L.
Mee stands the whole notion on its head as a character based on the
Dutch mythological heroine Dulle Griet recites poetic claptrap
while journeying through post-Cold War Berlin. But even the lack of
insight of Mee's characters does add up to less smug assumptions
about ourselves by the time we're through. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Catharsis in music &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A live musical performance can have the same cathartic effect. I
had always found Dmitri Shostakovich's string quartets a dreary
exploration of the composer's private feelings, as opposed to the
high drama of his symphonic output, but the Emerson String
Quartet's recent BankBoston Celebrity Series performance of his
15th quartet, written when he was hospitalized, was as emotionally
wrenching as ``Wit.'' As Lawrence Dutton, the Emerson violist, said
in the excellent liner notes to the recently released recording of
the quartets: ``These pieces are the aural representation of an
incredible spectrum of human tragedy and suffering, with occasional
glimpses of hopefulness. It's an amazing journey, this music.''
</P>
<P>
   Cinematic characters make their own journeys, too, and while
audiences appreciate their discoveries, it's harder to feel a
shared experience. Kevin Spacey's realization that there's life
beyond suburban fantasies in ``American Beauty'' didn't
particularly move me. And while I may lament the hatred of lesbians
and transsexuals displayed in ``Boys Don't Cry,'' I never felt I
was making the journey along with Hilary Swank's character in that
film. What changes do the protagonists of the much-praised ``All
About My Mother'' or ``Run Lola Run'' go through?
</P>
<P>
   Even when there are real revelations in films, audiences these
days don't seem to see that as a communal function of film. Witness
the cool reaction to Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' John
Sayles's ``Limbo,'' and Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown.''
Allen's film was not one of his best, but the Sean Penn character's
realization that he threw away his one chance at happiness in
pursuit of artistic glory was one of the most chilling epiphanies
I've seen on screen. Artistically it parallels Henry James's
``Beast in the Jungle.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Movies and pop culture &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There isn't any shortage of transformative journeys in the
movies and popular culture, but these depend largely on reducing
the mess of life to ``Star Wars'' banalities. Thus ``Hurricane''
has to remove the complexities of Rubin Carter's case and turn him
into a street-smart saint. We love tales of Kurt Warner's
transformation from supermarket clerk to Super Bowl hero. Next year
we'll find out he's unfaithful to his wife or took steroids, but
for now we'll swallow the Horatio Alger myth while watching Regis
Philbin bestow instant transcendence on the winners of ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no predetermined correlation between artistic
excellence and the mythological journey. Much in modernist and
postmodernist art sees the transformative journey as sentimental
claptrap left over from 19th-century romanticism. Patricia
Highsmith's ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is a gripping novel
precisely because Tom Ripley suffers no guilt from the mounting
pile of bodies. The film, as smart as it is, subverts itself
precisely because it tacks a hollow epiphany onto the ending
(although that isn't nearly as bad as the ending to ``Purple
Noon,'' the earlier film of the Highsmith book.)
</P>
<P>
   But if an artist walks strictly on the wild side of the street,
what happens when the insights aren't that wild anymore? Joe
Orton's '60s-era ``Loot,'' also at the American Repertory Theatre,
is an example of a work that gained its original power from a
darkly comic rejection of mythic transformations of any kind.
Orton's world is corrupt from head to toe and his characters are
beyond redemption, but now that we are living at a time in which
all institutions are viewed cynically, Orton's artistic power is
considerably reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit'' and ``Violet'' may be sentimental by comparison, but
there is still something that will probably give these 1990s plays
staying power. As Judith Light goes through her amazing
transformation from arrogant professor to dying patient, the
audience's transformation goes in the opposite direction. ``Wit''
isn't about how to die one's death, but how to live one's life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
