<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GRAMMYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING THE GRAMMYS (OTHER THAN CARLOS SANTANA'S) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stirring up excitement for this year's Grammy Awards is not
easy. It appears a foregone conclusion that Carlos Santana, the
sentimental favorite, will win most of the 10 Grammys for which
he's nominated. Fine, and he deserves them after a 30-year career
in which he's been virtually ignored by the Grammys except for one
award in 1988 for best rock instrumental performance.
</P>
<P>
   But where else do you look for excitement this year? That's
precisely the problem, as Grammy organizers try to build a ratings
winner out of a show that is overrun with plastic pop acts.
</P>
<P>
   Is the world waiting breathlessly to see if Britney Spears or
Christina Aguilera is going to win best new artist? Or to see if
the Backstreet Boys or Ricky Martin will win record of the year? Or
whether Cher will be crowned?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique year. We have quite a few acts that would be
generously referred to as pop-phenomenon acts,'' says Michael
Greene, president of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences. Its 11,000 members vote on the awards, which will be
handed out Wednesday night on CBS (WBZ-TV, Channel 4) starting at 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   To see how things have changed, just look at the artists who
performed on the show two years ago (and won a number of the
awards): Celine Dion, Barbra Streisand, Bob Dylan, Erykah Badu,
Shawn Colvin, Will Smith, R. Kelly, Fleetwood Mac, Fiona Apple,
Aretha Franklin, and Luciano Pavarotti. Then look at Wednesday's
key performers: Britney Spears, the Backstreet Boys, TLC, Santana,
Kid Rock, Ricky Martin, the Dixie Chicks, Whitney Houston, and
Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of crappy music to choose from,'' says one
Grammy executive who asks not to be identified. ``But you've got to
play the cards that you've been dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene blames today's radio landscape for the ``pop-pop-pop''
tone of the current music business. ``Radio is a cultural wasteland
and to expect (commercial stations) to do anything but jump on a
moving pop train would be too much to expect from them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One way to upgrade the entertainment value this year is to ask
some of the performers to do things they wouldn't ordinarily do.
For instance, half of the Backstreet Boys' segment will be a
tribute to a cappella groups throughout history. Anything to get
them away from the formulaic dance-production numbers that sell
oodles of tickets in the arenas, but can be numbing on TV.
</P>
<P>
   One sure winner should be a Latin segment featuring Marc
Anthony, Chucho Valdez, Ibrahim Ferrer (from the Buena Vista Social
Club), climaxed by Ricky Martin, whose explosive performance on the
Grammys last year started his meteoric rise. The Latin segment will
be the show's longest, and a good way to build momentum for the
first-ever Latin Grammys, to be televised from Miami on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, it seems, the Grammys have a dominant theme. In
1998, it was the year of female singer-songwriters, based on a
flock of nominations for Lilith Fair participants Sarah McLachlan,
Jewel, Sheryl Crow, and Shawn Colvin. Last year was the year of
soundtracks, with ``Titanic'' (and soundtrack goddess Celine Dion)
winning much of the glory. And this year is a case of an ageless
hippie (Santana) against all the flavor-of-the-month upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   Grammy voters are typically not kind to the teeny-bop
sensations. Two years ago, you may recall that the Spice Girls were
all the rage in the marketplace, but they garnered zero
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   So, given that history, here's a prediction this year in the
best new artist category: Susan Tedeschi, the blueswoman who hails
from the Boston suburb of Norwell, will win. She's going to beat
out Spears and Aguilera (whose supporters will cancel each other
out in the voting), Macy Gray (though she'll come close), and Kid
Rock (a group that is too politically incorrect for many
conservative Grammy voters).
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi will likewise be boosted by the same factions that
drove Bonnie Raitt and Eric Clapton to Grammy success in the '90s.
Tedeschi also plays her own instrument (guitar), sings her own
songs (no question of lip-synching, which Grammy voters are still
explaining after Milli Vanilli's bogus win in this category), and
she has a neat indie label, Tone-Cool Records. Tedeschi's win will
also be a way for Grammy voters to tweak the major labels and stand
up for the artistic underdog.
</P>
<P>
   The following are more predictions:
</P>
<P>
   Record of the year: Santana's ``Smooth'' (his hit single with
Rob Thomas) will edge out Cher's ``Believe,'' Martin's ``Livin' La
Vida Loca,'' TLC's ``No Scrubs,'' and the Backstreet Boys' ``I Want
It That Way.'' Don't bet against Santana, period.
</P>
<P>
   Album of the year: Santana's ``Supernatural'' by a landslide,
besting entries by the Backstreet Boys, TLC, Dixie Chicks, and the
biggest surprise nominee _ jazz artist Diana Krall. It's rare that
a jazz artist is nominated for this.
</P>
<P>
   Song of the year: This is a songwriting award and will go to Rob
Thomas and Itaal Shur, who wrote ``Smooth'' for Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Female pop vocal performance: A tossup between Alanis
Morissette's ``Thank U,'' Aguilera's ``Genie in a Bottle,'' and
Madonna's ``Beautiful Stranger.'' The Aguilera and Madonna tunes
were perfect pop ditties, but Grammy voters often like more depth,
so Morissette will win.
</P>
<P>
   Male pop vocal performance: Martin's ``Livin' la Vida Loca'' is
just too strong, beating tunes by Marc Anthony, Lou Bega, and
Sting.
</P>
<P>
   Dance recording: Cher will get some due here for ``Believe,''
which fueled an unexpected comeback for her.
</P>
<P>
   Rock performance by a duo or group with vocal: ``Put Your Lights
On'' by Santana and Everlast should be unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   R &AMP; B song: TLC's ``No Scrubs,'' hands down.
</P>
<P>
   Rap album: Look for Grammy darling Missy Elliott (and her album
``Da Real World'') to nip discs by Busta Rhymes, Eminem, Nas, and
the Roots.
</P>
<P>
   Country album: The Dixie Chicks' ``Fly.'' Old-line voters will
go with ``Trio II'' by Emmylou Harris, Linda Ronstadt, and Dolly
Parton. But the younger Chicks should prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional tropical Latin performance: The CD ``Buena Vista
Social Club Presents Ibrahim Ferrer'' is too potent to be thwarted.
Anything with the Buena Vista Social Club name is magic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
