<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH (Beirut) _ The streets of Beirut are seething
with anti-Israeli and anti-American sentiment in the aftermath of
Israeli bombing raids, but below the surface the sentiment is more
complicated. By Charles M. Sennott. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   HAIDER-PRESS (Klagenfurt, Austria) -- Joerg Haider, the man who
has been described by some as the next Hitler, looks more like the
provincial governor he is rather than the monster some warn he
could become. By Kevin Cullen. 1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-ANALYSIS (London) _ No one seems to know how to put the
Irish peace process back on track. A major factor is the IRA's own
precarious state: urban IRA members favor disarmament or moves in
that direction, while rural members say never. By Kevin Cullen.
1170 words.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-REFUGEES (Kasulo, Tanzania) _ For seven years, ethnic
violence in Rwanda and Burundi has sent thousands of people fleeing
into refugee camps in Tanzania. By Kurt Shillinger. 660 words.
</P>
