<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHRUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RAMBUNCTIOUS GALLOP THROUGH GEORGE W. BUSH'S CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SHRUB 
The Short but Happy Political Life of George W. Bush 
By Molly Ivins with Lou Dubose 
Random House, 184 pp., $19.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the flood of books being published about presidential
candidate George W. Bush, none is likely to have more personality
than ``Shrub: The Short but Happy Political Life of George W.
Bush,'' by Molly Ivins with Lou Dubose.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the book's personality derives more from the writers than
from their subject. Ivins is a syndicated columnist and former
coeditor of The Texas Observer, and Dubose is the current editor of
the Observer, the famously irreverent chronicle of all things
Texan, especially politics. Ivins, in particular, has made a career
of sticking needles into thick hides, with infectious glee.
</P>
<P>
   So a book by these Texans skewering their governor and then
roasting the would-be president on a rhetorical rack would seem to
be a natural, and ``Shrub'' does not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   That is, it will not disappoint liberals looking for a laugh at
the expense of the compassionate conservative, and it will not
disappoint Bush supporters who doubtless anticipate a negative
thrust from this quarter. Example: ``If you think his daddy had
trouble with `the vision thing,' wait till you meet this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Less partisan readers wishing to learn something about the
potential president will find here a view of Bush's role in Texas
politics that is entertaining and occasionally revealing, but that
is only one fairly narrow viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ivins and Dubose are candid about some of the things the
book is not. It is not, for instance, a psychological probe into
how an upper-class white boy became a tough guy growing up in Texas
politics. ``Somebody should probably be worrying about how all this
could affect his handling of future encounters with some Saddam
Hussein,'' they say, ``but that's beyond the scope of this book.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the authors make it clear they have no interest
whatever in the details of Bush's self-styled ``irresponsible
youth.'' Yet they are livid at Bush for securing ever-tougher
sentences for minor drug violations while cutting back
drug-treatment programs that had proved effective.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the book is a rambunctious gallop through Bush's six
years as governor. Ivins and Dubose first establish that relative
to other states, Texas has a constitution that gives its governor
limited powers. Even so, Bush has a record that is clear _ and
clearly lacking, in the authors' view _ on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   He has been extraordinarily harsh in enforcing the law,
especially the death penalty, they say, and extraordinarily tight
in helping the poor, those without health insurance and desolate
communities in the Rio Grande Valley. Compassionate conservatism,
they say, ``is a biblical and ideological justification for further
dismantling what remains of the social-welfare safety net.'' The
environment is another area in which they say Bush has led Texas
from bad to worse _ to being the most polluting state in the
country, by many measures. Overall, they say, ``From the record it
appears that he doesn't know much, doesn't do much, and doesn't
care much about governing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some attempt at providing balance: Ivins and Dubose
credit Bush with putting effort into education reform, including
high standards and better teachers. But they argue he has achieved
only mixed results, as several of the charter schools he has rushed
into existence have faltered, and he failed to turn a single
legislator's vote that would have given him a voucher program he
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The central theme of Bush's public life is his enthusiastic
sympathy for business interests _ especially big business. This
explains his early experience in oil (financed largely by wealthy
friends), the bonanza he struck through his interest in the Texas
Rangers baseball team, the pro-business environmental record, the
emphasis on tort reform, and the gushers of contributions that have
flowed to each of his political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrub'' contains little revelation or deep insight. It is
rewarding as an account of Bush's business-centered administration
_ and as entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
