<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S NEW PLANETARIUM: OUT OF THIS WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For nearly 40 years, astronauts have been rocketing
toward the stars. Now the rest of us can join in.
</P>
<P>
   The Space Age begins on 81st Street and Central Park West, a
strange place to herald a new stage of human experience. But that's
where you go to get to the Hayden Planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   The Hayden, which takes up the north wing of the American Museum
of Natural History, has been closed for three years, undergoing a
$210 million renovation. With its reopening Saturday, it will mark
the city's first architectural project in many years that is not a
restoration of some past glory, like Grand Central Station, Radio
City, or the Public Library Reading Room _ but, rather, a whole new
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building is what we all imagined a 21st century building
would be,'' says the planetarium's director, Neil de Grasse Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Its chief architect, James Stewart Polshek, calls it a ``cosmic
cathedral'': massive, sparkling, with a 100-foot-high ceiling,
crisscross angles, steep spirals, a curtain-wall of Pilkington
water white glass (the world's clearest glass), and, seemingly
floating at the center of it all, a 4-million-pound,
87-foot-diameter sphere.
</P>
<P>
   The sphere houses the main attraction, the Space Theater. It's
not a Sky Theater, like every other planetarium, including the old
Hayden, where you look up at a projection of the night sky. This is
a Space Theater, where you soar right through that sky, past the
planets, including an amazingly three-dimensional Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Then visitors set off to distant galaxies, into the Orion
nebula, out to the edge of the universe, then back to the Milky Way
via a shortcut: a black hole.
</P>
<P>
   The journey inside the black hole, of course, is sheer fancy,
and great fun: a vast, fast virtual-reality roller coaster, but the
rest is based on real science: data from the Hubble Space
Telescope, the European Space Agency's Hipparcos satellite, and, in
the case of the Orion nebula, three decades of collecting and
mapping at Rice University, all super-crunched through the Hayden's
bank of five Silicon Graphics Onyx-2 supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the stars are in their correct position, and the distance
between the stars is to the correct proportion,'' emphasizes
Mordecai-Mark Mac Low, one of the Hayden's eight staff
astrophysicists, who use the Onyx-2s for research at night, when
the Space Theater shuts down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in the Golden Age of astronomy,'' booms the
voice of Tom Hanks, who narrates the space show, which aims to
illustrate that claim as dramatically as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The images are beamed onto the dome from a one-of-a-kind Zeiss
Mark IX star-projector, bolstered by seven high-definition
SEOS-Prodas digital projectors, which display 9.2 million pixels
(five times the resolution of the most sophisticated
High-Definition Television, and on a much larger scale) _ all of
which account for a lifelike sense of motion, dimension, and depth
that even the brightest sky shows don't begin to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea,'' says Tyson, ``is to make your journey
through the universe personal, to make you realize your place in it
and that you are a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This, it does, in ways that some might find unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Cosmic Pathway, a 360-foot spiral ramp that lays out
the timespan of the universe. At the start of the ramp is the Big
Bang of 13 billion years ago. Each step you take marks the passing
of 50 million years, until you get to the end, where the entire
duration of human history, from cave dwellers to the present, takes
up the breadth of a strand of hair.
</P>
<P>
   In short, we are but a smidgen of a nanosecond, the tip of a
blip on the cosmic radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Scales of the Universe exhibit, a 400-foot
square walkway around the sphere. At the start, a sign reads, ``If
the Hayden sphere is the size of our observable universe, then this
model,'' _ a tiny ball _ ``is the relative size of the Virgo
supercluster of galaxies.'' Next: If the sphere is the Virgo
supercluster, this model, another tiny ball, is the local group of
galaxies. Then: If the sphere is the local group, this is the Milky
Way.
</P>
<P>
   And on it goes, smaller and smaller, till 30 stops later, we
reach the realm of rain drops, blood clots, and subatomic
particles.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brilliant way of portraying relative sizes and scales,
but the message is once again clear: We are but a speck's speck.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson acknowledges this: ``At every point, you learn how tiny
you are _ in time, in space, in size. That doesn't worry me. The
truth is always better than falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he goes on, his eyes widening, ``it's also empowering,
because you then realize: We've figured this out. Human beings have
figured it out. However small we are, however short a time we've
been here, our minds have grasped the universe, we understand how
it works. That makes me feel big.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' he adds, in a stage-whisper, ``some people in
this world need their egos deflated.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he laughs, loudly.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Tyson is the youngest director in the Hayden's 65-year
history. He grew up in the Bronx, and knew he wanted to become an
astrophysicist at age 9, when he first visited the old Hayden
Planetarium. ``I saw all those stars at the sky-show _ I'd never
seen so many stars in the Bronx, I was hooked,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   He continued his boyhood interest in sports, winning baseball
trophies and gold medals for track, swimming, and wrestling. But at
age 14, he also went on his first astronomical expedition, to the
northwest coast of Africa to photograph a total solar eclipse. The
next year, he gave his first professional lecture. He went on to
Harvard, then Columbia for his Ph.D., published books and articles,
taught at Princeton, and was appointed director of the Hayden in
1996, just as plans for the renovation began.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is also one of only a dozen or so black astrophysicists in
America. In his just-published memoir, ``The Sky Is Not the
Limit,'' he recalls an incident from his sophomore year at Harvard,
when a fellow black student, an economics major who was planning to
study urban poverty, told him, ``Blacks in America do not have the
luxury of your intellectual talents being spent on astrophysics.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long time after that, Tyson carried what he calls
``suppressed guilt for pursuing my esoteric interests in the
universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, nine years later, he had a revelation. A local news show
asked him down to the station to explain a series of explosions on
the sun that had been detected by a recently launched solar
satellite. That evening, as he watched himself on TV, he realized,
``At no time could I recall a black person . . . being interviewed
as an expert on something that had nothing whatever to do with
being black. For the first time in nine years I stood without guilt
for following my cosmic dreams,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson joined the Hayden in the hopes, above all, of inspiring
young people the way it once inspired him. Ellen Futter, director
of the Museum of Natural History, expects 500,000 schoolchildren a
year to visit the Hayden, or, as the entire complex is now called,
the Rose Center for Earth and Space. All told, Futter estimated the
Rose Center will boost the Museum's annual attendance figure, which
stands at 4 million people, by another million at least.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The most popular attraction at the old Hayden, by
far, was the Weight-on-Other-Worlds exhibit, an array of scales
that told you how much you would weigh on the moon, on Jupiter, and
so forth. It was a hokey exhibit, but everybody remembers it
because it gave you at least a hint of what another planet was
like.
</P>
<P>
   The new Hayden has digital scales next to various objects
throughout the building, not just the moon and the planets but also
a neutron star and Haley's Comet. As a separate exhibit, though,
the concept has been junked. After all, there's no thrill in
stepping on a scale and pretending you're in outer space, when you
can feel like you're really there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
