<HEADLINE>
THE FALL AND FALL OF `THE PRACTICE' AND `ALLY MCBEAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was but five months ago that ABC's ``The Practice'' and Fox's
``Ally McBeal'' won Emmys for best drama and best comedy,
respectively, and, mostly, deservedly.
</P>
<P>
   Like them or hate them, and many viewers have liked and hated
them simultaneously, David E. Kelley's quirky legal series have
brought an element of the unexpected to series television.
</P>
<P>
   The two shows, set in Boston, have also formed a neat little
Janus of the justice system, circa 2000: glum and sleazy on one
mask, surrealistic and silly on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it was but five months ago that both of these Kelley
creations began to slip rather quietly down the unisex toilet. They
say positive reinforcement fosters quality in performance, but in
the case of Kelley and his firms, the Emmys coincided with his
descent into softness. With ``Ally McBeal,'' the fall comes as no
big surprise; the strikingly original comedy had ``fast flight''
written all over it the day it hit the air in 1997. But ``The
Practice,'' which premiered in the spring of that year, has shown
real potential to become one of TV's long-term favorites, even to
join the league of memorable nighttime dramas such as ``L. A. Law''
and ``ER.'' Its decline has been harder to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' isn't exactly awful this season _ it does come
up with a good moment every few weeks _ but it has lost its dazzle.
One disappointment has been the minimizing of Camryn Manheim, whose
Ellenor Frutt is the show's least glamorous but most engaging
character. An actress who can knock down a house with a roll of her
eyes, Manheim has been given far too few plots this season.
</P>
<P>
   And the plots themselves, always a strength of ``The Practice,''
have lost their tension and originality, like last week's ``Primal
Fear'' knockoff, or the recent recovered-memory fiasco. At the peak
of its creative arc, the drama consistently delivered highly
charged situations _ Lindsay defending her former mentor, for
instance, or Ellenor dating a crooked chiropractor. And it boldly
developed them across episodes, despite the network logic that says
ongoing plots alienate new viewers. (``ER,'' which no longer
cultivates long story lines, has succumbed to that thinking.) But,
unless this week's episode worked some magic (it was unavailable
for preview), this season of ``The Practice'' has yet to build any
compelling long-term intrigues. Even the juicy George Vogelman
thread left dangling from last season was cursorily dumped in
October, with some crummy grade-B-horror moves.
</P>
<P>
   Add to all that the bummer pairing of Helen and Ellenor as
roommates, the unbelievable alliance of Helen and Richard Bay as a
romantic possibility, Eugene's redundant family drama, and the
out-of-character premarital woes between Bobby and Lindsay (she
wants more sex, he wants her in his mother's gown) and you've got a
too-far-from-perfect ``Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``The Practice'' hit its bottom two weeks ago, during
a two-parter that brought the gang to LA to defend a man Lindsay
barely knew. The whole scenario was incongruous, and not simply
because the hotheaded Bostonians looked so humorously alien on
planet Hollywood. Would Lindsay really have taken the case in the
first place? Would Bobby, Jimmy, Ellenor, and Lucy fly out to help
her simply because she intuits innocence against all odds? No and
no. And the quickie resolution of the case, which hits Lindsay in a
lightning flash as a woman puts on glasses, was ridiculous, a
throwback to more simplistic courtroom dramas such as ``Perry
Mason.'' For a show that has asked us to put on our thinking caps
to follow some gnarly legal twists, this was slumming.
</P>
<P>
   The clincher came in the final airport scene of that episode,
when their innocent client serenades the ensemble with bombast
about how worthy they are as lawyers. What has been so juicy and so
contemporary about the firm on ``The Practice'' is their disrepute,
their questionable tactics, their slippery morality, their
willingness to sling plan B at a moment's notice. Heroes? Thanks,
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' has been similarly engaged in efforts to make
its team of loonies into Cabbage Patch Kids. The result: four-star
cringe moments. Two weeks ago, Georgia sued the firm for the
breakup of her marriage, giving John Cage an opportunity to deliver
a rousing defense of the office's sexed-up atmosphere. It was
McBaloney. And it was equaled last week, when the suddenly
softhearted Ling bonds with an elderly man, and the most cynical of
characters, Richard Fish, is seen sobbing over the man's sad fate.
P-P-P-Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as ``Ally McBeal'' has deteriorated into a pandering
mess of titillation, schmaltz, and blondness, Calista Flockhart has
improved her acting style enormously. She no longer relies on
hyperventilating and stammering to convey Ally's anxiety, and she
is so much easier to watch. But her character has nowhere left to
go _ something both Gil Bellows and Courtney Thorne-Smith have
realized about Billy and Georgia. In recent weeks, both actors
announced their decisions to leave the show.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the problems with the show and ``The Practice''
may have more to do with Kelley's schedule than anything else. He
may be losing creative steam regarding his cranky Boston babies, or
he just may be stretched too thin of late, working on the canceled
``Snoops,'' the canceled half-hour ``Ally,'' and the retooling of
``Chicago Hope,'' as well as the other two. The temptations of a
bigger piece of the television pie might be undermining his
creative stamina. Now surely ``Ally McBeal'' has delivered some
wisdom on the subject of size?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
