elections. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MITROVICA (Mitrovica) _ Tens of thousands of Albanians
march on Mitrovica; peacekeepers turn them back. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC-ITALIANS (Montreal) _ Language wars. After two years of
petitions from Montreal's 200,000-strong Italian community,
Quebec's official place names commission voted two months ago to
rename a 32-year-old suspension bridge after Pietro Rizzuto, a
Sicilian who arrived here penniless in 1955, made a fortune in road
construction, and died three years ago, a senator in his adopted
land. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-RESIGN (New York) _ As antitrust pressure mounts on the
auction houses Sotheby's and Christie's, the president and chief
executive of Sotheby's, Diana D. Brooks, resigns. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-MERGER (Montreal) _ For much of the last century, the
Canadian National railroad helped define Canada. But now Canadian
National plans to merge with a giant American railroad, the
Burlington Northern and Santa Fe, and its focus has shifted to the
south. The merger underscores how far the formation of a true North
American economy has developed in the six years since the North
American Free Trade Agreement went into effect. Although they may
be less visible, the auto, banking, and telecommunications
industries already operate on a north-south axis and pay hardly any
attention to borders. Not everyone accepts the vision of the new
railroad or the changes it represents. In the United States,
shippers and unions want to derail the deal. In Canada, shippers
and farmers are concerned, while nationalists see the proposed
merger as the loss of a revered national symbol. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-CHARGES (Undated) _ A debate is raging within the
Federal Communications on whether to change the rules that allow
phone companies to charge cellular phone customers for both
incoming and outgoing calls. In Europe and other parts of the
world, callers to a wireless phone pick up the tab. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-STRIKE (Undated) _ An update on the strike by 17,000
engineers and technical workers against Boeing. While many
analysts, and possibly the company, had expected the white-collar
workers, unaccustomed to walkout and lacking strike fund benefits,
to knuckle under, nearly 90 percent are staying out. What effect
has the strike had on production? By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Like America Online and Time
Warner in the United States, Pacific Century's bid for Hong Kong's
flagship telephone company, Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, dramatizes the
gravity-defying levels of Internet stocks in Asia. But the gambit
by Pacific Century, an Internet start-up, is in some ways even more
brazen than AOL's: the company has no operating profits, no
customers, and has not even launched the Internet and television
service that is supposed to be its core business. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   FOX-MULTIMILLIONAIRE (New York) _ Developments inside Fox
Television Entertainment, after the ``Multimillionaire'' debacle.
Fox canceled the rebroadcast of its highly rated special ``Who
Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' after learning that the groom,
Rick Rockwell, once was accused of hitting and threatening to kill
an ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   MCI-EUROPE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The European Commission, which
nearly derailed the merger of MCI and Worldcom two years ago, plans
to take a hard look at MCI Worldcom's planned acquisition of
Sprint. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-SUIT (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ In court papers filed in
London Monday, the Wall Street hedge-fund manager, Leon Cooperman
joined another American investment fund in suing the Czech
investment promoter Viktor Kozeny. In the civil suit, Cooperman
alleged that Kozeny defrauded and enriched himself. The other
plaintiff is Marlwood Commercial Inc., a subsidiary of the American
International Group, a diversified insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   CGU-NORWICH (London) CGU Plc and Norwich Union Plc agreed to
combine in a $12 billion stock swap, creating the Britain's
second-largest life insurer, as competition for premiums increases.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, U.S. equity markets are closed today for the
Presidents' Day holiday.
</P>
