<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-CRESTED     02-21 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-CRESTED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 BUTTE-COLORADO-LADN  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The many charms of Crested Butte
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Irwin, Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   CRESTED BUTTE, Colo. -- Crested Butte Mountain Resort is known
for its extreme skiing. Where else would you find a mountain big
enough to hold the U.S. Extreme Freeskiing Championships for the
past three years?
</P>
<P>
   We're talking a Wild West sort of place with 824 acres of
ungroomed, double-diamond, out-of-your-mind terrain. And, after a
five-year closure, the resort plans to reopen Teocalli Bowl,
another 274 heart-pounding acres of extreme, backcountry-style,
patrolled terrain for experts only.
</P>
<P>
   Crested Butte boasts that it has the largest number of
expert-only slopes served by a chairlift in the United States --
steep and deep double-diamond runs, just the way extreme skiers and
boarders like them.
</P>
<P>
   But Crested Butte showed a gentler side on a recent ski trip
here. Resort officials were apologetic about the lack of snow,
which prevented them from opening the expert trails, and I wondered
whether the trip would be worth it. But after three days of nonstop
skiing, I responded in a resounding affirmative. Maybe only half of
the mountain was open, but it was my half.
</P>
<P>
   I rarely had to wait in a lift line, even though 1,600 college
students were there for their holiday break. The vast mountain is
served by 14 lifts that have an uphill capacity of 17,440 skiers
per hour, so lines seldom get long. Try nonstop skiing for hours on
end and you'll never go back to the long lines at our local
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the beginning and intermediate trails were covered
by a couple feet of man-made snow. And every night, the mountain
received a fresh coating of powder.
</P>
<P>
   The ski resort has snowmaking on 300 acres served by 12 of the
14 chairlifts. All in all, this majestic, 12,162-foot mountain in
the heart of the Elk Mountains provided a great beginning for the
ski season.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain, located 230 miles southwest of Denver, has 60
percent of its terrain devoted to beginner and intermediate skiers,
40 percent to advanced and expert skiers.
</P>
<P>
   From the peak, the views in all directions were sensational.
Surprisingly, an intermediate skier can ride all the way up to the
summit and still ski down easily. These are real intermediate
slopes, not expert runs disguised as intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ski mountain itself, the town of Crested Butte has a
split personality. Three miles from the resort, the old mining town
is an extensive historic district. The false fronts of this Western
town date back to the 1880s, when silver was discovered in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the town has maintained an authentic Western flavor.
On the outside, the buildings look like a splintery, authentic
mining town, but on the inside you'll find all the modern
conveniences of any small American city.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the century-old Victorian fronts lie some excellent
restaurants. The large number of restaurants once prompted Michael
Carlton of Southern Living magazine to comment that Crested Butte
has more fine restaurants per capita than any other town in
America. While that may be the subject of some debate, it's
certainly true that Crest Butte has more fine restaurants than you
could visit during a week-long stay.
</P>
<P>
   If history interests you, stop at the historical museum for a
free audio tour of the town. While the 45-minute tape may be a
little long for a walk in cold temperatures, it certainly gives you
an better understanding of the town's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about renting a car -- convenient shuttle buses run
from the resort to downtown every 15 minutes throughout the day.
Just jump on the bus and in a few minutes you're downtown for
dinner or shopping.
</P>
<P>
   If you're tuckered out after a long day of skiing, as I was,
you'll still find several good restaurants and bars on the
mountain. The elegant Woodstone Grille in the Sheraton serves
excellent dinners, while Antlers in the Marriott is a good place
for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   If nightlife is important to you, try Rafters, a huge nightclub
located literally in the rafters of the Gothic Building. There are
also several breweries downtown that are worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   The March Madness package costs $353 per person, double
occupancy, and includes five nights lodging and a four-day lift
ticket. This package is offered through April 1, at which time
prices drop to $114 per person, double occupancy, for three nights
lodging.
</P>
<P>
   The prices are reasonable when you consider that an adult
three-day lift ticket costs $156 if purchased separately (daily
rate is $52). And Crested Butte is very family friendly. Children
12 years of age and under pay their age for a lift ticket (a
6-year-old pays $6, for example). A special teen-ager rate of $40
is offered for students 13 to 17 years of age. From April 2 through
16, lift tickets are free for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Crested Butte was a great choice for a quick winter
getaway. If I had such a good time with a little snow, I can only
imagine what it might be like now -- the resort received 3 feet of
new snow at the end of January. The resort receives an average of
300 inches annually.
</P>
<P>
   ----IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: United Airlines offers numerous flights from
Southern California to Denver, and United Express has five daily
commuter flights to Gunnison, 30 miles from the resort. Airport
shuttles provide convenient transfers to the resort. America West
flies to Montrose, 91 miles from the resort. Hotel shuttles serve
that airport, too.
</P>
<P>
   SKI STATS: Crested Butte offers 1,434 acres of skiing, with 85
trails. The longest run is 2.6 miles long, running from Crested
Butte Peak to the bottom of East River. Its base area is located at
9,100 feet, giving the resort a vertical drop of 2,775 feet. The
resort's 14 lifts include three high-speed detachable quad
chairlifts, three triple chairs, three double chairs and five
surface lifts.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: In addition to the resort's Marriott and Sheraton,
there are more than 50 other hotels, inns, bed-and-breakfasts and
condominiums from which to choose. These are available in a wide
price range -- from the luxurious Plaza Condominiums to the
economical Crested Butte International Hostel. For more
information, call Crested Butte Mountain Resort's central
reservations center at (800) 544-8448.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: For current weather conditions, snow reports,
special deals or to register for lessons, visit the resort's Web
site at www.crestedbutteresort.com. Or call (800) 867-6933 for the
snow report, (800) 444-9236 for the ski and snowboard school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
