<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-IRWIN-C     02-21 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-IRWIN-COLORADO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biggest little ski resort in Colorado
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Irwin, Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   IRWIN, Colo. -- Powder skiers shouldn't miss a trip to Irwin
Lodge, the largest snowcat skiing resort in North America. Located
12 miles from Crested Butte, this rustic lodge is surrounded by
2,200 skiable acres. But the resort allows only 44 skiers to enjoy
this pristine wilderness every day.
</P>
<P>
   Built 10,700 feet above sea level, Irwin Lodge receives an
average of 600 inches of snow every season. That's more than 50
feet of clean, white powder.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has dreamed of carving perfect curves through virgin
powder will enjoy this adventure. To experience the steep slopes,
bowls and chutes, however, the skier should possess intermediate
skills or above.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, large snowcats carry guests up through the crisp
mountain air to begin a day of white revelry. Good skiers can fly
down six to eight long runs on an average day.
</P>
<P>
   For safety reasons, avalanche beacons are provided. And a 6-to-1
ratio is maintained between skiers and guides, who have all
received emergency medical training.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1974 as a private retreat, Irwin Lodge was refurbished
three years ago. Though quite rustic, the lodge is still
comfortable. Best of all, there are no phones in the lodge, which
offers 21 rooms and a master suite.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to get to the lodge is via heated snowcat or a
Chevy suburban on snowtracks. Literally cut off from the rest of
the world, the lodge asks guests to turn off lights and shut the
windows whenever they leave their rooms because the lodge has to
generate its own electricity. In fact, there's a brief power
interruption at 10:30 every night when the lodge switches to a
smaller generator.
</P>
<P>
   Clocks are provided in the rooms, but they gain 15 minutes every
day because of power surges. So be sure to reset your clock before
you go to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about being claustrophobic; the common room offers
8,000 square feet of open space. A huge field-stone fireplace
dominates the main room. Around the perimeter are bookcases, a pool
table, foosball and racks of board games. When was the last time
you played Monopoly or Risk with friends on a ski trip?
</P>
<P>
   A separate bar serves up libations, while the dining room
prepares excellent dinners. The chefs were out of their famous elk
stew during my visit, but the peppercorn steak was delicious.
</P>
<P>
   None of this comes cheap. A room for one night with a day of
skiing costs $375 single occupancy and $330 per person double
occupancy. A minimum stay of two nights is usually required --
three nights if your stay includes a Friday or Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That's not too bad, however, when you consider that all meals
are included and the skiing alone, if purchased separately, would
cost $225 per person. Besides, where else can you ski powder that's
this deep?
</P>
<P>
   In April, the rates drop to $260 single occupancy and $230 per
person double occupancy, and there is no minimum-stay requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lack of snow, I chose to visit the lodge on a
dinner snowmobile tour. It was beautiful as we wound our way up
through the mountain forests in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   When we stopped along the trail and turned our lights off, a
million bright stars flickered in the cold winter night. The
black-velvet sky was spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Snowshoe and cross-country ski tours are also available if you
want to quieter adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ----For more information, call the Irwin Lodge at (888) 464-7946
or check its Web site at www.goirwin.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
