<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-IRISHTRAVELLERS-1000(     02-21 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISHTRAVELLERS-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY ACCIDENT REVEALS HIDDEN LIFE OF IRISH TRAVELLERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MELODY MCDONALD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Five young cousins killed last month in a
horrific accident on Interstate 30 died as they lived: close
together, of necessity as much as fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   The accident shocked the public, but questions arose when
authorities learned that none of the boys were older than 14 and
four of them were carrying false driver's licenses that
misrepresented their age.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to gather details about the youths have led to a
fragmented mosaic of the culture from which they came: All were
children of Irish Travellers _ secretive descendants of 19th
century nomads who speak an archaic dialect, marry within the clan
and specialize in home improvement and business repair work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with a closed society,'' said Joe Livingston, a
South Carolina-based national expert on Irish Travellers. ``You can
infiltrate the Mafia, but you can't infiltrate this group. Unless
you're family, they won't talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the accident, the media coverage and public
attention tormented the group of Travellers who were wintering at
campgrounds in the Fort Worth suburb of White Settlement where the
victims had been staying. The parents were infuriated. ``It is our
grief,'' screamed Ed McDonald, father of the youngest victim,
12-year-old Martin. ``The truth is, five kids are dead. Let's leave
it at that. If you are part of my family, you can know about them.
If not, you don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Many North Texans expressed sympathy and sought to contribute
money to a memorial fund. The Travellers would have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Irish Traveller culture is limited as much by
lack of knowledge of the culture as by the reluctance of Travellers
to discuss their way of life with outsiders, whom they refer to as
``country men.'' Authorities estimate that only 30,000 Travellers,
of Irish, Scottish and English descent, live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Travellers react angrily to high-profile attention, Livingston
said.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the dead cousins declined repeated requests to talk
about either the Travellers' culture or the victims who were killed
when their westbound pickup truck veered out of control, flipped
over the I-30 median and crashed upside down on top of an eastbound
pickup. Shortly after the accident, some Traveller families
withdrew their children from school. Victims' families met with
investigators only once.
</P>
<P>
   The Travellers' detachment is centuries-old and focused on
preserving their culture.
</P>
<P>
   They regulate their own affairs, rarely attend school past the
sixth grade, and display a near compulsion for material goods.
Their hallmarks are wads of $100 bills, expensive cars and elegant
clothes. In Ireland and the United States, Travellers have had
reputations as accomplished con artists.
</P>
<P>
   They are descendants of an Irish group that came to America in
the mid-1800s to escape persecution and the potato famine. They
roamed the country by horse and wagon in search of various jobs.
Today, they roll through life in shiny new trucks and
travel-trailers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life that only Travellers understand, one scholar
insists.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Hancock, a professor at the University of Texas at Austin
who wrote the Irish Travellers entry for the Encyclopedia of the
South, questions the existence of credible outsider sources on
Irish Travellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to law enforcement officers, the only people they
know are people they have had contact with,'' said Hancock, who
also serves as the ambassador to the United Nations for his fellow
Romani, or Gypsies. ``If you talk to academics, they have spent
little time with them. There is a danger. I would say the bottom
line is that the people that can tell you the most don't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Most Irish Travellers roam the country, soliciting work and
wintering in such places as Murphy Village, S.C., and White
Settlement. Those in this area _ the Carrolls, Gormans, McDonalds,
Daleys and Jennings _ are known as the Greenhorn Irish Travellers
and generally work west of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders and residents said Travellers often frequent
Carswell Golf Course and Neiman Marcus and attend St. Patrick's
Cathedral, where the cousins' funerals were held.
</P>
<P>
   They drive new trucks laden with the tools and materials of
their trade, such as paint, water sprayers, and roof and sidewalk
sealants. They unhitch their travel-trailers at a handful of
campgrounds throughout the area and settle for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   During winter, the men solicit construction, roofing and paving
work, while the women travel in large groups to shopping malls,
beauty shops and tanning salons, paying cash for goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilmore said the Travellers have been frequenting the
north side bar where he works for about six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a bunch of girls and a bunch of guys that come in
and they all say they're cousins,'' Gilmore said. ``When the girls
come into the bar, they don't drink; the men drink. They won't let
anybody associate with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids come in with gobs of money. They spend $100 bills
like it's nothing. I have no idea where all this money comes
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the children attend area schools, though few seek higher
education.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Hope, principal of North Elementary in White Settlement,
said that many Travellers have attended her school but only for a
short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``None go to school year-round and none have ever been here the
entire year,'' Hope said. ``They come around Thanksgiving and leave
around Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope said that the boys in the accident did not attend North
Elementary but that some of their relatives withdrew from classes
shortly after the wreck. Some, she said, are still enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Members of one outsider family had befriended the accident
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Martinez, 10, and her mother, Genoveva Martinez, live
across the road from the mobile home park where many Traveller
families stay when they are in town.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinezes recognized the cousins who died in the accident
by their pictures on the cover of their funeral program.
</P>
<P>
   The boys hadn't volunteered much information about their lives.
``They would come over and jump on our trampoline every day for
about three months,'' Dolores Martinez said. ``They said they went
to home school. They said their dads traveled around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that Traveller children go to work at a young
age, often obtaining false identifications so they can drive and
work.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Travellers, especially the women, are pious Roman
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tim Thompson of St. Peter's Catholic Church in White
Settlement said that many Traveller women and children have
attended daily Mass during the winter months for at least four
years. They also attend on Sundays, he said, while most of the men
wait outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church seats 600 and we get an extra 200 in the winter and
then they leave,'' he said. ``It's overwhelming, but they have a
right to go to church, receive sacraments and practice their
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he first came into contact with the Travellers several
years ago when he was asked to give last rites to a dying woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a trailer park, and a lady directed me back,'' he
said. ``Her daughter and granddaughter were there. They were
responding to my prayers and responded in an Irish accent. Later, I
asked where they were from, and they said they have lived here all
their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the women are always beautifully dressed at
church. Other community members have also noted their seemingly
extravagant lifestyle _ new cars and trucks, large amounts of cash,
expensive jewelry and furs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to respect them, allow them to practice their faith and
let God be their judge,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Some Travellers are well-trained con artists, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, most of the ones we come in contact with are
scam artists,'' said Detective S.M. Haines of the Dallas Police
Department swindle section. ``Those are the ones we hear about.
I've made friends with them, whereas most officers only hear bad
things about their culture. If you never meet any Travellers except
crooks there is only one opinion you can have about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Haines said that jurors in Dallas County have convicted a few
English Travellers involved in home-improvement scams. But none of
the prosecutions involve Irish Travellers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that a common scam is spray-painting barns and
houses with paint diluted with water or gasoline. The finished job
lasts a couple of months before the paint blisters. By that time,
the workers are gone.
</P>
<P>
   The swindlers are rarely caught, Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out and rob a bank and get $1,500, there are 50 FBI
agents chasing you,'' said Livingston, who has assisted in a couple
dozen arrests of Travellers. ``But if you work an elderly lady and
take her for $250,000 in a two-year period, who is going to
investigate you? Some local deputy who has no idea what a Traveller
is?''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution is even rarer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Travellers try to negotiate their restitution and
release,'' Livingston said. ``They'll offer to give the victim
their money back. The prosecutor says, `Great.' Police are happy
because they don't have to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Miller, a Tarrant County district attorney for 12 years,
said he can't recall a single prosecution of an Irish Traveller in
Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States, juries have convicted Travellers for
scamming people, usually the elderly. But no law enforcement
agencies could say how many cases have been filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   Detective John McMahon, an agent with the Orange County, Fla.,
Sheriff's Department's special investigation division, studies
Irish Travellers across the nation, especially in south Florida. He
said that Travellers involved in con games are masters of
``confusion and illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   They are transients, never stay in one place very long, use
several addresses, and often carry false identifications, he said.
Because they share a limited number of surnames, dozens of
Travellers have variations of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid confusion within the group, Travellers often call each
other by nicknames. On the funeral program, for example, James
Thomas McDonald was also listed as ``Jim MC.'' John Peter McDonald
was called ``Johnny Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   The Travellers have their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Thompson Sr., of Gene Thompson and Associates, a real
estate investment company, said the Travellers have been staying at
his White Settlement campgrounds for about 10 years, always
arriving when the mercury drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 95 to 98 percent of those we have done business with
have been positive,'' Thompson said. ``I keep reading that they go
out and con people. But I know some people they have worked for
that are satisfied. They're not all crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that three Travellers with the last name McDonald
recently bought the RV campgrounds at 7409 Raymond St. and 410 N.
Cherry Lane, which contain a total of 90 spaces for recreational
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started dealing with them, we were scared to
death,'' Thompson said. ``They don't live like we live. The things
that are strange to us are the intermarrying. They're all related
somehow. There are more Marys and Johns and Jims. But after we got
to know them, we didn't worry about them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are good for the community. They come in and spend a lot
of money _ the clothes they buy, the cars they buy, the food they
eat. I would welcome them any time in my community if I was a
community leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the Travellers who stay in White Settlement also
spend time in Albany, a town of about 2,000 located 110 miles west
of Fort Worth. Each year, he said, the Travellers stay at motels he
owns there and work around the town.
</P>
<P>
   Nariman Esfandiary, owner of Fort Griffin General Merchandise
Restaurant and Beehive Saloon in Albany, said that Travellers with
the last name McDonald have been doing work for him for about six
years and are ``nothing but good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know their first names, but it is always the same
family _ a father, two brothers or maybe a cousin or nephew,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Esfandiary said they laid an asphalt parking lot at his
restaurant six or seven years ago, and they return each year to
reseal it as part of their regular maintenance. He said they have
worked for several people in town and that their prices are
reasonable, although he usually trades food and drink for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small town,'' he said. ``If they scammed anyone,
they would be ruined because everyone talks. ... They stay in the
motel, fill up their truck in town, go to the grocery store. They
spend a lot of money while they are here.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday afternoon wreck, just west of the Loop 820
interchange and the Alemeda Street exit, closed the eastbound lanes
of I-30 for several hours while rescue teams worked to free the
victims. Even the most hardened emergency workers were deeply
moved, some to tears, as they removed the bodies of the five boys
from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Police have closed their investigation of the crash, which
killed Edward James Jennings, 14; Harry Gerard Gorman, 13; James
Thomas McDonald, 13; John Peter McDonald, 13; and Martin James
McDonald, 12. Questions of why Jennings was behind the wheel and
why the four oldest boys carried false driver's licenses may never
be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Molinar of Plano, the driver of the other truck involved
in the accident, was released from Harris Methodist Fort Worth on
Jan. 6. He has declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the cousins were questioned after a funeral
program revealed that they were 14 and younger. Officials found
out-of-state driver's licenses on four boys, listing their ages
from 16 to 20 _ information that family members never disputed.
</P>
<P>
   The only official statement released by the Irish Travellers
came from Richard Waters, who authorities believe is a 62-year-old
Irish Traveller in New York State. Waters posted the following
statement on his Web site, Travellers' Rest:
</P>
<P>
   ``Five young Irish Traveller boys were killed in a truck
collision on Sunday afternoon, on the second day of a new year that
they will never enjoy, a new century that they can never know. A
country man named Ruben Molinar Sr. was seriously hurt in the crash
and was brought to Harris Methodist Fort Worth hospital. There are
lessons to be learned belatedly from this terrible accident and
while I offer prayers to God for their souls and Mr. Molinar's full
recovery I will also pray that we heed those lessons. Will you join
me in that?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Melody McDonald is a staff writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7386, or e-mail:
mjmcdonald(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
