<SLUG> BC-TOWNFORSALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTE CUSTOM TOWN FOR SALE, QUIET WEST TEXAS LOCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lajitas, an Old West resort, pop. 160, is going to the highest
bidder this week.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m. Thursday, an entire community will go be auctioned to
the strains of mariachi guitars.
</P>
<P>
   On the block is Lajitas, a resort town with 160 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Wedged between Big Bend National Park and Big Bend Ranch State
Park, Lajitas comes complete with a golf course, a hotel, three
motels, a 14-bed bunk house, condominiums, church, saloon, bakery,
trading-post-turned-grocery, sewage plant, an 80-spot RV park,
restaurants, six subdivisions, a 4,800-foot-long airstrip and
heart-achingly scenic vistas on 24,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the beer-guzzling goat named Clay Henry III, which
was elected ``mayor'' in November, and the town's full-gallop
footnote in history. Gen. John Pershing used Lajitas as a jumping
off point in his pre-World War I cavalry pursuit of Mexican
revolutionary Francisco ``Pancho'' Villa.
</P>
<P>
   During the years, the area has served as a backdrop to such
movies and TV programs as ``Barbarosa,'' ``Gunsmoke'' and ``Streets
of Laredo,'' as well as for Marlboro and Chevy Suburban
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me Ted Turner was interested,'' said Linda
Garcia, a native of upper Michigan who moved to the area in 1972,
joining an eclectic mix of urban dropouts, musicians, craftsmen,
river-rafting enthusiasts and desert fanciers in the
Lajitas-Terlingua-Study Butte area. ``One thing about living in a
small town, there's lots of rumors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston developer Walter M. Mischer, 77, bought a jumble of
rundown buildings that was Lajitas 23 years ago. He built himself a
five-bedroom, Santa Fe-style villa and invested millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves this country, but it's a good time to sell,'' said a
grandson, Randy Corson, 31, who served several years as the
resort's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneer William Bone, who specializes in trophy properties,
said there's been surprisingly scant interest so far from hotel
chains and business magnates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you that Ross Perot has been out there,
but he hasn't,'' Bone said in a call from his base in Gadsden, Ala.
``I wish I could tell you that the Bass brothers have been out
there, but they haven't either.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bone predicts a well-heeled Texan will fly in at
the last minute and buy himself (or herself) a town.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, you've got 2 1/2 miles on the Rio Grande. You've got
some of the best hunting anywhere,'' he said, not at all trying to
contain his professional enthusiasm. ``And it all pays for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The auctioneer wouldn't disclose any financial records but said
that the Brewster County tax district appraised the 2,650-acre
resort at $3.7 million and the adjoining 21,350 acres at about $1.5
million. And, it produces ``hundreds of thousands of dollars'' in
annual profits
</P>
<P>
   Bone said the auction was expected to fetch bids in the
neighborhood of $5 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pay that,'' said Bill Ivey, 44, owner of the nearby
Terlingua ghost town. Ivey grew up in Lajitas, which his father Rex
owned from 1949 to 1977. The town had a population of nine,
including four in his family back then. It processed candelilla wax
for cosmetics, crayons and chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Mischer then acquired the land and transformed it into a resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's put more than $5 million into it,'' Ivey said.
``But you've got to take into consideration the age of the
improvements, the condition they're in and the cost of repair. Some
of the past management didn't always keep things up well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the right plan, someone could pay that much and come
out way ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the auction, Ivey said: ``There's been a lot of concern
that some conglomerate could buy it and Lajitas would become just
another resort. Mr. Mischer has had a very personal interest in
Lajitas the entire time he's had it. So it's difficult for some of
us because it's the last stronghold of the last frontier in the
United States. And that might be gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   What: Auction of Lajitas
</P>
<P>
   Where: Lajitas, 170 miles south of Alpine
</P>
<P>
   When: Thursday, noon registration, 2 p.m. auction
</P>
<P>
   Tours: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. daily by appointment
</P>
<P>
   Contact: (877) 547-5560 or (256) 547-3434
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneers: The National Auction Group, Gadsden, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Barry Shlachter is a staff writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7718, or e-mail:
bshlachter(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
