<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADJUST YOUR NOSE RINGS, PLEASE; WE'RE IN FOR A LONG RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY DARYL LEASE
</P>
<P>
   NYT REGIONAL NEWSPAPERS
</P>
<P>
   The nation was preoccupied last week with multimillionaire Rick
Rockwell's televised quest to find a bride _ um, is it just me, or
does anyone else think we ought to be leery of encouraging a real
estate developer/motivational consultant to reproduce? _ so I
decided to keep an eye on the news for everybody in case anything
important happened.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to report that only two things of genuine consequence
occurred. First, a fellow in Germany found the cure for the common
cold. And, second, as the result of another amazing scientific
discovery, Lassie's pal, Timmy, is about to fall down a well again
and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   First, the medical news: Alexander Loschke of Sulzbach, Germany,
has found a sniffles cure. According to the Reuters news agency, he
stumbled upon it while gardening.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the neighbors' tomato plants were rotting, but his
weren't. Alexander zeroed in on one major difference in his
approach _ the little copper rings he uses to attach his tomato
plants to their stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Alexander then asked himself the obvious next
question, namely: ``Gee, I wonder what would happen if I stuck
these things up my nose?'' And that he did, despite the fact that
he had a cold. Miraculously, his sniffles disappeared in just 36
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Alexander is selling packs of copper rings for 20 marks,
or about $10.03, each. I suspect he's well on his way to becoming a
multimillionaire and, perhaps, hobnobbing with the Rockwells.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the update on Lassie and Timmy: The Washington Post reports
that scientists at Texas A&AMP;M University are progressing nicely in
their efforts to clone a dog.
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall, an anonymous pair of millionaires put up a
$2.3 million prize a few years ago for a little game of ``Who Wants
to Clone Our Dog?'' Scientists found the money motivating and are
trying to create a double of the couple's mutt, Missy.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Westhusin, a veterinary physiologist at Texas A&AMP;M, told The
Post his team is ``90 percent there'' in reaching its goal. The
carbon-copy pooch could be produced as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The Post reports, at least four companies are now
collecting down payments from people who want their pets cloned.
One firm, the Texas-based Genetic Savings and Clone, is charging
$1,000 to retrieve DNA samples from pets and store them for the day
when pet cloning becomes a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Woof. Isn't that rich?
</P>
<P>
   You know, I can stomach TV producers starting up an assembly
line for mail-order brides. I can even tolerate a fellow trying to
sell me pieces of wire to push up my schnoz. But _ really, now _
are we willing to be led around by our nose rings on this
pet-cloning thing?
</P>
<P>
   Every day, all across the country, thousands upon thousands of
dogs and cats are put to gruesome deaths in animal shelters because
no one adopts them. So what do we do? Rather than throw these
critters a lifeline, we look for a way to crank out more Bowsers
and Tabbies _ all because we can't be troubled by our pets growing
old and dying like every other being on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these Bowsers and Tabbies won't be the same as the
originals. They'll just look the same.
</P>
<P>
   Let's examine this in terms of Lassie.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that Timmy's parents notice one day that Lassie is
losing a step or two chasing sticks in the back yard, and they
decide it's time to drive down to the Genetic Savings and Clone to
brew up a new Lassie for their little boy.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that, when they get to the clinic, they find out it's
running a special and, in a burst of generosity, they decide to buy
the tyke six Lassies. So they load the Lassies into the pickup,
drive back to the ranch and surprise the Timster with six
mirror-image pooches.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know what they'll have to do next? They'll have to throw
Timmy down the well, pin him under a rock, toss him into a forest
fire and re-create all of those other misadventures six separate
times so that each and every Lassie will have the same set of
experiences as the vintage Lassie.
</P>
<P>
   And what do you figure the old Lassie will do when she realizes
she's just one more special dog in a long, long line of special
dogs? Probably crawl under the porch in a deep, whimpering funk.
Hell, I might join her.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
