w e BC-MADONNA-IN-THE-NEXT-B     02-21 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADONNA-IN-THE-NEXT-BEST-THING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT KINDS OF LOVE: MADONNA SETTLES FOR `THE NEXT BEST
THING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Madonna with Rupert Everett in a scene
from ``The Next Best Thing.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Is there any role Madonna hasn't played?
 &HT;    Virgin and boy toy, sinner and saint. Sex symbol and
trend-setter, icon and pariah. Singer and actress, material girl
and maternal woman.
 &HT;    Madonna has done it all, surprising people again and again since
she arrived on the scene nearly 18 years ago.
 &HT;    ``It's not that my career has been based on surprising people,''
Madonna insists. ``My creative instincts have been to challenge
myself and to constantly do things that are going to broaden my own
mind and, in the process, hopefully the minds of other people.
 &HT;    ``First,'' she says, ``it has to interest me: `OK, is this going
to take me to another place? Am I going to learn something from
this? Is this going to inspire me?' That's where I always start,
whatever it is, whether it's music or film or whatever.
 &HT;    ``Hopefully, the manifestation of that is work that has some
effect on the audience.''
 &HT;    She's unquestionably connected with millions of fans through her
recordings and her vibrant, dance-driven live performances. But
she's had less luck on the big screen.
 &HT;    After stealing the show with a supporting role in ``Desperately
Seeking Susan'' (1985), Madonna elicited groans in ``Shanghai
Surprise'' (1986), ``Who's That Girl?'' (1987), ``Body of
Evidence'' (1993) and ``Four Rooms'' (1995). Not all her films
flopped _ she had effective bit parts in ``Dick Tracy'' (1990) and
``A League of Their Own'' (1992) _ but it wasn't until ``Evita''
(1996), in which she played the doomed Eva Peron, that Madonna won
genuine respect as an actress.
 &HT;    She insists, however, that she didn't need ``Evita'' to give her
confidence in her acting ability.
 &HT;    ``I needed some good roles and time with a really good acting
teacher,'' she says during a conversation at Manhattan's Rihga
Royal Hotel. ``I don't think it was necessarily `Evita.'''
 &HT;    At 41, dressed in black slacks and a shimmering blue-and-black
blouse, she remains every inch the star, at once smart, blunt and
playful. But, despite her celebrity and her musical prowess, movie
stardom has proven elusive: All eyes seem to be on her when she
acts, and it's almost as if people are hoping she fails, with her
box-office duds eliciting smug headlines and nasty gossip.
 &HT;    Madonna admits that she's had bad luck with the critics.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't say it's a question of them paying more attention,
but I do think they're much more judgmental,'' she says. ``That
goes for anybody who has been really successful in one area and
then wants to go off into another area and take it very seriously.
 &HT;    ``How on top of Michael Jordan was everybody when he decided he
wanted to play baseball?'' she says. ``It's kind of that same
thing.''
 &HT;    Madonna hopes that ``The Next Best Thing,'' opening March 3,
will be the hit she's been waiting for. Her first film in four
years, it's a romantic comedy with a serious edge, starring Madonna
and Rupert Everett as Abbie and Robert, best friends who wind up
fooling around and having a child together.
 &HT;    It's not a terribly uncommon scenario, except that Robert is
gay. The two happily raise their son, Sam (Malcolm Stumpf), but the
bliss ends a few years later, when Abbie falls in love with the
understanding, handsome Ben (Benjamin Bratt).
 &HT;    ``My first impression was that it was too much like a sitcom,''
Madonna says. ``I liked the idea of the friendship between Rupert's
character and my character, but that was it. I thought it needed
some rewrites. And that's when Rupert came in.''
 &HT;    Everett overhauled the script, though he goes uncredited, and
Madonna was much happier.
 &HT;    ``Then it was, of course, written for Rupert and me to do,'' she
says. ``The more they worked on it, the more I liked it.''
 &HT;    Early in the film Abbie is dumped by her boyfriend, who
complains that she's too together, too smart and too in control.
 &HT;    Madonna, no surprise, could relate.
 &HT;    ``Even though I had nothing to do with the writing of the
line,'' she says, ``I have found myself in situations with a man
where I've said, `Wait a second, you mean if I had less to offer
you I'd have a better chance in a relationship?'
 &HT;    ``I didn't exactly say it like that,'' the singer says, ``but
there have been many situations in my life where I felt that my
accomplishments and my success actually hindered certain
relationships. So I could relate to that _ but my life and Abbie's
life are obviously very different.
 &HT;    ``But I think a lot of the choices she makes _ the way she chose
to have the baby and raise the baby _ I probably would have done,
too.''
 &HT;    And, no, while Madonna admits that she finds the openly gay
Everett very attractive _ ``I adore him,'' she says, ``I'm sure if
he was straight things would be different'' _ the ``Best Thing''
story line does not reflect reality. The new love in her life is
director Guy Ritchie, best known for ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking
Barrels'' (1999), whom she met at a lunch arranged by mutual friend
Trudie Styler, wife of the singer Sting.
 &HT;    ``Yes, he's the boyfriend,'' Madonna confirms. ``He's a very
important `guy' in my life. I adore him.''
 &HT;    Despite lingering scars from her marriage to actor Sean Penn,
which ended in divorce, Madonna says she'd consider marrying again,
and ``would love'' to have more children. For now, though, she
fills her time with her daughter Lourdes, 90 minutes of yoga each
day and work on a new album, which she describes as
``stripped-down, minimalist funk-techno.''
 &HT;    It seems unlikely, given her high-powered image, but Madonna
reports that, as the mother of 3-year-old Lourdes _ whose father is
ex-beau Carlos Leon _ she spends a lot of time on the same
child-rearing issues as parents everywhere, including matters of
religion, schooling and discipline.
 &HT;    And, of course, some extras. Life as the daughter of one of the
most recognizable women on the planet won't be easy, for one thing,
and Madonna is already wrestling with the possibility that Lourdes
might one day want to follow in her mother's footsteps.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't deter her,'' she says thoughtfully, ``but I'd want
to make sure she knew what she was getting herself into. I'm sure
by the time she's of a decision-making age she'll know.
 &HT;    ``The climate of the entertainment industry changes from decade
to decade,'' the singer adds, ``so who knows what it will be like
when she gets older? But I do think you need to be pretty
thick-skinned to understand that it's about the big picture, not
the small picture, and that everybody's career is made up of lots
of ups and downs.
 &HT;    ``You have to be prepared for lots of rejection,'' she
concludes. ``You have to do what you do for the right reasons. If
your intention is just to become famous and popular, then that's a
pretty bad place to start off.''
 &HT;    Madonna rocks her head back and forth, blond curls falling in
her face as she thinks.
 &HT;    ``I think it comes from having skills, being good at what you
do, having things to say and being talented,'' she says. ``It comes
from there, first and foremost.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
