<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-DOUGLAS-IN-WONDER-BOYS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDER' MAN: MICHAEL DOUGLAS ON LIFE, LOVE AND THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Michael Douglas in a scene from ``Wonder
Boys.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    His dad's new movie is called ``Diamonds,'' but you'll forgive
Michael Douglas if the word makes him wince.
 &HT;    The Oscar-winning actor's phobia stems from his efforts to
propose to actress Catherine Zeta-Jones.
 &HT;    ``Catherine and I were in Wales over Christmas,'' Douglas
recalls, ``and I kept taking the ring out of my overnight bag to
check it out.''
 &HT;    The couple jetted on to Colorado, and only then did he realize
that something crucial had been left behind.
 &HT;    ``I'm desperately calling the Marriott Hotel of Wales,'' Douglas
says. ``Finally housekeeping comes to the line to say, `Hello, Mr.
Douglas. Yes, we found a little box.'
 &HT;    ``I was like, `For God's sake, just hold onto it!'''
 &HT;    Perhaps it's because Zeta-Jones said `yes' that Douglas, tanned
and fit for an interview at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel, can
look back and laugh. Dressed in a black sweater and dark pants,
he's certainly in a good mood _ at least to judge by his response
to those who have looked askance at the romance between the
56-year-old Douglas and the 30-year-old Zeta-Jones.
 &HT;    ``Naa-na, naa-na, naa-naaah,'' he says, laughing and wagging a
finger.
 &HT;    More seriously, Douglas _ who has a teen-age son, Cameron, with
his soon-to-be ex-wife, Diandra Douglas _ says that his age makes
him all the more appreciative of the news that Zeta-Jones is
expecting their first child.
 &HT;    ``This baby is a second chance for me,'' Douglas says. ``The new
baby is obviously wonderful, because you don't have to tear
yourself between career and family now. You feel like you've done
it all.
 &HT;    ``You love working,'' he adds. ``But you know you'll love having
a kid even more than making a movie. I will be able to focus that
much more time on my child and my marriage.''
 &HT;    His divorce has dragged on _ ``We're working it out'' is all
Douglas has to say on the subject _ and many were surprised that he
would be so quick to remarry.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, I was very happily surprised that I fell in love
again,'' the actor says. ``I think I reached the point of many
people where you think, `OK, I'll spend the rest of my life
single.'
 &HT;    ``The last thing I ever thought I'd do is get involved with an
actress,'' he says, rolling his eyes. ``But Catherine is extremely
grounded.''
 &HT;    Apparently, she's as comfortable with their age difference as
Douglas is.
 &HT;    ``The age difference actually disappeared very fast in the
relationship,'' he says. ``We don't even think about it anymore.
 &HT;    ``It doesn't really bother me,'' he adds. ``It's gone on
throughout civilization. Older guys marry younger women _ there was
Frank Sinatra and Mia Farrow, Elizabeth Taylor and Mike Todd. There
are basically genetic and other reasons why. Women at a certain age
can have children, and men who are older want that family
lifestyle, too.''
 &HT;    About the only things Douglas won't discuss are wedding plans
and the baby's due date.
 &HT;    ``We have to keep something for us,'' he says firmly.
 &HT;    Almost lost in the hubbub over his personal life is that Douglas
has a new movie opening Feb. 25. In ``Wonder Boys'' he plays a
middle-aged college professor named Grady Tripp. Grady's life is
even more complicated than Douglas': He can't finish his latest
novel. His wife has left him. His girlfriend is pregnant. His best
female student is hitting on him. Another student is cracking up.
And he's running low on pot.
 &HT;    ``It was just this great, wonderful, rich character,'' the actor
says. ``I loved that you didn't know where the movie was going _
that insanity is life.
 &HT;    ``I've been blessed by the fact that audiences have pretty much
let me play whatever I wanted,'' he adds. ``And I've never had a
fear of being disliked.''
 &HT;    Which could be an issue, especially where drug use is concerned
_ Grady even supplies his students with marijuana. The issue is a
sensitive one, especially to Douglas, whose son recently has had
some widely publicized substance-abuse problems.
 &HT;    ``Of course, having had a liberal-arts education myself and
being a child of the '60s, there were certain reverberations that I
could remember,'' Douglas says, laughing nervously. ``I read the
script and thought, `Ah, college _ it's nice that it hasn't changed
that much.'''
 &HT;    The point is that he's playing a character, the actor adds, not
endorsing that character's actions or outlook. After having played
ruthless tycoons in ``Wall Street'' (1987) and ``The Game'' (1997),
a wandering sociopath in ``Falling Down'' (1993) and a coldblooded
murderer in ``A Perfect Murder'' (1998), he knows better than to
identify with his characters.
 &HT;    Besides, he says, there's a lot to admire in Grady.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to be the bad guy each time out,'' he says.
``After `A Perfect Murder' and `The Game,' which were two
prince-of-darkness, well-dressed, well-coifed, rich urban
characters, I knew I wanted to do some romantic comedies. I want to
do more heroic roles _ and who is a bigger hero than a regular guy
who is a little burned out, getting it all together again?''
 &HT;    Douglas admits to some periods of burnout in his own career,
especially after ``Wall Street'' and ``Fatal Attraction'' (1987)
catapulted him to stardom.
 &HT;    ``I would basically finish a movie,'' he recalls, ``and then I
would come back and face a production company where I had 20
scripts in development, one more mediocre than the next. And the
studios were saying, `Well, let's go.' I was exhausted.'''
 &HT;    Nowadays, he says, he's learned to take it a bit slower. And
he's also come to terms with his own aging. He doesn't want to hang
on to leading-man roles at the expense of his own artistic
credibility.
 &HT;    ``I watch too many of these men so concerned with their images
and trying to make the best role for themselves that they don't
care about making the picture work,'' he says with a grimace. ``Get
over yourself.''
 &HT;    That's a lot easier these days, with his growing family
encompassing most of his attention.
 &HT;    Douglas and Zeta-Jones met in France, when he was attending the
Deauville Film Festival to hype ``A Perfect Murder.'' She was in
town to perform similar duties for her breakthrough movie, ``The
Mask of Zorro'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``I had just seen `Zorro' three weeks before,'' he recalls. ``I
said, `Wow, who is this?' Maybe Julie Christie was the last time I
had seen an actress come on screen who literally took my breath
away.'''
 &HT;    Finishing up his promotional duties, Douglas noticed that ``The
Mask of Zorro'' was scheduled for the next day.
 &HT;    ``Find out if Catherine Zeta-Jones is coming here,'' he told his
publicist. ``Find out if she's coming alone. See if maybe I can
have some dinner with her.'''
 &HT;    As it turned out, she was coming, and coming alone. And, yes,
she'd love to have dinner.
 &HT;    One thing led to another, and soon the paparazzi were falling
all over themselves to snap the couple basking on a yacht in the
Pacific, smooching in Kirk Douglas' Malibu back yard and traipsing
across most of the golf courses in Europe.
 &HT;    Yes, golf courses. Douglas is a passionate golfer who, only a
couple of years ago, said that he planned to dedicate his life to
the game.
 &HT;    ``Hey, man, Catherine is a good golfer,'' Douglas says with a
laugh. ``When she said, `I like to play golf, too,' frankly it
brought tears to my eyes.
 &HT;    ``I was like, `I will marry this woman.'''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Wonder Boys,'' consult the
official Website at www.wonderboysmovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
