<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-SMOKEY-ROBINSON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTIMATE' SENSATION: THE RETURN OF SMOKEY ROBINSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Smokey Robinson.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    You can go home again, after all.
 &HT;    Or at least Smokey Robinson can. For his latest album, the
Grammy-nominated ``Intimate,'' the singer returned to his musical
roots at Motown Records, the imprint he helped Berry Gordy Jr.
launch in Detroit during the late 1950s.
 &HT;    Robinson had left the label a decade ago to sign with the
now-defunct SBK Records, and he says that his return was as
surprising to him as it was to anyone else.
 &HT;    ``When we were just about to complete the album,'' the
59-year-old singer says, ``my manager came to me and said `We're
going back to Motown.' I said `Wow,' because I never expected that.
I said `Why?' and she said, `I'm not going to tell you. I'm going
to show you.'
 &HT;    ``So she takes me to New York to Motown's offices,'' he recalls,
``and I felt the same type of energy and atmosphere conditions up
there that we had in the early days. They go for it _ there's a
real hustle-and-bustle, let's-go-get-'em attitude.''
 &HT;    Robinson knows that attitude when he sees it. He was one of
Gordy's chief lieutenants at the start of Motown, a multi-threat
talent as a performer, bandleader, songwriter and producer. He
composed Motown's first No. 1 hit, Mary Wells' ``My Guy,'' and
wrote and performed its first million-selling single, ``Shop
Around,'' with his group The Miracles.
 &HT;    And, along with fellow Miracle Ronnie White, Robinson provided
The Temptations with ``My Girl,'' one of the top pop singles of all
time and considered by many to be Motown's quintessential song.
 &HT;    Gifted with a voice that Bob Dylan declared his all-time
favorite, one that was celebrated by the British band ABC in its
hit ``When Smokey Sings,'' Robinson has never been afraid to
reinvent himself. After leaving The Miracles in 1972, he broke new
musical ground with the romantic, pillow-talking ``A Quiet Storm''
(1975). He then stormed the pop charts again with two 1987 hits,
``Just to See Her'' and ``One Heartbeat.''
 &HT;    His career highs _ including induction into the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame and the Songwriters Hall of Fame, as well as a
Lifetime Achievement Award from the National Academy of Recording
Arts &AMP; Sciences _ have been impressive, but he's had some lows as
well, most notably the end of his nearly 25-year marriage to fellow
Miracle Claudette Robinson and a drug addiction that he chronicled
in his 1989 autobiography, ``Smokey: Inside My Life.''
 &HT;    But well into his fourth decade of making music, Robinson says
that, overall, the good has far outweighed the bad.
 &HT;    ``What do I really have to complain about, man?'' he says. ``I
was part of the birth of one of the greatest companies in the
world, music or otherwise. I got to work and hang with some of the
greatest artists in the world. I've been part of history, man _ a
lot of it.
 &HT;    ``I'm still out there doing it, too.''
 &HT;    For a while, of course, he wasn't. ``Intimate'' is Robinson's
first release in seven years, after a long stretch of reflection.
 &HT;    What he wanted, Robinson says, was ``just to kick back and look
at myself, man, see what I wanted to do with my life, how I wanted
to pursue show business itself, and get a little closer to the
people who are the priorities in my life, my family. It just
increases my values.''
 &HT;    He wasn't necessarily thinking of so much time off. In fact, he
started work on ``Intimate'' _ a collaboration with
songwriter/producer Michael Stokes _ in 1995. It's probably been
made six different times, Robinson says, with the pressure mounting
as each year passed.
 &HT;    ``After four years, it's kind of crucial that you come out with
something you feel is good,'' says Robinson, who recorded about 30
songs before settling on the album's 11 keepers. ``After six years,
it's a little more crucial. And after eight years, man, you better
come up with something _ you know what I mean?''
 &HT;    About two years into the process, Robinson sent some of the
material over to Gordy, as he often does, to get his former
mentor's thoughts on the music.
 &HT;    Gordy liked some of the songs, Robinson recalls, including the
title track. But his reaction generally wasn't favorable.
 &HT;    ``Man, I think the rest of this stuff is going in the wrong
direction, doing the wrong thing,'' the singer recalls him saying.
``This is a very crucial album _ you better let me come in.''
 &HT;    Robinson eventually agreed, and Gordy signed on as executive
producer, bring with him one of his current proteges, Michael
Lovesmith, to work with Robinson and Stokes. Together the four
worked on new songs and honed a vision and a theme for ``Intimate''
as a whole, a theme summed up in the romantic implications of its
title.
 &HT;    ``Berry wanted to call the album `Intimate,' which was one of
the first songs we had,'' Robinson says. ``That meant the album had
to be intimate, and it wasn't. When we got to the point where we
had these 11 songs we felt were intimate _ for an intimate setting,
that you can listen to with the one you love, put this on and have
a great time _ we knew we were finally done.
 &HT;    ``Romance is timeless, man,'' adds Robinson, a divorced father
of three grown children. ``Love is never passe _ somebody's falling
in love ever second of every day. I hope that continues to be that
way, every day of humanity.''
 &HT;    In that spirit, Robinson says, he strives to make his songs
universal, so they're not necessarily about specific people or
events, including those in his own life.
 &HT;    ``I'm not that kind of writer, at least not consciously,'' he
says. ``I write what strikes me at the time. I don't have to be
happy to write a happy song or sad to write a sad song.
 &HT;    ``Whatever idea comes into my mind, I promise you, it's a
blessing, a gift,'' he adds. ``I have pounds of paper at home, just
ideas for songs or notes or words or something that I write down
when they come to me and I figure I'll use somewhere down the
line.''
 &HT;    Robinson's promotional duties for ``Intimate'' kept him off the
road for most of 1999. But in the wake of his Grammy nomination,
he's looking forward to bringing ``Intimate'' _ as well as his
40-plus years of hits _ to as many concert audiences as he can.
 &HT;    ``Performing is probably my favorite thing in life, as far as my
business goes,'' he says. ``I always have a great time performing.
Always have.
 &HT;    ``I don't look at it like entertaining,'' Robinson adds. ``I'm
always of a mind of `Let's have fun.' I go out and have the chance
to one-on-one with my fans and we _ by that, I mean my people, my
band and I, and the people in the audience _ have a show,
together.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Intimate,'' consult the Motown
Records Website at www.motown.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
