<HEADER>
A3685 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-21 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PESSIMISTS CHECK OUT EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if optimistic people weren't annoying enough, what with their
perky smiles and sunny dispositions, it now turns out that they
live longer than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   (By ``us'' I am referring, of course, to pessimists or as I
prefer to call us, realists.)
</P>
<P>
   According to researchers at the Mayo Clinic, optimistic people
live about 19 percent longer than pessimists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirmed our common-sense belief. It tells us that mind
and body are linked and that attitude has an impact on the final
outcome, death,'' Toshihiko Maruta, a lead researcher on the
project, told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Being a realist, it is my opinion that optimistic people do not
live 19 percent longer; they just make everyone else's life 19
percent shorter because they are so irritating.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mayo Clinic researchers have not confirmed this, I
suspect that every time a realist hears an optimist utter the
words, ``Have a nice day!'', a minimum of one full hour is lopped
off his lifespan. When you stop to think how often realists hear
these dreadful words, it is surprising that any of us are around
today to bemoan the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Bemoaning, of course, is what we realists do best. It can be an
art form or an aerobic exercise, depending on whether your
bemoaning is done on the run or while seated.
</P>
<P>
   If optimists serve any purpose in the world _ and I'm not at all
convinced that they do _ it's to alert realists of topics that are
in need of bemoaning. Optimists cannot go five seconds without
saying something good about someone or something, so we realists
are never in danger of running out of bemoanable material.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite topic of optimists is the weather. (One might suggest
to the Mayo researchers that people who are intellectually shallow
also live 19 percent longer, but let us save that for another
time.) There could be a hurricane raging outside and an optimist
will declare that we need the rain. In the mind of an optimist, a
glacier sliding over New York, signaling the start of a new Ice
Age, will just make the arrival of spring all the more welcome,
10,000 years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The cliche is that optimists see the glass as half-full, while
pessimists see it as half-empty. This is nonsense. All pessimists
want to know is what's in the glass, and whether it's safe to
drink. Optimists don't care what's in the glass or how full or
empty it is; they're just happy to be there.
</P>
<P>
   As a realist, I do not begrudge the fact that optimists will
live 19 percent longer than I. Knowing optimists as I do, they will
probably squander that extra 19 percent rhapsodizing about the
weather or contemplating a metaphorical glass. If there is an
argument against extending the human lifespan, this is certainly
it.
</P>
<P>
   What bothers me more is an editorial in the Mayo Clinic
Proceedings that accompanied the research findings. Martin
Seligman, a psychologist at the University of Pennsylvania, said
pessimism is both identifiable early in life and can be
``changed.'' (The quotes are mine.)
</P>
<P>
   He suggested putting pessimists in ``programs'' to ``change
their way of thinking'' and thereby lower their risk of physical
illness. (Again, my quotes.)
</P>
<P>
   Optimists are clearly trying to wipe out pessimists and take
over the world, which they will then rename The Big Happy Face.
While they are doing that, we pessimists _ excuse me, realists _
will be locked up in gaily painted classrooms listening to our
teacher _ an optimist, of course _ drone on about the weather and
half-full glasses.
</P>
<P>
   And they wonder why we check out 19 percent ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
