<HEADER>
A3693 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      02-21 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SIDE EFFECTS: Finding a Down Side to a Cleaner World &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists investigating the rise in asthma and allergies in
developed countries have long wondered whether the increased
incidence is the price being paid for the cleanliness of the modern
world, of immune systems being inadequately challenged in
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   A new Italian study, published Feb. 12 in The Lancet, has lent
new strength to that hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of air force cadets in Caserta, Italy, found that those
who had been exposed to orofecal infections, which are carried in
tainted food or by unwashed hands, were less likely to suffer from
respiratory allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the Immunology and Allergy Laboratory in
Rome, are not suggesting bad hygiene as a preventive measure for
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, hope that new studies can determine exactly
how immune responses are boosted by exposure to microbes.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, they wrote, is to develop ways of using molecular
mimics of the infectious agents to stimulate the immune system
without causing disease.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: When a Weary Brain Hops Over Hurdles &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A sleepy brain is never as sharp as a rested brain, but the
fuzziness can vary with the task at hand, according to a new study
that found signs of a mechanism that can sometimes limit the impact
of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The research was conducted by psychiatrists at the University of
California at San Diego and at the San Diego Veterans
Administration Medical Center using a brain scan to reveal patterns
of activity.
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrists gave 13 people a series of exercises designed
to test their math and verbal abilities while normally rested and
again over the course of 35 hours without sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The math results were reported in December in NeuroReport and
the verbal last week in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   For math, the people were asked to subtract single digit
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found was completely different patterns of brain
activation,'' and a striking drop-off in performance as fatigue
rose, said Dr. J. Christian Gillian, the lead author of the
research paper.
</P>
<P>
   When the subjects were rested, doing the math lit up substantial
parts of their cerebral cortex.
</P>
<P>
   But fatigue appeared to limit the brain function across the
board.
</P>
<P>
   For the verbal test, subjects were read a list of 20 words and
were asked either to recall them after leaving the brain scanning
machine or to recognize them when they were mixed in with a larger
list.
</P>
<P>
   The tired subjects had a poor recall of the words, but to the
researchers' surprise, fatigue made little difference in the
recognition test, indicating, Gillian said, that the information
``got into the brain and was registered.''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise was that the frontal lobes became more
active as the subjects became sleepier.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the parietal lobe, which normally plays only a
secondary role in verbal processing, began to be activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greater the activation of the parietal lobes, the more
subjects preserved their base line performance,'' said Gillian,
``which leads us to believe that perhaps the brain is in some way
compensating for loss of function elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSCLE GROUPS: Recruits Gauge Ways to Avoid Injuries &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Stretching out-of-shape muscles is the best way for the weekend
athlete to avoid injury, right? Wrong, says a new Australian study
that found no reduction in injuries among soldiers who stretched
before workouts, compared with soldiers who did not.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers who avoided injury were those who were more
physically fit to begin with, according to researchers at the
Kapooka Health Center and the University of Sydney, whose findings
were published in this month's issue of Science &AMP; Medicine in
Sports &AMP; Exercise.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, 1,500 male recruits were randomly assigned to two
groups, one of which added a stretching routine _ 20-second static
stretches of six muscle groups in the legs _ to a warm-up that
preceded physical training.
</P>
<P>
   During the 12 weeks that followed, the difference in the number
of injuries was not statistically significant: 158 injuries among
the men doing stretches, and 175 in the control group.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were ranked least fit, however, were 14 times as
likely as the recruits in the best shape to suffer injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAUMA: A Caution Flag on Breathing Tubes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A study involving California paramedics has found that placing
breathing tubes in the throats of unconscious children saved no
more lives than the less risky method of squeezing oxygen into
their lungs through a mask and hand pump.
</P>
<P>
   Intubating a child, or threading a breathing tube into the
throat, is often presented as a moment of high drama on television
medical shows, and well it might be, because complications are
common and can be fatal. But a belief that the more aggressive
treatment is the most effective method of keeping oxygen flowing to
a child's brain has caused intubation to becoming increasingly
common.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, conducted by emergency medicine physicians from
Harbor-UCLA Medical Center and published on Feb. 9 in the Journal
of the American Medical Association, was the first controlled
comparison of the two methods. Over three years, paramedics in Los
Angeles and Orange counties switched on alternate days between
intubation and bag-valve mask ventilation, known as BVM, as the
intended treatment method in 820 cases of children 12 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   Survival rates for the two methods turned out to be similar: 30
percent for children in the BVM group, and 26 percent of the
endotracheal intubation group. There was also little difference in
terms of limiting brain damage: 23 percent of the ventilation group
had good outcomes, compared with 20 percent for intubation.
</P>
<P>
   The study found two significant differences: paramedics involved
in intubations generally spent two minutes longer on the scene, and
potentially fatal complications were reported in 8 percent of the
children who were successfully intubated.
</P>
<P>
   The study's lead author, Dr. Marianne Gausche, said in an
interview that both counties had abandoned on-site intubations of
children after being informed of the study's findings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTION: Flu Spray Packs a Punch, Up the Nose &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A nasal spray form of a flu vaccine for children was effective
in a two-year test, even against an unexpected form of the virus, a
study in this month's issue of the Journal of Pediatrics reports.
</P>
<P>
   Few children get flu shots, even though children get the flu,
and spread it, more frequently than adults do, and often develop
ear infections that adults do not.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to injections, researchers have developed what
they call a cold-adapted live attenuated virus vaccine, which is a
weakened form of the disease designed to stimulate the body's
immune system in the cooler nasal passages, but unable to reproduce
in the warmer interior.
</P>
<P>
   They hope this form of vaccination can give immunity that lasts
longer and covers more strains than normal flu shots, which use
inactivated viruses.
</P>
<P>
   While testing the spray, called FluMist, researchers stumbled
into an unplanned test of the vaccine's ability to adapt to new flu
strains. In the winter of 1997-98, the predominant flu virus was
A/Sydney, a new form that the vaccine had not been designed to
block. Nevertheless, the spray proved to be 86 percent effective
against it, the study's lead author, Dr. Robert B. Belshe of St.
Louis University, reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's exciting here is evidence that a live attenuated virus
can provide broader protection, and in a form that may be easier
for children to take,'' said Dr. Linda Lambert, the influenza
program officer at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious
Diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
