<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMIES-PREVIEW-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE LIKELY WINNERS AND LOSERS IN WEDNESDAY'S GRAMMY
PRESENTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by GRAMMIES-TEXAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The argument could be made that the 42nd annual Grammy awards
are a battle between youth and experience _ which is to say,
between schlock and substance.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music has been been skewing down to appeal to an
ever-younger audience for years now, but the overwhelming success
of such pop-tart acts as the Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync, Britney
Spears and Christina Aguilera made this more of a dividing line in
the past year than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   And what made these acts feel all the more uneasily omnipresent
was the Polygram/Seagram merger, which trimmed dozens of artists
from major-label rosters. Put the two together, and in late '98 and
all of '99, it felt like good pop music for adults was in mighty
short supply, and would become all the more so in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   The other side to this coin, and what gives veteran rock fans
something to root for Wednesday, is the realization that this will,
to a large extent, be Carlos Santana's night. With 10 nominations _
including record of the year, album of the year and song of the
year _ the 6 million-copies-sold-and-counting ``Supernatural'' has
brought the Mexican-born guitarist/bandleader a higher profile than
he's had since his heyday in the early to mid-'70s, in no small
part due to the success of the ``Smooth'' single, featuring Rob
Thomas of matchbox 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smooth'' is an unstoppable single and a winning video, and
(thanks to the marketing savvy of Arista President Clive Davis) one
of the smartest moves a major veteran rock artist has made in
years.
</P>
<P>
   It brought together kids who loved
young-but-not-quite-alternative music, which matchbox 20 surely is
(and who had, in many cases, no idea who Carlos Santana was) with
veterans who had long since thought of him as a classic rocker
whose hit-making days were over.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps _ which are a sizable chunk of the pop music audience
_ discovered/rediscovered Santana with one fell swoop, ensuring him
more success than at any time since his first greatest-hits
collection in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Just as 1991 was Quincy Jones' year, '93 was Eric Clapton's and
'95 was Bruce Springsteen's, so Wednesday night will be all about
Santana. He has all the things that the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences members have proved that they love in
the past: mass name recognition, the hard-working classic-rocker
pedigree, and a touch of modernity about him.
</P>
<P>
   That equals at least five trips to the podium. NARAS tends to
make up for lost time and crown a rocker who came back big (Bonnie
Raitt, anyone?) and Santana's story is as close to a Cinderella
fairy tale as pop music has had to offer for a good long while now.
</P>
<P>
   What will be interesting, though, is just how well he does
against the fizzy-pop kids. The Record of the Year, Album of the
Year and Song of the Year categories all find a stark contrast
between him and performers who could easily be his children: The
Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync and Ricky Martin. My bet is he walks away
with at least two of the three above, as well as the Collaboration
With Vocals and Rock Instrumental statues, too.
</P>
<P>
   This is true, too, of TLC. The troubled R&AMP;B supergroup also came
back strong in '99 with the ``Fanmail'' CD and two of the biggest
R&AMP;B singles of the year, ``No Scrubs'' and ``Unpretty.'' Outside of
Santana, TLC is the longest-running group up for the big three _
Record of the Year, Album of the Year and Song of the Year. But
though they certainly deserve their fair share of attention _
they're a lock for Best R&AMP;B Album _ the odds are long that, with
all the negative publicity their squabbles have gotten, they will
be able to beat out Santana. These things do count, you know.
</P>
<P>
   But those, of course, are not the only categories, _ and, as
always, the nominations miss some of the best music that's been
released. Here, then, is my highly subjective list of who will win,
who should win, and who should have at least been nominated in the
top 15 categories.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Record of the Year
</P>
<P>
   ``I Want It That Way,'' Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe,'' Cher
</P>
<P>
   ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' Ricky Martin
</P>
<P>
   ``Smooth,'' Santana
</P>
<P>
   ``No Scrubs,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Minus the pap of ``Want,'' a tough category. In
another year, perhaps, ``Believe'' would probably take it, and ``No
Scrubs'' is definitely a worthy nomination, but I'm going with
``Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: That vote wasn't just because I'm an old fan, you
know.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: These are biggies, all right, but both Lou
Bega's ``Mambo No. 5 (A Little Bit Of ...)'' and Jennifer Lopez's
``If You Had My Love'' were also fairly omnipresent. As was,
frankly, Madonna's ``Beautiful Stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Album of the Year
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium,'' Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly,'' Dixie Chicks
</P>
<P>
   ``When I Look in Your Eyes,'' Diana Krall
</P>
<P>
   ``Fanmail,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' Santana
</P>
<P>
   What should win: Actually, my favorite CD here is ``Fly''; the
Chicks have crossed over to the extent that if anyone can win this
besides ``Supernatural,'' this is it.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: It's 75/25 ``Supernatural/Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Actually, I was very pleasantly surprised
that Krall got the nomination. I would have put in R. Kelly's
``R.'' _ not because it was consistently good (it wasn't) but
because it was so much a part of the urban landscape. And it
certainly wasn't any worse than ``Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song of the Year
</P>
<P>
   ``I Want It That Way''
</P>
<P>
   ``Livin' La Vida Loca''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smooth''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unpretty''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got a Way''
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``Unpretty'' certainly has the best message of
the five.
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   What was overlooked: While it wasn't my favorite song, there's
no question Smash Mouth's ``All Star'' was all over the place. As
was Kid Rock's ``Bawitdaba.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   New Artist
</P>
<P>
   Christina Aguilera
</P>
<P>
   Macy Gray
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tedeschi
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: No question, Macy Gray has the most talent of
any of the above. Kid Rock isn't new, Tedeschi is a Bonnie
Raitt/Janis wannabe, and Aguilera and Spears are, well, what they
are.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Kid Rock. And I don't even want him to. Gray's
been coming on strong in the past couple months, but it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: I was actually quite proud of NARAS for even
including Gray, but I also think that Eminem should have been here
in place of the Kid; while neither is actually a ``new'' artist,
Eminem is clearly the better rapper.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Female Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``Genie in a Bottle,'' Christina Aguilera
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful Stranger,'' Madonna
</P>
<P>
   ``I Will Remember You,'' Sarah McLachlan
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank U,'' Alanis Morissette
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby One More Time,'' Britney Spears
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Beautiful Stranger'' is one of the best pop
songs of the past decade. Hands down.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: That's never been enough. Madonna's already won a
slew of awards; ``I Will Remember You'' has stuck around a long
time and has broad-based appeal, and McLachlan's association with
Lilith Fair certainly doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Chrissie Hynde's vocals on ``Human'' from
``Viva El Amor!''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Male Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``I Need to Know,'' Marc Anthony
</P>
<P>
   ``Mambo No. 5 (A Little Bit of ...,)'' Lou Bega
</P>
<P>
   ``Sogno,'' Andrea Bocelli
</P>
<P>
   ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' Ricky Martin
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand New Day,'' Sting
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Marc Anthony. His vocal performance was far
better than Martin's _ and as for the Sting and Lou Bega songs, the
former was on a CD that flopped commercially and the latter was a
better video than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Ricky. This is a good, safe award to give him: He
burst onto the mainstream (read: white) consciousness on last
year's show and La Vida Loca is, despite being played to death,
darned catchy.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Robbie Williams' performance on
``Millennium'' is far better than Sting's _ it's a better song,
too. Ditto for the Artist's ``The Greatest Romance Ever Sold,'' a
fantastic single from an erratic record.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Duo or Group With Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``I Want It That Way,'' Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   ``Maria Maria,'' Santana
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me,'' Sixpence None the Richer
</P>
<P>
   ``All Star,'' Smash Mouth
</P>
<P>
   ``Unpretty,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: I'd be happy with anything but ``I Want It That
Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: TLC. Great song. Great hook. Great video.
Female-empowerment message.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: While their bid for adding the States to the
countries they've conquered didn't do that well, there's no
question that several songs from the Corrs' ``Talk on Corners''
deserve to be on here, among them ``So Young'' and ``Runaway.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rock Album
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakdown,'' Melissa Etheridge
</P>
<P>
   ``Signficant Other,'' Liit
</P>
<P>
   ``Echo,'' Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers
</P>
<P>
   ``Californication,'' Red Hot Chili Peppers
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' Santana
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Echo'' is a strong record from a guy who's
never gotten his due from the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: There's one big classic-rock playa this year, and
it ain't ol' T.P.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Kid Rock's ``Devil Without a Cause'' is a
better rock/rap CD than Limp Bizkit will ``ever'' make.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Alternative Album
</P>
<P>
   ``To Venus and Back,'' Tori Amos
</P>
<P>
   ``Mutations,'' Beck
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Come a Long Way, Baby,'' Fatboy Slim
</P>
<P>
   ``Play,'' Moby
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fragile,'' Nine Inch Nails
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Loved both the Beck and the NIN. Either one's
fine by me.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: But not by NARAS. Neither performed nearly as well
as expected, and Fatboy Slim has far more buzz. He's going home
with this puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: What wasn't? Both Built to Spill's ``Keep It
Like a Secret'' and the Flaming Lips' ``The Soft Bulletin,'' for
starters, and the latter certainly generated enough glowing reviews
to get a shot.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Female Rock Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``Bliss,'' Tori Amos
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Child o' Mine,'' Sheryl Crow
</P>
<P>
   ``Jukebox,'' Ani DiFranco
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels Would Fall,'' Melissa Etheridge
</P>
<P>
   ``Possession,'' Sarah McLachlan
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: McLachlan.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Etheridge's commercial fortunes fell dramatically
with ``Breakdown,'' but NARAS is still going to want to give her at
least one trip up to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Get a copy of Beth Orton's ``Central
Reservation'' and take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Male Rock Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Change Me,'' Chris Cornell
</P>
<P>
   ``What It's Like,'' Everlast
</P>
<P>
   ``American Woman,'' Lenny Kravitz
</P>
<P>
   ``The Promise,'' Bruce Springsteen
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold On,'' Tom Waits
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Waits _ no doubt about it. The song was one of
the very best on his ``Mule Variations,'' one of the very best of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Because ``American Woman'' is a cover _ and not a
very good one at that _ I'm hoping for ``The Promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Tom Petty's ``Rhino Skin'' is as sly and
funny and wise a vocal performance as he's ever given.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Country Album
</P>
<P>
   ``Ride With Bob,'' Asleep at the Wheel
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly,'' Dixie Chicks
</P>
<P>
   ``Trio II,'' Emmylou Harris, Linda Ronstadt and Dolly Parton
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Hard Truth,'' George Jones
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget About It,'' Alison Krauss
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Ol' George, because he darned near died, and was
snubbed at the CMAs last year and is, after all, a walking
definition of country music.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: The Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: ``The Mountain'' by Steve Earle with the Del
McCoury Band was one of the best country records of the past five
years. How it could be ignored is beyond me _ no! Wait! It's not!
It's NARAS! Now I remember!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Female Country Vocal
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinary Heart,'' Emmylou Harris
</P>
<P>
   ``Let Me Let Go,'' Faith Hill
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget About It,'' Alison Krauss
</P>
<P>
   ``I Love You,'' Martina McBride
</P>
<P>
   ``Man! I Feel Like a Woman,'' Shania Twain
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: McBride.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Shania. Sadly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Kelly Willis, Kelly Willis and Kelly Willis;
while it didn't sell as well as any of the above, Willis' vocals on
the title track earned being in this company. And what about Lee
Ann Womack's ``I'll Think of a Reason Later''?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B Album
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary, Mary,'' Mary J. Blige
</P>
<P>
   ``My Love Is Your Love,'' Whitney Houston
</P>
<P>
   ``R.,'' R. Kelly
</P>
<P>
   ``Back at One,'' Brian McKnight''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fanmail,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: TLC.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Hard to say. Because they've gotten so many other
nominations, TLC might actually lose out here to Whitney. Don't be
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Blackstreet's ``Finally,'' a very
well-assembled, convincing R&AMP;B/hip-hop/pop effort.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rap Album
</P>
<P>
   ``E.L.E. (Extinction Level Event _ The Final World Front,)''
Busta Rhymes
</P>
<P>
   ``Da Real World,'' Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slim Shady EP,'' Eminem
</P>
<P>
   ``I Am,'' Nas
</P>
<P>
   ``Things Fall Apart,'' The Roots
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: The Roots are clearly the best of the bunch
here, and ``Things Fall Apart'' is a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Missy. She's got the name value, the track record,
the cool videos _ and she's a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: I'm still stoked that, after all these years
of hard work and far too little recognition, the Roots got this
nomination. But I also would have liked to have seen Ja Rule's
``Venni Vetti Veccinominated.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX: The Grammy Awards will be broadcast at 7 p.m. CST
Wednesday on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
