r e BC-GRAMMIES-TEXAS-TEX     02-21 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMIES-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMMIES: THE TEXAS CONTINGENT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies GRAMMIES-PREVIEW) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans and those who want to be and/or who think they are, this
year's Grammys are for you.
</P>
<P>
   Not completely, of course _ the only connection that Ricky
Martin, Carlos Santana, Kid Rock and Cher have to the Lone Star
State is that they've all played here in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Texas musicians look to clean up on Wednesday: Not
only are there a ton of nominees, but several stand a very good
chance of coming home with a statue.
</P>
<P>
   There is, first and foremost, Dallas' Dixie Chicks, whose
``Fly'' is up for Album of the Year and Country Album. The Chicks
also look strong in the Country Duo or Group With Vocal category _
for ``Ready to Run'' _ and have a decent chance of seeing the same
song take home the country Song of the Year, although I think
George Jones' ``Choices'' will walk away with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choices'' is also up for Country Album of the Year _ it won't
win, however; ``Fly'' will because of the Chicks' youth, sassiness,
looks and enormous sales.
</P>
<P>
   The country Male Vocal category will go to a Texan: It'll be
``Choices'' or Lyle Lovett's ``That's Right (You're Not From
Texas).'' Jones' high profile _ and snubbing at the Country Music
Awards in September _ earn him a good shot here, and Lovett is
often in the news and never less than interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But the night's big winners from Texas may be the Austin-based
western swing band Asleep at the Wheel; while not ``technically''
Texans (the band was formed in Virginia in 1970) they've long since
been adopted. AATW is virtually a lock for the Collaboration With
Vocals Grammy _ after all, they've been nominated twice, once for
``Going Away Party'' (with Willie Nelson and Manhattan Transfer)
and twice for ``Roly Poly'' (with the Chicks, naturally).
</P>
<P>
   It's nice that their ``Ride With Bob'' got a nod for Best
Country Album, but it's a huge long shot there. But they might well
earn a third Grammy for Country Instrumental of the Year for
``Bob's Breakdowns.'' Two of the other four nominees in the
category (Marty Stuart and Steve Wariner) are better known as
vocalists.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Lonestar, a band that has some of its roots in
Fort Worth. ``Amazed,'' the band's biggest hit ever, is up for two
major country honors: Duo or Group With Vocal and Song of the Year.
My bet: It takes the former but loses the latter to Shania's ``Come
On Over.'' Unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget three other acts: Austin's Sixpence None the
Richer's ``Kiss Me'' is up for the Pop Duo or Group With Vocal
honor (it will lose to TLC's ``Unpretty''); Houston's Destiny's
Child, whose ``Bills, Bills, Bills'' got the nod for R&AMP;B Duo or
Group With Vocal _ it has a good shot, but my money's on Whitney
Houston's ``Heartbreak Hotel'' _ and good ol' Willie, whose ``Night
and Day'' has a so-so chance of beating out both Jeff Beck's ``A
Day in the Life'' and Santana's ``El Farol'' for Pop/Rock
Instrumental. This, however, will be Santana's night, so don't hold
your breath.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is Denton's own Brave Combo, whose
``Polkasonic'' should get the Polka Album award; it is the
long-running, hard-traveling band's third nomination in the
category, and our hopes are with them.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
