<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      02-21 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: THE TELLTALE SIGNS OF SORE THROAT DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is high season for sore throats. One of my friends awakens
with a scratchy throat nearly every morning on these cold winter
days. Another said the other day that his throat felt sore and he
guessed (correctly) that he was getting a cold. A third had gone
back to bed with a throat so painful she could hardly talk, let
alone swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Sore throat is a symptom, not a disease. In each case, there was
a different cause that dictated a different treatment. The scratchy
throat probably was a mechanical problem caused by dry, heated
winter air and aggravated by my friend's tendency to breathe
through her mouth when she sleeps. The very painful throat, on the
other hand, turned out to be an infection serious enough to warrant
a visit to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the findings of a recent nationwide survey of
1,000 adults, slightly more than half of Americans do nothing to
relieve a sore throat unless it becomes so severe that they cannot
swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people seem to resist acknowledging and treating their
sore throat pain,'' said Dr. John G. Campbell, president of the
American Academy of Otolaryngology. Yet, he noted, ``Sore throat is
a symptom of many medical conditions, and it's important that
people identify sore throat symptoms and their causes in order to
seek appropriate treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy warns people to see a doctor when a sore throat is
severe or persists longer than the five to seven days that is the
usual duration of a cold or flu and is not caused by an avoidable
allergen or irritant.
</P>
<P>
   The academy also advises that any of the following signs and
symptoms should prompt a visit to the doctor: difficulty breathing,
swallowing or opening the mouth; joint pain; earache; rash; fever
over 101; blood in saliva or phlegm; a lump in the neck; a sore
throat that recurs frequently; and hoarseness that lasts more than
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The common causes of sore throats include infectious organisms,
mechanical irritants and conditions like tumors that can result in
serious health consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Most sore throats result from viral infections, usually colds,
but possibly influenza. In children or adults who were not
immunized, the measles, chickenpox or whooping cough can cause a
sore throat. Sometimes, a canker sore or fever blister forms in the
throat, causing intense pain upon swallowing. When a sore throat
persists for weeks, accompanied by swollen glands in the neck,
armpits and groin, enlarged tonsils with white patches and possibly
breathing difficulties, infectious mononucleosis (``mono,'' caused
by a herpes virus) is a likely cause.
</P>
<P>
   Certain antiviral drugs may diminish the severity of such an
infection, but it is important to remember that ordinary
antibiotics are ineffective against viruses and should not be used
unless a bacterial infection is also present or is strongly
suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 percent of sore throats are due to bacterial infections,
usually strains of streptococcus bacteria. Strep throat must be
treated with an antibiotic to prevent damage to the heart valves
and kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   A throat culture is needed to establish a strep infection and,
after treatment, another culture should be done to be sure the
infection is gone. But if another bacterium is the cause, the
culture will be negative, and even if strep is the cause, the
culture sometimes fails to detect it. The quick strep test, with
results in 20 minutes, is less accurate than an overnight culture.
</P>
<P>
   Small children may be prone to infections of tonsils
(tonsillitis), the lymph tissues on each side of the back of the
throat. Repeated infections may result when bacteria are trapped in
the tonsils, which can swell and cause significant throat
obstruction. If such infections recur three or more times a year, a
tonsillectomy may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Epiglottitis, a bacterial infection of the flap that covers the
windpipe when a person swallows, is especially dangerous because it
can cause swelling that obstructs the airway. Emergency medical
attention should be sought when swallowing is extremely painful,
speech is muffled and breathing becomes difficult.
</P>
<P>
   A person with a deviated septum (the partition inside the nose),
nasal polyps or oversize tonsils and adenoids may be forced to be a
mouth breather, during the day as well as when asleep. This can
result in a chronically dry, raw throat. Consult an
otolaryngologist if this is your problem, since it may require
surgical correction.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, allergies to dust mites and pet dander often cause a
chronically raw or scratchy throat, usually accompanied by an
irritating postnasal drip or nasal congestion that results in mouth
breathing. Eliminating the cause is the best cure.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, breathing dry, heated air can cause a mild sore
throat, especially on awakening. The obvious solution: turn the
heat down at night, open a window a little and try to add moisture
to the air, perhaps by using a vaporizer. In hotels, I run the hot
water in the shower to steam up the room before retiring. Also,
drink lots of fluids (without alcohol or caffeine) to keep your
respiratory tract well hydrated.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution, most commonly from tobacco smoke, and straining
your voice by shouting or trying to talk in a noisy place can also
irritate the throat. If hoarseness accompanies a sore throat, rest
your voice, drink lots of fluids and avoid whispering or frequently
clearing your throat, which only compounds the irritation. If
hoarseness persists for several weeks or is accompanied by pain,
coughing up of blood, difficulty swallowing or a lump in the neck,
consult a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent heartburn can cause a chronic sore throat when stomach
acid that backs up into the esophagus reaches the throat. Acid
reflux is a serious problem that requires medical treatment if home
remedies fail to correct it. These include losing weight; quitting
smoking; avoiding spicy, fatty or acidic foods, chocolate,
peppermint, coffee, alcohol and carbonated beverages; eating
smaller meals and not eating anything for two or three hours before
going to bed; and elevating the head of the bed about six inches
higher than the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Cancerous tumors of the throat, tongue or larynx are most common
in longtime smokers and heavy drinkers. Symptoms may include a mild
chronic sore throat, difficulty swallowing, pain that radiates to
the ear, hoarseness, a lump in the neck, blood in the saliva or
phlegm, and unexplained weight loss. This problem requires
immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   In general, if you know the cause of your sore throat is not a
serious problem or, if serious, is receiving appropriate medical
treatment, it is all right to use an over-the-counter pain reliever
for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
