<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PATIENT-PROGNOSIS     02-21 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PATIENT-PROGNOSIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PATIENTS WANT TO KNOW THE DISTANCE TO DEATH'S DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My patient Charlie did not show up for his appointment this
month, an aberration for which I am deeply, selfishly grateful. It
means that he is feeling well, since he never fails to check in at
the first ache or sneeze. It also means that I get a little break
from the relentless cross-examination that is a session in the
office with Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do I have, doc?'' he asks. ``Say a year, I guess, for
sure, right? Am I right? Two?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, someone told Charlie, then newly diagnosed with
AIDS, that he had eight months to live. ``Can you believe that?''
he says now. ``Who would tell a person something like that, when it
wasn't, like, fixed?''
</P>
<P>
   But the inaccuracy of Charlie's last fortune has not dissuaded
him from seeking out another, better one from me. Logical perhaps
he is not, but who can blame him for a little illogic?
</P>
<P>
   He was at death's door; now he is fit and vigorous on
medications, working two jobs and newly engaged. He knows the
hairpin turns a person's health can take, and asks for no
guarantees. All he wants now is a little warning, a legible
roadside sign that gives him enough lead time to brake.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Charlie is concerned, if I can't do this one little
thing for him, then what earthly good am I?
</P>
<P>
   He does not actually come right out and say this, but I can see
it in his face every time I tell him that no one has a clue, these
days, how long his pills will work and what his future holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you ain't saying,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I protest that I can't begin to guess, he rolls his eyes, and we
leave it that way for another month.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that I really cannot predict Charlie's survival,
any more than I can tell people with diabetes, heart disease or
emphysema when the jig will be up for them. Down the road for all
are new studies, new machines, new enzymes, new organs, new genes
and new drugs upon drugs, all with new side effects.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your chronic disease, you and your doctor are
bombarded by breaking news these days. Most of it will not mean
very much in the long run, but a small fraction will turn
everything we think we know about a disease on its ear. Only a
sorcerer could feel comfortable measuring out most patients' life
spans.
</P>
<P>
   When I tell this to Charlie, he snorts and gestures at the
medical books stacked on the desk. ``Nothing in there?'' he says
with heavy sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is less and less in there, a change that has not
escaped the watchdogs of medical history. A hundred years ago,
telling people their prognosis was a major part of medicine, with
foretelling the future, as per Hippocrates, just as important as
doing no harm.
</P>
<P>
   But as treatments became better, the art of precise prediction
began to fall by the wayside. In a 1997 article in Social Sciences
and Medicine, Dr. Nicholas A. Christakis at the University of
Chicago illustrated this phenomenon by analyzing the chapter on
pneumonia in successive editions of a single medical textbook.
</P>
<P>
   He found that after the turn of the century the discussion of
prognosis got shorter and shorter, until about 30 years ago it
finally vanished, replaced by more and more detail on diagnosis and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   It is small wonder that doctors now tend to feel anxious and
uncomfortable when pressed to predict a patient's survival. They
admit on surveys that they are poorly trained for the task, dislike
doing it and avoid it whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, there is an increasing interest in
reviving these lost skills. Often, people still want to know how
long they have left, and, of course, cadres of insurers and health
care economists all want to know, too, because all health care
budgeting and resource allocation ultimately rest on the same
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   So the science of predicting survival marches on. Numerical
scoring systems have infiltrated many medical specialties: they let
surgeons predict the survival odds of burn and coma patients, and
critical-care specialists estimate a patient's chances of making it
out of intensive care alive.
</P>
<P>
   Systems for estimating the survival rate of cancer patients by
the stage of their tumor _ how big it is and how far it has spread
_ give oncologists numbers to work with, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when doctors try to use these numbers in conversations with
actual patients, all scientific clarity seems to vanish and chaos
and misunderstanding descend.
</P>
<P>
   Studies repeatedly show that even when they know exactly what
stage of cancer a patient has, oncologists will accurately predict
the patient's prognosis less than half the time. They tend to err
on the side of optimism, wildly overestimating how long their
patients will live and suggesting that wishful human thinking can
easily morph those rigorous survival curves.
</P>
<P>
   In other studies, doctors are right on target in estimating the
survival of their sick patients, and it is the patients who grossly
overestimate their own chances.
</P>
<P>
   Were the doctors not talking, or the patients not listening? The
transmitting and receiving errors seem to run in both directions.
Some doctors admit they convey to patients more optimism than they
actually feel, convinced that patients who think they are ``going
to beat this thing'' do better than those who realize their chances
are nil.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients, for their part, simply deflect unappealing
information away from themselves. The most graphic illustration of
this particular instinct is the repeatedly confirmed observation
that cigarette smokers who can recite the health risks of smoking
with complete accuracy always grossly underestimate their own
personal risks: an example of the ``I'm going to beat this thing''
school of thinking run amok.
</P>
<P>
   The whole area of predicting survival threatens to become
medicine's version of ``don't ask, don't tell,'' a jumble of unsaid
questions and subtly elided nonanswers desperately in need of some
philosophic coherence. If you fail to ask, should I assume you
still want to know? If you ask, should I tell? If I tell, will you
hear?
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it, when a patient like Charlie cuts
through the murk of innuendo and subtext with the clarity of a
laser _ ``Whaddya say, doc? You gonna tell me this month?'' _ then
he is someone there are no answers for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
