<HEADLINE>
HOW SMALL TOWNS IN TEXAS DEAL WITH HEALTH CARE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SMALL TOWN NURSE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLARENDON, Texas _ There's no shortage of rugged pioneer
traditions in this town of 2,067, among the oldest communities in
the Panhandle. Founded as a liquor-free ``Christian colony'' in
1878, it was so overtly pious that wags dubbed it ``Saints'
Roost.''
</P>
<P>
   An immense brick Methodist church and a new campus for the
102-year-old Clarendon College bear testament to a rich past but
can't make up for the lack of a hospital, a movie theater, a mall
or even a shoe store. For several years, there was no doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months ago, Clarendon and the rest of Donley County got
their own general practice physician, and he's no ordinary man of
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Howard, 46, is a former naval flight surgeon with jet
flight training who stands 6-foot-5 and holds degrees in law and
medicine from Tulane University.
</P>
<P>
   His move from Corpus Christi to the country has meant lower
earnings. But Howard said he still enjoys a good income, and he and
his wife purchased a 4,000-square-foot home, which they could not
have afforded in the city. Then, citing church involvement,
Clarendon's low crime rate and strong community spirit, Howard
said: ``My standard of living has risen dramatically by anything
that matters in this life.''
</P>
<P>
   Few doctors see small-town medicine in that light.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five Texas counties are without a physician; 13 others
have just one. Two rural hospitals have closed in the past year,
and many others hang on from week to week, according to the Center
for Rural Health Initiatives, a state agency. Last year, Texas
suffered a net loss of 44 small-town health clinics. And more than
250,000 rural Texans eligible for benefits have no Medicare HMO in
their counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, rural Texans are worse off in their access to health
care than they were two years ago,'' said Sam Tessen, executive
director of the rural health center. He blamed reduced funding
brought about by the federal Balanced Budget Act of 1997, which
cost some clinics as much as $20 per patient visit.
</P>
<P>
   To attract medical staff members, some small towns are
advertising generous salaries and start-up bonuses. Others try to
recruit doctors while they are still in medical school with offers
of hefty scholarships or future help in repaying loans. Similar
incentives are being offered to physician's assistants and nurse
practitioners, all with equally poor results, public health
officials and hospital administrators say.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, the 15-bed hospital in Morton, a town of 2,600
located 57 miles west of Lubbock, has been offering a $150,000
salary plus $30,000 toward medical school loans as incentives for a
second doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' said Paul McKinney, administrator of
Morton's Cochran Memorial County Hospital. ``First of all, we're
such a small community and it's not exactly the garden spot of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inundated with calls from foreign medical students who
want to stay after their schooling,'' McKinney said. ``The trouble
is getting the right one that the community will accept and who
will stay three or four years. They say they will stay, but most
just want to meet their obligation for a (permanent resident
status) green card by working in a medically underserved area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they leave,'' he said. ``I can't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   The professional isolation, lack of big-city amenities and
resistance to country living from spouses combine to make
recruitment and retention a never-ending challenge, many small-town
leaders say. Surprisingly, income is rarely the issue. Nationally,
the median income of rural family physicians is slightly higher
than that of their urban counterparts: $127,000, compared with
$126,000, according to a May 1998 survey by the American Academy of
Family Physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Being on his own doesn't faze Howard, who cites his experience
as a Navy flight surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a place where I'd be the only doctor in
town,'' said Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an hour away from the nearest hospital (in Amarillo), an
hour away from a lot of colleagues,'' he said. ``Being alone is not
scary, but it would be nice to have some professional
interchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight miles to the southeast is Memphis, a
cotton-producing town that once boasted 14 physicians, including
one who dispensed 50-cent prescriptions for pints of ``medicinal
whiskey'' during Prohibition, recalled Dr. Robert Clark Jr. ``And
it was good whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1930s, Hall County, of which Memphis is the county
seat, has lost 76 percent of its population _ from 17,000 to 4,000.
And Memphis, which has dropped from 4,000 residents to 2,465, has
just two doctors, Clark, 70, and his 46-year-old son, Robert Clark
III, who moved back to Memphis last year. The younger Clark had to
give up surgery because the local hospital no longer has an
operating room. Neither father nor son delivers babies, so pregnant
mothers must travel to Amarillo, 80 miles to the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has recruited a third doctor, a Romanian-born
internist in Cleveland, Ohio, who will arrive this summer _ if the
struggling facility is still there.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day at noon, a half-dozen men in cowboy hats and
plaid shirts spilled out of a packed meeting on saving the town's
hospital, which is bleeding red to the tune of $300,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone knew Bill Gates, we could solve the problem like
this,'' retired pharmacist Dick Fowler said, snapping his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Memphis knows the billionaire Microsoft chairman. But
they do know the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis has been through this before.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, the town raised $330,000 to save Hall County
Hospital the first time. A hand-drawn sign urging donations from
passing motorists on U.S. 287 wound up in ``Time'' magazine. One
trucker handed over his entire paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   John Boff, chief executive of the Austin-based Texas
Organization of Rural and Community Hospitals, said Medicare and
Medicaid cutbacks, compounded by a managed-care system that directs
patients out of their communities, are to blame for the squeeze on
small-town medicine.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``If you close a hospital that serves 5,000, there are going to
be lives lost,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Having a doctor has been a concern from the start in Clarendon.
An early settler, famed cattleman Charles Goodnight, offered an
annual subsidy of $1,500 _ worth $30,000 in today's dollars _ to
recruit its first physician, Jerome Stocking.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, Clarendon got a new hospital but couldn't
find a doctor to staff it permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``One stayed a week, another two weeks, and a third a month,''
recalled Delbert Robertson, an undertaker who served as hospital
district president. ``One doctor stayed a year as medical director
before moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarendon closed the hospital and reopened it as a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   When the town's sole general practitioner retired several years
ago, Amarillo's Baptist St. Anthony's Health System put a
physician's assistant into its tiny clinic. Then that person
decided to leave. It had been in the red for five years, said Ron
Rives, a system vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Baptist St. Anthony's tried to recruit Howard years earlier for
its Clarendon clinic, but he took a job in Corpus Christi. Then he
and his wife decided to rear their children in the country and
learned that Clarendon still needed a doctor. The Georgia-born
physician came.
</P>
<P>
   Patients began returning, and the clinic turned profitable for
the first time, Rives said. Although the Amarillo hospital system
agreed to sell the clinic to Howard after a year, it talked about
helping the county build a new, larger clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``BSA said they'd help us do bricks and mortar, that they were
in it for the long haul,'' recalled A.L. Graham, administrator of
the Donley County Hospital District.
</P>
<P>
   But just a few weeks later, in September, Baptist St. Anthony's
did an about-face and said it would pull out after all on Jan. 1.
Graham said he wasn't surprised: ``I was more concerned about how
to retain the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The move left Howard's fledgling practice in a precarious
situation. He had only a few months to get federal certification
for Medicare and Medicaid, usually a drawn-out process.
</P>
<P>
   Howard took over the clinic with the help of a $15,000 grant
from the local economic development council. A $25,000 matching
grant from the hospital district and Center for Rural Health
Initiatives helped with startup costs. More important, the
community has embraced his practice, and the certification came
through quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's made it successful in Clarendon was having a doctor
willing to work hard and patients willing to see him,'' Rives said.
</P>
<P>
   The patient load has doubled to more than 40 a day, and Howard
is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Practicing medicine in a small West Texas town presents
challenges not encountered by urban doctors.
</P>
<P>
   When an 82-year-old rancher was told he needed to go to Amarillo
so a heart surgeon could insert a pacemaker, the man refused,
saying, ``Who'll take care of my cows?''
</P>
<P>
   A part-time nurse-tech with a ranching background assured Howard
that he'd look after the herd, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Dr. Howard, my husband wouldn't have gone to
Amarillo,'' said the rancher's wife, Ola Stone, 85, who stopped by
recently for a check on her own kidney condition.
</P>
<P>
   Medical issues ran the gamut on a recent day.
</P>
<P>
   A young Clarendon woman came home from Texas Tech for treatment
after the campus health clinic in Lubbock gave her nothing for a
stubborn head cold. The basketaball coach from the local junior
college came in complaining of chest congestion, and a rural mail
carrier sought treatment for hip pain. There was no shortage of flu
cases and X-rays for possibly broken bones. Babies in their
mothers' arms arrived for vaccinations. Assorted residents got
their regular allergy shot or were treated for chronic conditions,
ranging from diabetes to high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   One woman had swollen legs; several children had ear infections.
And there are always dislocated shoulders from run-ins with steers.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven's ``Eroica'' symphony wafted from his office as the
tall doctor bent low to examine where a plantar wart had been
removed from a small girl's foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what your son got on his math test,'' the blue-eyed
girl squealed.
</P>
<P>
   Clarendon is a very small town.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's wife, Lori, says she initially took her children on
regular runs to Amarillo for their favorite fast-food and mall
shopping. Once a real estate appraiser, she helps her husband with
insurance forms and appointments until 3 p.m. when their two
children show up from school and she's relieved by a part-time
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Like their mother, they say they prefer the country.
</P>
<P>
   And such attitudes, said Tessen of the Center for Rural Health
Initiatives, is the key to retaining medical professionals. He also
cited a study showing that communities have the best chance of
keeping a doctor if the physician or the physician's spouse has a
small-town background. And communities have to rally behind the
incoming doctor, Tessen added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my whole mission _ keeping Dr. Howard happy,'' Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Howards bought a comfortable house on the town's outskirts,
and although the doctor could make considerably more in Corpus
Christi, he emphasized, ``I am not living in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God placed me here,'' the country doctor said in a
quiet, almost embarrassed tone. ``My life up to his point prepared
me for this. In a different time in my life, I might not have been
ready to live in a town like Clarendon.''
</P>
<P>
   (Barry Shlachter is a staff writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7718, or e-mail:
bshlachter(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
