s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NY     02-21 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BASE TENOR OF `SOPRANOS' TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 27)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a  &UR; goomah &LR; , and how does it differ from a  &UR; goombah &LR; ? Is
the adjective  &UR; skeevy &LR;  somehow related to the slang noun for
underwear,  &UR; skivvies &LR; ? Does the  &UR; come-heavy &LR;  Mafia talk on
television give you  &UR; agita &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   These are words from the HBO television series ``The Sopranos,''
which I first turned to hoping to hear a rendition of the mad scene
in ``Lucia di Lammermoor.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is centered on a relentlessly foulmouthed fictional
Mafia family with the surname of Soprano. My interest is in the
writers' adoption of a lexicon that is loosely based on Italian
words, a little real Mafia slang and a smattering of lingo
remembered or made up for the show by former residents of a
blue-collar neighborhood in East Boston.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Goombah &LR;  is derived from  &UR; compare &LR; , `godfather' or `dear male
friend,''' says Frank Renzulli, co-executive producer and a writer
of the show. ``Southern Italians tend to make the  &UR; c &LR;  a  &UR; g &LR; , so
 &UR; compare &LR;  becomes  &UR; gompare &LR; . Dropping the last letter is very
Neapolitan, so it becomes  &UR; goompar &LR;  and then  &UR; goombah &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Green, another executive producer (it's hard to figure
from the titles who is the show's  &UR; capo di tutti capi &LR; ), contrasts
the ``godfather'' meaning of that word with  &UR; goomah &LR; , which she
defines as ``mistress.'' She adds, ``The language we're using is
from the neighborhood, a street language that's bastardized Italian
_ American forms of Italian words.''
</P>
<P>
   I ran  &UR; goomah &LR;  past Jimmy Breslin, the Newsday columnist who
wrote ``The Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight,'' and he confirms
the ``alternative wife'' sense. While I had him on the phone, I
tried  &UR; come heavy &LR; , which Jimmy defined as either ``bring money''
or ``come armed''; the show's legion of executive producers prefer
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Agita &LR;  means ``acid indigestion.'' In that regard,  &UR; skeevy &LR; 
comes from  &UR; schifare &LR; , to disgust. The name of the mob leader's
boat is  &UR; Stugots &LR; , which Entertainment Weekly defined as ``idiot,''
but which has a meaning closer to the Spanish  &UR; cojones &LR; , ``the
courage symbolized by primary male sex characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   That should be enough to get you through a couple of episodes,
unless the other endless, unoriginal obscenities get you down.
HBO's parent company, Time Warner, had a useful glossary of what
the executive producers call their  &UR; mobspeak &LR;  on its Web site, but
the understandably offended National Italian American Foundation
all but  &UR; mock-whacked &LR;  the corporate brass who _ suddenly afflicted
with  &UR; agita &LR;  _ removed the offensive page.
</P>
<P>
   SWITCHEROO
</P>
<P>
   During the war of commercial spots between George W. Bush and
John McCain, Bush quoted The Wall Street Journal, saying McCain's
campaign was ``crawling with lobbyists,'' and McCain slammed back
with a charge that the Bush spot ``twists the truth like Clinton.''
When the McCain manager offered to call a truce, Bush reportedly
replied, ``It's the old game of  &UR; switch-and-bait &LR; : say one thing
and do another.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of the old game, as Bush quickly realized, is the
reverse:  &UR; bait-and-switch &LR; . In this dodge, an advertiser entices a
customer into the store with a low price on an attractive item, but
then says, ``We're out of it,'' and tries to sell a higher-priced
item.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a product or service is advertised at a price that seems
too good to be true,'' advises the Better Business Bureau of Los
Angeles, ``this may be a `bait' ad. Then, if the merchant refuses
to show you the advertised item, to take orders for it or to
deliver it within a reasonable time ... take this as a sign you are
being `switched.''' The point to remember in applying it
metaphorically in politics is that the  &UR; bait &LR;  always comes first.
Then comes the  &UR; switch &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been criticized for his overuse of alliteration. As
William Kristol noted on MSNBC's ``Hardball'' program,
``compassionate conservatism'' was followed by ``prosperity with a
purpose'' and then by ``a reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   But to me, alliteration always attracts. My favorite was the
unforgettable 1920 passage by Warren G. Harding, promising ``not
heroics but healing, not nostrums but normalcy, not revolution but
restoration, not agitation but adjustment, not surgery but
serenity, not the dramatic but the dispassionate, not experiment
but equipoise.''
</P>
<P>
   FAREWELL, MY LOVELY MISS/MS./MRS.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, reflecting the desire of the great
majority of its newspaper members, has just dropped the use of the
courtesy titles  &UR; Miss &LR; ,  &UR; Mrs. &LR;  and  &UR; Ms. &LR;  in its news reports.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the first reference to Emily Jones is her full
name, and the second reference is merely Jones, the same way men
are treated. Gee; after all the battling years ago in this space to
get The New York Times to adopt  &UR; Ms. &LR; , out it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Not completely; The Times, in the main news sections, will
continue to use courtesy titles on second reference for both men
and women. But, according to the stylebook, ``The Times Magazine
and the Book Review, edited in the more literary style of a weekend
periodical, omit all courtesy titles.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it all has to do with the appearance of sexual
equality. If you don't use the  &UR; Mr. &LR;  instead of repeating the first
name for men, equality demands the same treatment for women. And
who would be so boldly old-fashioned and out of joint as to stand
up for any form of inequality?
</P>
<P>
   Here goes. It's not such a hot idea, because it needlessly
conceals information useful to the reader _ specifically, the sex
of the person being written about.
</P>
<P>
   I could understand the change if first names reflected sex as in
olden times: ``Emily Jones today was appointed commandant of the
Marine Corps. Jones, who is 19, said ....'' In that article, the
reader knows that a woman was appointed and needs no courtesy title
in front of the second reference unless interested in the
commandant's marital status, which the reader knows is none of his
or her business, and do you have a problem with that?
</P>
<P>
   The problem I have with that is that you can no longer tell the
boys from the girls by their given names. A lineup of Alex, Chris,
Pat, Brett, Ashley, Cameron, Meredith, Adrian and Leslie could be a
bearded baseball team or a Miss America pageant (soon to be the
America pageant, skip the honorific).
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story: ``Cameron Jones today bench-pressed 300 pounds
in the Olympic trials. Jones, not even out of breath, said ....''
Is that a normal weight lifter's story, or a breakthrough for the
human spirit? How does an editor know, from the copy, whether to
bury it or call for a picture to be emblazoned across the front
page?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the new AP rule is a space saver and will boost
journalism's profits. It doesn't strike me as helpful to the
reader, and in my nonliterary style I will resolutely continue to
use the  &UR; Ms. &LR;  I fought for, but sometimes I feel as lonely as the
guy who played the harp in Phil Spitalny's All-Girl Orchestra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3729 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-POPULAR-STUDENTS-     02-21 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-POPULAR-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, THE IN-CROWD TURNS UGLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By SUSAN GILBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many other schoolchildren, Claire and Stuart Bullen of
Walnut Creek, Calif., have looked in awe at the people in the
in-crowd and wondered, how do they do it? What is so special about
them? But unlike many of their peers, Claire, 11, and Stuart, 8, do
not aspire to be in that social tier: they think being popular
means being unkind, making friends and then discarding them.
</P>
<P>
   This view may seem harsh, but several social scientists say it
may not be totally off base. Researchers are just beginning to
study the dynamics of popular students in elementary and middle
school, and some early findings show that while most popular
children are model students _ friendly, bright, athletic and
cooperative _ a significant minority can be cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some popular boys are extremely aggressive, intimidating and
mean,'' said Dr. Philip C. Rodkin, a psychologist at Duke, whose
study of popularity among elementary-age boys appeared last month
in the journal Developmental Psychology. ``I think a lot of them
are bullies.''
</P>
<P>
   Many popular girls are also highly aggressive, bullying
unpopular girls with snubs and gossip to maintain their high
status, according to research by a husband-and-wife team of
sociologists, Dr. Patricia Adler of the University of Colorado and
Dr. Peter Adler of the University of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But in preliminary unpublished research, Rodkin found
aggressiveness more common in boys than girls. He and his
colleagues looked at characteristics of 452 boys in fourth, fifth
and sixth grades at schools in North Carolina and Chicago. They
asked the teachers to rank each child by popularity and by other
traits like athletic competence, friendliness and aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the students were asked to identify three peers who
they thought best embodied certain traits, like ``cooperative,''
``disruptive,'' ``starts fights,'' ``leader,'' ``athletic,'' ``gets
in trouble'' and ``cool.'' The students could also place themselves
in any of these categories. Finally, the children were asked to
name groups of classmates who frequently were seen together.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers and students tended to agree on who was in and who
was out and on the traits of the boys in the class. Based on that,
the researchers concluded that most of the popular boys had
qualities generally considered socially positive, like being
friendly, cooperative and athletic.
</P>
<P>
   But 30 percent of the most popular boys had a combination of
some positive qualities and others that the researchers termed
antisocial. In addition to being athletic, they often got into
fights with classmates and were disruptive in class.
</P>
<P>
   Other behavioral scientists praised the study for being among
the first to look at popularity in preadolescents in great detail.
But they said that it was no surprise that the highly popular boys
often behaved badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It supports things that a number of us have said for a while,
that boys look up to other boys who are aggressive,'' said Dr.
William Pollack, author of a best-selling book, ``Real Boys''
(Random House, 1998), and co-director of the Center for Men at
McLean Hospital in Boston, which studies male behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Thompson, a clinical psychologist and co-author of
another best seller on boys, ``Raising Cain'' (Ballantine, 1999),
said that besides being aggressive, misbehaving helped boys gain
respect from peers. ``Taking on the teacher is considered brave for
boys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some researchers disagreed with the use of the term
antisocial to describe the disruptive boys. ``These boys were
highly social,'' said Dr. Patricia Adler. ``Being tough,
conquering, showing off _ these are exactly the same behaviors that
dominant male animals in herds engage in.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack said that in common parlance, people were considered
antisocial when they misbehaved, but that the clinical diagnosis
was reserved for those who cared little for other people's
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Though many boys in the study fit the popular definition of
antisocial, he said, there was no way to know which ones fit the
clinical definition because the study did not investigate emotions.
He said he believed that many boys were highly social since they
behaved in ways considered masculine by society. ``We inculcate
boys to act tough, then we are surprised when they bully and harass
people,'' Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   In their book ``Peer Power'' (Rutgers University Press, 1998), a
sociological study of their own children's classmates, the Adlers
said that most of the popular girls were high academic achievers,
whereas for boys there was a stigma to being seen as studious or,
worse, a teacher's pet.
</P>
<P>
   The Adlers also reported that being attractive and having good
clothes was important for girls' popularity but relatively
unimportant for that of boys. They found that athletic ability
elevated the status of boys and girls, but, like Rodkin, they
observed that boys who were athletic, and sometimes cruel, were
held in especially high esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Other research has shown that aggressive behavior can be a
factor in social problems like substance abuse and school failure,
and Rodkin said that many children at high risk might be overlooked
if they were popular, with prevention programs focused mainly on
unpopular children.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers have a more positive view. ``The popular,
aggressive children in the Rodkin study had few other social
problems,'' said Dr. Lewis Lewin, a psychologist at the Oregon
Social Learning Center, a research group. Lewin has studied what
happens to aggressive boys as they age.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some evidence that aggression accompanied by other
problems, such as withdrawal and shyness, is a stronger predictor
of antisocial outcomes than any single factor,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said most boys could resist temptations to be bad, if
they were shown other ways to be masculine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not get carried away and say that boys only like
negative leaders,'' he said. ``Seventy percent of the boys in the
study who were popular were model children, win-win social leaders.
There's a hunger in boys for positive leadership and also for this
other scary, negative leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
