<SLUG> BC-SMALLTOWNNURSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSE PROVIDES CARE BY USING TELEMEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies SMALL TOWN HEALTH) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HART, Texas _ There's no doctor, no hospital, no clinic in this
farming community of 1,221, where grain elevators reach for the
sky. The nearest hospital is 35 miles away and the only available
health care is at school.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Retta Knox, who cares for the 450 students at Hart
Elementary School and Hart Junior-Senior High, is not your typical
school nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Using grant money, Knox has arranged to have a pediatrician
visit from the Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center every
Wednesday and a ``telemedicine'' satellite link with another Tech
doctor each Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursdays, the dentist calls, and twice a week, there's a
dental hygienist. Then there's the social worker and once-a-week
psychotherapist running an ``abstinence'' program to curb teen-age
pregnancies. Knox provides space every other Tuesday to the Texas
Department of Health's WIC program for women, infants and children.
A converted broom closet serves as a pharmacy _ the only place in
Hart with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Monday, Knox worked alone and treated more than 60
children with strep throats, assorted viruses and infected ears.
</P>
<P>
   A tall woman of 51 with white hair, Knox has treated three
generations of students since 1972. She is adept at spotting and
stretching grant money. The Hart native also knows which parents
have used clothing to donate and which Lions Club member can
arrange eyeglasses for a needy student.
</P>
<P>
   Her clinic, across the parking lot from the schools, combines
her old office and a former Head Start classroom; the dental clinic
took over a tiny administration building. Both use refurbished
equipment, Army surplus and castoffs from retiring doctors in other
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went out lookin','' Knox said of her scavenging
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   The whole undertaking began in 1992 when a friend noticed a
$75,000 state grant that would cover startup costs for an in-school
clinic, saying, ``This looks like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the clinic is funded to care for children who are
not covered by Medicaid but are too poor to otherwise afford
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought many of the parents didn't care. The kids
were always sick and missed lots of school,'' Knox said. ``But once
I started the clinic and mothers realized they could get low-cost
or free care, the health of the whole family changed. These people
were struggling to feed their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the in-school clinic covers the basics and more. The ties to
Texas Tech have led to rapid care for a third-grader's ruptured
appendix and a diagnosis of diabetes for a young teen who couldn't
maintain his weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working 10 times harder as I did as a traditional school
nurse,'' she said. Asked why she has taken the program on, Knox
didn't hesitate to reply: ``The kids. The kids. You can do so much
more for the kids. It's a real nice feeling you are making a
difference in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
