<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barometric readings will be near 30.70 inches of mercury over
Maine on Tuesday morning, but instead of a dome of cold, dry air
covering the East, a milder air flow from the southwest should
dominate the country from the Plains to the Appalachians. A
retreating jet stream will also draw up patches of moist air above
10,000 feet resulting in varying amounts of clouds in most sections
west of the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Seaboard will be bright and noticeably milder after
a chilly dawn. A push of warmer air into New England will be marked
by some clouds over the interior. Strengthening onshore winds in
Florida will combine with a disturbance moving through the Bahamas
to bring coastal clouds and perhaps a shower to the northern
sections.
</P>
<P>
   The storm that drenched southern California on Monday will
emerge as a weaker disturbance in New Mexico on Tuesday. However, a
corridor of humid air streaming north from the western Gulf of
Mexico will set the stage for an outbreak of strong to perhaps
severe thunderstorms later Tuesday in west-central Texas and
Oklahoma. Showers will dampen a wider region of the eastern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably warm air will cover the Mississippi Valley and
Great Lakes promoting rapid snow melt in northern sections. Cool,
moist winds will ascend the west slopes of the Rockies causing
showers.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful front will push into the Northwest with gusty winds
and heavy rain at the coast from southern Washington to central
California. Showers will spread inland later on.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Eastern Avalanches
</P>
<P>
   Two lives were lost in freakish avalanches in the northern
Appalachians this past weekend. On Saturday, a skier was smothered
by snow at Lake Placid, N.Y., and another skier lost his life
Sunday on Mount Washington, N.H.. Last week was a snowy time for
this region, with two major snowfalls, and the vast majority of
avalanches occur within 24 hours after a snowstorm. Avalanches
usually form when either a cornice of snow breaks loose from the
edge of a mountain or a slab of snow slides off an existing snow
cover. It appears that the eastern avalanches were of the slab
type.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
