<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN THE SHADOW OF THE GIPPER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Arizona Sen. John McCain often invokes the revered
name of Ronald Reagan as he tries to appeal across party lines to
the independents and moderates once known as ``Reagan Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   His last commercial in South Carolina, for instance, bragged
that McCain is``a Republican like Ronald Reagan, who can win.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gov. George W. Bush seldom mentions his father's
predecessor in the White House, preferring to associate himself
with Bush administration strategists and surrogates, such as Dan
Quayle, his father's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have good political reasons for their approach.
McCain genuinely admires Reagan and was impressed by the way voters
treated the president as a rock star during his 1984 re-election
campaign. A star now himself, McCain identifies with Reagan and
finds embracing Reagan useful to stress his own conservative
credentials and optimistic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, is trying to project a youthful image of the
future that leaves the Reagan years behind. He was stung by early
accusations that he was leaning too much on his family name and is
now eager to be seen as standing on his own two feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have other reasons for overlooking the Reagan legend.
</P>
<P>
   In this, he is imitating his father's 1988 campaign; George the
elder never mentioned Reagan by name, as though he were trying to
erase a painful memory of the vice presidential years he spent as
Reagan's sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the White House, pappa Bush continued to ignore Reagan,
appearing with him in public only at the dedication of the Reagan
Library. He was repaying the Reagans in kind for their own
eight-year snub; they never invited Bush and his family to visit
them in the private White House quarters. Although the Bushes
attended official functions in the mansion's staterooms, they were
never asked to come upstairs where the presidential family really
lives.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush was preparing to seek the presidency in 1988,
conservative columnist George Will wrote a devastatingly critical
column accusing Bush of pandering to the rightwing. ``The
unpleasant sound Bush is emitting as he traipses from one
conservative gathering to another is a thin, tinny `arf' -- the
sound of a lapdog,'' wrote Will, who was close to Nancy Reagan and
had lunched with her shortly before writing the piece. It is widely
believed that she was the source of the ``lapdog'' crack.
</P>
<P>
   But Will was not alone in finding Bush a wimpy No. 2.
``Doonesbury'' cartoonist Garry Trudeau accused Bush of putting his
manhood in trust when he served under Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush proclaimed the dawn of a ``kinder, gentler'' era in
his 1988 presidential nomination acceptance speech, the Reagans
were predictably offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kinder, gentler than who?'' Mrs. Reagan was heard to snap.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the Reagans and the Bushes was awkward
from the beginning. In the 1980 Republican primary, Bush had
campaigned against Reagan, calling his tax cut plan ``voodoo
economics.'' Bush then had to swallow his words when he joined the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also flip-flopped on abortion, abandoning his pro-choice
position to embrace Reagan's anti-abortion stand. Mrs. Reagan, of a
less forgiving nature than the Gipper, never trusted Bush after
that.
</P>
<P>
   Once elected president in his own right, Bush promptly cleaned
house, getting rid of Reagan's intimates and ruffling feathers
among rightwing activists. He had a right to his own team, but
Reagan loyalists felt mistreated and underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder then that stories are circulating that Nancy Reagan
prefers McCain to Bush's son and might even endorse McCain if he
survives to reach the California primary on March 7. The McCain
camp has been quietly lobbying for her support but she is unlikely
to wade into the fight if McCain looks like a loser.
</P>
<P>
   In light of his father's experience, it is telling that George
the younger now tells reporters that if he wins the GOP nomination
he would select as his running mate ``someone who likes me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smart politics means putting personal grudges aside when it is
in a candidate's interest to do so. The Bushes have never
complained publicly about the tension between them and the Reagans.
President Reagan remains so high in public esteem that attacking
him would only backfire, particularly now when he is too ill to
defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   But presidents and presidential candidates are human, too,
believe it or not. They cannot totally escape their inner feelings
in their attitudes toward competitors or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
