<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-PRIMARY (Detroit) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen.
John McCain battle for votes in Tuesday's Republican primary. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain often invokes the
revered name of Ronald Reagan as he tries to appeal across party
lines. Gov. George W. Bush, by contrast, seldom mentions his
father's predecessor in the White House. Both have their political
reasons for this. But there are personal reasons as well. The
strain between the Bush family and the Reagans may surface
dramatically if Nancy Reagan endorses McCain, a rumored
possibility, although a distant one. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MICHIGAN-PRIMARY-HNS &LR;      02-21 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-PRIMARY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH AND McCAIN IN CLOSE MICHIGAN DUEL   
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Stands for Detroit-dated item on budget.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain on Monday cast himself as the
underdog against Texas Gov. George W. Bush's juggernaut of $70
million in campaign funds and endorsements by leading Republicans,
including 175 House members, 38 senators and 26 governors,
including Michigan Gov. John Engler.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're shooting from everywhere; everybody is against me,''
McCain told a thunderous, confetti-filled rally of high school
students in a school gymnasium here on Michigan's east coast. ``But
we're going to kill them, right? We're going to get them, right?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``If I win tomorrow in Michigan there's no
stopping us. I'm going right on to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, resuming his role as frontrunner after his victory in the
South Carolina primary, generally ignored McCain's attacks and
talked about tax cuts. He told rallies in the Detroit area on
Monday that he is counting down the days until he could ``the end
of the Clinton-Gore era in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did respond to McCain's ridicule of his claim to be a
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had said that Bush is the governor of a state ``that has
the most liberal campaign contribution laws. ... If Gov. Bush is a
reformer I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Monday that he is setting the pace in an important
area _ posting contributors' names on the Internet almost as fast
as their checks come in. He also criticized McCain for raising
money from lobbyists after criticizing the impact of special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Latest polls showed a too-close-to-call contest. A Detroit News
poll released Monday reported McCain leading Bush, 40 percent to 38
percent, a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign manager Rick Davis said he is preparing to
request protection for the candidate by the U.S. Secret Service in
the days leading up to the March 7 presidential primaries in more
than a dozen states, led by New York, California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds were manageable before but they're getting bigger
and they're getting more enthusiastic,'' Davis said. ``If the
crowds keep building like this, it will just get to the point to
where there's a crush even with the friendly crowds and that could
be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law authorizes Secret Service protection for ``major
presidential candidates`` who request it during the primary
campaign. Former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., requested Secret
Service protection following the New Hampshire primary. Vice
President Al Gore already has protection because of his role as
vice president. Taxpayers pay the costs for Secret Service
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service protection also has two beneficial side effects:
The agents assigned to the candidate pay for their seats on the
candidate's plane, thus helping defer the cost of the airplane; and
agents add to the candidate's entourage, imparting an aura of
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is protected by the Texas Rangers law enforcement agency
because of role as governor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his Michigan chairman, state Sen. John Schwarz,
sharply criticized Bush's campaign tactics that they said include
``attack ads,'' negative ``push polling'' telephone calls designed
to steer voters toward Bush, direct mail attacks and surrogates
quietly going around to local audiences to spread negative
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never do and say the things that have been (said) by
that campaign,'' McCain said on NBC News' ``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told a roaring rally of more than 1,000 in Traverse City
that Michigan voters ought to ``reject this character
assassination, reject the low road to the presidency and support
those who want to take the high road. You deserve a lot better than
the trash that's on your television set and over the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he hoped to win Democrats and independents in
Michigan's open primary in which all registered voters may take
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole business of governing America is not to divide up
along party lines but to appeal to ... the great center,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is fueling his insurgency with pledges to ``break
the iron triangle of lobbyists, money and legislation'' that has
``stolen'' the government from the people, struck at his rival's
fund raising. Bush, the eldest son of former President George Bush,
has set a record raising more than $68 million in campaign
contributions without federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   McCain cited cases of alleged access buying by generous
Democratic donors in 1996 and told his audience in Traverse City
that ``right now the Bush campaign is setting up the same apparatus
that the Clinton-Gore campaign set up in 1996 to funnel millions
and tens of millions of dollars of this so-called soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP has become ``addicted to the huge checks'' from special
interest lobbyists, McCain added, citing $7 million in so-called
soft money contributions to the party by the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it what we want?'' McCain asked his audience. ``I don't
think so.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has vowed not to accept the packaged ``soft money''
contributions that unions, corporations and other special interest
groups are permitted to donate to political parties to help the
parties convey messages not directly tied to a specific candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore re-election campaign raised more than $20
million in such contributions in 1996, including money from foreign
donors seeking access to Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said donor Johnny Chung, a generous contributor to the
Clinton campaign in 1996, made more visits to the White House in
1996 than did Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's 58 convention delegates make the state the richest
prize of in the delegate hunt so far. Bush came into Michigan with
66 delegates of the 1,035 delegates needed to win the nomination.
McCain had 13. Arizona, which also holds its primary on Tuesday,
offers 30 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
