<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0222-COX     02-21 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0222-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAGA OF ELIAN TWISTS, TURNS INTO U.S. COURTS; EXPERTS AGREE
RETURN JUST A MATTER OF TIME
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The topsy-turvy story of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez took new twists Monday as a federal judge handling his
case fell ill, even as a South Florida nun who played a key role in
the saga made dramatic new revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Unconfirmed reports also circulated that the boy's father might
travel to the United States to claim his son.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys arguing over whether the boy should stay here or
return to Cuba were scheduled to take up the key issue of
jurisdiction Tuesday before U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler,
but the 77-year-old Hoeveler suffered a stroke over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Chief Judge Edward B. Davis would meet with
attorneys in the case Tuesday, but only to officially inform them
about the plans to replace Hoeveler and to announce that a new
judge will be selected randomly by computer. It was unknown how
long the developments would delay Elian's case.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler, a veteran federal judge who presided over the trial of
former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega, was assigned the Elian
case after another judge withdrew last month because of a possible
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin _ who hosted a high-profile
reunion between Elian and his Cuban grandmothers in January _ said
that one of the grandmothers wanted to defect and that Elian's
Cuban family knew long in advance that the boy's mother planned to
flee the island with him by boat.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin _ who is president of Barry University and was asked
to host the reunion by her friend, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
_ also said that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, had
physically abused the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin made the statements in an interview with the Miami
Herald. After the Herald story was published on Sunday, however,
O'Laughlin released a statement saying the article contained some
misinformation. She said she never met privately with the
grandmothers, but learned of the details about the Gonzalez family
from ``other sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Herald editors have stood by the story's accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin's stunning statements are unlikely to have a major
impact on the court proceedings surrounding the boy. But they will
likely spark a new round in the bitter war of words between Miami's
volatile Cuban exiles and the communist government of Cuba _ not to
mention the two branches of the Gonzalez family.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was found floating in an inner tube off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and 10 other people
drowned after their small boat capsized on an ill-fated trip from
Cuba. Since then, Elian has lived with relatives in Miami's Little
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration officials have ruled that Elian should be
returned to his father in Cuba, a decision upheld by Reno in
January. Elian's Miami family filed a federal lawsuit challenging
the decision and asking that the boy be granted an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the law is squarely behind the government's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no question,'' said David Abraham, a
University of Miami law professor who specializes in immigration
matters. ``Immigration admissions decisions are not reviewable by
the courts. The law is clear, and has been clear from the outset.''
</P>
<P>
   If a judge rules that the federal courts have no jurisdiction
and that immigration officials were correct in saying Elian should
return to his father, the Miami family could appeal, meaning the
boy's return would be delayed for several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to granting an asylum hearing, Elian's Miami
relatives want the federal courts to recognize a controversial
ruling in Miami-Dade County family court in which a judge awarded
custody of the boy to his Miami great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. Reno,
however, has ignored that ruling, saying the Florida court had no
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   But the dry legal proceedings seemed to take a back seat Monday
to the new controversy sparked by O'Laughlin's comments.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old Roman Catholic nun was chosen by Reno to host
Elian's reunion with his grandmothers because of her reputation for
compassion and integrity. A day after the reunion, however,
O'Laughlin surprised many observers by taking a strong stand,
saying Elian should not go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she went into the reunion feeling the boy should
go back, but changed her mind after sensing a deep but unspecified
fear on the part of the grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   She remained vague on specifics until her interview in the
Herald.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction Monday from Elian's family in
Cuba, or from the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   But her comments that one of the boy's grandmothers wanted to
defect, that his father abused his mother and that the Cuban family
knew of boat trip 10 days in advance seemed likely to trigger anger
in Cuba. O'Laughlin has already been vilified in the official Cuban
press for saying the boy should stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a columnist for another South Florida newspaper
cited another journalist as the source of reports that Elian's
father, Juan Miguel, may travel to the United States to meet
secretly with his son. Official sources in Washington and Cuba have
said they know nothing of such plans, and Gonzalez has repeatedly
said in the past that he would not travel to America.
</P>
<P>
   However the case turns out, O'Laughlin says she fears it is now
too late for Elian to have a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had gone back immediately before so many people on both
sides wanted control of him, he would have been better off,'' she
told the Herald. ``But as it is now, I pray every day that whether
he stays or goes back, he can survive this.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
