   TOWN FOR SALE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ At 2 p.m. Thursday, an entire community will go to the
highest bidder to the strains of mariachi guitars. On the auction
block is Lajitas, a resort town with 160 residents. Wedged between
Big Bend National Park and Big Bend Ranch State Park, Lajitas comes
complete with a golf course, a hotel, three motels, a 14-bed bunk
house, condominiums, church, saloon, bakery,
trading-post-turned-grocery, sewage plant, an 80-spot RV park,
restaurants, six subdivisions, a 4,800-foot-long airstrip and
heart-achingly scenic vistas on 24,000 acres. Then there's the
beer-guzzling goat named Clay Henry III, which was elected
``mayor'' in November, and the town's full-gallop footnote in
history. Gen. John Pershing used Lajitas as a jumping off point in
his pre-World War I cavalry pursuit of Mexican revolutionary
Francisco ``Pancho'' Villa. By BARRY SHLACHTER. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
