<P>
   SMALL TOWN NURSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HART, Texas _ There's no doctor, no hospital, no clinic in this
farming community of 1,221, where grain elevators reach for the
sky. The nearest hospital is 35 miles away and the only available
health care is at school. But then, Retta Knox, who cares for the
450 students at Hart Elementary School and Hart Junior-Senior High,
is not your typical school nurse. Using grant money, Knox has
arranged to have a pediatrician visit from the Texas Tech
University Health Sciences Center every Wednesday and a
``telemedicine'' satellite link with another Tech doctor each
Friday. On Thursdays, the dentist calls, and twice a week, there's
a dental hygienist. Then there's the social worker and once-a-week
psychotherapist running an ``abstinence'' program to curb teen-age
pregnancies. By BARRY SHLACHTER. Story has moved in ``a'' general
news category. (Accompanies SMALL TOWN HEALTH.) &QL; 
