<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-HABITAT-EDGE-ART-     02-21 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HABITAT-EDGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SURVIVAL ON THE EDGE: HOW A BEETLE LED EXPERTS TO A NEW PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the American burrowing beetle that tipped off Dr. Rob
Channell and Dr. Mark Lomolino, conservation biologists, that one
of the basic tenets of modern conservation theory might be
misguided, to the possible detriment of many endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The geographical range of the beetle, Lomolino discovered, had
shrunk drastically over the years and now, confined to Rhode
Island, the insect occupies only the merest edge of its original
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not where it should have been living, according to
conventional biological wisdom. Left to its own devices, experts
have long believed, a wild species will persist most abundantly and
robustly in the center of its geographical range; populations at
the edges are fragmented, disjointed, isolated, ephemeral _ and
more likely to die out.
</P>
<P>
   This common-sense proposition has long led conservation
biologists to concentrate on core areas as they delineate habitats
to protect, or sites to reintroduce species. They have largely
neglected the edges.
</P>
<P>
   But the burrowing beetle led Channell of Fort Hays State
University in Hays, Kan., and Lomolino of the University of
Oklahoma to undertake a study whose results suggest that
conservation strategies that ignore the fringes of endangered
species' ranges may sometimes fail.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, the researchers said, is that conventional rules
often ignore the impact of people. Human activities like farming
and logging have already pushed many species out of their core
territories and relegated them to the edges, where they cling to a
precarious existence in less favorable habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human activity tends to spread like a contagion,'' Channell
said. The human presence typically moves like a wave front across a
species' range, he said, from one edge of the range, across the
middle, toward the far edge, destroying or disturbing habitat as it
goes, overwhelming the underlying natural ecology. The far edge in
many instances remains intact, and thus provides the only habitat
in which a fading species can be preserved and the only reservoir
from which it might eventually be able to reclaim some of its
former territory.
</P>
<P>
   The two scientists gathered maps delineating the changes in the
extent of the ranges of 245 endangered species. They included
birds, mammals, reptiles, amphibians, fishes, mollusks, arthropods
and plants on all continents except Antarctica and several islands.
After digitizing and comparing the maps, Channell said, they found
geographic patterns of species survival ``completely contrary'' to
conventional expectation.
</P>
<P>
   In case after case, from the giant panda of China to the
black-footed ferret, California condor and red wolf of North
America, plus scores of others, the maps told a clear tale: many
species have fled from the human onslaught and found refuge on the
peripheries of their ranges. The findings were published recently
in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``an extraordinarily regular pattern,'' said Stuart Pimm,
an ecologist and conservation expert at Columbia University. Like
humans, who mostly live in temperate zones rather than in the
arctic or the tropics, he said, wild species ``tend to pick the
places that are just right'' for them.
</P>
<P>
   That being so, he said, ``you might think that if you make life
hard for a species, it would withdraw from the periphery and move
to the center of the range where it has a better chance. But that's
not the pattern we see.''
</P>
<P>
   Many endangered species seem not to do very well once they
become rare, he said. ``The reason they do not,'' he said, ``is
that they are probably in the wrong place; they have never done
well at their edges, and now that's all they have left.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two major exceptions to the findings: Hawaii and
Africa. After humans arrived, species moved to the geographical
center of the Hawaiian Islands, not the periphery. But some
scientists have suggested that many Hawaiian species were confined
to the lowlands before humans arrived, and so inhabited
doughnut-shaped ranges. The interior volcanic highlands, therefore,
might properly be considered the ecological fringe of species'
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, species were distributed more uniformly across their
ranges than elsewhere. Channell and Lomolino note that people have
a longer history in Africa than anywhere else, and that human
activity has long been distributed rather than moving across it
like a wave front.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say this cannot be the whole explanation, since the
declines of African species examined by the two researchers are
recent. Overhunting might drive large species toward the center of
a range, suggested Dr. Thomas Brooks of the University of
Copenhagen, the University of Cambridge and Conservation
International, the Washington-based conservation group, in a
commentary in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks noted that 20 of the 24 African species included in the
Channell-Lomolino study were large mammals, compared with fewer
than half in other regions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the study's findings, Pimm said, there are still many
places in the world where core habitat areas are intact, or nearly
so. Obvious examples are the forests of Congo, Southeast Asia and
the Amazon, where a large proportion of the world's species live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It behooves us to get serious about protecting those areas
before they're reduced to fragments,'' Pimm said, adding that the
Channell-Lomolino study ``adds a new urgency to the conservation
actions we're already contemplating.''
</P>
<P>
   But while core habitat areas should not be ignored, Channell
said, conservationists should ``pay attention to the periphery
also,'' giving it equal status.
</P>
<P>
   This may be especially urgent in what experts call the world's
``hot spots'' of biological diversity. These are especially
biologically rich areas that, according to Brooks, contain perhaps
half of all the earth's species, even though they take up only 1.4
percent of its total land area.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Channell-Lomolino findings, Brooks wrote in Nature,
``we would expect disproportionate amounts of habitat to survive on
the peripheries of the hot spots.'' Conservationists cannot afford
to ignore these peripheral habitats, he wrote, since they ``may now
hold some of the last opportunities for conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
