<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER22-COX     02-21 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Monday night at the Apollo
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and Bill Bradley will go at each other Monday night in a
90-minute debate at the Apollo Theatre in Harlem. The event,
running from 9 p.m. to 10:30 p.m., will be moderated by CNN's
Bernard Shaw and telecast live on the cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLING IT OUT IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and John McCain were campaigning in Michigan on
Monday, with McCain, in Traverse City, accusing Bush of running a
campaign by ``character assassination.'' He was referring to TV ads
for Tuesday's Michigan primary. Bush, focusing on his economic
proposals in a Detroit speech, said he's ``taking nothing for
granted'' in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ANYONE'S GUESS IN MICHIGAN ...
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan GOP presidential race is close. A Detroit News poll
taken last week found George W. Bush and John McCain virtually
tied. Independent pollster John Zogby says he found the same thing
when he polled in Michigan on Sunday, after the South Carolina
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ... BUT MCCAIN SAFE IN HOME STATE
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters, political officials and potential voters all agree,
according to the Arizona Daily Star, that John McCain's defeat in
South Carolina shouldn't carry over Tuesday to Arizona, McCain's
home state. The paper says the the most likely effect ``will be to
boost the voter turnout _ already expected to be high. Anticipation
of a McCain victory hasn't changed. ... ``The question is by how
much _ and how much will be enough to make a significant political
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ENEMIES NO LONGER
</P>
<P>
   Communist Vietnam on Monday condemned John McCain's use of the
term ``gooks'' to refer to his Vietnam War captors, saying the slur
was hurtful and unworthy of someone running for the U.S.
presidency. ``The fact Mr. John McCain uses such words and makes
such statements that lack goodwill have hurt Vietnamese and Asian
people,'' Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Phan Thuy Thanh said in
response to questions on McCain's quoted comments of last week.
</P>
<P>
   NADER'S VOICE ADDED TO RACE
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader is a presidential candidate again, officially
declaring his candidacy Monday for the environmentalist Green Party
nomination. The consumer advocate said corporate influence is
controlling government, and promised to put more power in the hands
of the people. Nader got less than 1 percent of the vote last time.
He says he hopes to win 5 percent this time.
</P>
<P>
   COURTING MINORITY VOTES IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday night's debate with Bill Bradley at Harlem's
Apollo Theatre, Al Gore renewed his call for an end to racial
profiling by police and passage of federal hate-crimes legislation.
Gore told a largely black audience of more than 800 in a church in
Albany, N.Y., that the Republicans who hope to take the White House
are ``morally blind'' to racial concerns. Gore, campaigning for the
first time this year in New York with Hillary Clinton, never
mentioned Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   THEY CAN WALK IN FREELY NOW
</P>
<P>
   A day before the 90-minute Democratic debate Monday at the
Apollo Threatre centering on urban and racial issues, theater stage
hands and management reached a contract agreement. That averted a
threatened strike that would have caused complications, because
both Al Gore and Bill Bradley had vowed not to cross a picket line.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH LOVE IN DETROIT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, looking for support in Detroit's overwhelming
Democratic black community, focused on morality and self-reliance.
Keyes: ``It's all important to spread the word throughout this
country about what people can do if they are willing to put their
faith in God and one another.'' He called for morality in schools
and attacked affirmative action practices that provide
opportunities solely according to race.
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT RESULTS, DIFFERENT STRATEGIES
</P>
<P>
   The flip-flop of the finish between the New Hampshire and South
Carolina primaries has brought a role reversal to the campaign
styles of John McCain and George W. Bush. McCain, who beat Bush
decisively in New Hampshire but suffered an 11-point loss in South
Carolina, has gone on the attack, saying, ``If Governor Bush is a
reformer, I'm an astronaut.'' Bush, on the other hand, reverted to
a front-runner's posture of trying to ignore his rival and instead
lay out his agenda for the country.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK LAWMAKER SWITCHES TO MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after his defeat in South Carolina, John
McCain got a boost in New York from Rep. Peter King, who announced
his switch from supporting George W. Bush to McCain. In recent
days, some Republican leaders in New York have expressed
ambivalence about Bush, but King, from Long Island, was the first
to publicly switch sides in defiance of Gov. George Pataki, Bush's
state campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING NUMBERS ARE IN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain spent $6.8 million in January, bringing his total to
$21 million, according to reports filed with the Federal Election
Commission. George W. Bush spent $12.8 million, bringing his ttal
to $50.1 million _ more than any other presidential candidate ever.
On the Democratic side, Bill Bradley outspent Al Gore last month,
$5 million to $3.8 million, even as he lost both the Iowa caucuses
and New Hampshire primary. Bradley's total spending through January
is $24.4 million; Gore's is $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   GOING GETS TOUGHER IN OHIO
</P>
<P>
   Two potential weaknesses may hamper John McCain's campaign in
Ohio, site of one of the major Super Tuesday primaries March 7. The
Cleveland Plain Dealer reports that McCain's Ohio forces are thin
and poorly organized. More importantly, the independent vote that
helped him win the New Hampshire primary doesn't have a history of
turning out in Ohio primaries.
</P>
<P>
   HE'D LOVE TO SEE A CLINTON-GORE PROBE
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley publicly endorsed the appointment of a special
prosecutor to investigate campaign finance abuses by the
Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996, saying he thought there was clear
evidence that laws had been broken. Bradley asserted that the
decision by the Democratic National Committee to return money that
may have been collected improperly in 1996, and the criminal
prosecutions of several low-level Clinton-Gore fund-raisers
indicated that a broader investigation is needed.
</P>
<P>
   AND HER NEW HOUSE IS HEATED BY OIL
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton joined a growing chorus of Northeastern
lawmakers of both parties in calling for a regional oil reserve to
help states cope with future shortages of home heating oil and tamp
down soaring consumer prices. As OPEC has limited production, the
cost of heating oil soared to a peak of $2.02 earlier this month.
Her Senate opponent, Rudy Giuliani, has repeatedly criticized the
president for refusing to release oil from the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve to drive down the cost of home heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM THE ONE TO WATCH SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsay Graham (R-S.C.) backed John McCain in the state's
GOP primary, but that isn't expected to hold him back. He's ``South
Carolina's hottest media darling since the late Lee Atwater,''
according to The State newspaper in Columbia. Graham has been
polishing his speaking style with the national media, which
discovered how quotable he was during the Clinton impeachment
hearings. Now, says the State, Graham is the best bet to snag the
state GOP nomination for Sen. Strom Thurmond's seat when Thurmond
retires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
