<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ Less than one month before presidential
elections in Taiwan, the Chinese government releases the bluntest
warning yet that it will not wait indefinitely for the island to
reunite with the mainland. The Chinese have long made it clear that
any moves by Taiwan toward formal independence would lead to war,
but Monday's action adds for the first time that if Taiwan refuses
to pursue ``the peaceful settlement of cross-Straits reunification
through negotiations, then the Chinese government will only be
forced to adopt all drastic measures possible.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED; an early version of this story has moved; if
developments warrant, a 1stLd-Writethru will be filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECT (Tehran) _ Iran's triumphant reformers are beginning
to look ahead, beyond the stunning victory that appears to be
theirs from last Friday's parliamentary elections, and plotting
fundamental changes in how the country is run. Hossein Valeh, the
chief political advisor to President Mohammad Khatami and one of
his closest confidantes for more than 10 years, said in an
interview on Monday that the pro-Khatami forces have won 73 percent
of the parliamentary seats in the first round of elections and
could well control nine out of 10 seats after the second round in
April. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Nazran, Russia) _ A story of how Zina
Labazaneva died, in a west Grozny neighborhood called Aldi, and of
how a woman she never met, a plump, 40-ish mother of teen-agers
named Sapiyat, helped give her peace in death. But it is much more
than that. For Sapiyat and the other survivors of Aldi _ refugees,
trickling only now out of Chechnya into the makeshift camps that
pock the Caucasus Mountain foothills near Nazran _ are bringing
previously unreported stories of one of the worst civilian
massacres known to date in the Chechen war. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-RESIGN (New York) _ As antitrust pressure mounts on the
auction houses Sotheby's and Christie's, the president and chief
executive of Sotheby's, Diana D. Brooks, resigns. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-CHARGES (Undated) _ A debate is raging at the Federal
Communications Commission about whether cellular telephone
customers should pay to receive calls as well as to make them.
Cellular companies have pressed for a rule change that would extend
the ``calling party pays'' model of traditional telephone billing
to wireless calls. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DANIEL (New York) _ Clifton Daniel, the courtly North
Carolinian who served as managing editor of The New York Times from
1964 to 1969 after a career as a correspondent in wartime London,
war-torn Europe and the Middle East, died Monday at his home in
Manhattan. He was 87. The cause was complications of a stroke and
heart disease, said his wife, Margaret Truman Daniel. By Eric Pace.
</P>
