<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FESTIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMERSE YOURSELF IN TV
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Museum of Television and Radio's annual William S. Paley
Television Festival, a series of evenings honoring various TV shows
and pioneers, generally offers a mix of genuinely classic
television, some series too new for the participants to offer much
historical perspective, and outright padding. This year's
assortment offers fewer of the dubious choices but more recent
series. The festival runs Feb. 29-March 14.
</P>
<P>
   One genuine must-see event, ``An Evening With Garry Shandling,''
kicks off the festival on Feb. 29. Shandling, an undisputed
original, is notoriously reticent about discussing or accepting
praise for his work, so this will be a rare opportunity to watch
him squirm up close.
</P>
<P>
   Paley Festival events usually screen an episode or two of a
program before those who worked on it begin their discussion; in
Shandling's case, a reel of career highlights will be shown before
he takes questions from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Classic series ``MASH,'' ``The Carol Burnett Show'' and ``Outer
Limits'' will be honored. The ``MASH'' event (March 6) will feature
Alan Alda and cast members and writers from throughout the show's
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Carol Burnett Show'' (March 3) will include the entire
cast and some writers of the variety show, and they'll no doubt cut
up and laugh over one another instead of sticking to the script
during the Q&AMP;A portion of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   As a science-fiction anthology series, ``Outer Limits'' (March
10) didn't feature a permanent cast, so the evening will likely be
a spotty hodgepodge of incomplete memories. Nonetheless, some
decent names have been assembled, including Martin Landau and
Robert Culp, writer Harlan Ellison, ``American Beauty''
cinematographer Conrad Hall and former ``Star Trek'' executive
producer Robert Justman.
</P>
<P>
   New shows being feted include ``The West Wing'' (March 7),
``Once &AMP; Again'' (March 4) and ``Freaks and Geeks'' (March 11).
Second-season hits will include ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (March 1) and
``That '70s Show'' (March 13) and ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' (March 8). All
series' principles before and behind the camera will be on hand in
each of these events.
</P>
<P>
   The anarchic tykes of ``South Park'' will likewise be enshrined
in a museum event March 3 featuring creators Trey Parker and Matt
Stone as well as other behind-the-scenes talents. Chris Elliott's
cult comedy ``Get a Life,'' about a 30-year-old paperboy still
living with his parents, will be deconstructed March 9. And Fred
Coe, producer of live dramas during TV's golden age, will be
honored March 14. &QL; 
______
</P>
<P>
   All events will be at the Directors Guild of America, 7920
Sunset Blvd., Los Angeles. Tickets are $15 and are on sale to the
general public now at the Museum of Television and Radio, 465 N.
Beverly Drive, Beverly Hills. More information is available from
the festival hot line, (310) 786-1016, or the museum, (310)
786-1000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
