<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CGU-NORWICH-545&AMP;ADD-N     02-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CGU-NORWICH-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BRITISH INSURANCE COMPANIES TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Two of Britain's best-known insurance companies, CGU
PLC and Norwich Union PLC, announced Monday that they would merge
in a $12 billion stock swap that analysts depicted as a shield
against continental European predators.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would create Europe's fifth-largest insurer, with a
market value of around $28.3 billion. That would rank it close in
size to Britain's top insurer, Prudential PLC, but far behind
continental European insurance giants like Allianz of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took a dim view of the news. Norwich Union shares
dropped by as much as 9.8 percent and CGU lost up to 5.7 percent,
reflecting the perception that the absence of a premium offered no
cash reward to institutional investors. That in turn inspired
speculation that the deal could be threatened by a counterbid from
one of the big continental European insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after last year's acquisition of the British insurer
Guardian Royal Exchange by the AXA insurance company of France and
a wave of consolidation in Britain's financial-services market,
``it has long been perceived that the U.K. has been ripe for
another takeover or consolidation of this kind,'' said Chris
Rathbone, an analyst at the Williams de Broe brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Norwich Union shareholders would receive 0.48 of
a share in the new company, to be called CGNU, while CGU
shareholders would receive one new share for each CGU share.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement valued Norwich Union, Britain's fifth-largest
insurer, at 382.3 pence a share, 12 percent less than the price
when markets closed on Friday. The deal would give CGU shareholders
some 58.5 percent of the combined group, while Norwich Union
shareholders would control about 41.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But with both companies' share prices tumbling Monday, ``you
cannot rule out the possibility of a counterbid,'' said Trevor May,
an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The ferment in the insurance business is driven in part by the
prospect of rich pickings in the pensions business, as aging
societies in continental Europe force governments to consider
dismantling elaborate social networks.
</P>
<P>
   The shift towards private pension financing has been under way
much longer in Britain, where insurance companies are seen as
having accumulated valuable expertise coveted by their continental
rivals. At the same time, British companies say they are eyeing new
opportunities in continental Europe that resulted from the shift
away from state pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Scott, the chief executive of CGU, who would become the
chief executive of the combined group, said the merger would give
the new company more power in the growing market in continental
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that combining our resources will enable us to make
a much better job of pushing into the European life and savings
arena,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the merger would cost some $560 million as the two
companies shed some 5,000 of their 70,000 jobs _ 4,000 of them in
Britain _ the deal is expected to create annual savings of $400
million. The merged group will control global premium income and
retail investment sales of some $41.6 billion, with over $320
billion in assets under management, and will rely on life insurance
for 53.7 percent of its premiums.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pace of consolidation is made all the more brisk by intense
competition in Britain for new business, as insurers seek to offset
lower margins on premiums.
</P>
<P>
   That was illustrated Monday when United Assurance Group, a
British insurer with a market value of $2.4 billion, said it was
having talks with Royal London Mutual Insurance Society. The
negotiations could lead to a bid for United, which focuses on
door-to-door sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
