<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIMBS-COX     02-21 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computerized leg anticipates, regulates stride
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stacey Rice's tennis triumphs dangle from her red
equipment bag in the form of Atlanta Lawn Tennis Association
medals. She won them using her quick-pivoting wheelchair, which she
maneuvers with a swing of the hips.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 36-year-old faces an even greater challenge than
wheelchair tennis: playing the game fully upright.
</P>
<P>
   She has just been fitted with a computerized artificial leg that
allows her to bend both knees for ground strokes, put all her
strength behind a serve and slam home a backhand _ things her chair
just wouldn't allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played tennis before I lost my leg, so this stand-up
tennis is going to take some getting used to,'' Rice said Sunday
while hitting a few bright yellow balls with her purple racket, a
Wilson Sledge Hammer. ``My timing is way off. In wheelchair tennis,
the ball bounces twice to give us time to recover. And I'm used to
being lower to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she lost much of her right leg to bone cancer at age 15,
Rice has tackled many new activities: scuba diving, sky diving and
throwing the javelin in the Paralympic Games. Doubles tennis may be
next. What's giving her the chance to step up to the service line
is a new high-tech artificial leg called C-Leg, short for
computerized leg.
</P>
<P>
   Using a microcomputer placed behind the metal kneecap, hydraulic
controls and two tiny motors, the electronic knee of the C-Leg
regulates the rhythm of a wearer's walk and provides resistance
when the knee bends. While other companies make artificial legs
with flexible knees controlled by computerized electronics, the
C-Leg _ made by Otto Bock Orthopedic Industry Inc. _ is the first
system that anticipates and regulates movement, explained Will
Holbrook of Atlanta Prosthetics &AMP; Orthotics in Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time when the heel of the C-Leg touches the ground
until when it touches the heel on that same side again, the
electronic system is moving the knee at the rate of 50 times a
second,'' Holbrook said. Or as a beaming John Bagley said upon
trying out his new leg _ arriving just in time for his 30th
birthday: ``It's like having a prosthetist inside my knee making
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagley, who lives in Bold Springs,Ga., and breeds horses, is
missing his left arm, right leg below the knee and left leg above
the knee. Run over by a train in 1994 while working for a railroad
company, Bagley is believed to be the first triple amputee to use
the new C-Leg. He wears it only on his left leg because his right
leg uses a different type of extension and foot attached to his
remaining knee joint.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, Bagley and Curtis Lee were the first people in the
Southeast _ and among just 30 in the country _ to be fitted with
the C-Leg. They gathered last week at the Atlanta Prosthetics and
Orthotics to have the devices fitted and to attend a two-day
instructional workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel within 15 minutes I was walking better,'' said
Lee, a 23-year-old who lost his lower right leg after a
work-related accident. ``It felt almost normal when I put it on. I
should be able to go down ramps, steps, hills much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lee was one of 200,000 Americans who annually become
amputees, either from trauma, diabetes, infections, birth defects
or other illnesses. About 70 percent undergo leg amputations. The
C-Leg took five years to develop, and does not come cheap. The
total system costs about $50,000. Rice, Lee and Bagley's private
health insurance plans or workman's compensation coverage have all
agreed to pick up the charges. However, many insurance plans are
likely to question the need for such a sophisicated leg because
they ``just want to get amputees back up walking,'' said Larry
Rice, Stacey's husband, who is a prosthetist.
</P>
<P>
   The price is two to three times the cost of the more cumbersome
devices that the threesome were happy to take off for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This old leg, it's pathetic,'' Bagley said. ``This once was
the most high-tech leg on the market but there was only one setting
on it. I wanted to drive a standard transmission but I couldn't.
Now I should be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   The C-Leg will fit an amputee weighing up to 220 pounds. It's
made for active people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do run with it on,'' said Todd Anderson, a prosthetist
and technical manager with Otto Bock. ``They can't sprint. But it
is your 99-percent-of-life-activity leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee then demonstrated one such activity most people never think
twice about.
</P>
<P>
   Step by brick step, he walked down the front stoop of the
prosthetics office. He descended like an able-bodied person, knees
bending and weight shifting, except that he moved more tentatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go step over step,'' Lee said. ``Before, I went down
stairs sideways, with one leg at a time. I haven't been able to go
down like this. But the leg knows what it's doing. Until I put it
on and tried it, I didn't think it was going to be that good.''
</P>
<P>
   A custom-molded socket and suction connect the artificial leg to
a person's remaining upper limb.
</P>
<P>
   Most amputees treat their artificial legs like shoes, taking
them off to sleep and shower. Cosmetic covers are available to make
the device look more realistic, less bionic.
</P>
<P>
   But many amputees, such as Lee, don't care about hiding what
they don't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be open about it and to let people know that I have
an artificial leg,'' said Lee, who sports short, bleached hair and
a gold earring in his left ear. ``Just because you lose a limb,
your life is not over.'' Lee who lives in Jackson County, Ga.,
plans to test his new leg while hunting and fishing near his North
Georgia home.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his new clients raved about the new C-leg, Anderson
threw a reality check to the prosthetists who had just spent two
days learning how to program and adjust it. ``They're still going
to be amputees, and it's still an artificial leg,'' he said. ``It's
not magic. It's not the real thing. It's just a big step up. And it
still needs a person with fortitude and great motivation to use
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One such person is Rice, who is a minivan-driving mom to three
children, ages 9 months to 13 years, in addition to being a skilled
athlete and a coach to kids in the ALTA wheelchair division. To
date, she's gone through eight artificial legs but she thinks she's
finally found one that can keep up with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been an amputee for 21 years and I've seen my share of
prosthetic devices,'' she said while trying the blue, shiny metal
leg on the rolling green slope of her front lawn. ``I did not
believe this could be as good as the videotape showed it to be. But
it is. I have total confidence in this leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
