r e BC-NEWSSTAND22-COX     02-21 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex in the city: It helps sell Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   By Don O'Briant
</P>
<P>
   The March issue of Atlanta ($3.50) features a cover story on the
best lawyers in town, but the most intriguing article is Rebecca
Poynor Burns' expose of the city's sex business. Did you know, for
example, that you have a better chance of living next door to an
exotic dancer than to an employee of the Coca-Cola Co.? And that
the economic impact of nude dance clubs is greater than that of the
Atlanta Braves, the Atlanta Falcons and the Atlanta Hawks combined?
Despite moral protests, some officials say that nude dancing clubs
are the main reason Atlanta is a favorite destination for
conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rappers and rednecks: This month's Talk ($3.50) offers a
smorgasbord of subjects, from Jennifer Lopez and Sean ``Puffy''
Combs to Atlanta comedian Jeff Foxworthy. Why would a woman who has
transformed herself into a Hollywood diva risk it all for Combs?
It's love, she says. Of course, as one Los Angeles producer
observes, ``One false move, and she's Charo.'' In the Foxworthy
article, writer Eddie Dean notes that, although the ``You Might Be
a Redneck'' comedian lives in an exclusive gated community, he
knows his unsophisticated audience. They're the ones, he says,
who've ``got a few hundred dollars in the bank and the car's making
weird noises.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Entertaining politics: The most exciting political story these
days isn't the presidential campaign, but a weekly television
series. Both Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) and Brill's Content
($3.95) devote their covers to ``The West Wing,'' and both conclude
that the show does a better job of presenting a true picture of
political life than most journalists do.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to ``West Wing's'' success is Aaron Sorkin, 38,
a writer who relies on real-life politicos such as former Clinton
Press Secretary Dee Dee Meyers and former Carter administration
pollster Pat Caddell to sharpen the story lines and the dialogue.
Brill's Content writer Matthew Miller singles out a November
episode as an example of how the show teaches viewers about
government. More than one-third of that episode _ almost 15 minutes
_ focused on a plot line that gave a detailed explanation of the
impact of census tabulations. In comparison, Miller writes, the
network news devoted slightly more than two minutes to the census
in all of 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Donald: In his career as a free-lance journalist, Atlanta
writer Tom Junod has hung out with Tony Curtis, shared a bed (sort
of) with Nicole Kidman and seen Mr. Rogers naked. His latest
adventure, as brilliantly reported in Esquire ($3), is spending a
day on the golf course with Donald Trump and Ray Floyd. Trump,
Junod writes, is solicitous of the writer's mother, assigns
nicknames to people he's met only once, and is an incurable
backslapper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Self-interview: Premiere ($3.50) cuts out the middleman in its
cover story about Ben Affleck by letting the actor write about
himself. It's kind of refreshing for a celebrity to admit, as
Affleck does, that he wants to promote his movie ``Reindeer
Games,'' and therefore he has to do interviews with movie
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Art &AMP; Antiques ($4.95) offers a comprehensive
guide to the top treasures of the 20th century, including Dorothy's
ruby slippers in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' the 1964 Ford Mustang,
Jackson Pollock's painting ``Autumn Rhythm,'' Pablo Picasso's
``Three Musicians'' and Ansel Adams' photograph ``Moon Over New
Mexico.'' ... As guest editor for Marie Claire ($2.50), Brooke
Shields agreed to spend the night in an igloo in the Arctic with
her friend Chris Henchy and write about it. Very romantic, but very
cold, she says. ... Jane ($2.50) reports that Hollywood's hottest
health fad is Qi Gong. ``It is a beautiful dance,'' says Qi Gong
enthusiast Michael Stipe. ``A lot of the work I do with Master Liu
is almost like original tai chi.'' Qi Gong (pronounced chee-gong)
is an ancient Chinese philosophy that uses acupuncture, herbs,
exercise, diet and treatments for stress reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
