<HEADLINE>
EUROPE CONCERNED ABOUT MCI-SPRINT MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The European Commission's antitrust
regulators said Monday that they had ``serious concerns'' about the
plans of MCI Worldcom to acquire Sprint Corp. for $130 billion and
that they would carry out an intensive four-month investigation
into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation could easily cause MCI heartburn and may force
it to give up some of its high-speed Internet backbone networks to
satisfy regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In a toughly worded statement from Brussels, Belgium, the
commission's competition ministry said it was worried that the two
companies would control nearly 50 percent of the worldwide market
for Internet backbones _ the main conduits through which Internet
traffic flows before branching off into local connections. The
commission said that MCI controlled 30 percent to 40 percent of
this business and Sprint controlled a further 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said it was also worried about the combined
company's ability to dominate telephone links between the United
States and Europe. And it expressed concern about a merged
company's ability to control most of the market for services to
multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom, in a brief statement Monday, said it would
cooperate with the investigation but was confident that it would
win approval in time to complete the merger this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Though the deal is between two U.S. companies, the European
Commission has frequently invoked its authority to challenge
transactions in which the merging companies have significant
operations in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   When MCI and Worldcom agreed to merge in 1998, the commission
forced MCI to sell overlapping Internet networks. In doing so, it
pushed Worldcom beyond its original settlement proposal and
demanded that the company not try to win back customers from the
networks it had sold.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the competition ministry showed its mettle in
Europe by blocking a three-way multimedia alliance in Germany
involving Bertelsmann, Deutsche Telekom and the Kirch Group of
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the case against MCI Worldcom and Sprint was
hardly straightforward. Sprint has had no meaningful presence in
Europe since it reached an agreement late last month to pull out of
Global One, a joint venture with Deutsche Telekom and France
Telecom that provides networking services for multinational
corporations. France Telecom is buying out both Sprint and Deutsche
Telekom and taking full control of Global One.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sprint does have Internet backbone services in the United
States and elsewhere, it stayed out of Europe precisely because of
its former partnerships with the French and German phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the commission said that Sprint's withdrawal
from Global One was not enough to satisfy its concerns. ``Given the
negligible involvement of Global One in the market for top-level
Internet connectivity,'' the statement said, ``this undertaking
could not remove the serious doubts raised.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Susen Sarkar, a senior analyst at Yankee Group Europe, a
research and consulting firm, said the merger would do little to
change the balance of power in Europe _ particularly given the
rapid construction of high-speed fiber-optic networks by companies
that include Mannesmann of Germany, KPN Qwest of the Netherlands
and Level 3 of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that this sort of concern doesn't really hold
water in the context of all the fiber being put in the ground,''
Sarkar said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tscherney, a spokesman for the competition ministry,
said European regulators had received complaints about the deal
from companies here.
</P>
<P>
   The merger already faces scrutiny in the United States by the
antitrust division of the Justice Department as well as the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   One possible reason for additional European concern is that U.S.
companies continue to dominate the Internet's underlying network
structure. Many European Web sites are operated through computers
in the United States, with the result that much European Internet
traffic makes a round trip across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   While Sprint has little presence in Europe, MCI Worldcom has
already completed much of its pan-European network, called Ulysses.
In addition to providing long-distance fiber-optic networks between
cities, the network links high-speed local networks that serve
corporate customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
