<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-OFFICE-SURFERS-BOS &LR;      02-21 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-SURFERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING WORKERS A GROWING PROBLEM IN OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate crackdowns on personal use of office computers
apparently have not kept employees from trading stocks and shopping
online at work.
</P>
<P>
   A new study shows Americans spent an average of 21 hours online
at work last month _ more than twice the amount they did at home _
partly because their employers offered faster connections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the top 10 Web sites accessed from the office clearly
had nothing to do with work, according to the survey by
Nielsen/NetRatings. They included MyFamily.com, where users can
create a virtual family reunion, and RootsWeb sites, where people
can research their family trees.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the most popular site both at home and at work was eBay,
an auction site offering everything from Beanie Babies to
limousines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is potentially a distraction for people,'' said Allen
Weiner, vice president of analytical services for Nielsen/Net
Ratings.
</P>
<P>
   From their office computers, employees were more likely to shop,
plan vacations, and browse news sites. Investment firms ETrade,
Charles Schwab, and Fidelity Investments showed up on the list of
most popular at-work sites _ evidence that many employees are
trading online during office hours.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which was based on the Internet use of 6,500
employees in January, also found that people were taking advantage
of fast connections at work to download music at MP3 and other Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to adult Internet sites declined during office time.
About 12 percent of users acessed pornographic sites at work,
compared to 23 percent at home. But the amount of time spent ogling
_ four minutes _ remained unchanged at both home and work.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees may not be aware that an increasing number of
companies are monitoring their mouse clicks, online experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, officials at Xerox Corp. of Stamford, Conn., looked
over its employees' shoulders and discovered that some workers were
gambling, trading stocks, and leering at nudes online. Forty
employees were fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were spending two to four hours a day on
nonbusiness-related Internet sites,'' Xerox spokeswoman Christa
Carone said. ``At the end of the day, they weren't getting their
work done.''
</P>
<P>
   But some workers, especially those at technology and start-up
firms, believe long work hours entitle them to personal Internet
use on the job. And they believe their employers will overlook
their cyberslacking as long as it does not affect productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know (the rules), but they don't believe they're doing
anything wrong,'' said Dr. Kimberly Young, executive director of
the Center for Online Addiction. ``They're just answering personal
e-mail or making plans for vacation. It seems harmless.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees, however, can't seem to put the brakes on their
personal Internet use. An Oregon public official, for instance, was
fired for spending too much time on eBay's auction site, Young
said. She had begun by selling jewelry online but became obsessed
about checking on bids and reading what other eBay users had said
about her in reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, like hers, it started off as a little side
business,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a way to eliminate Internet abuse, some companies are
using software to filter out gambling and adult sites, among
others. But before blocking a Web site, employers should ask
themselves whether they're actually making workers more productive,
online experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather have a person taking out their checkbook and
paying their bills for an hour or have them spend 10 minutes doing
them online?'' asked Weiner of NetRatings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
