<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HAMBURG-BOOM-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMBURG IN BID TO BE ECONOMIC HUB BETWEEN EAST AND WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV:  map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Germany _ Hunting for the boom that never happened in
post-Cold War Berlin? Try this handsome port city that purrs with
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The boutiques _ from home-grown Jil Sander to Gianni Versace,
the cranes hoisting an enlarged port into being, the plans for a
vast new downtown on a former dockland area, the rising tide of
internet companies: all this speaks of boomtown Hamburg and of a
Germany still resisting the appeal of Berlin, its new capital.
</P>
<P>
   The theory when the Berlin Wall came down in 1989 was that
German industry would return to Berlin, a city it largely abandoned
in 1945, and that the bourgeoisie that Hitler's war decimated there
would be partially reconstituted. Instead, what the last decade has
confirmed is postwar Germany's deep attachment to a decentralized
federalism.
</P>
<P>
   That is evident nowhere more than in Hamburg. Its growth in
recent years suggests that Berlin, for all its dreams of being a
``Weltstadt'' or world-class city, will never enjoy the dominance
over Germany that Paris and London exercise over France and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is booming because it has recovered its hinterland
since the Cold War's end,'' said Theo Sommer, the executive editor
of the influential Hamburg-based weekly Die Zeit. ``By comparison,
Berlin's development seems lethargic.''
</P>
<P>
   That hinterland is Central Europe, which was unnaturally cut off
from Hamburg by the Iron Curtain, a mere 20 miles to the east. Now
the city is once again the major port of Prague, up the River Elbe,
and the old trading links of the Hanseatic League have been
re-established with towns like Gdansk in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, container traffic at the port has increased to over
77 million tons from 55 million five years ago. Projected growth is
so strong that a new port area is being built and the Elbe River
deepened at a cost of $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1989, we won back our neighbors on the Elbe river,'' said
Mayor Ortwin Runde, a Social Democrat. ``Trade between Germany and
the Central European states that have emerged from communism is now
bigger than with the United States. As the port for more than 20
percent of German exports, we have naturally benefited.''
</P>
<P>
   In the neo-Renaissance city hall, the offices of the Chamber of
Commerce adjoin Runde's office. Nothing could more eloquently
express the fierce attachment of this city to trade, its feeling of
looking outward to the world rather than inward to an often
despondent Germany. And it does not look only to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains in London, the umbrellas go up in Hamburg,''
goes an old saying here. It reflects the city's sense of closeness
to the British capital, with which it shares a taste for
discretion, an intense pragmatism and an evident openness.
</P>
<P>
   Among the statistics that Riesling-sipping Hamburg businessmen
like to spout over plates of succulent sole is the fact that no
other city, apart from New York, has more than 90 consulates. The
consulates, of course, serve trade.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is a country of both merchant cities and court cities.
Among the former, Hamburg is joined by places like Cologne and
Leipzig. The latter include Berlin and Dresden, places where past
tragedy weighs heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Although no German town has escaped this country's 20th-century
trauma _ Hamburg was heavily bombed in World War II _ it often
seems that the practical bent of the trading towns has enabled them
to heal their wounds faster.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's repetitive bluster about becoming the new capital of
``middle Europe'' has remained unbacked by much solid evidence even
as Hamburg has moved fast to exploit new opportunities to the east.
Unemployment in the port city has fallen to 9.6 percent, from 12.6
percent, over the past two years; in Berlin it has remained at
about 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The most startling sign of Hamburg's confidence is a $10-billion
development called Harbor City, planned on about 250 acres south of
the city center where old dockland warehouses now stand.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 20 years, the warehouses are to be replaced by
office space for more than 20,000 people, a terminal for luxury
cruisers, hotels, theaters, stores and several thousand apartments.
Construction begins this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bernd Tiedeman, the managing director of the project, said it
sums up ``Hamburg's new ambitions after unification.'' In his
vision, cruise ships will dock here bringing tourists who will then
go on excursions as far away as Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of Hamburg as a gateway to Berlin may seem
far-fetched, but if a long-planned high-speed train is ever built,
the capital will be only 60 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile it is a measure of the continuing isolation of the
capital _ deprived of its port by Poland's absorption of Szczecin
(the former German Stettin) after World War II, and still lacking a
direct flight to the United States _ that Hamburg may reasonably
see itself as a center from which to visit Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Berlin looks east, Munich looks south, and we look to
the west, which is where things are really happening for now,''
said Frank Sarfeld, the spokesman for America Online Europe, whose
headquarters are in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   He had a large muffin on his cluttered desk and a plate of ice
cream _ ``I only eat at my desk'' _ as he gazed at three television
screens providing news and stock prices. On his wall was a strategy
chart mapping out ``Operation Steady Drumbeat,'' a plan to keep AOL
Europe in the news by providing a relentless stream of press
releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of new media is coming here, because this is where the
old media companies are and the spirit is right,'' Sarfeld said.
``But with everyone looking for the same information-technology
people, you have to have a good stock-option program. That's a
must.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock options were certainly not in the thoughts of the Allies
when, in 1946, they gave licenses in Hamburg to two of the first
postwar German newspapers _ Die Welt and Die Zeit. But they did
have in mind a decentralized Germany where no city could be as
dominant as Hitler's Berlin. In this strategic design their success
now seems conspicuous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
