<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-KOSOVO-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-21 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KOSOVO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRONTLINE': BEHIND MILITARY INTERVENTION IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About a year ago the United States and its NATO
allies found themselves involved in a war in Kosovo that continues
with little prospect of peace or of the West's extrication. Tuesday
night and next week ``Frontline'' on PBS offers ``War in Europe,''
a sharply drawn two-hour account of how the allies embarked on
NATO's military conflict and the shaky way in which it was fought.
</P>
<P>
   The program reports that the main American voice in behalf of
intervention belonged to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
champion of what the narrator, Peter J. Boyer, calls a doctrine of
``virtuous power.'' She ran up against a president distracted by
his Monica Lewinsky troubles and a Congress disinclined to risk
American lives in a distant cause. But the train of bloody events
in the Balkans, of provocation and repression, forced the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Policy makers and players tell the story of Western diplomats
caught between the Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army, determined to
win independence from Yugoslavia, and Serbs led by Slobodan
Milosevic, who had already gained a reputation as ``Europe's most
ruthless man.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton committed what Tuesday night's critics call a
fundamental error by announcing that the United States would not
send in ground troops. But television images of Serbian killings
and the forced exodus of 50,000 Albanians into the hills as winter
threatened increased the pressure on the West.
</P>
<P>
   Finally NATO began bombing the Serbs. But even here the NATO
powers proved divided and indecisive. Gen. Michael C. Short,
leading the bombing campaign, reports that his political allies
repeatedly told him, ``Our parliament won't allow us to strike that
target.'' A message of ``War in Europe'' is that military strength
without political determination is an undependable weapon.
</P>
<P>
   With the Serbs still resisting despite increased bombing,
Clinton, under pressure from Britain's prime minister, Tony Blair,
allowed that Western ground troops might be used and with the
intervention of Russia, a deal was struck to end the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With allied troops now assigned indefinitely to Kosovo to stop
the sort of clashes that have occurred between Serbs and Albanians
lately, no one is claiming a great victory for ``virtuous power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
