<SLUG> BC-CANADA-INVEST-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-CANADA SECURITIES AGREEMENT MAY BE CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ In the last nine years, Canadian companies have raised
about $153 billion through debt and equity issues in the United
States, usually with little screening by the Securities and
Exchange Commission in Washington, because their filing documents
had already been approved by Canada's provincial regulators.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement that is unique to Canada and the United States,
known as the multijurisdictional disclosure system, has allowed
issuers of Canadian securities to file in the United States
quickly, saving enormous amounts of money and time. But their
advantage, they fear, could soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The threat lies in proposals first made by U.S. securities
regulators in 1998 for revising the registration system. The SEC
questioned whether Canada should have an edge that other major U.S.
trading partners _ Japan, Mexico, members of the European Union _
do not.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mandel, a Canadian lawyer with the New York firm of
Morrison &AMP; Foerster, who specializes in underwritings for Canadian
companies in the United States, said the SEC regulators had simply
raised the question of whether the U.S.-Canadian agreement made
sense, and ``the implicit answer was that the SEC did not think
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Bamberger, an SEC spokeswoman, said that the proposed
changes and industry comments were still under review and that no
decision had been made on the existing arrangement with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides automatic clearance by the SEC for
securities documents prepared in Canada and accepted by local
regulators, if information required by the SEC is included. That
means companies prepare one share-offering prospectus or takeover
offer or continuous disclosure filing, not two.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about the longevity of this arrangement began to grow
only after the Ontario Securities Commission, in a memo last
September, drew the SEC's own question about it to the attention of
Toronto's investment community. So over the last few months,
Canadian issuers have written dozens of letters to the SEC, hoping
to persuade the agency to keep the registration agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the registration agreement was once regarded as the wave
of the future, coming into effect along with the North American
Free Trade Agreement, some Canadians wonder why the SEC might be
backtracking. Toronto investment dealers point to securities
scandals _ Bre-X, YBM Magnex, Livent Entertainment _ as a big
reason that U.S. securities regulators have lost some faith in
their Canadian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware of that perception,'' said Kathryn Soden,
director of corporate finance for the Ontario Securities
Commission, ``but that's not what we have been told.''
</P>
<P>
   In discussions between the Canadian and U.S. securities
regulators, Soden said, ``the focus has been that this is a
philosophical shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the SEC's reasoning _ there are indications that it
wants to act this spring _ Canada's securities industry would be
shaken by the loss of the registration agreement. A few
underwriters said it would prove beneficial because more effort
would go into raising money at home. But Canada's capital markets
lack the scope of those in the United States, so the optimists are
a minority.
</P>
<P>
   The majority view is that corporate issuers will lose
flexibility on timing, that lawyers and other advisers will lose
business to their U.S. counterparts, and that underwriters and
stock exchanges will lose new financings and listings. Even with
the registration agreement, there is growing concern about the
number of fledgling high-technology companies that bypass Canadian
underwriters and exchanges to go public with offerings only in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of two filings is not a big problem for senior issuers,
but the time it could take to get full SEC approval is a concern.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David Chaikof, a partner in Torys, a law firm in Toronto and New
York, said the SEC clears the way for a Canadian company's U.S.
financing in five days if it comes with the Ontario Securities
Commission's stamp. A separate filing by a foreign company can take
up to 60 days _ long enough to ruin a deal in a volatile market.
Mergers and acquisitions through share exchanges that involve
shareholders in the United States will face similar delays, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaikof is among those who hope the registration agreement is
not scrapped. ``Losing it would be more costly, more time-consuming
and less efficient,'' he said. ``If there's not enough review now,
maybe there is some intelligent action that can be taken, short of
abolishing the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
