<SLUG> BC-TV-LETTERMAN-RETURNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERMAN RETURNS, TRUE TO FORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During David Letterman's much-publicized return to
his ``Late Show'' Monday night after quintuple-bypass surgery and a
five-week break, he walked onstage looking a little gaunt, but
immediately bent over to touch his toes. Later Robin Williams came
out in a surgical costume, carrying a cooler marked ``Human
Organs.'' (Michael Jackson's old nose and one of Cher's ribs were
inside, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   Letterman got a little choked up while introducing his surgical
team, though he did not get nearly as emotional (at least not on
the edited version) as reports from Friday's taping suggested. Yet
the most telling moment came early, when Jerry Seinfeld walked out
briefly during the monologue, looked at him and said casually, ``I
thought you were dead.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the same line Seinfeld used during his guest appearance
two weeks ago on ``Late Show Backstage,'' the shows that combined
old clips with new introductions during Letterman's absence. On
one, Charles Grodin said, ``Dave is faking, he never had an octuple
bypass.'' Seinfeld said, ``I thought Dave was dead,'' and the
entire enterprise fit seamlessly into the sharp, unsentimental tone
that ``Late Show'' thrives on.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's first night back worked in a similar way. It was not
outlandish or the slightest bit mawkish. It was, instead, true to
form, which is higher praise. He was clearly touched when he
brought on his doctors and nurses, introducing them one by one.
``It was five weeks ago today that these men and women saved my
life,'' he said. But he injected lightness into every introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Michelangelo with a bone saw,'' he said of the doctor who
cut him open, and concluded of the whole team, ``I couldn't be more
proud when these guys carved their initials in me.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained how bypass surgery was different from a simple
bypass. ``A bypass is what happened to me when I didn't get the
`Tonight' show,'' he said. That fleeting reference highlights the
difference between Letterman, who remains the master of the
late-night form, and Jay Leno, whose ``Tonight'' show is worth
watching only during the monologue.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman even got in a snide Clinton joke. Referring to the
highly rated appearance by Hillary Rodham Clinton during his
next-to-last show before the surgery, he said: ``I have a whole new
respect for President Clinton. I spent a half an hour with Hillary,
half an hour, and look what happened to  &UR; me &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he never wants her back on. But after her appearance,
which came after a very funny series of on-air offers and
negotiations, he had already moved on to a new project: getting
Gov. George W. Bush to appear. ``He's a pinhead, isn't he?''
Letterman asked his band leader, Paul Shaffer, at the time. Even
the targets of his jokes may have something to gain by turning up.
</P>
<P>
   During his many guest appearances, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
seemed to be a guy with a sense of humor about himself, contrary to
every other media appearance he has ever made. Letterman is
endlessly irreverent about politicians behind their backs and
perfectly respectful when they show up in person, which puts his
audience in a winning position.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman will appear three nights a week at first, returning on
Wednesday with Julia Roberts as his guest. (Bill Cosby will be the
guest host Tuesday night and, unfathomably, Kathie Lee Gifford on
Thursday.) Last night, the guests were much less the point than the
host. Regis Philbin, who had appeared on the last show before
Letterman's operation and had an eerily prescient conversation
about heart surgery, was introduced as ``the last man to see me
alive.'' When Philbin said how much Letterman had been missed, the
host laughed, ``It's surprising that people would miss me, isn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   The front-page attention his surgery got was surprising. But if
the well-orchestrated publicity for Letterman's return has worked,
it's because ``Late Show'' had achieved such a high level before he
left, and he seems to have picked up right there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
