<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-JOBCUTS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA LOSES JOBS BUT STILL NEEDS HIGH-TECH WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANNE BERRYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The layoff announcements seemed to be coming in waves.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp. said it would cut 800 workers beyond 2,000
who lost their jobs last year. BellSouth announced that it was
eliminating 1,300 jobs. Worst of all, Coca-Cola, long a bulwark of
the economic and social scene here, said last month that it was
laying off 2,500 workers _ 40 percent of its Atlanta work force.
</P>
<P>
   In a front-page article, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution asked,
``Is something going wrong?'' The question echoed widespread
worries that Atlanta's economy was in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A broad consensus of economists, government officials and
businessmen here believe, however, that if Atlanta's economy has
run into a rough patch, it is not because there is a shortage of
jobs. To the contrary, they say, there is a lack of people to fill
them, particularly in technology.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts have received wide publicity. But in reality they
are not having a major impact on the job market, with unemployment
hovering just above 2.5 percent. The job losses make a splash, said
David Echols, a Georgia Department of Labor statistician, ``but the
ripple is never going to make it to the shoreline.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ratacjak, a Georgia State University economist, said:
``It's going to hurt. But we think that Atlanta will still be a
significant job generator for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Atlanta created 113,600 jobs, more than any other
major metropolitan area in the nation. By comparison, metropolitan
New York, defined as New York City plus Putnam, Rockland and
Westchester counties, created 105,600 jobs in 1999, said Mike Wald,
regional economist for the Department of Labor. New York City alone
created 92,100 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, 15,000 technology workers are needed, said Sam A.
Williams, president of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce, even
though the ``dot-coms and telecommunications companies in Atlanta
added more than 30,000 workers'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talent-starved,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even with the layoffs, the chamber is running
advertisements in college newspapers at Rutgers University, Harvard
University, New York University and other schools around the
nation, as well as reaching out to students with its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The ads beckon the young to fast-paced fun and work in Atlanta,
where they can ``live in the current.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent news about the city has not been entirely positive,
however. In addition to the layoffs, Atlanta's battle with urban
sprawl has been the subject of news reports, along with the seamier
side of local night life after the pro football star Ray Lewis was
charged along with two other men in two stabbing deaths here the
morning after last month's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials are keeping a distance from the
employment issues. Gov. Roy Barnes is concerned about the hardship
for workers making transitions to other positions, said Henry
Thomassen, the governor's economic adviser. ``There is, of course,
nothing we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell has issued no public statements concerning
the job cuts, his spokesman confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Cardoza, commissioner for the Georgia Department of
Industry, Trade and Tourism, said each company had ``good solid
reasons for doing what they did.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's a little hard to interfere with the decisions that
corporate America has any right to make,'' Cardoza said.
``Everybody from a personal standpoint is very sorry for the people
who are losing their jobs.'' Not all of the workers will have
skills to match those needed for technology positions, Cardoza
said.
</P>
<P>
   For many laid-off employees at Coca-Cola, this is an extremely
painful time. Few have been willing to talk publicly about it.
``All my friends are being let go,'' said one employee who has
worked for the company for 20 years and who spoke only on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   She worries about a laid-off worker in his late 40s. ``Who's
going to hire him?'' she asked. She also worries about women who
have become their family's primary breadwinners. ``They have
$200,000 to $300,000 homes and they don't have jobs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Jacobi, 32, laid off Tuesday after two years as a Coca-Cola
marketing manager, said: ``I want to stay in Atlanta because of my
wife. I'm hoping to find a decent job here. So, we'll see. It's a
strong economy. If ever there were a time to be laid off, it's
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
