u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-21 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: REMEMBERING A GEORGE FOR ALL SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy Washington's Birthday! Tuesday we celebrate the career of
a George who became first in the hearts of his countrymen without
conducting a single town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, by the way, was actually born on Feb. 11, not 22. In
1752 Britain and its colonies jumped ahead 11 days in order to get
their calendar in sync with the rest of Europe. After that, he was
never entirely certain about his birthdate, or even birth year,
since the Americans also shifted New Year's Day from March 25 to
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Excuse me, but why in the world are you telling me all this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I just thought it would be a nice millennial touch.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Uh-huh. Actually, I was hoping you'd explain how the Bush
campaign managed to spend $50 million so fast.
</P>
<P>
   A: George W. Bush was asked that very question last week. He
told reporters that ``We have a plan in place,'' and also that
``We're on the plan.'' He went on to say that his campaign had
``got a plan,'' which was ``a broad plan'' and ``a plan that's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So in other words, it's a plan.
</P>
<P>
   A: The official theory is that the Bush campaign cannily and
deliberately threw all its resources into smashing John McCain in
South Carolina, confident that it would still be able to raise
heaps more money later on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the unofficial theory?
</P>
<P>
   A: Contrarians believe that Bush, like Al Gore before him, fell
victim to the Law of Financial Leakage, which dictates that a
candidate's assets will quickly come into equilibrium with
supporters' desire to spend them. Cynics refer to this as the
District Chairmen With Unemployed Relatives Rule, and it is far
more effective than the Federal Election Commission in leveling out
the presidential playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you tried that out on the Bush campaign people?
</P>
<P>
   A: They prefer it to the Gramm-Connally Law, which states that
presidential candidates who emerge from Texas bearing pots and pots
of money inevitably come to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is George Bush really a completely different candidate now?
How do you get a middle-aged man to change himself so fast?
</P>
<P>
   A: Stylistically, Bush has simply adopted the Al Gore tactic of
demonstrating his sincerity by raising his voice. But while Gore
likes to yell out entire sentences, Bush simply goes for every
other noun. (``The people of THIS STATE can start the end of the
CLINTON ERA in Washington D.C.'')
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you remind me again what compassionate conservatism is?
</P>
<P>
   A: To quote Bush: ``It is conservative to lower taxes. It is
compassionate to give the money back to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you lowered taxes, who else would you give the money back
to?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hey, you can't claim the low road from a high horse. We're
talking about reducing the toll booth to the middle class and
demolishing the tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How come when the other candidates are fuzzy on an issue,
reporters say they're ``ducking,'' but when John McCain does it
they say he's ``evolving''?
</P>
<P>
   A: When reporters point out contradictions in his positions,
Senator McCain often says, ``That's a good point, I'll have to
think about that.'' This is what we call evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How come he got whomped in South Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   A: Look, it's an unusual place. Half of American history
involves efforts to get South Carolina to stop acting out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw the Democrats had a debate last night. Whatever
happened to that primary?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some say John McCain sucked the air out of Bill Bradley's
campaign. My own theory is that Bradley's troubles began when women
realized that he sounds a lot like an extremely pompous husband
pretending to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does he still have a chance?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bradley is trying to re-start his campaign even as we speak.
He says the state of Washington could be the firewall that stops Al
Gore in his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Say what?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's the plan, and if it keeps the race alive until my
state gets a chance to vote, let there be firewalls. The Washington
primary, by the way, is on Feb. 29. Have I mentioned that, because
of calendric reforms initiated by Pope Gregory XIII, this is the
first '00 leap year since 1600?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
