<HEADLINE>
MISSING SKIER, 10, FOCUSED ON RESCUE, NOT COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY AND DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERVILLE VALLEY, N.H. _ Lost Sunday night on a pitch-black
mountainside covered with snow drifts up to 7 feet, a frightened
10-year-old Ryan Lanagan fought off thoughts of death by convincing
himself rescuers were nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 hours later, the young skier was found _ a wet and
hungry fourth-grader waving desperately at a Black Hawk helicopter
who had just spotted him with an infrared scope.
</P>
<P>
   After a mug of hot chocolate following his rescue Monday
morning, the 85-pound boy, missing only skis and mittens, was
declared physically fine and released to his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dark and I was scared,'' said an exhausted Ryan Monday,
his voice still scratchy and raw from the adventure in 10-15 degree
temperatures. He had trudged for hours in chest-high snow. ``I laid
down in the snow and got all wet and cold...but I knew they would
come for me. Then the men came and they gave me a peanut butter
sandwich and I kept saying, `Thank you for finding me. Thank you
for finding me.' I was really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a 100 rescue workers broke out in cheers when Ryan was
brought down the mountain in a sled shortly after 9 a.m. Monday.
Many skiers celebrating the start of school vacation had offered to
help look for the boy, but authorities declined, fearing they too
would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of rescue workers mobilized as soon as Ryan's parents
reported him missing around 6 p.m. Working through the night on
foot and skis and with dogs and infrared devices, the group scoured
the mountain twice, the base camp and town. Helicopters that were
prevented from searching for the boy because of bad weather Sunday
night joined the search at daybreak Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just grabbed him and hugged him and told him I loved him,''
said Tom Lanagan, Ryan's father, after the boy was brought down the
mountain. ``This is awesome...he said he knew we'd find him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan became lost after he took a shuttle bus to the slopes from
the vacation condo his family had rented. Ryan was to meet his
father at the bottom of the White Peak lift, rescuers said. But
bored or eager to ski one last time, he took the lift up.
</P>
<P>
   After finding only strangers at the top of the mountain, Ryan _
a solid skier _ turned right to go down the trail. After starting
down, he went over the left hand edge and into the trees. He fell,
and because of the deep snow, he decided to walk down.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan didn't realize he was descending farther and farther
into the valley _ and away from the ski resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got thick so I took my skis off and started walking down
and I got almost to the bottom and thought it wouldn't end,'' Ryan
said Monday, after taking a nap with his mother for more than two
hours. Usually rambunctious, Ryan was low-keyed Monday, family
members said. ``I started walking up but I got really tired and
just fell asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of his rescue, Ryan had awoken at 8 a.m., he told
rescuer Robert Eames, one of the first workers to reach him. When
Eames asked Ryan how he knew the time, the boy considered the
question and then said calmly ``Well, it could have been quarter to
eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers praised the boy for having the sense to stay calm
and in one place. Ryan found a small trail of packed snow, stuck to
it and fell asleep on it. He was found about 150 yards off the
Tangent Trail and about three-quarters of the way up the mountain,
rescuers estimated.
 heard the helicopters during the night and knew they were
there. I woke up and started waving at them and then the men showed
up,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he remembered what to do through an outdoor survival
program his older brother went through at Old Rochester Junior
High: How he shouldn't waste energy. How he should try to stay in
one place.
</P>
<P>
   He was also dressed well, rescue workers said: a burnt orange
and black ski parka, blue ski pants, a black helmet and layers
underneath. He was skiing on short, double-ended skis.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's father, Tom, said he cannot begin to properly thank
rescue workers from the state police, Waterville police, New
Hampshire Fish and Game, the National Guard and others.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Day, the resort's general manager, arranged for the family
to use a condo during the rescue. Debbie Moore, another worker at
the resort, comforted Ryan's mother, Laura, through the night.
Monday night, the family met with rescue workers at a local
restaurant to thank them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lanagan has been skiing with his wife and three children
every weekend in Waterville this year, along with about five other
families. They spent much of last winter there as well. No one
thought twice about having Ryan meet his dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course now, you kick yourself for having them ski alone,
especially that time of day,'' said Tom Lanagan. ``And he was
trying to catch up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Eames said there have been deaths on the mountain in the
last 35 years, he cannot recall anyone getting lost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Waterville and Tom Lanagan said the happy ending to
what could have been a tragic tale contains a warning for parents:
Just because ski areas look safe, they are still in the middle of
the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think parents...go to ski resorts that are perfectly groomed
and they get this sense of security,'' said Waterville deputy
police chief Al Burbank. ``Take heart...this is the wilderness and
if kids get separated it's no different than getting lost on a
hiking trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ryan says he can't wait to hit the slopes again. He
may take a day off. But he expects to be skiing again Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
