<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-PIONEER-SHAKEUP-BOS &LR;      02-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIONEER-SHAKEUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSIDENTS TO PRESS FOR SHAKEUP OF PIONEER GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After two years of trying to keep its troubles inside
the family, Pioneer Group Inc. appears headed for a shakeup led by
outside investors.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund group two weeks ago hired investment bankers to
review its strategic options, including a possible sale of the
company. But Lens Investment Management, a high-profile activist
investor group, says that's not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   In a release, Lens called Pioneer's announcement ``superficial
and disappointing.'' The Portland, Maine, investment firm declared,
``We plan to to press the company to take more aggressive steps to
increase shareholder value. We're exploring stronger actions.''
</P>
<P>
   What's stronger than mulling a sale? That could become clearer
this week, as Lens is expected to lay out its recommendations for
Pioneer. Lens is run by Bob Monks, a former top executive of the
Boston Co. who later did a stint overseeing pension plans in
President Reagan's Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   Lens has quietly become a significant _ but not dominant _
shareholder in Pioneer, acquiring about 4.1 percent of the stock
late last year. That's dwarfed by a 17.9 percent stake held by
Southeastern Asset Management Inc. of Memphis and 8.9 percent owned
by the Gabelli funds.
</P>
<P>
   There's also Pioneer's chairman, Hale and Dorr partner John F.
Cogan Jr., who holds 13.6 percent of the stock, according to a
recent securities filing.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer seems to be courting the favor of its biggest investor.
The firm named Southeastern Asset's retired cofounder, W. Reid
Sanders, 50, to its board this month, in one of three new director
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   David Tripple, president of Pioneer's mutual fund unit, said
expanding the board is ``all part of good corporate governance.''
He said the director seat for Southeastern had been a ``standing
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripple said Southeastern, which runs the Longleaf Partners
funds, has ``made good money'' on its Pioneer investment. That's no
small claim. Pioneer shares slumped 20.3 percent in 1999 after
diving 30 percent in 1998. This year they've climbed back 13.5
percent, to 17 7/8 at Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund analysts have long regarded Pioneer, one of the
industry's oldest fund firms, as a buyout candidate, because of its
modest size. The firm manages $24.5 billion worldwide, up less than
5 percent in a year when stock markets soared.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer's value-investing style has been a competitive problem
in a market in which fast-growth Internet stocks have dominated.
Geoffrey Bobroff, an independent fund consultant in East Greenwich,
R.I., said Pioneer entirely missed the growth surge of the late
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've added a couple of growth funds, but it's been a slow
grind for them,'' Bobroff said. ``Hopefully the purpose here is to
refocus the company.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pioneer, 1999 was a year of shrinking ambitions. The fund
firm had once hoped to build a portfolio of far-flung businesses,
from a Ghanaian gold mine and a Polish brokerage to Russian bank
and timber operations.
</P>
<P>
   It has now closed the once-profitable gold mine, after failing
to sell it. The Polish brokerage was sold, but Pioneer is still
losing money on its pension unit in Poland. The company lost $2
million on Russian timber last year. Its Russian bank became
corrupt and was shut down in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nagging problems, Tripple insists the company is on
its way to a turnaround. The fourth quarter marked its first profit
since early 1998. The question is whether investors want to wait
for improvements that could boost a sale price for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tripple, ``If we wanted to sell the company, we'd have gone
out and cut a deal with somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Lens may not sit idly by and wait for that to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
