<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News has moved the following feature
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients on Tuesday, Feb.
22, 2000. For questions about stories, please contact Steven
Rosenberg at the Daily News, (818) 713-3752.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-MARTIN-GUERRE _ Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel
Schonberg _ big-time Broadway writers of ``Les Miserables'' and
``Miss Saigon'' _ are downsizing the imperial scale of their
previous productions for ``Martin Guerre,'' the oft-told legend of
a 16th-century French soldier who returns home claiming to be
another man. The show that began in London's West End is now coming
to L.A. as the last stop on a national tour. What about Broadway?
It isn't going there ... and that's a whole 'nother story. By Reed
Johnson (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   TV-FESTIVAL _ The Museum of Television and Radio's annual
William S. Paley Television Festival brings the people behind the
medium together for panel discussions, offering a mix of genuinely
classic television, some series too new for the participants to
offer much cultural perspective, and outright padding. Thankfully
there's less padding this year, with the festival including
tributes to Garry Shandling, ``MASH,'' ``The Carol Burnett Show,''
``Outer Limits,'' ``The West Wing,'' ``Once &AMP; Again,'' ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' ``That '70s Show,'' and ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg.'' Other guests include ``South Park'' creators Trey Parker
and Matt Stone and ``Get a Life'' star Chris Elliott. By David
Kronke (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   HOME-THEMES _ The latest trend in home decorating is theme
rooms, with Disney character adorning the walls, a school of fish
on the bathroom walls and under the guise of soap dishes, towel
racks and the like, NASCAR-themed furnishings and more. By Evan
Henerson (moved on the ``e'' entertainment and ``l'' lifestyle
wires). ART moving to NYTNS clients.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE-THEATER _ For many doctors, bedside manner isn't high
on their list of skills, but a drama called ``Wit,'' written by an
elementary school teacher and currently on stage at the Geffen
Playhouse in Westwood, contains multiple lessons for doctors,
patients, students and teachers about how people in the medical
field should treat their patients. By Evan Henerson (moved on the
``l'' lifestyle wire).
