<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-B     02-21 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX SCRUBS `MULTIMILLIONAIRE' AMID CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fox network, mired in an embarrassing controversy over the
background of the first groom featured on ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'', has hastily scrubbed plans to air future
episodes of the ratings blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be going forward with any of these specials
in the future,'' a Fox spokesman, Tom Tyrer, said in an interview
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's abrupt abandonment of ``Multimillionaire,'' whose live TV
nuptials of complete strangers drew nearly 23 million viewers when
it aired last Tuesday night, vividly illustrates the risks inherent
in ``reality programming,'' a lurid format the networks have
embraced in a quest for smaller costs and larger audiences.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy blew up in Fox's face when it was reported that
42-year-old Rick Rockwell, the first ``multimillionaire'' to appear
on the program, had been the subject of a restraining order
obtained in 1991 by an ex-fiancee who had alleged in court
documents that Rockwell had assaulted and threatened her.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell denied the allegations to reporters Monday, saying:
``At no time have I ever struck any of my girlfriends, ever, for
any reason.'' But the old charges were enough to sink
``Multimillionaire'' just one week after it emerged as one of the
phenomena of the current TV season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' offered a two-hour
spectacle of women parading onstage in bathing suits and wedding
gowns while Rockwell, seated in shadows, made his choice: Darva
Conger, a 34-year-old emergency room nurse from Santa Monica,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, a veteran standup comedian who has performed in Boston
and who now describes himself as a real estate developer, proposed
to Conger on bended knee. The pair were married and left for a
Caribbean honeymoon, from which they returned Monday. Conger could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Even by the standards of sweeps-period stunts,
``Multimillionaire'' was viewed as extreme. But in ratings terms,
it was a coup for Fox, which had planned to rerun the program
Tuesday until controversy over Rockwell's past erupted.
``Multimillionaire'' ignited plenty of water-cooler buzz after its
Tuesday broadcast, and it touched off a national debate about
gender relations, with op-ed columns and newsmagazines weighing in.
</P>
<P>
   One person who wasn't sorry to hear the death knell for
``Multimillionaire'' is Patricia Ireland, president of the National
Organization for Women, who cracked last week that ``it took
something like this to make the Miss America pageant look good to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Boston Globe, Ireland said the program
``portrayed marriage as if it were no more important than a blind
date . . . It portrayed the most retro and regressive stereotypes
of women and men. It was women competing for a man based on their
looks and charm, and all they needed to know about him was his
money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it, my next question was: `How long is it before
they're going to want to show the honeymoon?' '' Ireland added. ``
`Who Wants to Honeymoon with a Millionaire?' This time, at least,
we had the fadeout before the honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the ``Multimillionaire'' debacle begin the fadout for
``reality'' programs? Few analysts think so.
</P>
<P>
   J. Max Robins, a columnist for TV Guide, said reality programs
are likely to survive because they tap into ``voyeuristic side of
viewers,'' though he predicted the networks will be ``a little more
careful in how they set it up, and police themselves a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rash, senior vice president at the Minneapolis-based
advertising agency Campbell Mithun Esty, also sees no end in sight.
``For right now, the networks are more than willing to risk
short-term embarrassment for even shorter-term ratings gain,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings gains can be dramatic. ABC's ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire,'' which kicked off the current craze, displaced NBC's
``ER'' as the most-watched show on television, drawing more than 30
million viewers and singlehandedly pulling ABC out of the ratings
doldrums. Likewise, ``WWF Smackdown!'', a low-brow wrestling show,
has almost resuscitated the UPN network.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks have taken note, and are developing ``reality''
programs of their own for the months ahead. Normally sedate CBS
plans to devote 13 weeks this summer to ``Survivor,'' a ``Lord of
the Flies''-like program in which 16 contestants will be stranded
on a remote island in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, one contestant is kicked off the island by a vote of
the others. The final contestant left wins a cash prize. In a
version of ``Survivor'' that aired in Sweden, one contestant
committed suicide after he was eliminated from the program.
</P>
<P>
   CBS also plans to air ``Big Brother,'' which throws a dozen
strangers together in a house and records their every move with
cameras and microphones; viewers can look in on them, night or day,
on the Internet. A syndicated show called ``Wed at First Sight''
will debut this fall, featuring a marriage per day.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Darnell, the Fox executive behind ``Multimillionaire,'' has
earned big ratings with such specials as ``When Good Pets Go Bad.''
It was Darnell who proposed last year that Fox crash an empty plane
on live TV _ an idea the network rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox is not likely to forswear reality programs altogether.
The network was trying Monday to figure out what had gone wrong.
Sources said contestants for ``Multimillionaire'' had undergone a
lengthy screening process, including a background check, but that
the screening had failed to discover the restraining order against
Rockwell because he had not been convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The network concluded, sources said, that it was best to
discontinue ``Multimillionaire'' because it is impossible to learn
every aspect of a contestant's background and potential behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear yet whether the production company behind
``Multimillionaire'' will be able to interest another network in
airing it. What is clear is that ``Multimillionaire'' is one of the
more memorable flameouts in recent TV history.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thompson, founder of the Center for the Study of Popular
Television at Syracuse University, called the ``Multimillionaire''
concept ``in incredibly bad taste, a ludicrous, terrible idea''
that nonetheless kept him riveted to his chair last Tuesday. It was
a combination of revulsion and fascination apparently shared by the
nearly 23 million other other viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Reality programs ``are using real people in what could be
fascinating stories, but have the potential for danger,'' Thompson
said. ``You're essentially taking these people and letting them be
absorbed by a process they may lose control of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PCC-MARKETPLACE-ART-N     02-21 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCC-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: DEFYING GRAVITY IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Alex Arena is trying to pull off the biggest deal in
the history of Hong Kong _ one that has confounded analysts and
roiled markets here for more than a week. But Arena, the managing
director of Pacific Century CyberWorks, seemed remarkably at ease
Monday, as he stopped for a sandwich between meetings in a
conference room packed with investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking a while for people to understand our strategy,''
Arena said. ``But I don't mind, because we like to have some
element of surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise has not been lacking in the short, fiery history of
Pacific Century CyberWorks Ltd. Since going public last April, this
Hong Kong Internet company has amassed a market capitalization of
$31 billion, invested in more than 30 start-ups and drawn an
avalanche of press coverage. Ten days ago, it disclosed that it
might bid for Hong Kong's flagship telephone company, Cable &AMP;
Wireless HKT.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between Pacific Century and Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT
continued here Monday, and a growing number of analysts now predict
that Pacific Century will trump previously disclosed merger talks
between Cable &AMP; Wireless and Singapore Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Arena declined to comment on the status of the negotiations, but
he left little doubt that his company was dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expression of interest in Hong Kong Tel represents the
sort of acquisitive position we're in as a company to accelerate
our business plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like America Online and Time Warner in the United States,
Pacific Century's bid for Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT dramatizes the
gravity-defying levels of Internet stocks in Asia. But Pacific
Century's gambit is in some ways even more brazen than AOL's: The
company has no operating profits, no customers and has not even
started the Internet and television service that is supposed to be
its core business.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century remains almost entirely a bet on the pluck of
its 33-year-old chairman, Richard Li, the son of Hong Kong's
legendary tycoon, Li Ka-shing. The younger Li started the company
in 1993 and owns a majority of its stock. So far, he _ and the
connections of his family _ have been enough to overcome skepticism
about its stratospheric share price and sketchy business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a classic Hong Kong mania,'' said David Webb, who
edits Webb-site.com, a site that tracks local stock offerings. ``We
had one for China-related stocks in `97, and we're having one for
Internet stocks now. Hong Kong always seems to catch this fever
worse than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb, a former investment banker, contends that Pacific Century
should have a market value of about $7.5 billion, based on its
existing assets and the anticipated future profits from its
Internet-access service. He said it traded at $31 billion _ more
than Amazon.com _ because of the perceived value of Li and the
general euphoria over anything Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century is not the only shooting star among Hong Kong
start-ups. People mobbed local banks Monday to pick up applications
for shares in Tom.com, a Chinese-language Internet portal that
plans to issue shares in Hong Kong on Wednesday. Analysts note that
Tom.com is the Internet vehicle of the elder Li's company _ a fact
that seems to outweigh the portal's rather meager offerings.
</P>
<P>
   But while Li Ka-shing has a hot stock, his son may soon acquire
one of Hong Kong's largest employers and most entrenched
monopolies. Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, which is 54 percent-owned by
Cable &AMP; Wireless of Britain, is itself valued at over $30 billion.
The company was for years the jewel in its parent's crown, though
its profits have been eroded by deregulation in the Hong Kong
communications market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that politics will help Pacific Century in its
bid. Neither the Hong Kong nor the mainland Chinese government is
pleased by the prospect of Hong Kong's local phone company being
taken over by archrival Singapore. Richard Li, by contrast, is seen
as a local boy made good. And his father has cultivated close ties
with senior Chinese leaders in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cable &AMP; Wireless has a tricky task in negotiating with
Pacific Century. Any offer is likely to be largely, or even wholly,
in the form of Pacific Century stock. Before agreeing to a deal,
the Cable &AMP; Wireless directors will have to estimate the underlying
value of the company's shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be stupid to accept large quantities of PCCW's
paper for what is still a valuable business,'' Webb said. ``When
you've got a solid currency, you shouldn't trade it for a
hyper-inflated currency.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena declined to comment on the stock. But he said it was
unfair to characterize Pacific Century as an empty vessel. He noted
that it had amassed a portfolio of Internet investments rivaling
those of Softbank of Japan and CMGI of the United States _ and
turned a $1 billion profit in the process. And he said it had
broken ground on Cyberport, a $1.7 billion technology park here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where this belief comes from that we don't have
any businesses,'' Arena said. ``We do have businesses, and we have
a huge pipeline of Internet investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's biggest imponderable is its core business. In
two months, it plans to begin rolling out an Internet-access and
interactive television service, immodestly called Network of the
World, that will be transmitted via satellite to cable operators
throughout Asia. The cable systems would then deliver the service
to subscribers, whose homes would be outfitted with modems
_allowing them to receive it either over their television sets or
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to create a new kind of medium,'' said Greg
Feldberg, an analyst at Indosuez W.I. Carr Securities in Hong Kong.
``The success or failure of this service is the big gamble here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pacific Century has focused on cable distribution,
Arena said the company would gladly deliver its service over
telephone lines or by wireless transmission. Indeed, analysts said
Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT would give Pacific Century instant
distribution in Hong Kong because the phone company is aggressively
upgrading its network to deliver broadband services in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the logic of a deal, Arena conceded that Pacific
Century's bid for its hometown phone company was, at heart, a
seat-of-the-pants move. ``Until the 24th of January, when Singapore
Tel and Cable &AMP; Wireless made their announcement, we didn't know
the asset was for sale,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
