<SLUG> BC-MICH-GOP-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, BUSH FACE VOTE BY DIVERSE ELECTORATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DeWITT TOWNSHIP, Mich. _ The men and women sitting around the
Edwin J. Leyanna Post 671 of the Veterans of Foreign Wars nursing
beers Sunday afternoon said they were for John McCain, and the news
that McCain and George W. Bush split the veterans' vote in the
South Carolina Republican primary had them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us here would like to see McCain get it,'' said Claude
Murdock, a past commander of the post, pushing his gray plaid tam
back on his forehead and shifting a well-chewed cigar from one side
of his mouth to the other. ``But I don't think he's going to make
it. He lost bad in South Carolina. I thought he would do better
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the expectations of probable voters interviewed
across central Michigan since the South Carolina vote last
Saturday, McCain faces an uphill battle in Tuesday's primary. The
polls say the race is too close to call, but Bush has strong
support from Michigan Governor John Engler, the party establishment
and whatever momentum his South Carolina victory provides.
</P>
<P>
   People here are figuring out what to make of McCain's defeat in
a much smaller state with a political culture that seems more than
a region away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be close,'' said Robert Wood, a Bush supporter and
insurance broker in Howell, a rock-solid Republican town that is
the seat of the fastest-growing county in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about it at the round table,'' he said,
referring to the old oak table by the grandfather clock in Hunter's
Family Restaurant where the town fathers meet to talk politics.
``You could almost flip a coin around this table _ it's half
McCain, half Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the table, Wilfred ``Bud'' Erwin, a McCain supporter and
former municipal judge, nodded in agreement. ``Bush has got the
edge because of Engler,'' Erwin said, ``but it depends who gets out
and votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Engler factor cuts both ways, people said, because the state
Republican party is rife with dissension, especially over education
issues. The state chairwoman, a member of one of Michigan's most
influential families, recently resigned after falling out with the
governor. And a poll published in the Detroit News said more voters
felt negatively than positively about the governor's staunch
support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, they said, that while Michigan and South Carolina both
have strong concentrations of religious conservatives, people here
are more inclined to tolerate differences of opinion and to balk at
moral prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those veterans'' who voted for Bush in South Carolina,
``they're vets, but they're part of the religious right too,'' said
Keith Penton, who calibrates manufacturing machinery for General
Motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling you if you're not a right-to-life person
you're not a Republican,'' Penton said. ``Well, I'm a Republican,
and . . . everybody's entitled to their own opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was shared by Scott Hilbert, a participant in
Howell's round table discussions, who said Bush's embrace of the
religious right in South Carolina helped him decide how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like religion. I think it is good,'' Hilbert said. ``But we
have separation of church and state in this country, and that is
getting too close to the line for me. It bothers me. Bush has lost
me over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, voters and outside observers alike point out, is
significant beyond the accident of timing that makes its vote this
year so vital for McCain. It is by far the most-populous, diverse
state to vote so far, with strong similarities to other
delegate-rich states of the upper Midwest such as Ohio and
Illinois. It is less conservative than South Carolina, less
contrarian than New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan is very much a microcosm of the whole country, the
first primary state that is a swing state in the general
election,'' said Mike Murphy, a top strategist for McCain and a
Michigan native whose family's farm was near Engler's family's,
outside Beal City.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy worked on Engler's last campaign, and the stratgist said
that ``not a day goes by that I don't wish he was with us. But
there's no Engler machine in Michigan, no machine that tells people
how to vote. Conservative Democrats and independents can vote'' in
the Republican primary, ``and many will.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising war that flared between Bush and McCain in the
last week of the South Carolina campaign is less prominent here,
though both men's attack ads were shown here at the time. Now, Bush
ads continue to accuse McCain. McCain criticizes Bush in public
discussions, but has withdrawn ads charging the governor with
Clintonesque untruthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bummer!'' said Daniel Markey, night clerk at the Muskegon
Holiday Inn, on the western border of the state, as the South
Carolina results rolled in. ``I like McCain because he just says
what he really thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But McCain made a big mistake calling Bush like Clinton,''
said Markey, who described himself as very conservative. When he
saw the McCain ad likening Bush to Clinton, ``it was, like, ouch!''
Markey said. ``It was not a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also hurt himself, according to Adam Sobczak, who was
selling campers at a trade show in the Muskegon Mall, because he
lacked grace in defeat in South Carolina. ``He accused Bush of
taking the lower line, but it was McCain who was tossing the mud,''
Sobczak said.
</P>
<P>
   As in South Carolina, while some people here resent what they
see as Bush's attempt to ride to victory on his father's
reputation, far more give him points for his paternity. They also
said Bush senior has been better campaigning on his son's behalf
than he was on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was funny and relaxed, a delight to listen to,'' said Roger
Dachter, police chief in Northern Shores, near Muskegon, after
listening to the former president. ``He did a Ross Perot imitation
that cracked me up. If George senior had been like that in '92,
he'd have beaten Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   At a front table in Hunter's Family Restaurant, Lori Westendorf
and Jackie Bohn, friends and nursing colleagues at McPherson
Hospital, went back and forth over McCain and Bush at breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Westendorf said she liked Bush because ``he's a little more
conservative gentleman. . . . He's got a lot of those Midwestern
values I find important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohn said she liked McCain ``for all the reasons she just said
about Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of debate that, in Michigan at least, will only
end with the voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
