<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DOWNSHIFT22-COX     02-21 2302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSHIFT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Downshifting': Atlantans exchange corporate jobs for careers
with a mission
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A man who ditched a public relations job at
Scientific-Atlanta with the nutty notion of painting pictures for
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who left Bank of America after 30 years to run a church
shelter for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   A man who started on the fast track and then slowed down for his
child.
</P>
<P>
   A man who got downsized by Coca-Cola and upsized his enjoyment
in a bicycle shop.
</P>
<P>
   The four metro Atlantans profiled below have, in current
parlance, ``downshifted.'' Mostly by choice, they made a dramatic
change in career or lifestyle, giving up well-paying jobs they had
worked years to attain.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because something in their lives was missing. Call it a
sense of mission _ even spiritual fulfillment _ in their work.
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone. Some observers feel that such midlife career
changers are the leading edge of a broad-based reaction against the
intense careerism of our time. Sometimes it's a 50th birthday _ and
a lot of baby boomers are having them these days _ that reminds
them they don't have so many years left to do what they dreamed of
doing before they got sidetracked into more lucrative work. But
downshifting isn't limited to boomers: Witness the announcement
last month that high-flying, 33-year-old Turner Broadcasting
executive Bill Burke was leaving to spend time with his family and
consider his career. ``I don't know what's missing,'' he declared,
``but I'm looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing more and more people saying, `This job is hollow
for me _ I can't fake it anymore,''' says Joan DiFuria, who
switched from international business to psychology and co-founded
the Money, Meaning and Choices Institute, a California organization
that counsels people on how to use their energies and capital.
``Regardless of income, there are more people asking, `What kind of
message does my work send to my children? What can I do that I can
be proud of?'''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of regrettable career choices may go all the way back
to school days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The educational system blindly guides kids toward preparing
for a career they think they'll want, before they're even old
enough to know who they really are,'' says Gerald Celente, director
of New York's Trend Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Jef Murray, 40, a research engineer at Georgia Tech, runs a
group that meets to exchange views about simplifying their lives
and reducing expenses in order to afford doing the work they love.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people are working harder to buy more in a fruitless
attempt to buy happiness,'' Murray says. ``Whether it's a vacation
home or a $7 latte, it's just a way to reward themselves for a
workweek in hell. The moment's pleasure keeps them locked to work
they hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our group,'' he says, ``we see many dreams pulled out of
closets, dusted off, shined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Following are four such dreams.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN FEIGHT
</P>
<P>
   You never know what you're going to find on a quiet suburban
lane. Push the doorbell of a handsome home on a wooded hilltop
overlooking the Chattahoochee River, for example, and presently,
amid the yipping of a dachshund, the door is answered by a
pleasant-looking, middle-aged fellow wearing surgical scrubs
spattered with multicolored paint.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a visual riddle: Is this a physician who gets carried
away with his art hobby, or a professional artist who likes to
dress up as a doc?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is odder still. John Feight, 60, is a former
advertising and public relations exec who is now devoted to
creating art for hospitals _ painting it himself, and helping
patients in hospitals all over the world paint it, too. This is not
some semi-retirement lark. It has been Feight's dream for 25 years.
Today, his Foundation for Hospital Art, operating out of his roomy
basement, stacked to the ceiling with canvases and paints, has
placed paintings in 500 hospitals in 165 countries.
</P>
<P>
   An Ohio native, Feight swept up the ladder of a leading New York
ad agency in his 20s. But he always had a mystical side. He still
quotes from ``Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance,'' a key
document of 1970s zeitgeist, as if it were published yesterday. He
portrays himself not as the mastermind of the foundation but simply
the conduit for generous people who have helped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good idea,'' he says, quoting the Brazilian
writer Paulo Coelho, ``all the universe will conspire to help
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Feight's idea, and the happy conspiracy, developed in stages.
After moving to Atlanta to join Coca-Cola and head its Fresca ad
campaign in 1969, he gave his wife, Linda, some art supplies. He
ended up as the one dabbling with them. His first painting in a
medical setting went up in a friend's animal clinic.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, the ever-restless Feight volunteered to
work Sunday evenings in a hospital psychiatric ward and was struck
by the sight of a young patient staring at a blank wall. Soon he
was showing the patients slides of paintings and instructing them
to create their own.
</P>
<P>
   Feight: ``Hospitals look so sterile, I wanted to fill those
walls with color, get that young woman thinking about her painting
instead of her pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, with a grant from the Woodruff Foundation, he quit his
job as head of public relations for Scientific-Atlanta to devote
himself to his foundation, which has a budget of $200,000 from
donations and pays him a modest salary. (Linda's schoolteaching job
``is our security blanket,'' he says.) During the Barcelona
Olympics in 1992, Feight led an ``Olympic Paint Fest'' _ athletes
and everyday citizens painting hospital murals for 16 days _ that
brought requests for his work from all over the world. On March 25,
he'll coordinate a Global Paint Fest, consisting of his own
painting session with inner-city youngsters in Baltimore and
simultaneous events in England and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   One of Feight's strategies is to prepare stacks of small
canvases with outlines of color-coded scenes that even artistic
novices can fill in with paint. The canvases are then assembled
into murals that may represent the collaborative painting of an
entire hospital ward. As Feight leads a tour of his basement mural
factory, one sees outlines of palm trees, zebras, tropical birds
and flowers _ images of dreamy lushness and escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, of all places, shouldn't a hospital be beautiful?'' he
asks.
</P>
<P>
   Once, at Central State Hospital in Milledgeville, Ga., Feight
was struggling to help a patient who could barely speak or control
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put my hand next to his cheek and leaned his head right
into the canvas,'' Feight recalls, ``and I realized that he was
steering my brush in the only way he could.'' Suddenly Feight was
reminded of his grandfather, a tireless country doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I've always wanted to make a difference,'' Feight
says, ``the way he did.''
</P>
<P>
   MARY JOE DELLINGER
</P>
<P>
   Bankers can surprise you: Look at T.S. Eliot. Another who long
harbored a poetic passion is Mary Joe Dellinger. Last year, at the
age of 54, she walked away from a 30-year career with Bank of
America to become the full-time head of community outreach programs
for the First Presbyterian Church of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Her income took a tumble, of course, as she left the post of
assistant vice president _ but she didn't hesitate to take the
leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I decided that I wanted to do something more than
crunch numbers _ and that was the day this job became available,''
the Charlotte, N.C., native says at her church office. ``I wanted
to deal with people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading a tour of the 14-bed women's shelter at First
Presbyterian _ including a dining room with books, paintings,
flowers on each table _ Dellinger couldn't be more proud if she
were showing off a sprawling new office complex that she'd financed
in her former life.
</P>
<P>
   She'd arrived a bit late for the interview: She'd been driving
one of her homeless clients on vital errands, above and beyond the
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Joe's amazing, always giving of herself,'' says her
assistant, Rick O'Neal. ``I don't know if she takes any time for
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dellinger, a member of ``First Prez'' since almost the
day she arrived in Atlanta in 1963, admits that volunteer work _
building Habitat for Humanity homes, managing the church's food
bank and clothes closet _ has consumed countless nights and
weekends. She's never married: ``Didn't have time, I guess,'' she
says with a laugh. But she does have an indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horseback riding!'' she exclaims with a flash of her steady,
penetrating dark eyes. ``I started seven years ago. I'm part of a
saddle club that's planning to ride across Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' she adds, gazing out the window at a cusp-of-spring
afternoon, ``I wish I were riding right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, commitment _ ``duty'' would be too harsh a word _ calls.
Today Dellinger is busy enlisting more volunteer supervisors so
that she can expand the shelter to 20 beds.
</P>
<P>
   Her rewards are many.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my first day on the job here, in October, I received calls
from three people who used to stay at the shelter,'' she recalls.
``All had found a place in life. One _ a person we asked to leave
because she wasn't trying to improve her situation _ turned her
life completely around and just called to say `Thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger smiles. ``That's when I knew: This is where I'm
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   LMICHAEL GREEN
</P>
<P>
   Jetting hither and yon around the world, from one five-star
hotel and expense account meal to another, LMichael Green in 1994
was the Southeastern regional director for marketing with Pepsi
Cola. Only in his mid-30s, he was one satisfied man.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Then his daughter was born, bringing real joy, but with it a
troubling question. Holding the infant in his arms, he thought back
to his boyhood home in Berkeley, Calif., and his parents, who were
cheerful crusaders for social justice, leading the boycott of a
winemaker that they believed exploited migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down at my beautiful baby,'' recalls Green, 43, ``and
I thought, `What am I going to tell her that I did with my life? Am
I proud of selling these products?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of spending my time on planes,'' he adds, ``I wanted
to spend it with her.''
</P>
<P>
   By a chance that he calls a godsend, CARE had recently relocated
to Atlanta and offered Green the position of head of marketing. He
sat down with his wife; they decided they could handle the 40
percent cut in family income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comfort in my soul is the compensation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's still some glamour in his work: He got to work with
Eddie Vedder of Pearl Jam to arrange the marketing of that band's
benefit album for CARE. There's still more travel than he'd like,
though the trips put him more, not less, in touch with the real
world. Seeing women in Ecuador who pick through garbage heaps,
finding cardboard to recycle into beautiful hand-painted cards,
``was an image that tears at your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's daughter is now in first grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do the geography lessons,'' he says, ``I love to tell
her what CARE is doing in each country.''
</P>
<P>
   JAMIE ADAMS
</P>
<P>
   For 26 years, as a market research manager for Coca-Cola, Jamie
Adams draped his hearty, Falstaffian frame with respectable office
attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my time at Coke, and I was lucky enough to get hold
of some company stock back in its golden age,'' says the longtime
Atlanta resident, 52. ``But I was never sure that pushing
carbonated water was going to save mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that selling bicycles will achieve that lofty goal, either.
But at least it's what Adams enjoys, and he can afford to do it
only a few days a month, whenever his friend, the owner of Intown
Bicycles, is short-handed. On the first springlike day of the year,
Adams cracks that he is ``dressed for success _ bike shop style.''
He's wearing a tie-dyed shirt _ ``bright colors are a survival
technique in Atlanta traffic'' _ running shoes and black shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're regular shorts, though,'' Adams adds. ``They don't
make bike shorts in my size.''
</P>
<P>
   This disarming wisenheimer has a classic Atlanta resume: raised
in Cascade Heights, got a math degree at Georgia Tech, ``then
walked across the street'' to Coke. Unlike the other three people
described here, Adams wasn't questing for deeper meaning in life
when he downshifted. He simply pined for more time to goof off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of these Calvinists who believe in the inherent
value of work,'' he declares. ``I believe you do it and then you're
outta there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' story is also different from the others in that he did
not end his corporate career by choice. When his job was eliminated
in a 1988 reorganization, he had enough severance to realize his
longtime dream of biking from Los Angeles to Savannah. When he was
rehired a year later, he and his wife, who also had a corporate
job, made a point to eliminate their debt and pump up their
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   So when the downsizing ax fell again on Adams in 1994, they were
ready. And free. Adams' wife took early retirement, and they took
off for a biking tour of back-country New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We travel cheap: just solid country food, wine and beer,''
Adams declares. ``Especially beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams loves working in the shop. ``I get to talk about bikes,
travel. Sometimes I meet homeless people whose bikes are their only
transport; I also meet people who ride $5,000 bikes. Everyone's
interesting, nobody's angry. It ain't like selling water heaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here partly though preparation, partly dumb luck,'' he
adds. ``Either way, I'm having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
