<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-WESTBANK-CAVES-ART-     02-21 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WESTBANK-CAVES-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS DISRUPTS A WAY OF LIFE FOR PALESTINIAN CAVE DWELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; the graphic is a map)  (ART ADV: Graphic and a photo are being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AL-MUFAQARA, West Bank _ Wrapped in a head scarf against the
rain that lashed the barren rocky hills southeast of Hebron, Mahmud
Hamamdeh stood recently in the home that he had been expelled from
and extolled the virtues of life in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade this for anything,'' Hamamdeh, 35, said of
the cave from which he, his wife, nine children and a flock of
sheep were ousted along with scores of other Palestinian cave
dwellers by Israeli soldiers in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather opened this cave,'' said Hamamdeh, who raises
sheep and goats and farms land in the valleys among the hills. ``I
was born here. My children were born here. My wife gave birth here.
This was our hospital and clinic. If we were sick, we went out to
the field, collected herbs and made medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, it's as cool in here as if it were
air-conditioned, and in winter it's warm. I'm used to this, and I'm
not comfortable anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamamdeh and his family now occupy an abandoned one-room
structure in a neighboring village, storing belongings in a tent,
like others who were forced out of their caves.
</P>
<P>
   The evictions from Al-Mufaqara and other cave hamlets in an area
of the Hebron hills that the Israeli army has declared a firing
zone can be seen as another chapter in the grinding struggle
between Israel and the Palestinians over how much land each side
will control if they finally negotiate a permanent peace.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be seen as the latest encroachment on a
centuries-old way of life that has been caught up in political
conflict as the Israeli authorities try to restrict the
cave-dwelling shepherds and farmers who roam the rugged hills near
the West Bank's southern boundary with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, the army has been emptying and sometimes
sealing caves on the grounds that the people were living in closed
military areas, usually declared firing zones.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, Jewish settlements were built on some hills. Now,
as Israel and the Palestinians have begun negotiating a final
agreement to divide the disputed land, the military authorities
seem to be consolidating their hold on West Bank areas that remain
under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   The removals from Al-Mufaqara and neighboring hamlets were
carried out on Nov. 16, a few days after Israeli soldiers and
police dragged away militant Jewish settlers and their supporters
from Maon Farm, a nearby outpost that the government said had been
built illegally in the firing zone.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers demanded equal enforcement against the
Palestinians, and days later soldiers moved on the caves.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses here described children as crying and women as
pleading with soldiers who ordered them out: ``Where will we go?
This is our home. God help us.'' People gathered mattresses and
kitchen utensils and loaded them on tractor-drawn wagons. Tents and
sheep pens were torn down, and soldiers hauled away bedding and
animal feed, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The people of Al-Mufaqara and other hamlets trekked to
neighboring villages, where they took shelter in tents and empty
buildings. According to a list compiled by residents and given to
an Israeli human rights group, B'Tselem, 300 people were evicted.
The Israeli military government in the West Bank, known as the
Civil Administration, said it had received reports from the Red
Cross of more than 100 people displaced.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said cave dwellers were seasonal farmers who
lived in the caves a few months a year when they were cultivating
their land and grazing flocks, while actually maintaining houses in
the neighboring town of Yatta. They were allowed into the firing
zone 90 days a year and on weekends and Jewish holidays, when the
army does not train, to cultivate their lands in season, an
administration spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamamdeh and neighbors at Al-Mufaqara said they were part of
a core group that lived there year-round, joined by others who
arrived in the rainy farming season. Some people have relatives
living in family homes in Yatta, residents said, but the houses are
full and cannot accommodate the displaced people.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after it had been emptied, Al-Mufaqara still bore signs of
long-term settlement. One cave had a large wood door, locked by its
owner with a big key, with a small herb garden and earthen oven
outside. Hamamdeh had a rain-fed well near his cave, and among the
debris inside were a battered cupboard, plastic and tin
kitchenware, bags of sheep dung that had served as fuel, and
branches for a fire. A cooking stove supplied by gas canisters and
a television set powered by a car battery had been taken away, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The emptying of Al-Mufaqara and surrounding communities has
hastened the decline of what was a widespread way of life in the
hill country south of Hebron for generations of Arabs, dating from
the Muslim conquest of Palestine in the seventh century.
</P>
<P>
   A 19th-century American biblical geographer, Edward Robinson,
referred to cave dwellers in the area in a book published in 1841.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yaacov Havakook, an Israeli who has written a study of cave life
in the Hebron hills, said that 20 years ago the communities there
were among the most extensive known in the world, with more than
8,000 people living in hundreds of hamlets.
</P>
<P>
   But evictions of cave dwellers and restrictions on their access
to farm land by the Israeli authorities over the years have reduced
their number to a third of what it had been, Havakook said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest people to be displaced are now living in limbo,
feeling cut off from the distinctive way of life that sustained
them for hundreds of years. Israeli lawyers have petitioned the
Israeli Supreme Court to allow them to return.
</P>
<P>
   On a muddy hillside swept by wind and hail, Niman Jabarin and
his extended family camped in burlap tents that provided little
shelter from the cold. Evicted from a hamlet that was cleared a few
weeks before Al-Mufaqara, they are hunkering down with their
flocks, keeping alive the hope that they will be permitted to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a life,'' Jabarin said as red-nosed children in
thin sweaters picked their way among the tents. ``It's like living
in a jail. We have to go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
