<HEADER>
A3863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT &LR;      02-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING EURO HAMPERS EFFORTS OF PRO-EUROPEAN FORCES IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Almost a year ago, Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain
seemed to nudge this country closer to joining in the European
single currency, offering a cautious and conditional timetable for
signing up to use the euro.
</P>
<P>
   It was, at best, a tentative testing of the cloudy waters of
British nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, even that nebulous schedule _ foreseeing
possible entry somewhere between 2002 and 2005 _ has receded as the
economics of the euro have sunk ever deeper into the politics of
British ambiguity toward Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The currency itself, down more than 15 percent against the
dollar since its introduction in January 1999, has lost 14 percent
of its value against the pound, pushing the price of British
exports to Continental Europe ever higher. Opinion surveys have
shown sentiment in this country swinging not simply against joining
the euro zone, but for a sizable minority, against remaining a
member of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Some representatives of British big business, citing the
government's lack of leadership, have backed away from their
previously vocal support for the single currency. And Blair's
euroskeptic adversaries have delighted in developments _ ranging
from the continued ban on British beef in France and Germany, to
European Union calls for harmonized tax policies _ citing them as
evidence of Continental malevolence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a particularly bad year for the European cause,'' said
Ben Hall, research director at the Center for European Reform,
which is pro-European, ``and the decline in the euro did not make
it easier to persuade the British people to ditch the pound.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Blair has switched tactics. Rather than try to persuade
his compatriots of Europe's virtues, he is increasingly telling his
European partners that it is up to them to make themselves more
alluring in British eyes by embracing the kind of freewheeling
economic ways that Britain has sought to import from the United
States. At the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, last
month, he told the powerful and the wealthy: ``The question for
Europe is clear. Can it take on the attitudes and interests of the
past and move decisively to gain a lead in the new economy and
industries of the future?''
</P>
<P>
   The risks of remaining outside the euro zone are clear, too. At
Davos, Noboyuki Idei, president of the Sony Corp., bluntly told the
prime minister that Sony's future investments in Britain would be
jeopardized by the government's refusal to commit itself to joining
in the single currency.
</P>
<P>
   That raised a question about Britain's role as Europe's most
powerful magnet for investment by companies who see their British
operations as a springboard to the European Union's single market _
and who seek the simplicity of a single currency.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs have been brought into the argument, as well. The trade and
industry minister, Stephen Byers, cited recent studies Monday to
say that 3 million British jobs _ 1 million of them in exporting
industries _ depended on membership in the European single market.
More than half of Britain's trade, he said, is with Continental
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, these arguments fudge the issue. By portraying the
euro's opponents as enemies of British membership in the European
Union, Blair's government is seeking to discredit its critics as
people prepared to put what Byers called ``political dogma'' before
the nation's economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   William Hague, the leader of the opposition Conservative Party,
said Monday that Blair was ``trying to link the mainstream majority
who want to keep the pound with the extremist minority who want to
leave the European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real debate in British politics is not about Europe _ in
or out _ as Tony Blair wants us to pretend,'' said Hague, who
recently embarked on a tour of the country in a truck emblazoned
with the Union Jack, part of a campaign to keep the pound. ``The
real debate is about the euro _ in or out _ and Tony Blair knows he
is losing the argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Blair's ministers acknowledge that Hague may have a
point. ``I accept criticism, either of me personally or perhaps of
other members of the government, that we haven't done enough,''
Byers said Monday. ``And what we now need to do, I think, is to
engage in the debate. There is a real battle here that we have to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   That is important because the government has committed itself to
seeking popular support for joining in the single currency in a
referendum after the next national election, which must be held by
May 2002 and may be held earlier. And if Hague has his way, the
election will hinge partly on the question of British adoption of
the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has laid down five conditions for joining in the euro,
one of which is that there be ``sustainable convergence'' between
the British and Continental European economies. Those conditions do
not prevail today: Britain's short-term interest rates are roughly
twice the level of the 11 euro zone countries, while its
unemployment rate below 5 percent is perhaps half the Continental
European average.
</P>
<P>
   But the single currency has never been a purely economic issue
anywhere in Europe, least of all in Britain, the only major
European country where the question of membership has been aired in
a public, if sometimes fanciful debate. For some opponents here of
the single currency, the Europeans are often depicted as conducting
a sinister plot, especially by France and Germany, to dictate a
political and economic agenda contrary to British interests.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's shift in demanding reforms on the Continent _ where some
Britons see only slow attention to issues of economic change _ is
intended as an antidote to that argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Blair is seen to be shaping the reform agenda,'' said Hall
at the Center for European Reform, ``the theory is that that will
persuade the British people that things are moving in our direction
and not just run by the French and the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate, he said. ``never will be rational.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
