<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HOUSTON-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON EXPANDS ITS PROFILE IN FINE ARTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For years the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston has
enjoyed a national reputation and attracted prominent traveling
exhibitions, most recently the work of Diego Rivera. Last year, 1.3
million people visited the museum, underscoring its importance in
Houston's profile as a cultural destination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many of the museum's antiquities and paintings have
languished in storage, unseen for lack of space to display them.
Now that problem has been solved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On March 25, three years after groundbreaking, museum officials
will open the Audrey Jones Beck Building, an expansion that with a
single flourish takes the museum from 30th to 6th largest in the
country measured in the amount of space dedicated to exhibitions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a mini version of the Met,'' said the museum's
director, Peter C. Marzio. ``That's the model.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marzio, who grew up in New York, thinks that the expansion will
finally give the 100-year-old museum a size worthy of the nation's
fourth-largest city and its 40,000 works of art. ``You'll be able
to visit virtually every culture in the world,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grand opening comes as the oak-lined museum district south
of downtown is undergoing a face lift. The nearby Hermann Park,
owned by the city, is in the midst of a major renovation, and the
adjacent Park Plaza Warwick Hotel has finished a renovation that
includes a new outdoor patio bar and restaurant facing the museum
and the Mecom Fountain on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Within easy walking distance are several city museums: the
Contemporary Arts Museum, the Museum of Natural Science, the
Holocaust Museum and Memorial, the Children's Museum and the Health
and Medical Science Museum. The renowned Menil Collection of art is
a short drive away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Beck Building was designed by Rafael Moneo (Mies van der
Rohe designed the principal building), the Pritzker Prize-winning
Spanish architect. Clad in Indiana limestone, it rises three levels
and occupies a city block. Inside, visitors will find an 80-foot
lobby-atrium flooded with natural light. An underground tunnel
connects the building with the Caroline Wiess Law Building and a
newly constructed visitors center and parking garage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 192,447 square-foot Beck Building will offer a range of art
for visitors. Shortly after the groundbreaking, the museum
announced the purchase of 18 works from the estate of Jackson
Pollock, nine of which will be on view on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   The building will also serve as the primary repository for
European art from antiquity to 1920. An Impressionist and
Post-Impressionist section on the second floor will include works
by Braque, Monet, Renoir and Seurat, and Baroque art from the Sarah
Campbell Blaffer Foundation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the first floor, permanent galleries will be dedicated to
American art from the late Colonial period through World War II,
including prints, drawings, photography and other works on paper.
Roman, Greek and Egyptian antiquities will be on permanent view. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of the art and antiquities of China opened in the
existing building this month and continues through May 7. In the
new galleries for traveling exhibitions, two shows will be part of
the grand opening. From March 25 through June 4, ``Irving Penn: A
Career in Photography'' will display more than 100 vintage prints
from the photographer known for his portraits of celebrities like
Truman Capote as well as his fashion and travel photography. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Faces of Impressionism: Portraits from American Collections,''
March 25 through May 7, includes ``Woman Reading'' by Mary Cassatt,
``Clovis'' by Gauguin, and paintings by Degas, Cezanne, Manet and
Renoir. The exhibition was seen last year at the Baltimore Museum
of Art and will go to the Cleveland Museum of Art after leaving
Houston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marzio said he hoped that the expansion would bring further
recognition for the fine arts in Houston. Too many outsiders, he
said, still equate the city with oil and cowboys, though cowboys
are seen only during the annual rodeo and livestock show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe,'' he said, ``that the next 10 years will
make all the rest of the history of the museum look like we were
asleep.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
