<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK-SPRINT22-CO     02-21 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-SPRINT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprint invests $77 million in EarthLink
 &HT;    By Frances Katz and Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an effort to make sure it holds on to a piece of
the residential Internet access market, Sprint Corp. has invested
an additional $77 million in Atlanta-based EarthLink Inc., bringing
its holdings to 14.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That investment preserves Sprint's option to increase its
investment further or even to eventually purchase all of EarthLink.
The company became the nation's second-largest Internet service
provider with its merger this year to MindSpring Enterprises. While
EarthLink remains one of the few large ISPs, Sprint's decision
seems to signal that the company could become part of a
telecommunications giant someday.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint itself has agreed to be acquired by Mississippi-based MCI
WorldCom, but telecommunications analyst Jeff Kagan said the
investment in EarthLink is warranted whether or not that deal is
consummated. ``This is something Sprint would do without regard to
the (WorldCom) merger. This might be a way of hedging their bets in
case something happens with the merger. Then they still keep a
strong residential Internet position.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint plans to use EarthLink to provide Internet service when
it launches ION, its service package that will include high-speed
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``This additional investment in EarthLink signifies Sprint's
commitment to maintaining its long-term relationship with
EarthLink,'' said EarthLink chief executive Garry Betty.
``Currently, part of the alliance we have is, as Sprint bundles
Internet service and other products, we are that Internet
service.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink issued additional stock for the Sprint purchase, just
as it did when Apple Computer invested $200 million in January. In
fact, it was the Apple investment that forced Sprint's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, the third-largest telecommunications company in the
United States bought 2.73 million shares at about $28.10 a share.
The Kansas City, Mo.-based telecommunications company made the
investment following regulatory approval of Apple's $200 million
investment. Apple's new stake in the company reduced Sprint's
ownership in EarthLink to a level that put its two seats on the
EarthLink board in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the original Sprint-EarthLink agreement,
Sprint has the option of adding to its investment in EarthLink to
maintain its percentage of ownership when others buy shares in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   At an analysts' meeting in January, Betty said Sprint had six
months after the close of the MindSpring merger to ``top up'' its
investment level. If the telecommunications company decides not to
do that, its ownership will fall below 20 percent and the company
will lose its two board seats. Those seats are held by William S.
Esrey, Sprint chairman and chief executive officer, and Len J.
Lauer, president of the company's consumer services group.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint merged its own Internet access customers into EarthLink
when it first invested, and Sprint Vice President Bill White said
the company is pleased with the payback. ``We believe they provide
outstanding service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has until August to decide whether it wants to boost its
share of EarthLink. It originally held 28 percent and returning to
that level is an expensive proposition. At EarthLink's current
per-share price, 14.7 percent of its stock is worth $455 million,
so doubling the Sprint share would cost about that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided what we will do,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink President Michael McQuary said he is uncertain how
Sprint's acquisition by MCI WorldCom would affect EarthLink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they are trying to do is keep all of their
options open,'' he said. ``If they didn't top up, it could limit
their options in terms of the alliance after WorldCom or future
acquisition possibilities. As long as they continue to top up, they
have maximum flexibility to make decisions on what they do or don't
want to do with us.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom's Vice-Chairman John Sidgmore was among the early
members of the EarthLink board. He resigned from the EarthLink
board when then-rival Sprint made its first investment.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications analysts say Sprint's actions continue the
blurring of lines between different kinds of services as well as
between different ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you could separate players. ISPs,
broadband, technology vendors. ... But what's happening is that to
be really successful on the Internet, you need to do everything,''
said Jack Staff, chief Internet economist for Zona Research.
   Staff also said the investment in EarthLink is valuable for
Sprint and for WorldCom, if and when it merges with Sprint. Staff
endorsed the notion that WorldCom does envision a post-Sprint
purchase of EarthLink. ``I think that is definitely part of the
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``EarthLink provides access to customers,'' Staff said. ``The
content offerings get the most press, but beneath the surface, when
you take a financial stake, you also have access to customers. And
customer acquisition costs can be very, very high.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink's business-to-business Web hosting is another key part
of the deal, he said. ``One thing that EarthLink does that phone
companies don't do so well is Web hosting for business. That
really, I suspect, is the sweet spot behind the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
