<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     02-21 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL ARE RUSHING TO OPEN _ SOMETIMES BEFORE THE PAINT IT DRY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio)  (af) 
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall I spent a night at the W Tuscany, a stylish, newly
refurbished hotel in New York. My room was comfortable, quiet and,
for the most part, smartly renovated. The lobby was another matter.
No one had warned me when I made my reservation that it was still
under construction. The elevators opened near a new front desk
still shrouded in packing wrap.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, the hotel set up a Continental breakfast in an
old sitting room next to the new lobby. As I poured my coffee, buzz
saws screamed and hammers pounded. I fled to my room, appalled but
not particularly surprised.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These are buoyant times for the hotel industry, with new
properties opening and old buildings being refurbished at a speedy
pace. But an increasing number of hotels are throwing open their
doors prematurely, taking in guests almost as soon as the ink dries
on the certificate of occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has become almost accepted practice for new hotels to
house guests before a restaurant or health club is complete, in
today's fervid climate it is not unusual to stay in a hotel with a
construction site for a lobby, padded elevators, and hallways
awaiting car-pets.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall I was shown a room at the Belleclaire, a renovated,
moderately priced hotel in New York, that had wires dangling where
the light fixture was supposed to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotels are so anxious to cash in on this boom that they
are being more aggressive about opening than they should,'' said
Chekitan Dev, a professor of marketing at Cornell University's
Hotel School. ``If a hotel stays closed for one more day, it loses
revenues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With fewer hotels and resorts owned by private individuals and
more by large corporations, the pressure to show returns quickly
has increased. ``If you've already given the analysts a projection
for third-quarter results and it includes that hotel, you're going
to want to make the money, even if it means alienating a few
guests,'' Dev said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel publications can add to the problem. If a hotel receives
a blaze of advance publicity, the management may be tempted to open
it even if not everything is ready. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as a soft opening, of accepting guests
before a hotel is finished isn't new and isn't always a problem.
Soft openings are the hotel equivalent of an out-of-town opening
for a Broadway play, a low-key period when management and staff can
correct mistakes before hundreds of guests arrive.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels stage soft openings for insiders, including friends,
members of the management, and travel operators, as knowledgeable
but sympathetic guests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once a hotel opens to the public, the management often limits
the number of guests until things run smoothly. ``Some places even
overstaff during soft openings, because they don't want people to
have a bad experience on their first visit,'' said James Eyster, a
professor emeritus at Cornell University's Hotel School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more accurate term for the recent rash of soft openings, which
can drag on for months, is under-construction openings. Since most
hotels lower their prices during construction, rooms can be a
bargain. But be sure to ask what services will be missing if you
stay in an unfinished hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what price they give, the property should tell you
up front there are no pros on the tennis court or there's a snack
bar but no restaurant,'' said Doris Schechter, a travel agent at
Valerie Wilson Travel in New York. Or that construction noise will
be starting at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   However you book _ by telephone or over the Internet _ find out
what to expect in the way of service cutbacks. And if a price seems
too good to be true, ask if you'll be rooming next to the guys with
buzz saws.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Construction is a complex process that can defy the best of
plans, which is one reason so many hotels are only partly
completed. ``You don't have to slip behind in your construction
schedule very much to have a problem,'' Richard Brush, a dean at
Johnson &AMP; Wales University, said. ``It could be a strike at the
furniture plant in North Carolina or a large building project that
uses up all the steel in the state.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Club Med in Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic,
which reopened the week before Christmas after an extensive
six-month renovation. ``We arrived to find huge mud puddles,
dangling electric wires, no stair lights, pathways not lit, dirt
everywhere and trucks creating clouds of dust,'' said Anne Sager of
New York, who had gone to the resort for a weeklong holiday with
her husband, their children and grandchildren from France, and a
son and his fiancee from California. Worse still, there was no
air-conditioning or hot water, and the toilets did not flush.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The resort offered a variety of compensations, including
transfers to other Club Med villages and lodging at another hotel
on the island with shuttle services to the resort for meals and
activities. Full and partial refunds, linked to whether guests
stayed, returned home or moved to another property, were also
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the resort failed to inform guests that the property
wasn't ready, Carole Boucard, a Club Med spokeswoman said: ``There
were last-minute delays that got us off the timetable, but we fully
expected to have things fixed by then.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel construction delays also marred a visit to New York for
Alan Hart and his wife from Akron, Ohio. After seeing a newspaper
ad, Hart booked a room at On the Ave, a new boutique hotel in New
York, for $135 a night. After receiving a written confirmation, he
paid for their flights and ordered opera tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Four days before they were to arrive, the Harts received a call
saying that because construction of two floors of the hotel had not
been completed, they could not stay. The caller suggested they stay
at the Habitat, an affiliated but less expensive hotel. Since many
Habitat rooms have shared baths, Hart declined and wound up paying
$320 a night for a room elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say a hotel should offer some compensation to a
guest if it can't honor its agreement to provide a room. ``The
generally accepted practice is to offer a complimentary or upgraded
room for one night at a hotel in your group,'' said Eyster of
Cornell. ``If you have to send the person to a more expensive hotel
outside your company, you pay the difference.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the policy at On the Ave, Ron Simoncini, a spokesman
for the hotel, described Hart's canceled reservation as an
embarrassment, but added that the policy is to provide a free room
at another hotel only if someone with a reservation shows up and
can't be accommodated. ``Part of the reason the prices are so low
right now is because the hotel is under construction,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When is the ideal time to try out a new or renovated hotel?
Schechter says she usually waits six months, especially if she is
sending a client to a resort. Knowing when to open a hotel can, in
fact, be something of an art.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wait for everything to be done, you'll never open,''
said Nancy Polley, a travel agent with Valerie Wilson Travel. ``But
once you open, you had better hop to and get things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
