<HEADER>
A3876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-MICH-CATHOLICS-BOS &LR;      02-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-CATHOLICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MICHIGAN, MCCAIN RIPS BUSH VISIT TO BOB JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Since he landed on Michigan soil, John McCain
has minced no words about George W. Bush's visit to Bob Jones
University, a fundamentalist institution in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigots,'' he calls the university officials there who forbid
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid,'' he says of their views of the Pope, and of
Catholicism as someting of a cult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idiots,'' he adds for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had comparatively little to say about the Bush visit
while the Arizona senator campaigned in the Palmetto State, where
fundamentalists make up at least 33 percent of the population and
provided Bush with his winning edge in Saturday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Michigan, the Christian conservative community is
far less potent and far less radical. They make up anywhere from 13
to 17 percent of the population compared to Roman Catholics, which
compose about a quarter of the state. And the McCain campaign hopes
to energize these Catholic voters, spurring them on to protest
Bush's Bob Jones visit with a vote on behalf of McCain Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Religion and politics are intricately intertwined in the race
for the Republican nomination for president this year. Although
both Bush and McCain oppose the practice of abortion, the National
Right to Life has backed Bush and opposed McCain, informing people
in phone calls throughout South Carolina and now Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the two campaigns volleyed accusations about telephone
campaigns that turn on accusations of religious intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   First, the McCain camp said it had uncovered evidence _ on the
answering machine of a McCain voter _ that the Reverend Pat
Robertson has taped a message that is being played for voters
across this state urging them to vote against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protect unborn babies and restore religious freedom once again
in America,'' Robertson says. ``Tomorrow's Republican primary may
determine whether our dream becomes reality or whether the
Republican Party will nominate a man who wants to take First
Amendment freedoms from citizens groups while he gives unrestricted
power to labor unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also slams McCain for choosing former New Hampshire
Senator Warren Rudman as his national chairman, calling him ``a
vicious bigot who wrote that conservative Christians in politics
are anti-abortion zealots, homophobes and would-be censors.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a message that drew a sharp rebuke from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous. It's disgraceful. Pat Robertson should go
back to wherever he came from,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two Michigan women reportedly called the Bush
campaign to say that they had receive taped messages that broadly
characterized Bush as anti-Catholic, for having made the Bob Jones
visit, and McCain as a friend to Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The latest point-counterpoint comes after a South Carolina
campaign in which religion proved a powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Sanford, the wife of South Carolina Rep. Mark Sanford,
called McCain Monday to tell him that churches throughout her state
had told parisioners last weekend that they should not support a
man who's wife is a drug addict. Cindy McCain, the senator's wife,
was once addicted to perscription painkillers after suffering from
chronic back problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Bush took umbrage at suggestions that he might be
anti-Catholic, when Rep. Peter King, the New York Republican,
switched allegiances to McCain. King said he was offended as a
Roman Catholic by the governor's visit to Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   ``That to me just showed a willingness to take any road to the
White House,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is a Methodist, denounced the inference that he is
biased against Catholics, noting that his younger brother practices
Catholicism. At his side was Governor John Engler, a Catholic, who
vouched for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Catholic voters in Michigan have been paying close
enough attention to the Bob Jones debate in the final 48 hours
before the primary remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue for McCain and Bush is with those moderate
Catholics,'' said John C. Green, an expert on politics and religion
at the University of Akron. ``Are they going to vote in that
Republican primary and how are they going to react to this
controversy?''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Schlesinger, an emeritus political science professor
at Michigan State University, said he does not believe Catholic
voters are a distinct voting bloc. Many, in fact, are liberal and
vote Democratic, while others are more conservative and vote
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of them know anything about Bob Jones University, I
don't know,'' Schlesinger said.
</P>
<P>
   But Green warned that while McCain tries to energize Catholics,
he may inadvertently fire up the Christian right here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were advising Senator McCain, I would say, `Be very
careful about the rhetoric,' '' Green said. ``That 13 to 17 percent
in Michigan could be decisive in a close election, and that group
could get really irritated by that language.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
