<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-GRAMMYS22-COX     02-21 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's `Smooth' sailing for Santana at Grammys
 &HT;    By Michael Corcoran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here we go again. It's time for that annual act
of shooting minnows in a horse trough known as predicting the
Grammys. Last year I made the mistake of thinking the Grammy voters
were as sick of that ``Titanic'' song as the rest of us, and I got
slaughtered. More than half of the readers who took up the ``Beat
the Critic'' challenge bested my 7-9 record, and we, briefly,
considered changing the name of this exercise to ``Pummel the
Pundit.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's gonna be different, my friends. I think I might be
able to pick the winner in every one of these major categories. I
can at least write the headline for the morning after the Wednesday
evening awards ceremony. ``Widespread Hispanic'' is a little
esoteric, so it'll just say ``Ole!'' after Grammy signals this as
the ``Year of the Latino.'' Look for Carlos Santana to pull an Eric
Clapton and walk away with a lifetime of golden gramophones in one
night. The only bit of suspense is which God he's going to thank.
</P>
<P>
   RECORD OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   ``I Want It That Way,'' Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe,'' Cher
</P>
<P>
   ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' Ricky Martin
</P>
<P>
   ``Smooth,'' Santana Featuring Rob Thomas
</P>
<P>
   ``No Scrubs,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   And the winner will be: ``Smooth.'' Capping off Santana's night
of ``Smooth'' sailing will be this well-deserved nod for the song
that was No. 1 for 12 consecutive weeks. A possible upset could be
the omnipresent ``Livin' La Vida Loca.'' Last year's Grammys
telecast was Martin's coming out party of sorts, and the grateful
National Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences could reward him for
this kernel of catchiness.
</P>
<P>
   ALBUM OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium,'' Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly,'' Dixie Chicks
</P>
<P>
   ``When I Look In Your Eyes,'' Diana Krall
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' Santana
</P>
<P>
   ``Fanmail,'' TLC
</P>
<P>
   And the winner will be: Santana. There's absolutely no contest.
A brilliant guitarist for more than 30 years, Carlos Santana put it
together on an album that just sounds better than everything else.
What's more, the record was a career triumph for Clive Davis, the
Arista chief who was rumored to be on his way out around balloting
time.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NEW ARTIST
</P>
<P>
   Christina Aguilera
</P>
