<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MICHIGAN22-COX     02-21 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush backs off McCain heading into Michigan primary
 &HT;    By William Hershey and Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Arizona Sen. John McCain, the former Navy
fighter pilot, continued blasting away at George W. Bush on Monday,
while Bush, in contrast to his South Carolina campaign, labored to
avoid attacking his chief rival as the Republicans finished up two
frenetic days of campaigning leading up to today's Michigan
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll released by WDIV-TV in Detroit showed the race
to be a statistical dead heat going into today's voting. McCain led
Bush 46-42, based on weekend interviews conducted with 500 likely
voters. The margin of error was plus or minus 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A similar poll conducted by the station before Saturday's South
Carolina primary _ which Bush won decisively _ showed McCain
leading 46-38.
</P>
<P>
   With such a close margin between the two Republicans, a
statewide backlash against a third _ Michigan Gov. John Engler _
could have consequences for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by mostly black, mostly Democratic Detroit, voters are
promising to turn out en masse to vote against Bush only because he
is being supported by Engler.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it will send a message to Engler to vote for McCain, I
will,'' said autoworker Sheila McCaulley, a Detroit Democrat who
said she plans to vote in the GOP primary today.
</P>
<P>
   McCain pinned his hopes here on a big turnout, which would
include crossover votes from Democrats such as McCaulley who are
free to vote in today's GOP primary under Michigan law.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a very large turnout, there's not a doubt in my
mind, we'll win,'' McCain said Monday evening to about 200 people
near Detroit, before flying off to Arizona, which also has a GOP
primary today.
</P>
<P>
   Engler's decision to turn control of the Detroit public schools
over to a board appointed by the mayor drew widespread wrath among
residents. They also object to Engler's decision to merge two local
court systems and his signing of a bill that did away with
residency requirements for city employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a lifetime Detroiter, I feel real disrespected at this
point,'' said Carol Banks, 39, as she handed out leaflets urging an
anti-Engler vote for McCain. ``I think the only way we're going to
send a message is to let him know that our votes do count.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Engler has used the Democratic pro-McCain strategy
as a walk-up call to Republicans to get out and vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your help is urgently needed because some of Al Gore's
supporters here in Michigan ... plan to interfere with our ...
primary,'' Engler wrote to Bush supporters recently.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, spent Monday in populous southeastern Michigan,
greeting workers at a Detroit factory, addressing a breakfast
meeting of The Economic Club of Detroit and a President's Day rally
at Michigan State University, and working the crowd at a restaurant
in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he invoked his South Carolina win and, except
when pressed by reporters, took swipes at Vice President Al Gore
rather than McCain.
</P>
<P>
   While both candidates want to win in Michigan _ the first state
in the nominating process that provides a microcosm of the nation _
a victory is more important to McCain than Bush, said political
scientist John Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute of
Applied Politics at the University of Akron.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's credibility as a successful insurgent took a big hit
when Bush defeated him soundly in South Carolina, Green said. He
needs to regain the momentum that began with his victory in New
Hampshire if he wants to successfully compete March 7, when 12
states _ including Ohio, New York and California _ hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's first stop Monday was the town meeting in Traverse
City, in northern Michigan, where he depicted Bush as a
mean-spirited campaigner who will stoop to anything, even character
assassination, to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reject the negative campaigning. Reject the character
assassination. Reject the low road to the presidency,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was out early, shaking hands at the American Axle &AMP;
Manufacturing plant in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a blue ``Gov. George W. Bush'' windbreaker under a wool
dress coat, he bounded off the bus and moved inside to the factory
lobby to talk with workers.
</P>
<P>
   He continued the upbeat mood later at a packed GOP President's
Day rally at Michigan State University in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel victory here in Michigan,'' he told the crowd. ``It's
voting time in Michigan. It's time for the people of this state to
stand up and say, `Tomorrow is the beginning of the end of the
Clinton-Gore era in Washington, D.C.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving in Michigan, Bush has tried to avoid attacks on
McCain, answering reporters' questions about McCain's recent
remarks, but not broaching the subject himself. That's in stark
contrast to the bitterly fought South Carolina battle where Bush
began daily news conferences by attacking his main Republican
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't duck McCain completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Senator McCain wants to make sure that there is campaign
funding reform, what he ought to do is stand up and put his
contributors on the Internet,'' Bush said in answer to a reporter's
question. ``... And he ought to support my calls for banning
contributions from federal lobbyists to members of the legislature
during legislative sessions. You know, he talks about the Iron
Triangle in Washington, D.C. He's been ringing that Iron Triangle
like a dinner bell raising the money from lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush softened his tone when asked if he would consider McCain as
a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain does not want me talking about him in terms of the
vice presidency,'' Bush said. ``He's running for president. So long
as he's a viable presidential candidate, I think he deserves the
respect of not being talked about in terms of the vice
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he could, Bush saved his scorn for Gore _ a nod more to
the general election in November than to today's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to Vice President Al Gore coming into your city
to explain to the workers why his statements about the automobile
industry make sense,'' Bush told roughly 1,200 people at The
Economic Club of Detroit. ``I look forward to him standing up there
and saying, `You know, my vision for America is one that you won't
be working.'''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1992 book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' Gore called for
eliminating the internal combustion engine within 25 years _
perhaps a tough sell in the Motor City.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
