<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VA-MURDER-ART-2TAKES-     02-21 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-MURDER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 RULING RENEWS INTEREST IN MYSTERIOUS 1992 DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ If Roger Zygmunt Comte de la Burde had been
found dead in his Jaguar or Mercedes Benz downtown on Broad Street,
David M. Riley, a senior special agent of the Virginia State
Police, said, ``the whole world would have been a suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the victims of his shady art and real-estate deals as
detailed in court records. There were his enemies, whether real or
perceived, at his former employer, Philip Morris. There were his
many women, including an ex-wife, a lover, and a married biochemist
who was carrying his baby, not to mention the woman's disapproving
husband.
</P>
<P>
   But de la Burde, a 60-year-old Polish emigre, tobacco-research
scientist and collector of African art whose pedigree was as
suspect as the paintings he aged in the rain on his roof, did not
die on the streets of Richmond. He died at Windsor, his 220-acre
estate, under circumstances that greatly narrowed the list of
possible suspects. He died on a couch in his library under icons of
Eshu, a Nigerian deity of chaos, with a bullet in the head from his
own revolver found in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case is under judicial review, the violent end of
the enigmatic de la Burde seems as much a riddle as ever. Was it
murder? Or was it suicide?
</P>
<P>
   If it was murder, a murder driven by jealousy and greed as a
jury concluded, the killer, to the satisfaction of Riley, is
serving 22 years in the Pocahontas Correctional Center in
Chesterfield.
</P>
<P>
   If it was suicide, the same prisoner _ Beverly Anne Monroe, an
organic chemist and mother of three who ended her marriage for de
la Burde and became his closest companion for 12 years _ is a
victim of a miscarriage of justice stemming from admissions coerced
by Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, years after the 1992 shooting and trial, a judicial ruling
on an appeal by Monroe's family has renewed interest in the case.
Last April, a federal judge in Richmond, Richard L. Williams,
questioned whether her conviction had been justified, and he has
given the defense an opportunity to present evidence questioning
whether prosecutors had established her guilt beyond a reasonable
doubt and whether her constitutional rights to counsel had been
violated. The findings could come sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Monroe, put herself at the setting of her
lover's death. She said they had dinner, worked on an art-book
manuscript and kissed goodbye hours before he took his life in
despair over failing health and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Riley focused quickly on Monroe in what he believed was a murder
and, after she flunked a polygraph examination, presented her with
his idea of what happened: that she had been present during the
shooting but had blocked it from her mind. Eventually she agreed
with him, and prosecutors then charged her with murder, although no
forensic evidence tied her to the shooting and she had an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not kill Roger,'' Monroe, 62, said in a recent prison
interview, reiterating the innocence she has maintained over the
years. ``I loved Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   Her supporters, led by a daughter who has devoted her legal
career to vindicating her mother, include Richard A. Leo, a
professor of criminology and psychology at the University of
California at Irvine and a specialist in police interrogations,
confessions and wrongful convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most outrageous cases I've ever seen,'' said
Leo, accusing Riley of crossing the line from permissible police
deception into illegal intimidation. Leo characterized Monroe as
someone who begins ``to imagine they could have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he was precluded from discussing the case but offered
no apologies for the conviction of a defendant he has portrayed as
a clever actress who, when shortchanged in de la Burde's latest
will and spurned for a pregnant rival, turned to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the testimony concerned the convoluted doings of de la
Burde, a man consumed by art, music, science, business and romance.
</P>
<P>
   He had boasted that he was the descendant of a royal overseer of
tradesmen in 14th-century Paris, but The Richmond Times-Dispatch
uncovered some discrepancies in his claim. He also said that he had
fled Poland in the 1950s and married a West German pediatrician and
that they had two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually settled in Richmond, where his background in
organic chemistry landed him a research job with Philip Morris in
1961. He stayed with the company until 1987.
</P>
<P>
   From 1968 to 1969, de la Burde also served as a U.N. technical
adviser to Nigeria, where he acquired tribal sculpture which he
later claimed to a writer for the journal ``African Arts'' had been
collected by his father before World War I. A curator for the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Susan Vogel, later found evidence
contradicting the claim.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, witnesses testified, he was trading in suspect
art. A stone carver, Frank Vegas, said he was employed to produce
fakes of well-known sculptures which de la Burde then donated as
originals to Radford University, the alma mater of one of his
daughters, Corinna. The FBI confirmed that there had been an
investigation but said it was dropped after de la Burde's death.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Monroe, meanwhile, had grown up on a farm in South
Carolina and obtained a degree in organic chemistry. She married a
scientist and had two daughters and a son.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1979, Monroe was hired by Philip Morris to work in the
patents department. She soon met de la Burde and they began an
affair. She and her husband, Stuart, separated in 1981, and de la
Burde and his wife, Brigette, split up not long after.
</P>
<P>
   At Philip Morris, de la Burde had developed a carbon dioxide
process to expand tobacco, which the company later acknowledged
saved about $300 million from 1979 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was cheated out of promised rewards, de la Burde sued,
and Philip Morris countersued, accusing him of threatening to
disclose ``certain confidential information and documents.'' The
lawsuit was settled with a payment to his estate and a return of
documents after his death.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, meanwhile, court testimony established, de la
Burde had affairs with co-workers and a married biochemist,
Krystyna Drewnowska. Consumed by a desire for a male heir, he
contracted with Drewnowska for a child. Monroe, learning of the
unorthodox arrangement, informed Drewnowska's husband, Wojtek.
Drewnowska gave birth to a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors seeking to show that Monroe was angry enough to kill
later produced a letter, written in 1990, in which she berated de
la Burde for his unfaithfulness.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of March 4, 1992, as Monroe told it, she left
Windsor about 9:30 p.m. and drove home, stopping for gas. Arriving
about 10 p.m., she said, she talked to her son, Gavin, and drove to
a Safeway store. She said she tried to call de la Burde but he did
not answer.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, she said, she decided to pass by Windsor,
where she and the caretaker found him on a couch, with a
.38-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson gun in his right hand and a bullet wound
above his right eye. In checking for a pulse, the caretaker later
recalled, he might have dislodged the gun.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The death scene was compromised in other ways, police witnesses
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe told investigators that de la Burde had been depressed.
But other witnesses insisted that he had been making plans _
including a sexual threesome for later that week _ and that
jealousy had unhinged Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Riley quickly focused on Monroe, suspecting that although no
fingerprints or other forensic evidence tied her to the shooting,
she had wielded the gun and then planted it in de la Burde's hand.
</P>
<P>
   He remained skeptical of her claim, which was supported by a
Safeway receipt stamped 10:40 p.m. _ around the time de la Burde
was first believed to have died _ and a canceled check to the
store, that she had left de la Burde alive, since he made a
telephone call around 10 p.m. Later an eyewitness from the store
came forward as well. Prosecutors countered that Monroe could have
returned to Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the death, Riley asked Monroe to take a
polygraph examination. Monroe waived her right to a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was naive and stupid,'' she said in an interview.
But she said she had been taught to cooperate with the police and
felt she had nothing to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe was told that her responses had indicated that she was
not telling the truth. Then Riley pressed her to acknowledge that
she might have been present when de la Burde shot himself.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as Riley later testified, he had forgotten to restart
the tape recorder, most of Monroe's responses were not recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Police witnesses later testified that Monroe acknowledged being
present, but Riley was unable to get her to say that on tape after
restarting the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Amid prosecution pressure for a confession, Riley testified that
he arranged to meet Monroe again on June 3, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Again the exchange was not taped. But at the end, after an
encounter that was later portrayed by Monroe as intimidating and by
Riley as congenial, he wrote a series of statements to which Monroe
put her signature. They began: ``I was on the sofa. Roger was on
the other sofa. A noise made me jump. I don't recall getting up. I
recall standing over Roger who was on the sofa and seeing the
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   But then the statements veered into the hypothetical: ``The
above I remember clearly but I don't remember exactly what happened
next, but I do know that having seen Roger in that circumstance my
natural reaction would be (not knowing whether he was alive or dead
at that instant) to try to stop him and that reaction would have
been to try to take the gun away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My next reaction would be (upon realizing he was dead) to put
back the gun. It would be natural to have put the gun back where I
thought it had been or where it would appear it should have been
considering the position of his body. It would have been natural
for anyone realizing they shouldn't have touched the gun to have
wiped it off before putting it back.''
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of both sides, the jury took only two hours and
55 minutes to find Monroe guilty. She posted bail to remain free
during appeal but in March 1996 began serving her 22-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Williams granted defense depositions on six issues,
including whether prosecutors relied on statements by Monroe that
were involuntary and in violation of her constitutional rights, and
whether prosecutors erred in failing to disclose a witness who saw
a black Bronco speeding out of Windsor's driveway on the night of
the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general the court is impressed with the substance of many
of Monroe's claims,'' Williams wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
