<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CHANGING TO `SMALL BALL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ These are strange times for that ballclub
forever known as the Arsenal in Arlington. Partly by design, partly
by surprise, the Rangers have opened this Florida camp committed to
a nuclear-disarmament program.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, and generally to the detriment of all else, the
big-bang theory had become a franchise trademark. Over the years,
and the decades, the game plan was pretty simple: Let somebody hit
a three-run homer, and then pray the bullpen could hold an 8-7
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, baseball in Arlington may have to be a case of
mind over muscle. And for that to happen, and if it's going to be
successful, then manager Johnny Oates says the transformation will
have to begin right here in the Charlotte County swamps.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of six weeks of spring training, what Oates has promised
will be more like a baseball version of sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, men, is what's called the bunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw the bunt sign, I remember it well,'' left
fielder Rusty Greer said yesterday. ``It was two years ago, and I
struck out on three pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat scary is that under this new concept, Greer will be
considered one of the team's better bunters.
</P>
<P>
   Oates: ``Once we begin the games down here \RMarch 3\S, every
player in our lineup will be bunting, and every player will be on
his own \Ron the bases\S. I want to find out right now who can
bunt, who can possibly steal a base, who can hit-and-run, and so
on. We are going to need all this later on.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``small ball'' game, of course, will be a radical change for
the Rangers. But if it actually works, it will also be a positive
change, as long as the other component of ``small ball'' is in
place. Which means better pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Big, hulking first baseman-DH Lee Stevens was sitting beside
Greer in the clubhouse yesterday after a morning workout. Stevens
said it was also two years ago when he last saw a bunt sign from
Oates. ``The funny thing was, I had homered the bat before,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``But while every one thinks it's a given we won't be scoring
runs like we always have,'' continued Stevens, ``what if our
pitching is better? What if our staff ERA drops a full run, which
it could? That means over the season, we'd give up 162 less runs.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, is the way the Rangers are promoting the
2000 season. Less pop, much-better pitching.
</P>
<P>
   How much better pitching, well... that's a promising concept, at
least.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the last two postseason offensive
disasters against the Yankees hammered home the oldest point in
baseball: Nobody outscores good pitching. Leading the world in
almost every offensive category, as the Rangers did in 1999,
resulted in one whole run in 27 innings last October. And the
October before that, there had also been one run in 27 innings
against the same Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it was time to try something else, but neither general
manager Doug Melvin nor Oates planned it exactly this way. In other
words, the change is more drastic than they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Juan Gonzalez was by design. In the name of preventing a
long-term salary problem, Melvin moved out Juan last November in a
deal with Detroit that has been hailed throughout baseball as
shrewd. Actually, it's Melvin himself who is repeatedly advising
caution in judging that trade ``because you don't give up Juan's
run production and his presence] in a lineup without a lot of
sleepless nights,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin wanted the big-bang drain to stop right there.
Nothing was on his drawing board about also losing third baseman
Todd Zeile. In a shocker to Melvin, he suddenly learned Zeile
wouldn't be accepting the contract Melvin thought Zeile had
accepted. Instead, Zeile was gone to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Between Juan and Todd, that's a combined 63 homers and 226 RBI
from 1999 that won't be reporting here this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find ways, and manufacture ways, to make up what we
no longer have,'' said Oates, known as a managerial disciple of the
great Earl Weaver. And Weaver lived by the doctrine of ``pitching,
defense and the three-run homer.'' In other words, Weaver would
have given up smoking before he'd dare bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make chicken salad if you don't have any chickens,''
added Oates. ``I will never know if Juan could bunt because I never
wanted to find out. But I like to think I can adjust to the talent
I've been given.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the adjusting starts immediately; from the big bang to
the little bunt, the Rangers are very different this spring.
Better? Don't know. But definitely different, and two runs in two
Octobers says it was time to try another way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
