<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-449&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BREAKTHROUGH EXPECTED IN BOEING STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Representatives of Boeing Co. and its striking engineers and
technical workers are expected to meet separately with federal
mediators this week amid signs that tension between the two groups
is escalating.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's 17,000 engineers and technical workers, represented by
the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace
union, walked off their jobs Feb. 9 after contract negotiations
broke down over wages and health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bofferding, the executive director of the Society of
Professional Engineering Employees, said that he expected to meet
with federal mediators Tuesday but did not expect an imminent
breakthrough in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason as of yet to have a joint meeting with
Boeing,'' Bofferding said. ``But I share that view'' (of some Wall
Street analysts) ``that our differences in the contract dispute
with Boeing are not that far apart. I don't understand why Boeing
doesn't say, `Let's work together to solve this.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Conte, a Boeing spokesman, said the company was willing to
speak with federal mediators, but had no scheduled meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations Monday, neither Boeing nor its engineers
appeared willing to back away from sticking points in their
bargaining positions. The union, which represents 22,000 engineers
and technical workers at Boeing, has demanded guaranteed wage
increases and a bonus plan similar to the one that the company
granted last year to its machinists. As a group, the machinists
should receive bonus pay of about $4,400 each.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has refused to grant the bonus plan to its engineers. The
company has proposed to set up three funds for merit raises. The
engineers would receive increases of about 8 percent during the
first year of the contract, while technical workers would receive 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Conte said Monday that Boeing was willing to negotiate with the
union but not on any of their new demands, including a bonus plan.
</P>
<P>
   That remark riled Bofferding, who said, ``Well, if that's true,
then we don't have much to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Condit, the chairman of Boeing, said last week that the
company could maintain its position in the strike for a long time.
Union officials have echoed similar sentiments, but both groups
have begun to feel the effects of the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Since the strike began, Boeing has missed scheduled deliveries
on seven jetliners. The company delivered one last week and three
others over the weekend. Two more jets were expected to be
delivered Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has also frightened Boeing's investors. After
approaching a 52-week high of $47.625 in mid-January, Boeing's
stock has tumbled 24.4 percent to close Friday at $36 a share.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Boeing's engineers have also begun to feel the pinch of lost
paychecks. The union, which had no strike fund, has raised about
$70,000, largely through donations, to help overcome its members'
hardships. Bofferding said Monday that the fund has already paid
one member's power bill and other disbursements would be made as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had warned that a drawn-out dispute could damage morale
at Boeing, just when the company's commercial jet division had
begun to show signs of a financial recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of ill will are becoming increasingly evident. Union
officials have said that if they are forced to return to work, they
will begin a ``work to rule'' campaign to stall operations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's striking engineers were also skeptical about the
company's recent claims that it had delivered jets. Boeing has
admitted that the strike has lengthened the time it takes to have
engineering processes certified by qualified engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Bofferding noted that all but 24 of Boeing's 416 designated
engineering representatives, who certify the planes, are on strike.
The certification process, Bofferding said, usually requires 50
engineers for each plane.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said that it has enough engineers, who are not on
strike, to complete the certifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boeing is delivering planes, then we don't know how they're
doing it,'' Bofferding said. ``They don't have enough engineers.
The ones they have must be spread around like a dog's breakfast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
