<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CARSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEE CARSON, 70, PIANIST IN COUNT BASIE ORCHESTRA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (kd) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald Tecumseh (Tee) Carson, who inherited the piano chair from
Count Basie after the band leader's health failed, died on Feb. 13
at his home in Cedar Park, Texas. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lung cancer, said Shirley Cason, his sister.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his career as a jazz musician, Carson was a U.S.
marshal working at the Justice Department on surveillance duty. He
retired from the department in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, when Count Basie's health problems began,
Carson started to fill in occasionally as pianist. He was something
of a Basie protege, having a similarly self-editing, bare-bones
rhythmic style.
</P>
<P>
   When Basie died in 1984, Carson became the band's pianist,
playing in the posthumous Count Basie Orchestra alongside such jazz
luminaries as the saxophonist Frank Foster and the longtime Basie
guitarist Freddie Green.
</P>
<P>
   John S. Wilson, writing in The New York Times about a 1985
performance of the Basie orchestra under the direction of Eric
Dixon, said that Carson ``manages to suggest Basie's manner without
adopting it, using single-note lines that are a variant of Basie's
lines, and dropping gentle but propitious chords behind the
soloists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s Carson recorded with the Basie band as well as
with the saxophonists Frank Wess and Richie Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Washington, Carson became an electronics engineer at the
Federal Aviation Administration in the early 1950s and joined the
Army in the mid-'50s.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the Washington area in the late '70s, he lived in San
Francisco for a time, where he played jazz and was a jazz disc
jockey on WCSM.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his sister, of Fairfax, Va., Carson is survived
by his wife, Robin LaStofka Carson; two daughters, Ja Don Carson of
Las Vegas and Jan Hill of Boise, Idaho; a son, Donald, of Austin,
Texas; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     02-21 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO LONGER MISSING FROM NBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Los Angeles Clippers were being introduced
at the Garden on Monday, you heard, ``the assistant coaches, Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar. ...'' And there he was near the bench, holding a
clipboard, standing tall and slim in a gray double-breasted suit,
his dome shaved slick, his mustache and goatee flecked with gray.
</P>
<P>
   His name provoked a quick cheer that might have been even louder
had more people realized he was hired last Friday after a decade as
pro basketball's missing person.
</P>
<P>
   After having been the 7-foot-2-inch center of gravity on six
National Basketball Association championship teams, a six-time
winner of the most valuable player award and the career scoring
leader with a total of 38,387 points and another 5,762 in the
playoffs, he had all but disappeared from the NBA planet.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Abdul-Jabbar was missing by choice. He wrote three
books, lectured, worked as an actor and film producer, signed
card-show memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very burned out when I retired,'' he was saying now
about leaving the Los Angeles Lakers. ``It took me three or four
years to get a sense of equilibrium back.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Abdul-Jabbar realized that he wanted to coach, that
basketball was still in his blood. But whenever he tried to get a
coaching job, nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Mr. Sterling once or twice two or three years
ago,'' he said, referring to the Clippers' owner. ``I talked to
some of the NBA general managers: Al Attles, Wes Unseld, Wayne
Embry, Ernie Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the chancellor at UCLA when Jim Harrick was in a
bind there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his reputation as aloof and moody still lingered.
</P>
<P>
   Had he felt blackballed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken aback by why I couldn't get interviews,''
Abdul-Jabbar said. ``That bothered me. I talked with Willis Reed at
the Nets and he was very encouraging, but I never heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In his frustration, he spent five months last year helping to
coach high school boys on the White Mountain Apache Reservation in
Whitewater, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoops was not what that was about,'' he said. ``It was about
teaching them how to lead productive lives, to go to college. A lot
of the kids there didn't want to leave the reservation. They don't
think they can cope with the world outside the reservation. One of
those kids is now in college in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, last Friday, the Clippers hired him.
</P>
<P>
   By joining the Clippers at age 52 as an assistant (along with
Dennis Johnson) to Jim Todd, the recently appointed head coach,
Abdul-Jabbar was obviously willing to start at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their 16-season existence, the Clippers have been the
NBA's worst franchise. Including Monday's 87-76 loss to the Knicks,
they have lost 11 in a row. Their 11-43 record is the worst in the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole lot about the game is not being translated,''
Abdul-Jabbar said. ``Young guys don't know how to do things I
learned in high school. They've got size and agility, but they
don't know how to get it done with four other guys. How to play
defense. How to help teammates on defense. How to be instinctive on
offense when you see the opportunity. They don't stay in college
long enough to learn how.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom, the Clippers' prize rookie, whom he described as a
``giant Swiss Army knife; he can do everything,'' played only one
season at Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the money,'' he said. ``These kids dream of
being wealthy, but they don't understand the game. And college is
losing its best players. It's something the NBA, the NCAA and the
AAU has to address.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged having learned ``everything'' about basketball
from John Wooden in his three championship seasons at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Wooden taught the mental approach to the game, what the
team knew as a group,'' he said. ``You have to practice that way.
Of my pro coaches, the guy that really impressed me was Jack
McKinney, who was only with the Lakers for a few months when he had
a bicycle accident and couldn't coach anymore. He understood the
game and the players.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Pat Riley, his longtime Lakers coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``He had three different incarnations,'' Abdul-Jabbar said. ``He
changed. Sometimes success has its problems. I'm not putting him
down. He had a lot to cope with.''
</P>
<P>
   And did Kareem Abdul-Jabbar hope to be a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do this well,'' he said, ``and ultimately. . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
