<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3893 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-MOOD-1STLD-WRI     02-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MOOD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TRIES TO RECOVER MOMENTUM IN MICHIGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, In the end ... with 2 grafs to ADD first
reference for Weaver and tighten.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT4, 5, 7, 10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain's high command huddled
conspiratorially in the darkened aisle of his campaign plane on
Sunday night, plotting their latest move to stop Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They fretted that Bush had been scheduled to appear first on
NBC's ``Today'' program on Monday, followed by McCain. No way, they
decided. McCain would go first on the highest rated morning program
_ or defect to ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's political director, uttered an expletive
about the Bush campaign, and added, ``That's what it's come down
to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, McCain prevailed and Bush wound up on ``Good Morning
America.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a minor triumph for a presidential candidate who
after his convincing win in New Hampshire has not had to scrap for
position on the morning programs. Only two weeks ago, his beaming
face was emblazoned on the cover of Time and Newsweek; this week,
it is Bush staring resolutely from both covers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of the primary here on Tuesday, McCain and his
aides are still thunderstruck by their loss to Bush in South
Carolina three days ago _ the first defeat of the senator's
political career.
</P>
<P>
   Inside McCain's famously chatty bus, the afterglow of New
Hampshire is dimming by the day. Despite friendly crowds from
Traverse City to Grand Rapids to here in Saginaw _ and polls that
show the Republican rivals neck and neck in Michigan _ McCain and
his aides were revisiting what might have been. They said that
while they got too mired in tactics in New Hampshire and did not
adequately respond to the governor's onslaught of advertising and
oratory, they are still struggling to grasp what went awry.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his prediction before the South Carolina primary
that a high turnout would assure a win for McCain, Weaver _ who
just days ago was being hailed in the press for his political
deftness _ confessed, `'Obviously, we didn't know what we were
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Bush's victory was not even close, as polls had
predicted, Rick Davis, the campaign manager, said, ``Everyone ought
to be firing their pollsters.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, McCain refuses to yield, acknowledging that ``we took
a shot to the stomach,'' but reminding audiences that he has
``crashed a few airplanes'' and knows how to recuperate. As he put
it at a packed rally Monday morning in Traverse City, ``I'm telling
you, we're coming back! We're coming back!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of McCain's upbeat talk about primaries next month
in possibly friendly territory, like California and New England _
``I still think this thing will be decided by March 7,'' the
senator told reporters on his bus _ two senior campaign officials
said privately that their hopes of snatching the Republican
nomination would be effectively over if he does not win here.
</P>
<P>
   The big quandary for McCain is how to make up his mind over how
aggressively to respond to the relentless 30-second broadsides from
Bush that started in South Carolina and are continuing here.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in South Carolina fresh from New Hampshire,
McCain announced that unlike Bill Bradley in the Democratic race,
he had no qualms about defending himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Bradley campaign,'' he said then. ``We will
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   But days later, McCain pulled a commercial questioning Bush's
trustworthiness _ and comparing him to President Clinton _ and he
has essentially ceded the airwaves to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Michigan, McCain has faced the very conundrum Bradley
has in his battle with Vice President Al Gore: If he goes on the
attack, McCain undermines his theme that he is a reformer who will
not stoop to going negative. Yet, by not attacking, McCain allows
Bush to define him.
</P>
<P>
   So McCain has settled on a strategy in which he came out
swinging at Bush at stop after stop in Michigan, saying if Bush is
really a reformer, than ``I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has not dared run television commercials that denounce
Bush, even as the governor is running his own advertisements
pounding McCain's record. It is a somewhat ambivalent approach _
and one that is strikingly reminiscent of the high-minded tone of
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the guy doesn't want to run a negative ad,'' said Greg
Stevens, McCain's media adviser. ``Does it make me a little edgy?
Nervous? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The same conflicting impulses were on display in the senator's
truculent concession speech on Saturday night: He insisted that he
would ``keep fighting clear,'' even as he pounced on Bush _ without
citing him by name _ for a ``negative message of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, questioned aboard his bus, refused to acknowledge that
he had not followed his own counsel to avoid the trap Bradley put
himself in: ``I don't want 20 years from now when my kids are grown
and they're majoring in political science and they pick up a book,
`And so, John McCain, in South Carolina, out of desperation because
he was losing, launched negative attacks on George Bush.'''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to accuse the Bush campaign of dirty, negative
tactics. ``We all know what caused the loss,'' he said. ``I would
never be associated with people and the things that were done in
that race in South Carolina and I'm proud that we had nothing to do
with that kind of campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I probably didn't do as well as I should have or
could have. But do you think that would have made any difference? I
could have invented a cure for cancer and it couldn't have
mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, McCain acknowledged what his advisers
have said bluntly: ``Perhaps I should have defined myself a little
more as far as different positions on issues,'' he said. ``We're
doing more of that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator still harps on how offended he was when Bush held an
event in South Carolina at which a former prisoner of war
questioned whether he had sufficiently fought for veterans. And
Monday, the campaign distributed articles that cited the Bush
operation's under-the-radar efforts to crush him in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At campaign events here, the silver confetti still falls and the
disco music still pounds, but the loss in South Carolina is in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   In East Lansing, at a rally at Michigan State University, John
Schwarz, a state senator, sounded in his warm-up for the challenger
as if he had to justify his endorsement of McCain over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one defector on the Michigan Legislature,'' Schwarz
said. ``I'm  &UR; still  &LR; comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has tried mightily to persuade the press that his
campaign is not sputtering. ``By the way,'' he said on the bus
Sunday, ``small item: Since yesterday, there's an uptick in our
contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about the size of the uptick, McCain said it was ``like
ten or fifteen thousand'' dollars ``from what it was the day
before.'' But more than anything else, the sum underscores how the
dynamic has changed. After New Hampshire _ and before South
Carolina _ the campaign took in roughly $3 million on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also made sure to trumpet the endorsement of Rep. Peter King,
R-N.Y., who defected this week from the Bush camp. But on the eve
of South Carolina, some McCain aides had predicted that a win in
that state would have spurred countless big-name Republicans to
jump as well.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush's newfound potency has clearly addled the McCain camp.
Officials say they are bewildered at polls showing that South
Carolina voters now see the governor as the more genuine reformer.
And they admitted that their merry band of rebels would benefit
from some Republican reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really getting tired of being defended by Bill Press,''
Davis said of the co-moderator on the CNN program, ``Crossfire,'' a
former chairman of the California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain and his supporters are mindful that the days of an
exciting insurgency hinge on what happens here, now. The senator
cannot for much longer be introduced, he as was in East Lansing, as
``The winner of the New Hampshire primary by a landslide!''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he tries not to think too hard about his mistakes or
his prospects, though he quipped that ``I hum `Hail to the Chief' a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he fixes his thoughts on Bush, and what that win in South
Carolina might do for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have gotten some bounce,'' said the senator who had
hoped that bounce would be his. ``But who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0341 </DOCNO>
