<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-MOOD-1STLD-WRI     02-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MOOD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TRIES TO RECOVER MOMENTUM IN MICHIGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS 7th graf, When asked ..., to ADD first reference for
Weaver, McCain's pol'l director.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT4, 5, 7, 10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain's high command huddled
conspiratorially in the darkened aisle of his chartered campaign
plane on Sunday night, plotting their latest move to stop Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They fretted that Bush had been scheduled to appear first on
NBC's ``Today'' program on Monday, followed by McCain. No way, they
decided. McCain would go first on the highest rated morning program
_ or defect to ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, McCain prevailed and appeared on ``Today,'' accusing
Bush supporters of ``calling up little children and telling them
that John McCain is a thief and a liar.'' Bush wound up on ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch was a minor triumph for a presidential candidate who
after his whopping win in New Hampshire never had to scrap for
position on the morning programs. Only two weeks ago, his beaming
face was emblazoned on the cover of Time and Newsweek; this week,
it is Bush staring resolutely from both covers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of the primary here on Tuesday, McCain and his
aides are still thunderstruck by their loss to Bush in South
Carolina three days ago _ the first defeat of the senator's
political career.
</P>
<P>
   Inside McCain's famously chatty bus, the afterglow of New
Hampshire is dimming by the day. Despite friendly crowds from
Traverse City to Grand Rapids to here in Saginaw _ and polls that
show the Republican rivals neck and neck in Michigan _ McCain and
his aides were revisiting what might have been. They said that
while they got too mired in tactics in New Hampshire and did not
adequately respond to the governor's onslaught of advertising and
oratory, they are still struggling to grasp what went awry.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his prediction before the South Carolina
primary that a high turnout would assure a win for McCain, John
Weaver, McCain's political director _ who just days ago was being
hailed in the press for his political deftness _ confessed,
`'Obviously, we didn't know what we were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Bush's victory was not even close, as polls had
predicted, Rick Davis, the campaign manager, said, ``Everyone ought
to be firing their pollsters.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, McCain refuses to yield, acknowledging that ``we took
a shot to the stomach,'' but reminding audiences that he has
``crashed a few airplanes'' and knows how to recuperate. As he put
it at a packed rally Monday morning in Traverse City, ``I'm telling
you, we're coming back! We're coming back!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of McCain's upbeat talk about primaries next month
in possibly friendly territory, like California and New England _
``I still think this thing will be decided by March 7,'' the
senator told reporters on his bus _ two senior campaign officials
said privately that their hopes of snatching the Republican
nomination would be effectively over if he does not win here.
</P>
<P>
   The big quandary for McCain is how to make up his mind over how
aggressively to respond to the relentless 30-second broadsides from
Bush that started in South Carolina and are continuing here.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in South Carolina fresh from New Hampshire,
McCain announced that unlike Bill Bradley in the Democratic race,
he had no qualms about defending himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Bradley campaign,'' he said then. ``We will
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   But days later, McCain pulled a commercial questioning Bush's
trustworthiness _ and comparing him to President Clinton _ and he
has essentially ceded the airwaves to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Michigan, McCain has faced the very conundrum Bradley
has in his battle with Vice President Al Gore: If he goes on the
attack, McCain undermines his theme that he is a reformer who will
not stoop to going negative. Yet, by not attacking, McCain allows
Bush to define him.
</P>
<P>
   So McCain has settled on a strategy in which he came out
swinging at Bush at stop after stop in Michigan, saying if Bush is
really a reformer, than ``I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has not dared run television commercials that denounce
Bush, even as the governor is running his own advertisements
pounding McCain's record. It is a somewhat ambivalent approach _
and one that is strikingly reminiscent of the high-minded tone of
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the guy doesn't want to run a negative ad,'' said Greg
Stevens, McCain's media adviser. ``Does it make me a little edgy?
Nervous? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The same conflicting impulses were on display in the senator's
truculent concession speech on Saturday night: He insisted that he
would ``keep fighting clear,'' even as he pounced on Bush _ without
citing him by name _ for a ``negative message of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, questioned aboard his bus, refused to acknowledge that
he had not followed his own counsel to avoid the trap Bradley put
himself in: ``I don't want 20 years from now when my kids are grown
and they're majoring in political science and they pick up a book,
`And so, John McCain, in South Carolina, out of desperation because
he was losing, launched negative attacks on George Bush.'''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to accuse the Bush campaign of dirty, negative
tactics. ``We all know what caused the loss,'' he said. ``I would
never be associated with people and the things that were done in
that race in South Carolina and I'm proud that we had nothing to do
with that kind of campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I probably didn't do as well as I should have or
could have. But do you think that would have made any difference? I
could have invented a cure for cancer and it couldn't have
mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, McCain acknowledged what his advisers
have said bluntly: ``Perhaps I should have defined myself a little
more as far as different positions on issues,'' he said. ``We're
doing more of that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator still harps on how offended he was when Bush held an
event in South Carolina at which a former prisoner of war
questioned whether he had sufficiently fought for veterans. And
Monday, the campaign distributed articles that cited the Bush
operation's under-the-radar efforts to crush him in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At campaign events here, the silver confetti still falls and the
disco music still pounds, but the loss in South Carolina is in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   In East Lansing, at a rally at Michigan State University, John
Schwarz, a state senator, sounded in his warm-up for the challenger
as if he had to justify his endorsement of McCain over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one defector on the Michigan Legislature,'' Schwarz
said. ``I'm  &UR; still  &LR; comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has tried mightily to persuade the press that his
campaign is not sputtering. ``By the way,'' he said on the bus
Sunday, ``small item: Since yesterday, there's an uptick in our
contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about the size of the uptick, McCain said it was ``like
ten or fifteen thousand'' dollars ``from what it was the day
before.'' But more than anything else, the sum underscores how the
dynamic has changed. After New Hampshire _ and before South
Carolina _ the campaign took in roughly $3 million on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also made sure to trumpet the endorsement of Rep. Peter King,
R-N.Y., who defected this week from the Bush camp. But on the eve
of South Carolina, some McCain aides had predicted that a win in
that state would have spurred countless big-name Republicans to
jump as well.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush's newfound potency has clearly addled the McCain camp.
Officials say they are bewildered at polls showing that South
Carolina voters now see the governor as the more genuine reformer.
And they admitted that their merry band of rebels would benefit
from some Republican reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really getting tired of being defended by Bill Press,''
Davis said of the co-moderator on the CNN program, ``Crossfire,'' a
former chairman of the California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain and his supporters are mindful that the days of an
exciting insurgency hinge on what happens here, now. The senator
cannot for much longer be introduced, he as was in East Lansing, as
``The winner of the New Hampshire primary by a landslide!''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he tries not to think too hard about his mistakes or
his prospects, though he quipped that ``I hum `Hail to the Chief' a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he fixes his thoughts on Bush, and what that win in South
Carolina might do for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have gotten some bounce,'' said the senator who had
hoped that bounce would be his. ``But who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     02-21 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, FIXING HEADLINE0 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio)  
 HOTELS ARE RUSHING TO OPEN _ SOMETIMES BEFORE THE PAINT IS DRY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27)  
(af) 
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall I spent a night at the W Tuscany, a stylish, newly
refurbished hotel in New York. My room was comfortable, quiet and,
for the most part, smartly renovated. The lobby was another matter.
No one had warned me when I made my reservation that it was still
under construction. The elevators opened near a new front desk
still shrouded in packing wrap.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, the hotel set up a Continental breakfast in an
old sitting room next to the new lobby. As I poured my coffee, buzz
saws screamed and hammers pounded. I fled to my room, appalled but
not particularly surprised.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These are buoyant times for the hotel industry, with new
properties opening and old buildings being refurbished at a speedy
pace. But an increasing number of hotels are throwing open their
doors prematurely, taking in guests almost as soon as the ink dries
on the certificate of occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has become almost accepted practice for new hotels to
house guests before a restaurant or health club is complete, in
today's fervid climate it is not unusual to stay in a hotel with a
construction site for a lobby, padded elevators, and hallways
awaiting car-pets.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall I was shown a room at the Belleclaire, a renovated,
moderately priced hotel in New York, that had wires dangling where
the light fixture was supposed to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotels are so anxious to cash in on this boom that they
are being more aggressive about opening than they should,'' said
Chekitan Dev, a professor of marketing at Cornell University's
Hotel School. ``If a hotel stays closed for one more day, it loses
revenues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With fewer hotels and resorts owned by private individuals and
more by large corporations, the pressure to show returns quickly
has increased. ``If you've already given the analysts a projection
for third-quarter results and it includes that hotel, you're going
to want to make the money, even if it means alienating a few
guests,'' Dev said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel publications can add to the problem. If a hotel receives
a blaze of advance publicity, the management may be tempted to open
it even if not everything is ready. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as a soft opening, of accepting guests
before a hotel is finished isn't new and isn't always a problem.
Soft openings are the hotel equivalent of an out-of-town opening
for a Broadway play, a low-key period when management and staff can
correct mistakes before hundreds of guests arrive.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels stage soft openings for insiders, including friends,
members of the management, and travel operators, as knowledgeable
but sympathetic guests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once a hotel opens to the public, the management often limits
the number of guests until things run smoothly. ``Some places even
overstaff during soft openings, because they don't want people to
have a bad experience on their first visit,'' said James Eyster, a
professor emeritus at Cornell University's Hotel School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more accurate term for the recent rash of soft openings, which
can drag on for months, is under-construction openings. Since most
hotels lower their prices during construction, rooms can be a
bargain. But be sure to ask what services will be missing if you
stay in an unfinished hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what price they give, the property should tell you
up front there are no pros on the tennis court or there's a snack
bar but no restaurant,'' said Doris Schechter, a travel agent at
Valerie Wilson Travel in New York. Or that construction noise will
be starting at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   However you book _ by telephone or over the Internet _ find out
what to expect in the way of service cutbacks. And if a price seems
too good to be true, ask if you'll be rooming next to the guys with
buzz saws.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Construction is a complex process that can defy the best of
plans, which is one reason so many hotels are only partly
completed. ``You don't have to slip behind in your construction
schedule very much to have a problem,'' Richard Brush, a dean at
Johnson &AMP; Wales University, said. ``It could be a strike at the
furniture plant in North Carolina or a large building project that
uses up all the steel in the state.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Club Med in Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic,
which reopened the week before Christmas after an extensive
six-month renovation. ``We arrived to find huge mud puddles,
dangling electric wires, no stair lights, pathways not lit, dirt
everywhere and trucks creating clouds of dust,'' said Anne Sager of
New York, who had gone to the resort for a weeklong holiday with
her husband, their children and grandchildren from France, and a
son and his fiancee from California. Worse still, there was no
air-conditioning or hot water, and the toilets did not flush.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The resort offered a variety of compensations, including
transfers to other Club Med villages and lodging at another hotel
on the island with shuttle services to the resort for meals and
activities. Full and partial refunds, linked to whether guests
stayed, returned home or moved to another property, were also
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the resort failed to inform guests that the property
wasn't ready, Carole Boucard, a Club Med spokeswoman said: ``There
were last-minute delays that got us off the timetable, but we fully
expected to have things fixed by then.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel construction delays also marred a visit to New York for
Alan Hart and his wife from Akron, Ohio. After seeing a newspaper
ad, Hart booked a room at On the Ave, a new boutique hotel in New
York, for $135 a night. After receiving a written confirmation, he
paid for their flights and ordered opera tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Four days before they were to arrive, the Harts received a call
saying that because construction of two floors of the hotel had not
been completed, they could not stay. The caller suggested they stay
at the Habitat, an affiliated but less expensive hotel. Since many
Habitat rooms have shared baths, Hart declined and wound up paying
$320 a night for a room elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say a hotel should offer some compensation to a
guest if it can't honor its agreement to provide a room. ``The
generally accepted practice is to offer a complimentary or upgraded
room for one night at a hotel in your group,'' said Eyster of
Cornell. ``If you have to send the person to a more expensive hotel
outside your company, you pay the difference.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the policy at On the Ave, Ron Simoncini, a spokesman
for the hotel, described Hart's canceled reservation as an
embarrassment, but added that the policy is to provide a free room
at another hotel only if someone with a reservation shows up and
can't be accommodated. ``Part of the reason the prices are so low
right now is because the hotel is under construction,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When is the ideal time to try out a new or renovated hotel?
Schechter says she usually waits six months, especially if she is
sending a client to a resort. Knowing when to open a hotel can, in
fact, be something of an art.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wait for everything to be done, you'll never open,''
said Nancy Polley, a travel agent with Valerie Wilson Travel. ``But
once you open, you had better hop to and get things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
