<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ARIZ-REPUBS-755&AMP;ADD-N     02-21 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-REPUBS-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN HAS STRONG SUPPORT IN HIS HOME STATE  
(See also MCCAIN-MOOD) 
(lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The home-state headquarters of the campaign that John
McCain has called a crusade is a drab stucco office court known as
Camelot Square, and on Monday a hardy core of volunteer knights
errant like Bryan Erion, a 61-year-old Navy veteran, made a last
round of get-out-the-vote calls on the eve of the Arizona primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has represented us in Congress for 17 years, and now we
can show America that we need an Arizonan as president,'' Erion
read over and over again from the script in front of him, even when
the only answer was a machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has made our state proud in this campaign, and now we
need to make him proud by voting on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems little doubt that Arizonans will vote for McCain on
Tuesday. How proud they will make him is another question, since
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has spent considerable effort, and an
estimated $2 million on a television-advertising and direct-mail
blitz, aimed at embarrassing the Arizona senator by keeping him
from winning in the sort of blowout that native sons usually enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Talk radio in Phoenix buzzed on Monday with prognostications
about McCain's likely margin of victory, and what kind of win would
really be a win, and whether he could bounce back from his defeat
in South Carolina, and why his concession speech there had seemed
so sour.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk, too, of the famous McCain temper, and constant
reminders that the state's top Republican office-holder, Gov. Jane
Dee Hull, is backing Bush. In fact, she walked precincts for him on
Saturday, and also made a television advertisement that has been
broadcast heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less a question of Governor Bush getting a win than
Senator McCain avoiding a loss,'' Jay Heiler, a Bush supporter who
was chief of staff to former Gov. Fyfe Symington, said on ``High
Noon,'' a conservative talk show on KTKP-AM.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain does not win by 20 to 25 points, Heiler said, it will
be a blow. ``This is his layup, and if he doesn't make the layup,
he goes back to the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the latest poll by The Arizona Republic found McCain
leading by more than 20 points among registered Republicans, with a
margin of error of three percentage points. Other polls of likely
voters have given the senator an even larger edge, but on Monday
his campaign aides said the outcome depended entirely on turnout,
with a higher turnout being better for them.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in a strong sign of interest, a record number of
absentee ballots have been returned in Maricopa County, which
surrounds Phoenix, and some experts estimate that overall turnout
could reach 50 percent, up from the typical 35 percent in a
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta win the delegates, gotta win the delegates, gotta spend
no money, got it?'' said Wes Gullett, a McCain aide, summing up the
campaign's goal here, where even a one-point victory gives the
winner all 30 of the state's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a big turnout, we'll do well. A win is a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some polls last fall actually showed Bush with a slight
edge here, and although Steve Forbes, who carried the state four
years ago, had a large staff on the ground before dropping out, the
Arizona contest has never loomed as a particularly significant test
this year, precisely because of McCain's favorite-son status.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made no recent visit to the state, and even McCain was
not due to arrive until late Monday evening from Michigan for a
final rally at the University of Arizona in Tucson, before voting
Tuesday morning in Phoenix. The only visible signs of an election
were the small McCain signs studding the occasional front yard, and
Bush's commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advertisements have been on the air since December, but
McCain could afford only about $200,000 in radio advertisements
appealing to Arizonans' state pride, Gullett said, noting that he
had received five pieces of targeted mail from the Bush campaign in
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to South Carolina, where a variety of interest
groups ran independent advertising campaigns aimed at supporting
Bush, no such ads have run here, McCain aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Merrill, a pollster and political science professor at
Arizona State University in Tempe, said the Bush campaign appeared
to be purely an effort to show its financial strength and
establishment support.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were them, I'd take the money and go some place where it
could really help them,'' Merrill said. ``If McCain loses in
Michigan, he's done. I think he's done already, frankly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic, with whom McCain has long had an
adversarial relationship, in sharp contrast to his smooth sailing
with much of the national press this year, declined to endorse him,
or Bush, in an editorial on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to some reservations on domestic policy, we fear
that McCain's approach to politics doesn't fit the need or
temperament of the times,'' the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain too frequently is dismissive of those who disagree with
him, and their reasons for that disagreement. We believe, for
example, that there is much to dislike about the current system of
financing campaigns. But we also believe that First Amendment
concerns are more than an irritant, or a ruse, as McCain treats
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial went on: ``McCain's political style is not that of
persuasion; too often, it's the politics of brow-beating,
confrontation and intimidation. It's no accident that only four of
his Senate colleagues support his candidacy, and this is for
reasons that go well beyond McCain's calls for campaign-finance
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no telling that to volunteers like Erion, who
worked the McCain phone banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an American,'' Erion said simply. ``I think the best way
to describe John is like the movie `Saving Private Ryan.' You
remember where the guy says, `Earn this.' Well, John McCain did
earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   When voters had questions about McCain's record on education or
other subjects, Erion would turn them over to a staff member, like
Bettina Nava.
</P>
<P>
   ``And did you find out where your voting location is?'' Ms. Nava
asked one woman, before hanging up the phone and telling Erion: ``I
think she's persuaded. She's tired of the mudslinging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
