u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN22-COX     02-21 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cross-over and GOP votes a must for McCain to win Michigan
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Voters in Michigan and Arizona get their turn today to
decide whether the Republican nomination race ends early or keeps
rolling toward the March 7 primary when 11 other states vote.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John
McCain in a virtual tie in Michigan, which divides its 58
convention delegates by percentage, with 10 going to the overall
winner, and 3 to the winner in each of 16 congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, where the overall winner takes all 30 delegates,
McCain's supporters are hoping for a double-digit victory
comparable to his lead in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   His Arizona advantage makes it likely McCain will add to the 16
delegates hehas picked up, compared to 69 for Bush after his solid
victory in South Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But unless he can regain his momentum with a convincing showing
in Michigan, prospects for a McCain insurgency will rapidly begin
to dim.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the final polls before the New Hampshire and South
Carolina primaries have accurately named the winners but
significantly underestimated the margin of both McCain's win in New
Hampshire and Bush's victory in South Carolina. Republican pollster
Whit Ayres says that's because late-deciders moved strongly in the
direction of the winner.
</P>
<P>
   That could be good news for Bush, if he gets a boost from South
Carolina. The polls show the GOP front-runner, who stepped up his
ad campaign in Michigan, has been regaining the support he lost to
McCain in Michigan after his New Hampshire loss.
</P>
<P>
   In a Zogby poll conducted in Michigan after the South Carolina
primary, McCain led by 43 percent to 41 percent. In a Detroit News
poll conducted before the South Carolina primary, McCain's lead was
40 percent to 38 percent. Both polls had results within their
margins of error, amounting to a statistical tie, and showed
McCain's lead narrowing from earlier polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has turned up the heat after his scathing nonconcession
speech Saturday night, accusing Bush on the stump in Michigan of
``trash'' campaigning and ``character assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McCain picked up the endorsement of a former Bush
supporter, U.S. Rep. Peter King of New York. King criticized the
Texas governor for speaking at Bob Jones University, a South
Carolina fundamentalist school that King accused of ``anti-Catholic
bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has appealed to independents and Democrats, McCain
has to hope he picks up the support ofrank-and-file Michigan
Republicans as well.
</P>
<P>
   In both contested primaries so far, McCain has done well among
independents and Democrats. The key difference is that in New
Hampshire, he also won a narrow majority of Republicans, while Bush
led heavily among GOP voters in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   What the two results suggest is that while outside votes can add
to the margin in a GOP primary, the most dependable, and essential,
votes are those cast by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That factor favors Bush in Michigan if Gov. John Engler can
deliver the party faithful like former Gov. Carroll Campbell did
for Bush in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Michigan campaign has taken the unusual step of mailing
cards to independents and Democrats assuring them they have the
right to vote in the open primary.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain disavowed Sunday a call by the Rev. E.L. Branch,
minister at Detroit's Third New Hope Missionary Baptist Church, to
vote for McCain as a means to send a message to Engler. The
governor has angered black leaders in Detroit by moving to
eliminate independent school boards, end public assistance for
single adults and end the requirement that municipal workers live
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his drive for the GOP nomination alive, McCain has to
win the votes of Republicans who do not automatically reject him
over abortion or taxes and who are willing to listen to a message
that challenges the orthodoxy of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's voters have a reputation for boosting maverick
candidates throughout the political spectrum _ from McCain's hero,
Teddy Roosevelt, in 1912, to Ross Perot in 1992. George Wallace,
Jesse Jackson and Pat Robertson have all run strong races in
Michigan. McCain has to hope the tradition holds for him.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials in Michigan and Arizona were predicting heavy
turnouts, indicating the interest level in this struggle remains
high. After a record turnout resulted in a big Bush victory in
South Carolina, there aren't many confident predictions about who
that will help.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
