<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Feb. 27) 
(jt) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Music, Lace and Wine &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many amateur musicians may know of the French town of
Mirecourt, which is noted for cello-making and is also near the
Alsatian Wine Road. We wanted guidance on visiting both the Wine
Road and a maker of string instruments as well as on seeing the
sights, attending festivals and finding a place to stay. _Betty and
Tom Cox, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   A. Over the years, Mirecourt attracted not only artisans who
made string instruments but lace makers as well. The town, in the
departement of Vosges, is 25 miles south of Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Mirecourt began developing as a center for the makers of
stringed instruments (not just cellos) in the late 18th century.
With the founding of conservatories at that time, there grew a need
for more and cheaper ``factory fiddles,'' in the words of The New
Grove Dictionary of Musical Instruments. The best known of the
violin makers from Mirecourt was probably Jean-Baptiste Vuillaume,
who went on to set up shop in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   String instruments are still being produced in Mirecourt. Of the
dozen makers, several can be visited by appointment. Among them are
Jean-Jacques Pages, 70, rue Chanzy, telephone (33-3) 29.37.11.33,
and Alain Carbonare, 22, rue Georges Clemenceau, (33-3)
29.37.41.78.
</P>
<P>
   A museum for string instruments, the Musee de la Lutherie, is
currently housed in the Town Hall and will be transferred on April
30 to the halles, where the market stood.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th and 17th centuries, thousands of women were engaged
in bobbin-lace making, a technique that requires plaiting, twisting
and interweaving the threads. Today, only two lace makers are left
in town; both are full-time employees of the Maison de la Dentelle,
1 bis, rue Chantaire; telephone and fax: (33-3) 29.37.3959. But
over 100 local residents who make lace as a hobby visit the maison
regularly and make small doilies. The maison is open daily from May
1 to Sept. 30 and closed Saturday during the rest of the year. More
information: Mirecourt Tourist Office, telephone (33-3)
29.37.01.01, fax (33-3) 29.37.52.24.
</P>
<P>
   There is no particularly noteworthy hotel in Mirecourt. The
closest town of some importance is Epinal, 21 miles to the
southeast. The nicest hotel there is La Fayette, where the rate is
about $70 for a double room; (33-3) 29.81.15.15, fax (33-3)
29.31.07.08. Epinal also has a restaurant, with one star in the
Michelin guide, called Relais des Ducs de Lorraine; (33-3)
29.34.39.87, fax (33-3) 29.34.27.61.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the Wine Route (Route des Vins d'Alsace) from Epinal,
drive east 57 miles through St-Die, over the Vosges Mountains and
into Ribeauville or Riquewihr, two villages famed for their wines.
The villages have a Web site, www.ribeauville-riquewihr.com, that
includes a list of hotels. Officially, the 106-mile route _ which
actually comprises several roads _ runs from Marienheim south to
Thann. But the map shows it extends a bit farther north (to
Gimbrett) and south (to Leimbach). The Wine Route has a site, 
www.vinsalsace.com/rte(underscore)des(underscore)vins(underscore)uk.
html) run by the Maison des Vins d'Alsace in Colmar, (33-3)
89.20.16.20, fax (33-3) 89.20.16.30; e-mail, civa(at)rmcnet.fr. The
site lists local wine festivals, which run from May to October.
</P>
<P>
   The two main regional tourist offices of Alsace, in Colmar and
Strasbourg, can suggest hotels. For the Colmar office, call (33-3)
89.20.10.68, fax (33-3) 89.23.33.91; e-mail adt(at)rmcnet.fr. For
Strasbourg, call (33-3) 88.15.45.88, fax (33-3) 88.75.67.64; e-mail
adt-adm(at)sdv.fr.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home is France on Call, the French Government Tourist
Office service, at (410) 286-8310. Its Web site is
www.easternfrance.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greece to Israel by Ferry &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We plan to take a ferry from Piraeus, Greece, to Haifa,
Israel, in May. Do you have any suggestions? _ L.McW., Yardley, Pa.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Greek lines, Poseidon and Salamis, link Piraeus and Haifa.
Their vessels take two and a half days; call at Patmos and Rhodes,
Greece, and Limassol, Cyprus; and depart Piraeus at the same time:
7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Poseidon's Sea Harmony, which carries 1,500 passengers, leaves
Piraeus on Monday and arrives in Haifa on Thursday at 6:30 a.m.
During May and into the summer, Poseidon may add another vessel,
the Sea Symphony, according to the Paleologos Shipping and Travel
Agency, which can book trips. The Sea Symphony, with up to 250
passengers, would leave Piraeus on Thursday and arrive at 8 a.m. on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Salamis Lines vessel, Nissos Kypros, departs on Thursday and
arrives at 6 a.m. Sunday. It carries about 900 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   A two-bed inside cabin with shower and toilet is $187 on the
Poseidon vessels and $181 on Salamis, based on 338 drachmas to the
dollar; a two-bed cabin outside is $206 on Poseidon and $195 on
Salamis. For all three vessels, the lowest rate is about $75 (for
space on deck) and the port charge is $14.80 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The Paleologos agency can make reservations by e-mail
(info(at)ferries.gr), with payment by credit card. Tickets can be
picked up at the port two hours before departure; they can also be
sent express-registered mail for $5.90 or by DHL Worldwide Express
for $22. Paleologos is at 5, 25th August Street, 712 02 Heraklion,
Crete, Greece; telephone (30-81) 346185, fax (30-81) 346208.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Luggage in Bilbao &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are going from Madrid to Bilbao for a day,
flying on to Barcelona late on the same day. Will there be a place
to store our luggage at the Bilbao airport? Also, are there guides
to talk about the Guggenheim Museum? _ Susan L. Schlechter, New
York, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are no lockers at the Bilbao airport. But you can take
a cab or bus to the Termibus bus station or to the Abando train
station and leave your luggage at either one for a nominal charge.
From either terminal it's a walk of 10 to 15 minutes to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Free one-hour tours in English are given daily at 4 p.m., except
Monday, when the museum is closed; the topic depends on the day. A
private tour costs a total of $71, at 169 pesetas to the dollar _
be it for one person or up to 20 _ and requires a reservation.
Participants can ask the guide to focus just on Frank Gehry's
design of the museum or on both the architecture and art on
display. Reserve at least two weeks ahead at (34-94) 435 9090 or
fax (34-94) 435 9039.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is 7.10 when there is a special exhibition. Starting
in early May, many galleries will be closed awaiting new shows, and
admission will be $3.55. On June 14 most of the museum reopens. For
details, see www.guggenheim-bilbao.es. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
