<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-ART-6     02-21 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-ART-654&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS QUESTION PURPOSE OF U.S. RADAR IN NORWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russia and the United States are in a drawn-out
dispute over a powerful American-made radar in Norway that can
track missile launchings in western Russia, according to American
and Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The radar began quietly operating last summer as a joint
U.S.-Norwegian intelligence project at Vardo, just 40 miles from
the Russian border. It has been the subject of talks between
Washington and Moscow ever since its assembly began a year and a
half ago, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from intelligence concerns, Russians have objected that
the radar, which was previously used in the United States for
research into anti-missile defenses, could be linked to a proposed
new system to defend American territory against limited nuclear
missiles attacks. The Clinton administration has insisted that it
wants the system to guard against countries like North Korea, not
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Officials discussed the installation of the new radar, which has
not been widely noted outside Norway, in response to questions
about articles that will be published on Tuesday in the Bulletin of
the Atomic Scientists. Articles by a Norwegian journalist and an
American scientist describe the radar's capacities and raise
questions about its purpose. The radar, known by the code name Have
Stare, was built in the United States and initially used in 1995 at
Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif., in several early tests of the
national missile defense system, according to Pentagon officials.
Eventually it was dismantled and shipped to Norway, where it was
renamed Globus II, the successor to an intelligence radar operated
during the Cold War by Norway and the United States to monitor
Soviet missile tests.
</P>
<P>
   While Norway and the United States say the primary purpose of
the new radar is to monitor space debris, Russia has raised
concerns that it will track and gather intelligence on missiles
launched from bases in western Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian military believes that the Norwegian radar is
meant to monitor their ballistic missiles and that the radar was
developed as part of the national missile defense,'' said Anatoly
Diakov, director of the Center for Arms Control at the Moscow
Institute of Physics and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The new radar at Vardo can collect detailed radar images of
Russian warheads and decoys, providing the United States with a
very precise ``radar fingerprint'' using the same radar frequencies
as the proposed national missile defense system, according to
Theodore Postol, a scientist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and author of one of the articles in the Bulletin, a
nonprofit publication that specializes in nuclear arms control and
has often been critical of missile defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vardo radar can provide critical information for a
national missile defense system aimed specifically at Russia,''
Postol writes.
</P>
<P>
   Since last January the Clinton administration has been pressing
the Russian government to modify the 1972 Anti-ballistic Missile
Treaty signed between Moscow and Washington that prohibits either
country from building a system to protect their entire countries
from a missile attack. President Clinton has set a self-imposed
deadline to decide this summer whether to build a national missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   While early warning radar stations in Greenland and Britain
would be upgraded and used in such a system, administration
officials denied that the Norway radar was ever intended to be part
of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia and the United States have discussed this Globus II
radar on a number of occasions over the last 18 months up to the
assistant secretary level,'' said Kenneth H. Bacon, the Pentagon
spokesman, who refused to say whether the radar was collecting
intelligence on Russian missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that the operation of the Vardo radar ``does not
violate either the letter or the spirit of the Anti-ballistic
Missile Treaty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union built a radar in the 1980s at Krasnoyarsk,
Siberia, to fill a gap in its radar coverage, the United States
argued that it was a violation of the 1972 treaty and persuaded the
Russians to dismantle it.
</P>
<P>
   But during negotiations last October, the United States offered
to help Russia complete a large missile tracking radar if it agreed
to modify the ABM treaty, long considered the bedrock of all arms
control treaties.
</P>
<P>
   As currently envisioned, the missile defense system would
involve building a powerful new radar in Alaska and deploying up to
100 anti-missile interceptors there.
</P>
<P>
   The Vardo radar's initial use to track missiles in national
missile defense tests was first disclosed in the Norwegian
newspaper Bergens Tidende by Inge Sellevag, a journalist who is the
other author writing in the Bulletin this week.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the Norwegian government had said the radar would
track space debris, an assertion questioned by Postol. He contended
that space debris is best monitored by radar built near the
equator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious to any technically informed person that this
claim is simply another misrepresentation,'' Postol wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian and Clinton administration officials have said that
the radar is ``under full Norwegian control'' and used for
Norwegian national security. But the radar is directly linked to
the U.S. Air Force's defense center at Cheyenne Mountain, Colo.,
which receives the data gathered and processed at Vardo, according
to Postol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The radar appears to be doing things that makes it look as if
the defense system is aimed at Russia,'' said Postol, who admitted
that this ``is a very gray area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
