<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY-ART-     02-21 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANONYMITY STRIKES OUT AS GRIFFEY JOINS REDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Ken Griffey Jr. desperately wants to fit in
with the Cincinnati Reds. He wants to amble into the clubhouse in
blue jeans, a blue T-Shirt, sneakers and gold earring, as he did
Monday, play center field for the team he cherished as a boy and be
as anonymous as a utility infielder. Good luck on that last one,
Junior.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey maneuvered his black Mercedes-Benz CLK-60 with the
license plate ``Wickid 1'' past 100 fans and into Ed Smith Stadium
at about 9 o'clock Monday morning. He tried to move inconspicuously
as dozens of reporters trailed every step as if it might be his
last. And when he entered a crowded clubhouse that was foreign to
him, the best player in baseball was fidgeting.
</P>
<P>
   As Griffey glanced at the names on the lockers, he looked like a
stranded commuter staring at an unkind airport flight schedule. He
stared, squinted and searched for a friendly face. But Griffey was
soon at home because he found the two corner lockers the Reds had
assigned to him, an obvious nod to his superstardom, and he found a
weighted bat that he swung to calm himself. Finally, he exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Griffey said later, describing a scene of 150 members
of the news media poised in front of him, ``is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was normal for a relocation of this magnitude. As
Griffey sat in a folding chair on top of the first-base dugout, the
same dugout where Michael Jordan held a news conference six years
ago when he tried a crossover dribble from basketball to baseball,
the setting seemed normal. The dugout as makeshift stage seemed
liked the perfect place to reintroduce Griffey to the world as a
Red after the four-for-one trade with the Seattle Mariners on Feb.
10 and his signing of a nine-year, $116.5-million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unique, though, to be able to bring the Michael
Jordan of baseball home where he was raised in Cincinnati,'' said
Jim Bowden, the Reds' general manager, who tried to minimize how
the contract favors the Reds. ``I think he'll not only pay for
himself, I think we'll probably make more than that over the term
of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously and rightfully, the Reds, who had to set up 10 new
telephone lines in their busier ticket offices, are giddy about
Griffey, and vice versa. While Griffey reiterated how excited he
was, he also explained that it was not his personality to show much
excitement unless ``I'm sliding into home against the Yankees'' in
the 1995 division series.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey, who talked so softly that a club official asked him
to move the microphone closer to his mouth, was tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nervous? No, my leg's not shaking,'' said Griffey, who caused
everyone to laugh because, indeed, his right foot was shaking.
``Yeah, I'm nervous. I want to go out and play. There were some
things written and said about me that were not true. I just want to
go out there and make people forget about it by playing.''
</P>
<P>
   That has always been Griffey's strongest argument to anything.
He has been called petulant and he has been called moody, but
Griffey has always played hard and he has always been an incredible
joy to watch. Now Griffey _ 10-time All-Star, 10-time Gold Glove
winner, member of the All-Century team and the favorite to eclipse
Hank Aaron's career home run record _ is on the team his father
used to play for, currently coaches and will probably eventually
manage.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Griffey wore his Reds uniform for a photo shoot
for a baseball card company, the first time he had worn it since he
played in a father-son game as an 8-year old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairy tale ending,'' said Deion Sanders, a colorful
two-sport athlete who is trying to come back in baseball and who
was obscured by Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it might be a fairy tale. Griffey would not specify
which details of the trade saga bothered him, but he bristled when
asked about the perception that he held Seattle hostage by only
agreeing to be dealt to the Reds. Griffey's rights as a 10-year
veteran who had played the last five years with his current team
allowed him to veto any deal, which he did in a possible trade to
the Mets and which ruined the Mariners' chances of getting equal
value for him.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey claimed that Seattle didn't have to trade him, but even
Bowden said: ``We had the leverage. We had the cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden haughtily began Griffey's news conference by saying,
``Baseball is back in Cincinnati,'' which might not have sit well
with Jack McKeon, who managed the team to 96 victories last year
and who was sitting beside Bowden. Pokey Reese wondered if he
should bow to Griffey. Sean Casey recalled how he stole Griffey's
1989 rookie baseball card from a store as a 13-year old, was caught
and harshly scolded by his father. Barry Larkin, the Reds' captain
who said Griffey usually returns phone calls 72 hours late, knew
the deal was inching closer when Griffey constantly called him.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader in a harmonious clubhouse, Larkin will be an
important link for Junior and there is already a tight bond. Both
Larkin and Griffey played at Moeller High School in Cincinnati,
both now live in Orlando, Fla., and Larkin quickly started
Griffey's initiation Monday by shouting ``Hey, Junior, you're on
TV,'' when the well-known face flashed across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never had a situation where this clubhouse is
dysfunctional,'' Larkin said. ``We've had superstars with strong
personalities come in here before and it's worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but there is only one Junior and there is only one Senior
waiting for the manager's position. Griffey impressed his teammates
by deferring $57.5 of the $116.5 million and coming to Cincinnati
for roughly half of his market value. Other players will surpass
his total salary, but that did not matter to the newest Red who
will try in vain to be just another Red.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they pay a light bill at my house,'' said Griffey, about
the salaries of players in the future, ``then I'll worry about what
they make.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
