<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTODY CASE OF CUBAN BOY CHANGES HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A hearing scheduled for Tuesday to determine whether a
federal court has jurisdiction in the Elian Gonzalez custody case
was expected to be postponed, because the judge handling it was
admitted to a hospital on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be temporarily turned over to Judge Edward B.
Burns of Federal District Court here and he will preside over the
hearing on Tuesday. Burns is likely to focus on reassigning the
case by a random computer selection and scheduling further
hearings, officials in his chambers said today.
</P>
<P>
   Judge William M. Hoeveler had planned to hear arguments on
Tuesday to decide whether the court could intervene in the case of
6-year-old Elian, who was found clinging to an inner tube in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The child is at the center of an international fight between his
father in Cuba, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and relatives in Miami. Last
month, the Immigration and Naturalization Service ordered the
return of the boy to his father, but relatives took the case to
court to block the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exactly sure what will happen tomorrow,'' said Roger
Bernstein, a lawyer for the Miami relatives, including Lazaro
Gonzalez, a great-uncle who is caring for Elian. ``But we've been
told that we should be prepared to argue tomorrow so we will be.''
</P>
<P>
   In another development Monday, Manuel Gonzalez, another of
Elian's great-uncles, told reporters he was also seeking temporary
custody of the boy. His lawyer, Jeffery Leving, said Gonzalez had
filed a petition to intervene in federal court on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy's father is the only person who is allowed to speak
for Elian, and he has asked that Elian stay with Manuel until he
can be returned to Cuba,'' Leving said. ``I think the court should
honor and respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who has maintained a low profile throughout the
custody battle, is in disagreement with the other Miami relatives,
including his brother Lazaro.
</P>
<P>
   After briefly meeting with Lazaro Monday afternoon and speaking
to reporters, Manuel complained of chest pains and was taken to a
nearby hospital. A hospital spokesman said he was in stable
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler, 77, was admitted to a hospital in a Miami suburb on
Sunday morning, after being unable to move his right arm and leg
and having slurred speech. He was in serious condition in the
intensive care unit on Sunday, a hospital official said, adding
that he was in stable condition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler's illness is likely to mean the case will be assigned
to a new judge for the third time. At first, a court computer had
assigned Judge James Lawrence King the case, but he recused himself
because of possible conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The case was then turned over to Hoeveler, who is well known
around the Miami community for presiding over the trial of
Panamanian dictator Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-CLIPPERS-N     02-21 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CLIPPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TRIUMPH OVER CLIPPERS, 87-76 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One after another, the spindly stars of the league
came floating into town this past week with helium in their moves
and a first razor in their pockets. But as the exciting neophytes
rounded the corner on their dream paths to glory at the Madison
Square Garden, they found a crafty former All-Star clogging their
way like a Winnebago in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been able to get around Larry Johnson all week. Not
Minnesota's Kevin Garnett, not Indiana's Jalen Rose, and on Monday
not the Los Angeles Clippers' Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Larry Johnson completed a trifecta.
</P>
<P>
   If the Queens-born Odom had envisioned a homecoming filled with
dramatic points and fancy passes, he found reality the moment
Johnson stuck his Popeye-sized chest on the rookie and nudged him
out of his comfort zone during the Knicks' 87-76 victory against
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   All Odom had for his effort was 14 points and a technical foul
for his frustration. He was not expecting this.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Odom scored 24 points against a Knicks team patched
together without an injured Johnson, Marcus Camby and Patrick
Ewing. In November, Odom's face was beaming from the 100 watts of
joy he had after the Clippers left the Knicks miserable in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Johnson was healthy. And everything was different
except for the Knicks' habit of turning blowouts into cliffhangers.
After building a 19-point, fourth-quarter lead with the omnipresent
Latrell Sprewell slipping into the tough-man role of Charlie Ward,
the Knicks relaxed on a few possessions.
</P>
<P>
   That was all it took. Three consecutive 3-pointers, and the
Clippers were on their way to a 14-2 run and had cut the Knicks'
lead to 4 points with 2 minutes 25 seconds left in the game. Fear
stricken, the Knicks tightened up their defense and ended the game
on a 7-0 run. Disaster avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been getting a lot of knocks about taking nights off,''
said Patrick Ewing (15 points, 12 rebounds), who came up with a key
block on Maurice Taylor in the final minute on a play that could
have cut the Knicks' lead to 3 points. ``They cut into our lead,
but we were able to keep our composure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was actually the calm hand that guided them. Thriving
in the big backcourt lineup with Allan Houston (24 points), he had
9 assists to go with 16 points and 7 rebounds. For a player who is
not usually awake for early games, Sprewell was alert enough to
jump in front of two oncoming Clippers in the first half and draw
two charging calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to catch Charlie,'' said Sprewell, who has taken 11
charges this season to Ward's 19. ``He's out with an injury right
now, so maybe I can catch him. He's our hustle player. I'm just
trying to help fill that void.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is pitching in for the injured Camby. He is not as tall
and lively or a shot-blocking threat, but Johnson stopped Odom his
way on Monday. Almost every time Odom tried to slip into position
for a pass, Johnson was there to deny him. Almost every time the
6-foot-10-inch, 220-pound Odom tried to work his way inside for a
layup, the 6-7, 235-pound Johnson was there to dare him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those younger guys have to put some muscle on them,''
Johnson said. ``But I like his skills. I really do. He can play a
lot of positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has stopped three versatile forwards just like Odom over
the last week during the Knicks' three-game winning streak, a surge
that has the team tied with the Miami Heat for first place in the
Atlantic Division. Johnson held Garnett to 5-of-17 shooting and 23
points, and Rose to 5 of 13 and 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kevin, I tried to use my strengths to combat his
weaknesses because he's 6-foot-11 and he can definitely shoot over
me,'' Johnson said. ``I was trying to push him off the box. Rose
and Odom are definitely quicker than I am. I am trying to body them
up and get them out of position. Sometimes I win; sometimes I
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Just his transformation from go-to man with the Charlotte
Hornets during his All-Star days to defensive stopper for a team
already decorated with superstars is part of Johnson's unselfish
evolution, a metamorphosis that began the day he arrived in New
York in a trade for Anthony Mason almost four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was traded for Mase, it was: Can you play defense like
he does?'' Johnson said. ``Maybe I'm a little biased, but I thought
I could always play defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
