<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MILAN-FASHION-NYT &LR;      02-21 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFHAND AND FRESH, PRADA BREEZES IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ So many Prada bags, so many fabulous pairs of
Prada shoes, still gleaming with tissue-paper goodness, bowling
ball-size bags, purple ostrich-skin bags, golden tan, deep magenta
and navy-piped-in-white bags were lined up at the feet of front-row
editors at the Versus show, and it was only Sunday. Six shopping
days left.
</P>
<P>
   What can it mean to any designer who isn't Miuccia Prada to look
down that big runway through a tiny peephole in the back and see _
drat! _ all those magazine editors and newspaper columnists waiting
with their latest Prada accessories like spiffed-up Iowa teen-agers
beaming over prize heifers? The video cameras will record them.
There will have to be judicious cropping if one is to avoid seeing
an editor's bubble-toe Prada shoe popping into a photo of a
candy-bright Versus dress.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote has been cast. Here in Milan, the personal
preferences of the international journalists and retailers
attending the Italian fall 2000 collections can go a long way in
influencing public tastes.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems that, for now, the object of their collective
desire is not a cozy, over-the-shoulder Fendi pouch or even the
mother of them all, a Hermes Kelly sac. It is a large,
half-moon-shape leather bag with clutch handles, which, if you
didn't know any better or catch the Prada label, looks as if you're
trampling off to the Bowl-a-Rama.
</P>
<P>
   This is a curious time in Milan, hilarious even, and hilarious
has never been a word anyone would use to describe the Milanese,
whose chic-to-a-fault tastes make them nothing if not predictable.
But whether because of the economy, a boom in Internet and wireless
ventures, or just boredom with the old status symbols, a new
attitude is emerging.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the streets were thronged with shoppers, much more
so than in recent years, and they were buying things like fuchsia
snakeskin shoes, rhinestone-covered belts, rimless rose-tinted
sunglasses _ bags of stuff that would have been too horribly gauche
to consider before. ``All of a sudden, you see Milanese wearing
things that only fashion people would have worn,'' said Angela
Missoni, who designs a family knitwear line. ``They want something
that looks rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Gabbana agreed, saying before the show of the D&AMP;G line,
on Sunday: ``This is a conservative city. It is really Armani,
Milano. But I am even surprised myself what's happening. We did
these wide, jeweled belts for spring, and if we had made them look
less expensive or crazy, they wouldn't be selling.''
</P>
<P>
   So, on the one hand you have this rich old city and on the other
an infusion of new taste. Added to this is the excitement created
by the success of the Italian boat Luna Rossa, owned by Prada, in
the America's Cup, which is being televised nightly between 2 and 4
a.m. ``Every morning, you see these Italian executives with bags
under their eyes,'' said Pierfilippo Pieri, a Milan fashion
publicist. ``Life here is camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the speed with which fashion changes also means that nobody
wants to get stuck with last year's prize heifer, so to speak. As
someone who understands camp, who is herself a kind of camp queen,
Donatella Versace might naturally be expected to have some fun with
Versus, her secondary line.
</P>
<P>
   But the collection she sent out Sunday evening was almost
demure, in the ladylike groove she started last season, with fitted
blazers over creased trousers, slinky dresses and silk tops in
patterns that suggested an oil spill, and those flashes of
baby-doll violet and green that signal to all Versace ladies, ``You
can be bad, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Versace called the effect of mixing a lavender leather coat, its
seams raised in a grid pattern, with a lace-cut velvet dress over
grass-green tights ``the chic twist look.'' She might have gone for
more twist than chic _ chic being the theme of the week _ but the
show had some good pieces, particularly laminated shearling and
pleated leather coats.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing wrong with John Bartlett's collection Monday
for Byblos, with its sleek tweed trousers, sequined dappled skirts
and prints based on Kasimir Malevich's abstract paintings. But
neither was there anything special about the idea, expressed in the
idiotic program notes, of ``sexy school girls cutting class to
flirt'' with the avant-garde at ``the Cafi Flora.'' He's too smart
to write such drivel, and he's too good a designer to be spinning
his wheels with a company that obviously doesn't have a vision.
Maybe that's why he bolted down the runway at the end of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Ferretti's Philosophy collection on Sunday was trapped
in some late 1960s pubescent time warp. If it's true that young
women are growing up faster, they're not going to see the allure of
wearing flats with heavy tights and plaids of the Villager mode.
</P>
<P>
   The D&AMP;G show, by Gabbana and Domenico Dolce, had plenty of wit.
Laminated floral-print raincoats and red, tartan-lined capes
flashed over graffiti-print jeans, mini-kilts and souvenir T-shirts
with rolled-up sleeves. There was lots of gold, fake fur and a kind
of home-grown outrageousness, The cue was a set of drums and
guitars set up in the middle of the runway. This was garage
couture.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, though, the story is Prada. Prada's mesmerizing show
tonight, on a pale pink runway that resembled the translucent color
nail polish gets on a much-lacquered hand, advanced the ladylike
look she started last season. The clothes had a certain formality
offset with a sense of relaxed sophistication. That might mean a
chaste black coat tied just above the waist with a ribbon; a knit
polo shirt or cardigan with a broadtail front over a trim pair of
wide striped trousers in black and brown tweed; or a
salt-and-pepper tweed coat, with a loose fur collar tied at the
neck and worn over an abstract-print organdy dress.
</P>
<P>
   The show had a 1940s feel, mostly because open-toe platform
shoes, the casually pinned up, bed-slept hair and tweeds and
slightly out-of-kilter fur collars that will recall for anyone who
lives in New York countless dowagers steaming up Park Avenue in
their white gloves and good Delman shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Prada and her team of assistants have a knack for stepping
back and deciding what looks modern _ bare, wind-chafed legs, the
unexpected coyness of a lavender pansy print on a creamy chiffon or
organdy dress, slightly jarring proportions and uneven hemlines,
including some with a trace of chiffon hanging down, like a slip or
a loose lining. Karl Lagerfeld tried a similar effect last season
at Chanel, but Prada made it look somehow naive.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she is anything but naive at this point. One of her
new fall bags looks like a cross between an LP record jacket and a
cosmetics case. Anyway, it doesn't look like a bowling bag, and
that's the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage after the show, she looked exhausted. ``I was just
doing what is instinctive to me,'' she said. ``It's about the
pleasure of being feminine and just relaxing.'' She added that her
husband, Patrizio Bertelli, who is with the Prada racing team in
New Zealand, wondered if she was thinking of the '40s, ``but that's
just the way the clothes worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to watch the race again tonight. ``Absolutely,'' she
said with a drowsy laugh. ``In fact, I'm dead from staying up all
night and working in the day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
