<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INVEST-SUIT-410&AMP;ADD-N     02-21 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SUIT-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER INVESTOR FILES SUIT OVER AZERBAIJAN OIL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ In the second such complaint by a Wall
Street investment fund, a Czech promoter has been accused of fraud
by his biggest client in a $450 million Azerbaijan privatization
venture dominated by prominent Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Leon G. Cooperman, chairman of Omega Advisers, contended in a
civil lawsuit filed Friday in London that Viktor Kozeny defrauded
the hedge fund of $126 million. Cooperman joined a suit filed in
December by another investor in the venture, Marlwood Commercial
Inc. Marlwood, a subsidiary of the diversified insurance company
American International Group, has sued Kozeny for $15 million, the
sum it says it invested.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny, 36, is seen as a cautionary example of the Klondike
atmosphere on the Caspian in the mid-1990s. The suits contend that
he promised investors profits of up to 100 times their money
through the purchase of undervalued state properties, chiefly a
stake in Azerbaijan's state oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the Azerbaijani government said it never intended to
sell the extremely valuable oil company, and Cooperman has said
that Omega's investment is almost worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman asserts that Kozeny wrongly enriched himself by
grossly inflating the price of privatization ``options'' necessary
for bidding on properties, charging investors $25 apiece for them
when he paid an average of 40 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   The Azerbaijani privatization program is still stalled. And
though the government has repeatedly vowed to extend the expiration
date, the investors' vouchers and options are scheduled to lapse in
August.
</P>
<P>
   The London High Court has sealed the lawsuit and has forbidden
any of the parties to discuss it. By telephone Monday, Cooperman
declined to comment, as did Kozeny's lawyer, Jacqueline S. Miller,
contacted at her Palm Beach, Fla., office. Calls placed to Kozeny's
estate in Lyford Cay, Bahamas, repeatedly received busy signals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Cooperman has described the background of the
investment, and some of the suit's details were contained in a
routine notification filed with the clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other investors, none of them a party to the lawsuit,
were George J. Mitchell, the former Senate majority leader; the
real estate mogul Richard Friedman, who owns a Martha's Vineyard,
Mass., estate where President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
have vacationed, and Frederick Bourke, chairman of Dooney &AMP; Bourke,
the handbag company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kozeny moved to the United States at 16, went on to earn an
undergraduate degree at Harvard, and then earned a fortune in the
early 1990s in questionable stock dealings in his native Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   From that fortune, estimated to be in the hundreds of millions
of dollars, Kozeny bought his Lyford Cay estate; a private Bahamas
island; a London mansion once owned by the playwright Andrew Lloyd
Webber, and an Aspen, Colo., ski chalet said to be worth $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamas properties have been frozen under a court order
granted in the Marlwood suit, according to Bahamas press reports.
There is no public record of the order, nor is there a record of
whether the London or Aspen properties have also been frozen. It
was not possible to confirm the press reports independently.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have met Kozeny describe him as charming, willful and
persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Kozeny returned to his native republic as it embarked
on economic reform, including privatization of its state-owned
enterprises. Displaying expertise in American-style marketing,
Kozeny went on television and promised enormous returns for Czech
citizens who turned over their privatization coupons _ every adult
was entitled to them _ to the company he had formed, Harvard
Capital &AMP; Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Some 800,000 Czechs did so. But while he became rich, his
clients' investment plummeted to a fraction of its original value.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech government investigation resulted in a finding of
wrongdoing by Kozeny's company, which was fined and ordered to
reimburse $6.8 million of investors' money that had been improperly
spent on advertising and consulting fees.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman has said that he learned of Kozeny's past and
therefore took the precaution of demanding contractual clauses that
ostensibly prevented Kozeny from marking up the price of vouchers
and options.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and other foreign analysts had long expressed doubt
that the oil company, which possesses some 8 billion barrels of oil
reserves and is the chief source of income for Azerbaijan's corrupt
officials, would be privatized in any meaningful way.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the value of the vouchers has plummeted from a high of
about $100 in 1997 to approximately $5 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
