<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MICH-REPUBS-ART-NYT     02-21 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ALLIES SEEK TO SOW DOUBTS ABOUT MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also MICH-BUSH, ARIZ-REPUBS, MCCAIN-MOOD) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1-7, 10, 11 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNETT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ While Gov. George W. Bush tried Monday to
rally Michigan voters for Tuesday's primary here with a sunny
message of tax cutting and political reform, a second, shadow
campaign by his allies sought to sow suspicions of Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCain reported receiving automated telephone
calls in which the recorded voice of the televangelist Pat
Robertson urged them to ``protect unborn babies and restore
religious freedom'' by opposing McCain.
</P>
<P>
   As he has on his cable television program, Robertson, a
supporter of Bush, accuses McCain of having chosen as his national
chairman ``a vicious bigot who wrote that conservative Christians
in politics are anti-abortion zealots, homophobes and would-be
censors.'' That is a reference to Warren Rudman, the former New
Hampshire senator, who expressed concerns about Christian
conservatives in his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain continued to openly assail Bush on Monday
as a character assassin and a pretender to the mantle of Republican
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Robertson said Monday night that he had made the
recording for the Michigan Christian Coalition, without the
knowledge of the Bush campaign. Bush aides said they knew nothing
of the calls and that the direct calls they were making to voters
were all positive. ``All of our scripts are positive
get-out-the-vote scripts,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel campaigns here against McCain, one above the fray
and the other slashing, recalled the pattern in South Carolina,
where third parties spread damaging, exaggerated, and sometimes
false information about McCain. Other third-party groups are also
coming to Bush's aid in Michigan with radio commercials that
inflame doubts about McCain's commitment to ending abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As the McCain campaign revealed late Monday that it had a
recorded instance of Robertson's calls, the Bush campaign accused
McCain of ``attack phone calls.'' The campaign released transcripts
of two such calls, in which an automated voice repeated many of the
same criticisms that McCain has made publicly. One call accused
Bush of increasing public spending by a greater percentage in Texas
than Bill Clinton has in Washington. ``Both McCain and Bush are
good men,'' the caller continued, ``but John McCain has a much more
conservative record on fighting spending.''
</P>
<P>
   The second call accused Bush of a ``negative smear campaign''
and urged a vote against ``negative smear politics.''
</P>
<P>
   That was largely McCain's message Monday. ``I'm just like Luke
Skywalker trying to get out of the Death Star,'' declared the
senator, delighting in his new Star Wars imagery before a rowdy
crowd at Heritage High School in Saginaw, north of here. In an
appeal to Michigan's independent-minded voters, he held Bush's
establishment support, including from Gov. John Engler, against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, they're shooting at me from everywhere.
Everybody's against me. Governor Engler, Governor Bush, all the
governors, all the senators. And we're going to kill them, right?''
</P>
<P>
   As some in the crowd chanted ``No more Bush,'' McCain replied,
``I thank you. There's our secret weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to ignore his Republican rival Monday, explaining to
reporters that ``this is the time to rally the vote.'' He preferred
to direct his barbs at Vice President Al Gore, who he accused of
``politics that's so stale and so negative.''
</P>
<P>
   But when pressed, Bush once again questioned McCain's commitment
to cleaning up the political system. ``He talks about the iron
triangle in Washington, D.C,'' Bush said, referring to the
senator's complaints about the links between lobbyists, campaign
donations and legislation. ``He's been ringing that iron triangle
like a dinner bell.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Bush's simile, McCain responded, ``He's the one taking
all the money from them. Seems to me he's had a Pavlovian
reaction.'' With a laugh, he essayed a metaphor, accusing Bush of
having ``both feet in the trough.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of boutique politicking in New Hampshire and South
Carolina, the candidates, short of time to impress voters and short
of patience with each other, were counting on their national images
and a burst of appearances to make and correct impressions in what
Bush on Monday called an abbreviated ``two-day primary.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Bush was buoyant as he moved from east to west,
from the company of workers at a Detroit factory to a rally among
Grand Rapids' more conservative voters Monday evening. McCain
traveled from north to south before flying home in the evening to
Arizona, which also votes Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
