<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: VIOLENCE OVER MUSLIM LAW
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 people were killed as mosques and churches were set
on fire in clashes between Christians and Muslims in the northern
city of Kaduna after thousands of Christians marched to protest
plans to carry out Islamic law in Kaduna state. Another state,
Zamfara, formally adopted Shariah last month, and other northern
states have announced plans to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: TALKS IN TANZANIA
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Mandela opened a new round of peace talks on Burundi,
combining diplomacy and showmanship in an effort to end six years
of ethnic civil war. To increase international pressure on the
combatants, Presidents Clinton and Jacques Chirac of France were
scheduled to address the talks via closed circuit television. But
any immediate breakthrough seemed remote because the two main armed
groups did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: TRIAL ADJOURNED
</P>
<P>
   The sexual misconduct trial of the former deputy prime minister,
Anwar Ibrahim, was adjourned for at least two weeks Monday to allow
his lawyers to prepare an appeal of his earlier conviction and
six-year jail term for corruption. The adjournment postponed the
judge's decision on whether to require Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad to testify, as the defense has demanded.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: PRESIDENT SPEAKS OF PARDONS
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid said in an interview with the Voice
of America that he would pardon any former president, vice
president or military chief who is convicted of a crime. Former
President Suharto is currently being investigated for corruption,
and a former armed forces chief, Gen. Wiranto, is being
investigated for human rights abuses in East Timor. The president
said pardons were appropriate because any such crimes were
``political acts.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FRONT-RUNNER'S LEAD NARROWS
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the presidential candidate of the
governing party, the PRI, has lost some of his edge, according to a
poll by the Reforma. The newspaper showed Labastida with 39 percent
support, Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action Party with
32 percent, and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, of the leftist coalition, with
11 percent. A Reforma poll last month showed Labastida with 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: A 2ND SAFE HAVEN
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a wave of kidnappings and sabotage, the government
has said it is willing to create a safe haven for the National
Liberation Army, the country's second largest Marxist-Leninist
guerrilla group. The rebels have been demanding creation of such a
zone in the northern state of Bolivar since 1998, when President
Andres Pastrana placed a Switzerland-size area under the control of
the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: BLUNT U.S. WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of State Thomas R. Pickering told military
officers during a visit to Quito that they are ``obligated to obey
authority and not involve themselves in politics.'' The admonition
came less than a month after a military-led junta overthrew Jamil
Mahuad, the popularly elected civilian president, and installed
Vice President Gustavo Noboa as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: `RED KEN' MAY RUN YET
</P>
<P>
   The maverick left-wing politician Ken Livingstone has lost the
Labor Party's nomination to be its candidate for mayor of London by
the thinnest of margins. But Livingstone, long known as ``Red
Ken,'' has refused to rule out running as an independent in the May
4 election. John Prescott, the deputy prime minister, defended the
party's choice, Frank Dobson, the former health secretary, and said
that Livingstone should stop ``whining'' and concede defeat.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: IRA DEAL SUGGESTED
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Republican Army might be willing to disarm if Britain
agrees to withdraw troops, a spokesman for Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political arm, said. ``I think people are obliged to look at all of
the possibilities in these very trying circumstances,'' Mitchel
McLaughlin, Sinn Fein's chairman, told the BBC. Earlier this month,
the British government suspended Northern Ireland's fledgling
home-rule government because of the IRA's failure to hand in its
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL FACES SEARCH
</P>
<P>
   German prosecutors are planning to search the home and office of
the former chancellor, Helmut Kohl, in their investigation into a
campaign financing scandal, the magazine Der Speigel reported.
Because Kohl enjoys immunity as a member of Parliament, they need
to ask the Parliament for permission. Kohl has admitted taking $1
million in illegal campaign donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
