<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MICH-BUSH-NYT &LR;      02-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN CONSERVATIVES RALLY AROUND BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This was budgeted earlier as BUSH-RIGHT; see also
MICH-REPUBS) 
(sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ Gov. George W. Bush's weak showing in the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 1 prompted conservative Christian and
antiaboriton groups in Michigan to begin what has become a
strenuous effort in recent days to get out the vote for Bush,
leaders of those organizations said.
</P>
<P>
   Right to Life of Michigan, one of the most powerful lobbying
groups in Michigan's Republican politics, endorsed Bush on Feb. 7,
six days after Sen. John McCain beat Bush in New Hampshire. Since
then, the group has sent a mailing endorsing Bush to 400,000
Michigan households and, in the last four days, placed a
pre-recorded phone call to each of these households as well, urging
them to vote for Bush on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a recorded telephone message from the evangelical
leader Pat Robertson went out to conservative Christians in
Michigan harshly criticizing McCain for having a top adviser who
had attacked the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to repeat a strategy that proved successful in the South
Carolina primary on Saturday, the Bush campaign has been actively
pursuing Christian voters here, including conservative Catholics as
well as evangelical Protestants. The campaign's strategy has relied
on advertisements on Christian radio stations, appearances by
Bush's allies on Christian talk shows and appeals to home-schooling
organizations, as well as mailings and phone calls to families
belonging to Christian groups.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christians, particularly those active in
anti-abortion causes, have long been important in Republican
primaries in Michigan. Robertson attracted considerable support in
Michigan in 1988, when he ran in the Republican primary against
George Bush, the governor's father. When Ronna Romney, an
anti-abortion candidate, competed in the 1996 primary for the
Republican Senate nomination against Jim Nicholson, a businessman
supported by much of the state's Republican business establishment,
she won easily, only to be defeated in the general elections by
Sen. Carl Levin, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   James Muffett, the president of Citizens for Traditional Values,
a lobbying group that leans toward Governor Bush, said that while
some pastors had initially favored McCain, sentiment has shifted as
Bush has increasingly been perceived as more conservative. Muffett
said that he had met with three groups of conservative pastors on
Monday and found that almost all of them supported Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But pastors in Michigan seldom make political statements from
the pulpit, particularly in favor of one Republican candidate over
another. Also, he said,m ``The campaign didn't get competitive
until New Hamshire. `There wasn't a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Listing, president of the Michigan Right to Life group,
said that in the recording her group made she had highlighted
Bush's anti-abortion record, while criticizing McCain for not being
sufficiently committed to opposing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But Listing said that before most elections, the group sends
three mailings to each household, followed by a phone call from a
volunteer prepared to discuss the upcoming vote. Because Right to
Life of Michigan was slow to become active in this race, it might
be less effective, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are limited in this campaign, and we're always best when
there's a clear difference for the voters,'' Listing said. ``McCain
is indicating he's pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has responded to the moves from the right by
emphasizing the endorsement of Gary Bauer, a conservative Christian
who recently dropped his own bid for the presidency and has spent
the last two days criss-crossing Michigan to speak in favor of
McCain. The Arizona senator firmly opposes abortion, said Michael
Hudome, his top adviser in Michigan, who added that criticisms by
Right to Life were ``completely unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the voters in Tuesday's primary are likely to
be conservative Christians and they are likely to support Bush,
said Edward V. Sarpolus, a politically independent pollster here.
But unlike in South Carolina, the number of conservative Christians
voting on Tuesday might be little changed from previous Republican
primaries, because conservative Christians have long had the
highest percentage turnout so there is little room for further
increases in their numbers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such predictions have not slowed the Bush campaign's energetic
efforts. Alan Cropsey, a born-again Christian and former Republican
member of the Michigan House and Senate, said that he had switched
his loyalties to the Bush after Steve Forbes pulled out of the
race, and was making phone calls on Bush's behalf to many
conservative Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very concerned about John McCain because of his
softness on the right-to-life issue and the support he's getting
from the Log Cabin Republicans, the gay rights groups,'' Cropsey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative political analysts here think that support
from the Christian right could be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right to Life is very active on behalf of Bush,'' said Mickey
G. Craig, the Ross Alexander professor of political science at
Hillsdale College, a conservative Christian school in Hillsdale,
Mich. ``They seem to be really pushing their people to get out the
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of anti-abortion activists and Gov. John Engler
of Michigan, a long-time backer of Bush, could prove a formidable
obstacle for McCain, he said, adding, ``When you have Right to Life
for Bush and you have Engler's party machine for Bush, you would
think you're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Political opinions were mixed at Detroit-area churches on
Sunday, but some were decidedly for Bush. ``I'm going to vote
pro-life, and that's George Bush,'' said Linda DeClark, 47, a
teacher's aide, as she headed for Sunday services at St. Malachy
Catholic Church in Sterling Heights, Mich. ``I think he has good
pull with the people that are into religion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
