<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EPA-WEB22-COX     02-21 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-WEB22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EPA gradually restoring its Web site
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's Web
site, which was shut down last week over concerns about hackers,
was partially restored Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement on the site's home page said the agency was
working to restore public access to the information as quickly and
securely as possible. It added that several other systems
supporting the Web site are not yet ready to be reattached to the
Internet server.
</P>
<P>
   The shut-down was the result of a General Accounting Office
report, made public by Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-W. Va.) that said the
system was ``riddled with security weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The site contains information on air pollution, water pollution,
toxic chemical releases, scientific studies and records of
enforcement. It is widely used by researchers, public interest
groups and the public.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. EPA greatly expanded the amount of information on the
site and its accessibility during the Clinton administration.
Information about pollution in any area of the country can be
obtained by entering a postal ZIP code in a search engine.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. EPA said that the remaining systems will be put online
as soon as their security is upgraded
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOLD-ATLANTA-JOBCUTS-     02-21 0058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLD-ATLANTA-JOBCUTS-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
