<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC DEBATES WHO PAYS FOR CALLING CELLULAR PHONES
</P>
<P>
   A debate is raging at the Federal Communications Commission
about whether cellular telephone customers must continue to pay to
receive calls as well as to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular companies, hoping to make wireless phones a viable
alternative to the desk phone, have pressed for a rule change that
would allow them to bring wireless calls under the same ``calling
party pays'' system used with the traditional telephone network.
Traditional phone companies and some consumer groups oppose such a
change.
</P>
<P>
   MCI-SPRINT MERGER INVESTIGATION
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission's antitrust regulators said that they
had ``serious concerns'' about the plans of MCI Worldcom to acquire
Sprint Corp. for $130 billion and that they would carry out an
intensive four-month investigation into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN CONCERN BUYS THE MUPPETS
</P>
<P>
   EM.TV &AMP; Merchandising, a German television program distributor,
agreed to buy Jim Henson Co., creator of the Muppets, for $680
million.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH PROMOTER SUED BY INVESTOR
</P>
<P>
   A second U.S. investor has sued a Czech promoter who sold
investments in Azerbaijan, primarily the state oil company, which
was being privatized. The suit seeks $126 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH INSURANCE COMPANIES MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Two of Britain's best-known insurance companies, CGU PLC and
Norwich Union PLC, announced Monday that they would merge in a $12
billion stock swap that analysts depicted as a shield against
Continental European predators. The deal would create Europe's
fifth-largest insurer.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL IN EUROPE AND ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Most European and Asian stocks fell amid concerns that higher
interest rates in the United States would hurt corporate profits.
Much of the fear stemmed from comments made last week by Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman, indicating that more
rate increases were likely if the U.S. economy did not cool down.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS CLOSED FOR HOLIDAY
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States were closed Monday in observance of Presidents' Day. They
reopen Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
