<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA22-COX     02-21 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCAA's punishments could bring change
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The problem, Mike Krzyzewski said, is illustrated
through this analogy:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a kid working in your yard who you know comes from a
disadvantaged background,'' the Duke basketball coach said. ``Turns
out the kid has all A's in school and is really bright. You decide
to help the kid get into a private school and give him a leg up on
life.''
</P>
<P>
   If the young man got a scholarship to play the tuba, fine. But
if he earned a basketball scholarship, Krzyzewski said, you have
committed an NCAA violation that could cost the young athlete all
of his eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   That apparent double standard is at the heart of a major
philosophical fight going on quietly behind the scenes in the NCAA.
The conflict could result in legislation to redefine the concept of
amateurism in college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of cases, high-profile players have been suspended
for violation of the NCAA's ``extra benefit'' rule: ``There must be
no preferential treatment, benefits or services because of the
individual's athletics reputation or skill or pay-back potential as
a professional athlete, unless such treatment benefits or services
are specifically permitted under the NCAA.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest rulings, the NCAA has looked at relationships that
existed before the athlete became a college student:
</P>
<P>
   _ St. John's guard Erick Barkley was suspended for three games
after he swapped cars with the brother of his former coach in the
Riverside Church basketball program. The NCAA still is checking
into the possibility that a benefactor connected to the Riverside
Church program paid Barkley's tuition to a Maine prep school.
</P>
<P>
   _ With the permission of his mother, Jamal Crawford went to live
with local telecommunications executive Barry Henthon in another
part of his hometown of Seattle. Crawford lived with Henthon for
three years and later signed with Michigan. Henton has no ties to
Michigan, but the NCAA suspended Crawford and said he must repay
$15,000 that Henthon spent while Crawford was in his care. Crawford
does not have the money and might have to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brothers Kareem Rush of Missouri and JaRon Rush of UCLA both
served suspensions for taking money and other benefits while in
high school. Kareem Rush originally was suspended for half the
season, but the suspension was reduced on appeal to one-third of
the season. JaRon Rush will not be eligible until the 18th game of
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches are complaining that the NCAA is too quick to suspend
players when there might not be any wrongdoing involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to get into the modern ages in regard to college
basketball,'' Krzyzewski said. ``As a result, the kids are
sacrificed at times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope and pray I see the day when there is no NCAA,'' said
St. John's coach Mike Jarvis, who referred to the NCAA as a
``Gestapo'' for the punishment of Barkley. ``This is about America.
This is about human rights, the right of each individual.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA points out that it is composed of its member
institutions and that their representatives put the rules in place
in response to cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the fault of the NCAA office trying to enforce
wherever the membership draws the line,'' David Berst, former
director of enforcement, recently told CBS Sportsline. ``In a way,
it's testimony that the NCAA is pretty good at what the membership
says. If they say enforce it, we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes might be on the way. Among proposed NCAA legislation is
a rule that would allow an athlete to play professionally for one
year and return to college if he thinks he has made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a basketball player can return to school if he does not
like his position in the draft. But his eligibility is over if he
receives money from a pro team or hires an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is gaining some momentum. ``I can have some empathy
for a young man if he leaves for a year, thinks he's made a mistake
and wants to come back,'' Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley
said. ``But anything more than a year would be going too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Other legislation would make it permissible for high school
athletes, until they enroll in college, to receive financial
benefits, such as prize money and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The current situation involves several factors:
</P>
<P>
   _ The NCAA knows it can't control the influence of agents and
foreign players on the sport. Trying to determine whether foreign
players have received benefits is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   _ The NCAA realizes it would lose any legal battle over its
ability to control the lives of athletes before they sign college
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   _ After the NCAA and CBS reached agreement on the new $6.2
billion contract to televise the men's basketball tournament, talk
has increased about athletes getting their share of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to squelch such talk is to loosen the rules that
prohibit athletes from making a living. But some athletics
officials are opposed to such changes, because they see college
athletics as the last bastion of amateurism. Others say that
amateurism changed long ago and that college athletics must adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Even the basketball coaches are opposed to the specific changes,
which they fear would damage the integrity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what the problems are and what this legislation
proposes, and frankly we don't connect the dots,'' said Jim Haney,
executive director of the National Association of Basketball
Coaches. `We believe in getting more money to the players, but
this is not the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has to do something or run the risk of breaking up into
smaller, sport-specific organizations. Krzyzewski, for one, thinks
college basketball should have its own governing body. The earliest
that any legislation could pass would be for the 2001-2002 school
year. Until something changes, the NCAA will continue enforcing the
letter of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The result, coaches say, is that more kids will be hurt
undeservedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have helped poor people forever, but when a poor
basketball player is helped, it's a crime,'' Krzy- zewski said. ``I
don't understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
