</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
  HOTELS HARBOR PRESIDENTIAL LORE    By HARRY SHATTUCK  c. 2000
Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the intense campaigning of an election year, we pause to
reflect not on White House wannabes but on Ike and the wayward
fish.
</P>
<P>
   The setting: Denver's Brown Palace Hotel, a favorite overnight
respite for Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to please the president, who loved to fish, the
hotel staff created an ice carving of a mountain complete with pine
trees and a miniature lake at the mountain's base. Three small,
live trout swam in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Eisenhower was so enchanted by the lake and
its tiny inhabitants that he was among the first to notice one
trout flipping out of the pool and onto the hotel carpet. The
president leaped to the rescue, nearly upsetting a table in his
eagerness to save the fish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  MEMORABLE MOMENTS &QL;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ike's adventure is among many memorable moments relived by
guests at Historic Hotels of America, operated by the National
Trust for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Peabody, still a Memphis, Tenn., institution, future
president Harry Truman wrote a letter to his wife, dated Nov. 16,
1941, that reads: ``I got up at 7:15 a.m. and had breakfast in the
coffee shop downstairs, and they charged me 55 cents for tomato
juice, a little dab of oatmeal and milk with toast. I don't mind
losing $100 on a horse race or in a poker game with friends, but I
do hate to pay 55 cents for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, Truman was escorted to his room at the Boston Park
Plaza by Leo Montgomery, who spent 40 years as a bell captain at
the hotel. According to legend, Truman poured a shot of whiskey
from his flask and offered it to Montgomery. The bell captain,
aware that drinking was prohibited while on duty, hesitated.
``You're not saying no to the president, are you?'' Truman asked.
So Montgomery had what he said was his first and only drink on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   The Menger Hotel bar in San Antonio is renowned as the location
where Theodore Roosevelt recruited many of his Rough Riders in 1898
in preparation for the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   The employee cafeteria at the Renaissance Vinoy in St.
Petersburg, Fla., lays claim to feeding Calvin Coolidge. Seems this
president found the fare in the Vinoy's celebrated dining room too
rich for his simple Yankee tastes; a bellman led Coolidge to the
cafeteria, where the food suited him well.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cranwell Resort &AMP; Golf Club in Lenox, Mass., folks still
talk about a July 4 celebration for President William McKinley and
his wife, Ida Saxton McKinley, conducted more than a century ago,
when the hotel was a private residence.
</P>
<P>
   As a festive meal began, the butler removed the U.S. flag from
the table's centerpiece to reveal an enormous replica of a bald
eagle. Backed by the sound of clockwork, the eagle began to nod and
wink persistently in the direction of the first lady. With each
nod, its wings ascended and came down with a jerk, creating the
impression that the eagle was about to take off in flight. A
startled Mrs. McKinley had to be escorted from the room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  OTHER HISTORICAL SITES &QL;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A traveler's pursuit of presidential lore isn't restricted to
grand hotels, of course. Museums and libraries all across the
country honor chief executives. And then there are these
attractions uncovered by William Clotworthy in his book
``Presidential Sites'' (McDonald &AMP; Woodward, $18.95):
</P>
<P>
   In Charlestown, Mass., the Warren Tavern is touted as the Boston
area's oldest working inn. Early customers included George
Washington and Paul Revere.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, Vt., the American Museum of Fly Fishing features
equipment that belonged to Presidents Eisenhower, Jimmy Carter,
Grover Cleveland and Herbert Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   A marker beside South Carolina State Highway 5, about 14 miles
southeast of Rock Hill, commemorates the birthplace of Andrew
Jackson. But wait! Just across the state line in Union County,
N.C., another marker testifies to Jackson's birth site. No one is
certain which claim is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, the Gold Coast Railroad Museum's collection of vintage
cars includes Railroad Car 1, the Ferdinand Magellan, which served
as traveling office and home to Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt,
Truman, Eisenhower and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   On a more sobering note, the Southeastern Railway Museum in
Duluth, Ga., displays the Superb, a 1911 Pullman car used by Warren
Harding on his ill-fated 1923 ``Voyage of Understanding.'' The car
carried Harding from Washington, D.C., to Tacoma, Wash., where he
embarked for Alaska. It then took him down the coast to San
Francisco, where Harding died, and carried the president's body
back to the nation's capital and to Marion, Ohio, for his burial.
</P>
<P>
   Still on display, too, at the Union Pacific Historical Museum in
Omaha, Neb., is the rail car that carried Abraham Lincoln's body
from Washington, D.C., to Springfield, Ill., after his
assassination in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Clotworthy's book describes more than 1,000 places associated
with U.S. presidents from Washington to Bill Clinton. Bookstores
stock or can order the publication.
</P>
<P>
   For information about Historic Hotels of America, access
http://historichotels.nationaltrust.org on the Internet. Call
800-678-8946 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;  $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
