<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, FEB. 22
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CATS-CLOSING-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Feb. 19,
about the planned closing of the Broadway musical ``Cats'' on June
25 referred incorrectly to a record held by its London production,
which is still playing. ``Cats'' is Britain's longest-running
musical; the longest-running play is ``Mousetrap,'' which opened in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Feb. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Feb.
16, about the endorsement of Senator John McCain by California's
secretary of state, Bill Jones, referred incorrectly to his victory
in 1998. It was not the only one by a Republican in statewide
elections; the insurance commissioner, Charles Quackenbush, also
won.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-RIOS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Feb. 8)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Christopher Rios sent by the New York Times News
Service on Tuesday, Feb. 8, who recorded under the name Big Pun,
misidentified his debut album. It was ``Jealous One's Envy''
(1995), on which he sang a verse of ``Watch Out,'' not ``Don
Cartagena'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Feb, 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Feb, 9,
about Jerry Goldman, a political scientist who is making the 12{
hours of Nixon White House tapes available free online, misstated
the price he paid for them. It was $732, not $432.
</P>
</TEXT>
