<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GRIFFEY22-COX     02-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GRIFFEY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   The Reds' hot glow
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Junior went to camp Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If only life were so simple.
</P>
<P>
   It took 150 media members and nine television trucks to verify
it. Photographers flocked to document the license plate _ WICKID 1
_ on his jet-black Mercedes-Benz CLK 60. Grown men harbored
nitwitted thoughts. When asked if he would be cheated toward the
line this summer, left fielder Dmitri Young winced and said, ``Oh,
hell, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Donning a Cincinnati uniform for the first time since he was an
8-year-old playing in a father-son game, Ken Griffey Jr. appeared
on a second-story porch at the club's City of Sarasota training
facility, like Sinatra posing on a Las Vegas balcony. Thirty
shutters snapped. The new Reds are born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Griffey surmised, ``this is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the next day in the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Reds manager Jack McKeon, beginning his 51st year in baseball,
declared, ``This is the best group I've ever had.'' At the club's
main ticket office, the Reds have installed 10 new phone lines to
handle new orders. The office is open on weekends. It wasn't open
on weekends even when the Big Red Machine lived there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' general manager Jim Bowden said, ``I think our
young players learned they could play with the big boys.''
</P>
<P>
   And this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stay healthy and our starting pitching can give us six
or seven innings a game,'' Bowden said, ``we've got a chance to win
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``every night'' mantra used to be the exclusive domain of
the Braves and Yankees. Even though the Reds' pitching remains a
wobbly vessel, no one disputes how Griffey in one swoop has tilted
the National League. This club won 96 games without him in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's hoping we can increase it to 106, hopefully,'' pitcher
Denny Neagle said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 57 years, only three National League teams have won
as much _ the 1998 Braves (106), 1975 Reds (108) and 1986 New York
Mets (108). But that's what Monday was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no extra pressure,'' Griffey said. ``I just go out
there and do what I do and play hard. As far as all the excitement
in (Cincinnati), I've got family there and they've been calling me
and saying they're flying my name on planes and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `Here we go again.' But I'm happy. I grew up
there, and it's every childhood dream to play for your hometown
team. And I'm doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even almost two weeks after the deal that sent Brett Tomko, Mike
Cameron and minor-leaguers Antonio Perez and Jake Meyer to Seattle
for the player of the decade, the Reds continue to pinch
themselves. Second baseman Pokey Reese, who said he considered it
an honor to be mentioned in a trade for Griffey even if he was for
months the stumbling block to the deal, can't wait to get in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just two Gold Glove winners up the middle, now
we'll have three,`` Reese said. ``It's going to be a whole lot of
fun during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin, who has stolen more bases than any player in team
history, was asked if he had any assurances that Griffey would take
a pitch to let him run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he'd take one,'' Larkin said. ``One strike. That's
what he told me. That's cool. I want him to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That will all come. But on the first day, Griffey talked up the
club, met some new teammates, modeled his new No. 30 _ Ken Griffey
Sr.'s old number _ and strolled the grounds, appearing almost
weary.
</P>
<P>
   Not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably as excited as I get,'' he said, looking off,
``other than sliding into home against the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
