<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
  CONFIDENT BUSH ATTACKS GORE IN MICHIGAN    By R.G. RATCLIFFE  and
CLAY ROBISON  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ George W. Bush, showing renewed confidence that
he could be the Republican presidential nominee, told Michigan
voters Monday that Vice President Al Gore's environmental views
threaten jobs in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hardly mentioned his primary rival, John McCain, whom he
beat by 11 points in Saturday's South Carolina primary. Polls in
Michigan show the two men in a tie leading into Tuesday's primaries
in Arizona and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, standing on stage in a packed gym at Heritage High
School in Saginaw, portrayed himself as the outsider and underdog
to several hundred cheering students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like Luke Skywalker trying to get out of the Death
Star,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're shooting at me from everywhere. Everybody's against
me. (Michigan) Governor Engler, Governor Bush, all the governors,
all the senators. But we're going to kill them, right? We're going
to get them. I'm getting out of the Death Star, and we're going to
win this election.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a senator from Arizona, continued to preach
campaign-finance reform, which he has made the cornerstone of his
campaign. As he did Sunday, he attacked Bush's claim to be a
reformer, a mantle Bush adopted after McCain beat him in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, guess what? There is a new reformer on the scene. His
name is Governor Bush,'' McCain told the Traverse City crowd,
poking fun at his rival from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He called Bush's campaign-finance proposal, unveiled in South
Carolina, a ``joke and a fraud.'' He also said Texas had the ``most
liberal'' campaign-finance laws of any state because they didn't
limit donations to most political races.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his speech to The Economic Club of Detroit, said McCain
should support his call to ban contributions from federal lobbyists
when Congress is in session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about the iron triangle in Washington, D.C. He's been
ringing that iron triangle like a dinner bell, raising the money
from lobbyists,'' Bush said. ``It's one thing to talk the talk,
it's another thing to walk the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, Bush raised
$5.2 million or about 7 percent of his money from lawyers and
lobbyists in 1999. McCain raised $627,926, or about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had been critical of McCain almost every day in South
Carolina, but he acknowledged that he was intentionally avoiding
mention of McCain in the two-day Michigan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a two-day primary here, this is the time to rally
the vote,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts are uncertain what, if any, effect several
local ballot propositions could have on the Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   Because the primary is open to all 6.7 registered Michigan
voters, regardless of party registration, Bush supporters were
concerned about a call from a Detroit minister to back McCain as a
way of showing no confidence in Engler, Bush's state chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign released the text of a recorded message left
on a voter's telephone answering machine. The caller, who claims to
be the Rev. Pat Robertson, exhorts voters to participate Tuesday
and criticizes McCain's campaign-finance proposal and his attitude
toward the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign released a McCain mailing telling Democrats
that they could vote Tuesday and still be permitted to participate
in ``future Democratic Party political activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign sounded similar warnings about Democratic
crossover votes in South Carolina, where conservatives ended up
outnumbering Democrats and independents and costing McCain
significant support.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the presidential candidates, Detroiters will vote
on two library tax propositions.
</P>
<P>
   Other local governments will vote on additional fiscal measures.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Ferndale, a Detroit suburb, will act on a measure that
would repeal a gay civil rights ordinance passed last year by the
city council but referred to the electorate by opponents. A
Detroit-area gay newspaper carried a story this week in which gay
activists urged a vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush launched his assault on Gore, the Democratic presidential
front-runner, while speaking to the elite business group, a
traditional stop for presidents and presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that Gore has called the environmental impact of the
internal combustion engine in cars a ``mortal threat to the
security of every nation,'' and has called for a ban on such
engines in less than 25 years, Bush said: ``I look forward to Vice
President Gore coming into your city to explain to the workers
about why his statements about the automobile engine made sense,''
Bush said. ``I look forward to him standing up there and saying,
`My vision for America is: You won't be working.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes clean air can be achieved through
leadership instead of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sue our way to clean air. We can't regulate our way
to clean air. We can have a president who works with stake-holders
to lead our way to clean air,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the economic club that his administration will reflect
the diversity of America.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his lead foreign policy adviser, Condoleeza Rice,
Bush said: ``Who is she? She's a brilliant lady who happens to be
African-American. But I want to emphasize brilliant lady first,''
Bush said. ``I want to reflect America in my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was asked on a Detroit radio show Monday about the
controversy that surrounded Bush's first campaign appearance in
South Carolina at Bob Jones University, a fundamentalist religious
institution that bans interracial dating among its students. McCain
didn't visit the school.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been invited, McCain said, ``I would have gone and
told them they were a bunch of idiots for their racial policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that, Geoffrey Fieger, a lawyer who once represented
assisted-suicide Dr. Jack Kevorkian, is running radio commercials
in Detroit attacking him and his state chairman, Gov. John Engler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to remind Republicans we can't allow the Kevorkian
lawyers of the world to decide who the Republican nominee is going
to be,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;  $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
