<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seanez healthy, and grown up
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Braves' new minor-league pitching
coordinator, Rick Adair, probably has the clearest persective on
how far Rudy Seanez has come.
</P>
<P>
   Adair was a pitching coach in the Indians organization in
Seanez's first year in professional baseball. The 17-year-old had a
thick neck, arms busting out of his jersey and a 100 mph fastball
as he set off on his professional baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez threw nothing but hard and wild. Adair watched him throw
a no-hitter that year in which he walked eight batters. The manager
was ready to take Seanez out after the eighth inning, not even
aware of the no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And while that kind of intimidation could work against
minor-league hitters, it took another dozen years before Seanez
figured out how to get major-league hitters out on a consistent
basis. And much of what he learned, he says, came when he signed
with the Braves in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really opened my eyes to what you can do as far as
changing speeds and getting control of the strike zone,'' Seanez
said. ``When I got here, I realized I didn't have to throw
everything 100 percent. I could back it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the best two years of his career. His 56
appearances last year were a career high. He has kept his ERA close
to 3.00 _ 2.75 in 1998 and 3.35 in 1999 _ in consecutive seasons
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   He has been healthier too, compared with what he had been
through before he came to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez went on the disabled list each of the past two
Septembers, and last year it cost him the postseason. But since
then, the stress fracture in his elbow has had time to heal, his
bone spurs have been removed surgically, and Seanez says he is
feeling stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Adair, who has been watching Seanez up close in camp for the
first time since 1986, likes what he sees. ``He's a whole lot
smaller, but he has a lot more control,'' he said. ``He's just
grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Seanez is still strong, but he doesn't look like
a body-builder. He has a much simpler delivery, with a side step
instead of a giant leg kick.
</P>
<P>
   His fastball usually hovers in the low- to mid-90s. But he
throws both a slider and a change-up for strikes. Instead of giving
hitters the fastballs they would expect, Seanez can throw his
offspeed pitches in a fastball count.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez said he learned it from watching not just Greg Maddux,
Tom Glavine and John Smoltz but such younger pitchers as Derrin
Ebert, Damian Moss, Bruce Chen, Kerry Ligtenberg and Mike Cather,
when he first signed with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing they didn't overexert themselves on every single
pitch,'' Seanez said, ``I was thinking, `What am I doing here? No
way I can do what those kids are doing.' Young kids, so polished.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the really tough part,'' he said, ``having faith and
belief in yourself that you can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
