<HEADLINE>
BLUE WALL OF SOLIDARITY AT DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By DAN BARRY and AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shoulder to shoulder, they crowd the courtroom's back pews. They
are almost all white, almost all male. Many of them wear the
blue-and-white button that makes plain their purpose: ``Free the
Bronx 4.''
</P>
<P>
   They are New York City police officers who have come north to
Albany to express solemn support for the four officers charged with
shooting to death Amadou Diallo, an unarmed black immigrant, in the
Bronx last February. And their solidarity hovers over the murder
case, the way their cigarette smoke permeates the court from a back
room long after breaks in the trial have ended.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are scheduled to begin Tuesday in the case,
which has riveted the rank and file more than any police trial in
recent memory _ including last year's Abner Louima case, in which
an officer admitted torturing a Haitian immigrant with a broom
handle in a Brooklyn precinct station house. That was a disgraceful
aberration, many officers say. This, however, ``could have happened
to any one of us,'' said Patrick J. Lynch, the president of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   And because the four officers took the stand in their own
defense, the nationally televised trial has also given civilians a
rare glimpse into authentic police culture. It was there in the
constant concern for the safety of one's partner, there in the
lingo: ``no man's land,'' ``funhouse,'' ``field inspection.'' It
was there in the implication that few know the feeling of venturing
into the night with a gun and memories of a bible known as the
patrol guide.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have portrayed the four defendants _ Officers Sean
Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard Murphy _ as
reckless, even callous. They present a disturbing case: Four burly
men in street clothes, all wearing bulletproof vests, all armed and
all white, confront a slim, unassuming and unarmed black man
outside his apartment building one night. In a few moments he is
dead, hit by 19 of 41 bullets fired.
</P>
<P>
   But in well-rehearsed testimony last week, the four officers
described a rapid succession of events that they said led to a
tragic mistake, not a crime. They said Diallo peered up and down
the street, did not respond to the commands of approaching
officers, turned away, frantically reached into his pocket and
pulled out a black object.
</P>
<P>
   They said that Carroll yelled ``Gun!'' and that McMellon tripped
backward, as though he had been shot. All four officers fired their
weapons, with Carroll and McMellon emptying their 9mm handguns by
shooting 16 bullets each. Next to Diallo's outstretched hand was a
black wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has also tried to portray the four defendants as
normal citizens who happen to serve in a paramilitary operation.
For all the cockiness of the Street Crime Unit (its motto is ``We
own the night''), each officer admitted to fearing death that
night. All four said they believed they had been caught in what
officers call ``no man's land'' _ without cover, in front of a man
they thought had a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' Boss recalled thinking, ``I'm going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James J. Fyfe, a nationally recognized criminologist, former
New York City police officer and frequent critic of the police,
interviewed the officers and chose to testify in their defense. He
said that from the moment two officers approached Diallo to the
moment that one of them wept over his bullet-riddled body, the
police followed proper procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-officer turned to the jury to reveal a semi-secret of
police work: ``Their whole job is dealing with uncertainty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The potential danger of the unknown is drilled into the officers
at the Police Academy. Two of the defendants recalled training at
the ``funhouse,'' an apartment building rife with gunmen and other
faux dangers. When a prosecutor asked whether the training included
learning to distinguish between guns and innocuous objects, Carroll
said: ``The only objects they ever pulled on us were firearms. In
every incident we were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty is especially prevalent in the Street Crime Unit, a
police division whose tactics seem to be on trial as much as four
of its members. The unit has become particularly aggressive under
the Giuliani administration in trying to anticipate crime with
constant patrols and ``field inspections,'' the stopping and
frisking of people suspected of carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
   Given the unit's mission, its defenders say, Diallo's mere
action of looking up and down a street was enough for Carroll to
tell his partner to back up the car _ to say, ``I have something on
my right.''
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors argued that the police had no real reason to
approach Diallo, Carroll and McMellon looked puzzled, as if to say:
This is what we do. ``I took an oath to protect and serve,''
Carroll explained, ``not to sit and watch, not to pass by.''
</P>
<P>
   That oath includes protecting fellow officers, the defendants
said, an interpretation that figures in their explanation that
McMellon's fall prompted their fusillade. ``I had to seek cover and
defend my fallen brother,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternal bond among the police has often led to the
so-called blue wall of silence, the intense pressure among officers
not to testify against their own. In the Diallo case, the four
officers have sidestepped questions about who among them fired
first. But prosecutors have generally encountered a blue wall of a
different kind, one in which officers used almost identical
language to defend their actions that night.
</P>
<P>
   The best example centers on the lighting in the vestibule where
Diallo was killed. Several witnesses for the prosecution, including
a couple of officers, have said that overhead lights illuminated
the vestibule _ enough, the prosecutors suggest, for the four
officers to discern a wallet from a gun. But the defense cleaved to
another description.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dimly lit area,'' McMellon said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said, ``In my observation it was dimly lit.'' When asked
by a prosecutor whether there was a light in the vestibule, he said
he did not know. ``It was dimly lit,'' he repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Adhering to that language, however, seemed to trip up Sgt.
Robert Patelli, a Street Crime Unit colleague of the defendants who
arrived on the scene after the shooting. ``It was dimly lit,'' he
said. ``The lighting was poor, to the best of my recollection.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to vividly describe a distraught Carroll, hunched
over Diallo's body in the vestibule. The officer's face was red, he
said, and his eyes were welling with tears. But when a prosecutor
questioned how he could see such detail in a dimly lighted
vestibule, Patelli backpedaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I remember seeing it in the vestibule,'' he
said. It must have been in the street, he added, after Carroll was
led away from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers subpoenaed to testify for the prosecution
had no choice but to reluctantly comply _ and come perilously close
to treading traitorous ground.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Kevin Cantwell, a prosecution witness and the first officer
to arrive after the shooting, managed to fulfill both his legal
obligations and fraternal expectations by painting an emotional and
sympathetic picture of four traumatized officers. Watchful officers
in the back of the room later praised his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Bell, a prosecution witness and a young cadet in the
Police Academy, found himself under the fraternity's intense
scrutiny even before he could join it.
</P>
<P>
   Bell testified that shortly before the shooting, he walked down
Wheeler Avenue toward his home and spotted Diallo standing in front
of an apartment building. At some point, he said, he crossed to the
opposite side of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers tried to get Bell to say he crossed the street
because he feared the stranger, Diallo. But Bell insisted that
another fear of urban life altered his course: he wanted to avoid
the rats that scurry through the garbage outside a particular
building.
</P>
<P>
   The police cadet also testified that he later heard a pause of
three to five seconds in the gunfire _ the longest that any witness
remembered, and a time lapse that prosecutors suggest should have
allowed the officers to determine that Diallo posed no threat.
Finally, Bell disputed the way that Detective Peter Schumacher, an
internal affairs investigator, had transcribed an interview with
him the night after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The officers in the back of the courtroom did not appreciate
Bell's testimony. ``Arrogant,'' one of them muttered.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days after Bell's appearance, Schumacher took the
stand as a defense witness. A defense lawyer sardonically asked him
whether, during his investigation into the shooting, he had seen
any rats on Wheeler Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   No, the detective said stoically. He had not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
