<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-CHARGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1065(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC DEBATES WHO SHOULD PAY FOR CELL-PHONE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes 2nd graf. Inserts new 3rd graf. Changes 2 grafs
beginning ``The wireless carriers ...'') 
(lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A debate is raging at the Federal Communications Commission
about whether cellular telephone customers should pay to receive
calls as well as to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular companies, hoping to make wireless phones a viable,
everyday alternative to the desk phone, have pressed for new rules
that would allow them to bring wireless calls under the same
``calling party pays'' system used with the traditional telephone
network.
</P>
<P>
   But traditional local phone companies, which benefit from the
current system, see far less need to change the rules. And some
consumer groups argue that a change would mean higher rates for
regular phone customers.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC had been scheduled to vote on final rules for such a
system last Thursday, giving cellular companies the option of
adopting caller-pays billing systems. But the vote was canceled
amid continued wrangling among commissioners, lobbyists and staff
members. The commission could still reach a decision over the next
few weeks, but with heavy lobbying from all sides, the process
could well stretch into the spring.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the wireless industry's ability to become a true
competitor in the $100 billion local communications business. More
than 80 million American consumers now use wireless phones, but
only for very few of them has wireless become a true replacement
for the standard home telephone.
</P>
<P>
   When the telephone rings at home, people in the United States
generally answer without worrying about fees. Unless the call is
made ``collect,'' any charges will be the responsibility of the
person who placed the call.
</P>
<P>
   But as anyone with a cellular phone knows, wireless subscribers
almost invariably pay for incoming as well as outgoing calls. That
is a big reason that many wireless users do not give their numbers
to others and generally leave their phones off.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the rise of so-called ``one rate'' plans, pioneered by
AT&AMP;T, which eliminate roaming fees and long-distance charges,
subscribers still pay for incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residential local phone markets remain generally de
facto monopolies, dominated by the regional Bell companies and a
handful of independent operators including GTE Corp., which has
agreed to merge with Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and wireless executives believe that eliminating
wireless fees for incoming calls _ as most other countries have
done _ could go a long way toward making wireless carriers viable
long-term competitors to local phone monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get a level playing field with the local phone
companies,'' Andrew Sukawaty, chief executive of Sprint Corp.'s
wireless unit, Sprint PCS, said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at almost every other country in the world, they
all have calling-party pays as a standard. In those countries where
you have calling-party pays, you have a much higher percentage of
people giving out their number and using it for inbound calls. In
this country there is a lot more hesitancy to give out the
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Wireless carriers are not prohibited from offering calling-party
pays. But with the FCC having spent the last few years studying the
issue, few carriers have been willing to bring such plans broadly
into the market until they know what the commission's national
rules will be.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's wireless unit, for instance, began a trial
program in Delaware last November called ``Call Me,'' but has not
expanded the plan past a ``couple of thousand'' subscribers,
according to a Bell Atlantic spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   As a general proposition, many of the communications
commissioners appear to agree that fostering calling-party pays
could increase overall competition between wired and wireless phone
operators, according to people close to the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   But there are big hurdles concerning consumer protection and the
internal financial structure of a caller-pays system that must be
cleared before any consensus can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding consumers, the most important issue is to make sure
that people who dial a wireless subscriber who uses a caller-pays
plan are made aware that they will be charged, and how much.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who makes a conventional telephone call from the United
States to, say, Kazakhstan, is not told the charges. But the caller
presumably has a reasonable expectation that the fee will be
substantial, if only because of making an international call to a
place so far away.
</P>
<P>
   The complication posed by a caller-pays system in the wireless
sector is that a call to what appears to be a local number could in
fact incur big per-minute ``roaming'' fees because the user is
traveling on the other side of the continent. Without some sort of
notification, the caller would have no way of knowing about those
fees until a bill arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless carriers appear to be in favor of less notification
rather than more. For example, Sukawaty said consumers could
eventually be informed by a simple tone that the call they were
placing was to a wireless number that would incur a charge.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where the caller-pays system is generally the rule,
wireless phone numbers often include one or two digits more than do
traditional lines. So while European callers do not generally hear
a notification message, the additional digit indicates that
additional fees may apply.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, many communications experts say it would
not be feasible to add another digit to wireless numbers, if only
because the cost of modifying communications switches across the
nation could be prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   It is also somewhat simpler for European carriers to implement
caller-pays systems, because most wireless companies in Europe own
nationwide licenses, reducing the prevalence of roaming fees. In
the United States, few wireless carriers own licenses for the
entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC is thought to be leaning toward a substantial
notification system _ one that would require that a caller hear a
message indicating what the charge will be and that would give the
caller an opportunity to disconnect before incurring any fees at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the conventional local phone companies appear to hope
that extensive notification messages would discourage people from
calling wireless subscribers who use a calling-party-pays plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other major issue that stands in the way of consensus on a
caller-pays system is one that would not be obvious to most
consumers but which is vitally important for the carriers: billing.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, local phone companies are no longer obliged to
include the services of other companies on their bills. That is why
some consumers now receive separate bills from their local and
long-distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Extending that logic, some local phone giants are arguing before
the commission that they should not be obliged to include charges
on their bills for calls their customers make to wireless phones
under a caller-pays system.
</P>
<P>
   If that argument succeeded, it could mean that consumers might
receive separate bills from various wireless carriers. Or,
alternatively, they could be forced to use a credit card to make
such calls in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   All of the complications strike some consumer advocates as
ridiculous. They argue that people who choose wireless phones
should pay for their use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is one of the silliest ideas to hit the policy
arena,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office
of Consumers Union, a consumer-advocacy group. ``The notion that
people who don't use wireless phones should pay extra to reach
people who are using the new technology is just absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
