<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     02-21 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING IN THE NCAA STRAITJACKET
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those still counting, Monday's loss to the Knicks made 20
defeats for Lamar Odom and the Los Angeles Clippers in their last
21 games. At least Odom got paid, and no one cared what mode of
transportation he used to get himself home.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Odom never did get his driver's license, so he didn't
have the problem that provoked the National College Athletic
Association to tow Erick Barkley in for an interview and to start
checking under the hood of the St. John's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick it out, finish the year and go from there,'' Odom said,
offering advice for Barkley, one New York City prodigy to another.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley would be following Odom's sad excuse for a pro team into
Madison Square Garden, St. John's coming out of what it hopes is a
sanction-proof bunker Monday night to blast defending national
champion Connecticut, 79-64. Odom, the 20-year-old pro from St.
John's territory, the Jamaica section of Queens, didn't want to
sound as if he was lecturing Barkley, two years his senior. He did
sound confident that Barkley will have had enough of an education
when this process is over, and will realize it is high time to ``go
from there'' to the National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, this is the reason why kids are going
to the NBA,'' he said. ``The situation with the high school coaches
and the AAU coaches and the college coaches _ a lot of it gets out
of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   When Odom was trying to dribble his way through the hypocrisy of
amateurism in academia, a national magazine suggested that some of
his test scores might have involved sleight of hand, resulting in
an NCAA inquiry. ``The best time of my life,'' the rookie
nonetheless said of his time-share at Rhode Island, before the
Clippers fell to the Knicks, 87-76, in front of a decaffeinated
holiday crowd that didn't wake up until the last six minutes, when
the Knicks fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted to having these romantic notions mostly because his
college team didn't lose 20 out of 21, he got to experience March
Madness and navigating the campus without a set of wheels was
almost as doable as it was in New York. But the reality of
amateurism was that he attended three schools as a high school
senior and had an ill-fated courtship with the University of
Nevada-Las Vegas that produced only a citation for soliciting a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   At Rhode Island, he worked his way to eligibility only to have
his one-season college career screech to a halt when he hired an
agent before he was certain he wanted to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   This climactic development ended three years of headlines that
flashed across the college basketball sky, with all the
stereotypical rumblings. But Odom was here to tell Barkley not to
despair, not to worry, because it can all go away with the first
no-look pro pass for an uncontested dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Odom scored 30 points and had a bundle of assists in his first
game for the Clippers, and was immediately heralded as the next
Magic Johnson, a good kid after all. It helped that he is 6 foot
10, with a point guard's handle and eye for the game and a knack
for getting right to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't judge a person and everything they're going through
at 17 or 18,'' he said. ``If you do, you have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   While right-minded adults would have to agree, Mike Jarvis,
Barkley's suddenly crusading mentor, has been on a mission to
vilify the NCAA for trampling the young man's reputation. What
Jarvis should understand is that most people are way past judging
individual players who break the arcane governing rules of a sport
that is philosophically corrupt. Removed from the cesspool, no one
will care, or much recall, that Erick Barkley swapped a car, any
more than they remember Marcus Camby's collegiate missteps.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis should be more concerned about what a sport like college
basketball is doing for the collective reputation of young
African-American men, too often cast as academic losers who would
trade their future for trinkets. Would the legion of white hockey
jocks hold up under such scrutiny? Doubtful, but their
developmental system for the pros does not require a minimum
College Board score.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone profits in college basketball except the kids who don't
belong in college or can only pretend to live the life of a student
even if they wish to. In the case of Lamar Odom, his coach at Rhode
Island (Jim Harrick) used the player's talent to land a bigger job
at Georgia. And his third coach during his senior year of high
school (Jerry DeGregorio) somehow wound up as the coach at Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story, in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
