<HEADLINE>
TICKET DEMAND SURGES FOR FINAL SHOWS OF `CATS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 7,251 performances _ and more lives than even
the hardiest feline could reasonably expect _ New York has still
not had its fill of ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the show's producers confirmed that the musical,
which opened at the Winter Garden Theater in 1982 and has been
there ever since, will have its final performance on June 25. The
announcement has sparked a surge in ticket sales, theater spokesmen
said, surprising even the people who helped turn Broadway's
longest-running production into one of the city's most enduring and
lucrative attractions.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 tickets were sold on Sunday and Monday, for a
sales total of $380,000, said Bill Evans, the show's publicist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's way, way more than many, many Sundays and Mondays in
the last several months,'' Evans said exultantly, adding that sales
total $20,000 on a typical Sunday, and $50,000 to $75,000 on a
typical Monday. ``There's been a huge response.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the show's producers have been concerned that
the pool of people who had not yet seen ``Cats'' was slowly drying
up. Indeed, it would have seemed impossible to round up 500 _ let
alone 5,000 _ human beings who had either never witnessed the
musical or wanted to witness it again. ``Cats'' has been produced
in 30 countries and seen by an estimated 50 million people
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But as a testament to the idea that you can never get enough of
a good thing, a veritable stampede of tourists, returnees and the
uninitiated swamped the Winter Garden's box office Sunday
afternoon, waiting in lines that stretched out the door and down
the block. ``It was a madhouse,'' one ticket agent said. ``I saw
it. It was absolutely nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were only scattered clumps of ticket buyers at the
Broadway theater Monday, Evans, the publicist, said the phone lines
were busy all day. And there were enough people waiting in line to
suggest that if the producers had decided to continue their run of
``Cats,'' the show's motto _ ``Now and Forever'' _ could eventually
prove true.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the headline a few days ago about the closing,'' said
Ted Conway of New Canaan, Conn., who drove to Manhattan Monday
morning with his wife and three daughters, ``and said, `We've got
to go see this thing before it's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Conway, his wife, Erin, and his daughters Emily, 5, and Julia,
4, got seats for a performance on April 1. Abigail, 15 months old,
was not invited. ``I guess in her lifetime, she's not going to see
the show,'' Conway said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lourdes Estrella, a tourist from the Philippines, saw ``Cats''
several years ago but bought two tickets Monday, one for herself
and one for her 13-year-old son, Andrew, who was not even born when
the show made its debut. She said she wanted Andrew to be able to
say that he, too, had seen the musical, a melodic gloss on T.S.
Eliot's ``Old Possum's Book of Practical Cats'' composed by Andrew
Lloyd Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't want to miss it,'' said Estrella, 42. ``We
listen to it all the time at home. We're never tired of the
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Shara Walker, 9, of Upper Marlboro, Md., was sitting in her
hotel room in Manhattan on Sunday night when she heard the news on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``So she said, `Mommy, I want to see it before it goes away,'''
said her mother, Denise Walker. ``We spent $225 on three tickets
for her, myself and her father. But it's worth it. We want our
daughter to be into the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Karchuk, a self-described procrastinator and chemist
vacationing in the city from Ukraine, said Monday that he had
waited four days after arriving to visit the Statue of Liberty, but
wanted to act fast when he heard that ``Cats'' was closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything else my thought was, `What's the rush? New
York is not going away,''' Karchuk said. ``But I have no idea when
I will be back. I had to get my tickets today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
