<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   KEYES MAKES MICHIGAN ROUNDS: Alan Keyes campaigned Monday in
Grand Rapids and Kalamazoo, both strongholds of Michigan's
religious right, in advance of the state's Republican primary
Tuesday. He has been making television appearances and radio
appeals and held a rally at Western Michigan University in
Kalamazoo, where about 700 supporters turned up, said a
spokeswoman, Connie Hair. Tuesday, Keyes plans to appear in
Detroit, where he started his Michigan campaign swing on Saturday,
appearing at a Christian school there. He has done no campaigning
in Arizona, the home state of Sen. John McCain, which also holds
its primary on Tuesday. After taking two days off, Keyes plans to
resume his campaign in Virginia, which holds a primary on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Robyn Meredith
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   NO HOME-COURT ADVANTAGE: Even in his home state, Missouri,
former Sen. Bill Bradley appears to face daunting odds in his race
against Vice President Al Gore. Bradley trailed the vice president
48 percent to 31 percent in Missouri, according to a poll published
on Sunday by The St. Louis Post-Dispatch. The outlook was even
worse across the Mississippi River in Illinois, where Gore was
holding a lead of 59 percent to 24 percent. Among Republican voters
in Missouri, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas held a 55 percent to 26
percent lead over Sen. John McCain of Arizona. The poll did not
include a survey of Republicans in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Dirk Johnson
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   STICKING WITH THE HOUSE: After meeting with his fellow
Tennessean Vice President Al Gore, Rep. Harold E. Ford Jr.
announced on Sunday that he would not seek to unseat Sen. Bill
Frist and become the state's first black senator. For almost a
year, Ford, 29, the second generation of a powerful political
family in Memphis, has traveled the state talking up the idea of
running against Frist, a Republican. His decision not to run was
based in part on the fact that he had not raised enough money for a
campaign against the wealthy incumbent. ``I hope one day to have
the opportunity to serve the entire state of Tennessee,'' he said.
Ford said he would seek re-election to the House and would travel
around the country reaching out to voters under 30 on behalf of
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Emily Yellin
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Queens County and Garden City, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Royal Oak and Canton, Mich.; Kansas City, Mo.;
and Burbank, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No events.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Phoenix
</P>
