u k BC-EDIT-GERMANY-NYT &LR;      02-21 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GERMANY'S TROUBLED CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Shock waves from Helmut Kohl's illegal fund-raising activities
continue to buffet Germany's main opposition party, the Christian
Democrats. Last week the party was hit with a stiff, $21 million
fine for illegal campaign reporting, and Kohl's hand-picked
successor as party leader, Wolfgang Schauble, announced his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to Europe and America that Germany have a
healthy center-right party to represent conservative voters and
challenge the ruling Social Democrats. A thorough housecleaning
will be required for the Christian Democrats to recover public
trust. But the party should not be so weakened in the process that
the extremist far right has a chance to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats have been a guiding force in postwar
Germany, helping to make the country a stable democracy and
providing the Federal Republic's chancellors for 37 of the past 50
years. But Kohl, who led the Christian Democrats for 25 of those
years and the country for 16, treated the party as his private fief
and helped turn it into a corrupt fund-raising machine.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months prosecutors have discovered that Kohl illegally
raised at least $1 million in the mid-90s, and it now appears that
the party collected tens of millions of dollars in illegal
contributions during the 1980s and 1990s under his leadership. Even
now, Kohl ignores his legal responsibility to identify these
illegal donors. It is clear that for all his impressive
achievements in office, Kohl did his party and country a disservice
by abusing his legal trust and stunting the normal development of
new party leaders not dependent on his favors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Christian Democrats are paying the price. Last Tuesday
the speaker of Parliament announced the $21 million fine, applying
a formula that assesses the party three times the value of its
illegal contributions. While sending an admirably strong message
about legal accountability, the fine and others that may follow
could seriously crimp the party's ability to campaign. Then came
the resignation of Schauble, who was one of the party's most
experienced leaders but was implicated in the fund-raising
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   His departure leaves no obvious successor. Among the possible
choices when the party convention meets in April are Angela Merkel,
the party general secretary who has pushed for a clean break with
the past, and Volker Ruhe, the former defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats' discomfort will be welcomed by
Germany's small and splintered far-right parties, which have
generally failed to attract more than 5 percent of the national
vote. The example of neighboring Austria demonstrates the
possibility of a breakthrough for xenophobic nationalism if
mainstream conservatism falters. To compete effectively in German
politics, the Christian Democrats need to transform their campaign
practices under credible new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
