<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      02-21 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY BELITTLE EACH OTHER'S COMMITMENT TO BLACKS' ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Clashing bitterly over the depth of their commitment
to racial justice, Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey
senator Bill Bradley accused each other Monday &UR;  &LR; night of earlier
betraying a bedrock principle they claim to embrace: affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate at the historic Apollo Theatre in Harlem, Bradley
cited a former White House aide's published account that portrayed
Gore, while vice president, advocating ending affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fired back that Bradley had voted against a measure that
would have expanded opportunities for blacks to own radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the showdown, Bradley also thrust before Gore a
list of votes he cast in Congress to protect the tax-exempt status
of Bob Jones University, a school in South Carolina that bans
interracial dating, and called on Gore to explain the votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to face up to this if you are going to be a strong
leader,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sounding a little desperate because you're trying to
build yourself up by knocking somebody else down,'' Gore replied,
refusing to accept the document from Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The debate unfolded with Bradley desperate for a breakthrough as
he trailed Gore by double digits in polls in all 15 states that
hold primaries on March 7, a day that could effectively end
Bradley's candidacy if he fails to post some significant victories.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere were the stakes higher than in New York, which Bradley
has long considered home turf because of his 10-year career with
the New York Knicks. Bradley, who has made racial unity a
centerpiece of his platform, also badly needed to break Gore's
strong bond with black voters, one of New York's most powerful
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth, and the most contentious, debate between the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore stood about 3 feet apart on the red-carpeted
stage of the Apollo, answering questions from the audience,
viewers, and a panel of three journalists from CNN and Time
magazine. The forum was sponsored by the United Missionary Baptist
Association and an array of community groups and individuals in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was conceived two weeks ago when Bradley attended
services at the Allen AME Church in Queens. The pastor, the Rev.
Floyd Flake, a former congressman, and the Rev. Al Sharpton, who
was also there, jointly proposed a debate in the black community,
to which Bradley readily agreed and Gore later signed on to.
</P>
<P>
   After Gore attended a service at his church last week, Flake
endorsed the vice president. Sharpton, who wields considerable
influence among black voters in New York, continues to say he is
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate began, Sharpton said had he endorsed either
candidate, the debate would not have taken place in Harlem because
there would have been no incentive for them to appear there. Asked
if he would make an endorsement after the debate, he said, ``If
somebody knocks me off my feet, but I doubt if that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has seen a steady rise in his poll numbers as coverage
of Republican presidential hopeful John McCain has taken attention
away from his Democratic challenger, was not eager to give Bradley
any free publicity, let alone a platform to peel off black
Democratic primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   Polls say the vice president holds a 2-to-1 advantage over the
former New Jersey senator among black voters in New York. Those
voters constitute nearly a quarter of registered Democratic voters
statewide, and almost half of the party's vote in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley pursued the attack strategy Monday &UR;  &LR; night that he used
to his advantage in their last debate, on Jan. 26 in New Hampshire.
After weeks of absorbing Gore's attacks without retaliating,
Bradley took the offensive in New Hampshire, challenging Gore's
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The attack last month thrust Gore onto the defensive and helped
Bradley surge back from a double-digit deficit in the polls to
finish four points behind the vice president in the state's primary
on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bradley has yet to recover from the defeat, as his campaign
has been all but smothered by the massive media attention given
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Bradley has been relegated to hoping that Bush
will knock out McCain Tuesday in the Michigan primary, clearing the
stage for Bradley to emerge as the last ``reform'' candidate for
the White House. To that end, Bradley hammered Gore Monday &UR;  &LR; night
on his role in the 1996 campaign fund-raising scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been widely criticized for appearing at a Buddhist
Temple outside Los Angeles in 1996 at which contributions were
allegedly funneled illegally to the Democratic Party. Gore also was
hit for making fund-raising calls from the White House. He drew
even more criticism for arguing that ``no controlling legal
authority'' prohibited the fund-raising activity.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said his attacks on Gore were a prelude to a
speech at Adelphi University Tuesday in which Bradley is expected
to lambaste the vice president over his record as a member of the
House and Senate from Tennessee. Gore's voting record was generally
more conservative than the views he espouses now on issues such as
tobacco regulation, gun control, and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will argue that Gore's congressional record is stronger
evidence of his core convictions than his loyalty to President
Clinton's positions. ``We're going to make the case strongly that
convictions are important, and it's hard to know where Al Gore's
are, if he has any,'' said Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, desperate for momentum before March 7, plans to spend
most of the next week in Washington to try to win that state's
nonbinding primary on Feb. 29. Washington officially picks its
delegates in caucuses on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy will dilute his effort in the 14 other states that
are up for grabs on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have been squabbling for weeks over expanding
their debate schedule before March 7. Bradley had agreed to four
more debates, but Gore has said he would agree to additional forums
only if Bradley would join him in shutting down their television
advertising campaigns, a condition Bradley has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the only remaining debate before the March 7
primaries is scheduled on March 1 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At the Apollo, both candidates tapped allies from the realms of
politics, sports, and entertainment to showcase the depth of their
black support. Bradley brought along Harvard University professor
Cornel West, film director Spike Lee, and former New York Knicks
star Willis Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore brought along some of New York City's black political
elite, including Congressman Charles B. Rangel of Harlem, former
New York Mayor David Dinkins, and New York Comptroller H. Carl
McCall.
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo is famous for, among other things, its amateur night
called Showtime at the Apollo. Some of world's greatest performers
have passed through its doors, and over the years many singers,
musicians, and comedians have walked on its stage, rubbed their
hands against the carved tree bark for good luck, and watched their
fortunes rise or fall with the applause of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo debate was the second that turned the focus of the
Democratic contest on minority issues. As they did several times
Monday &UR;  &LR; night, Gore and Bradley all but tripped over each other
last month in a forum in Iowa to demonstrate their concern for race
relations and civil rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
