<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DREYFUSS-TV-SEMINAR-A     02-21 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREYFUSS-TV-SEMINAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RICHARD DREYFUSS, IMPRUDENCE BEGETS PRUDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's hosting a Middle East television seminar at
Columbia University, but his Upper West Side apartment is
off-limits, hostage to a sub-let until March. Face it, when you've
gone and married your accountant, you no longer get to pour money
into an abode you rarely inhabit. Prudence dictates otherwise, even
if you happen to be Richard Dreyfuss, a movie star with four
decades of celluloid service, and a history of imprudence, under
your belt.
</P>
<P>
   So Dreyfuss _ fresh from shooting the 37th film of his checkered
career, in the jungles of French Guyana with an iffy jaguar and an
anaconda capable of wreaking far more havoc than mere
scene-stealing _ is making do in an under-lit hotel suite just
north of Lincoln Center, in his favorite neighborhood in the city.
</P>
<P>
   No matter if the bathroom is the only room bright enough to
remind him what color his prematurely gray hair _ ``I think that
was just God saying I'm going to give you, at 20, a little clue to
the rest of your life, bing!'' he shrilled, deploying his signature
rat-a-tat sequence of machine gun laughter _ has turned now.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying out a new strawberry blond hue for his upcoming
role as the president (Henry Fonda was the original) in the
live-for-television remake of Fail-Safe, produced by George
Clooney, who will also co-star. As an involved citizen who harbors
``senatorial fantasies''(no need to worry, Hillary, this
celebrity's target is California), Dreyfuss is piqued by the chance
to play president.
</P>
<P>
   And doing live TV is a career first for Dreyfuss (as was working
in a jungle populated ``by bugs as big as your face'' in a country
that will never invite him to promote tourism).
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it starts, nothing will stop it, including when you say,
`I forgot my lines,''' he said of the live television project. ``I
think a lot of people are going to tune in like they tune into a
car wreck and say, `Hey, let's see how far out of control HE can
go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty far. After spending the '60s and '70s high on one drug or
another, then spoiling his entry to the 90s with what he calls a
``common as dirt mid-life crisis'' and divorce, he is serious about
making up for lost time. And mad at himself for wasting time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really understood until recently how my one life that
I will ever have was so desperately damaged by my own behavior,''
he said, one knee clasped for ballast. ``I never shot up, but I
took your garden variety things far too much; I was losing friends
left and right, had a car accident, was arrested, and I publicly
humiliated myself, but I thought I was having a fine time.'' Yes,
he won an Oscar. ``But I should have won two. I was less than I
should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fail-Safe telecast is one of a handful of challenges
Dreyfuss is juggling now that he's sober enough to enjoy juggling
again _ others include two recently wrapped films, a lecture tour
and Tuesday's seminar melding his interest in Israeli politics and
wariness of television as a social policy tool. Here is his take on
television, domestic or not: ``If you don't exercise thought and
scrutiny over television, it will become ever more terrible and
ever more crass and affect us in ever more terrible ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's West Side is where he said he flees from Los Angeles
when he gets the urge to conduct an intelligent conversation about
something besides the movie business. According to him, you can get
arrested for violating L.A.'s one-note conversational code, but
here in New York, where he was born into a left-of-center Jewish
household in Brooklyn 52 years back, anything goes. Including
forgiveness. No sooner does he hit the (``dirty, filthy, crowded'')
sidewalk in his gray suede sneakers and airport-issue Statue of
Liberty baseball cap than ``some 220 pound aesthetically
challenged'' male lumbers up to announce, with authority, ``My wife
says I look just like you!'' Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his Oscar-nominated title role in Holland's Opus _ the
sleeper that exerted such feel-good magic behind the scenes that
its cast spent their evenings bonding in Portland, Oregon's karaoke
bars _ it's come to that: he's an approachable everyman.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Dreyfuss, the host and underwriter of ``Opening The
Channels,'' a seminar that assembled TV types from six Mideast
nations Tuesday to discuss that medium's impact on everything from
pop culture to the peace process, is a changed man. Bliss with
Janelle, whom he married last May during a London run of ``The
Prisoner of Second Avenue,'' has helped.
</P>
<P>
   He has recovered from his kamikaze period, the one in which the
Best Actor Oscar for his Goodbye Girl performance at 29 faded like
an unkept promise. Obsessed with operating at peak efficiency,
Dreyfuss the actor-activist has a checklist of things left undone:
travel to the moon, win the Pulitzer Prize, the Nobel Prize, write
a novel and perhaps begin a real-life Senator Holland's Opus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never doubted that I would make it as an actor,'' said
Dreyfuss, who is ``85 percent proud'' of his film resume and 100
percent grateful he did not listen to the critic who said he would
make a better plumber than actor. ``My little rap about this is I
wanted to be an actor, then a movie star, then a senator from
California and then a history teacher. I don't know what's in
store, but I'm always glad I didn't become a plumber.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
