<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Burmese Cruise Far Beyond Mandalay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   East is east and west is west, but for four years they have met
on the Road to Mandalay, a luxury ship sailing the Irrawaddy River
in Myanmar. It has allowed Westerners to explore the exotic land
that many still call Burma, mainly between Mandalay and Bagan to
the south. This August they can sail north to and beyond Bhamo in a
special sailing through the rarely visited Three Narrows area of
the Irrawaddy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Nick Varian, chief executive of Venice
Simplon-Orient Express, operators of the ship, there are about six
weeks after the rainy season when the water is high enough for the
Road to Mandalay to sail north of Bhamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different part of Burma,'' he said,
``untouched for thousands of years.'' During a test sailing last
August he visited villages whose residents had never seen
Westerners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In these northern areas, the Irrawaddy twists and turns through
three sets of narrows less than 100 yards wide between cliffs and
forests. The current gets fast and whirlpools are common. The Road
to Mandalay will not be able to navigate the last set of narrows to
Sinbo, 55 miles north of Bhamo, and passengers will take an
excursion through them on Zodiacs and, perhaps, small local boats,
Varian said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On-board amenities include a pool and air-conditioning.
Passengers can choose from a variety of excursions each day _
including one to a camp that trains elephants for logging _ or
explore villages on their own. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This cruise, from Aug. 15 to 26, is limited to 90 passengers
(with a crew of 70) and is close to a sellout, Varian said; if it
sells out, Orient Express may add a second cruise. The cost is
$3,340 to $6,230 a person, double occupancy, plus air fare.
Reservations: (800) 524-2420. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town Scenic Road Closed by Falling Rocks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chapman's Peak Drive, one of the Cape Town area's most
breathtaking routes, will be closed until the end of May. The road
was closed after a motorist was killed by a falling boulder last
month. The coastal road, about six miles long, has become a popular
route for sightseers traveling between Cape Town and Cape Point,
the tip of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But with lots of loose rock, the hills that overlook the drive
have made it risky, forcing frequent closings during heavy rain or
strong winds. This time rock climbers have been sent up to remove
or secure the boulders thought most likely to fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 80-year-old road was not heavily used until about a
decade ago, when travel on it increased from as few as 800 vehicles
a day to as many as 8,000 now, according to Chris Atkins, the chief
roads engineer for the Cape Metropolitan Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until 1989, there had been no deaths recorded on the road; since
then there have been four involving rocks, including this latest
one, Atkins said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The traditional routes of two of the season's biggest events,
the Cape Argus Pick 'n Pay Cycling Race in March and the Two Oceans
Marathon in April, both include Chapman's Peak Drive, and
organizers of the events have been forced to map out new, more
grueling routes for the thousands of people planning to
participate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henri E. Cauvin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Museum Explores Midwestern Identity &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition at the Columbus Museum of Art in Columbus, Ohio,
examines the Midwest through historical works and four newly
commissioned pieces. ``Illusions of Eden: Visions of the American
Heartland,'' continuing through April 30, tries to place past
artists in a contemporary context. Works by 31 painters from the
first half of the 20th century, including Grant Wood, Thomas Hart
Benton and John Steuart Curry, will be on display, along with
photographs by Margaret Bourke-White, Walker Evans and others.
Newly commissioned work by Malcolm Cochran, Maya Lin, Mary Lucier
and Kerry James Marshall forms the contemporary component. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus Museum of Art, 480 East Broad Street, is open
Tuesday through Sunday. Admission is $4, free on Thursday evening.
Information: (614) 221-4848, www .heartlandproject.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Branson Opens a String of Fancy Hotels &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Branson, who is almost as well known for piloting a
hot-air balloon as he is for founding Virgin Atlantic Airways, is a
man who readily mixes pleasure with business. And when he recently
announced his new hotel collection, Limited Edition by Virgin,
Branson said that it was more about good times than good strategy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might be shrewd marketing to have hotels in cities served by
the airline, Branson conceded, but ``it's not a lot of fun.''
Instead, the group's five hotels are in places Branson likes and
expects his friends to like: Necker Island, his home in the British
Virgin Islands; Ulusaba Private Game Reserve _ the only new
property in the collection _ near Kruger National Park in South
Africa, with 20 rooms in two lodges; La Residencia, set on 30 acres
in Mallorca, with 63 rooms plus a beach house; the 12th-century
Palazzo Sasso, with 43 rooms in Ravello on the Amalfi Coast in
Italy, and Le Manoir aux Quat' Saisons, which has 32 rooms on 27
acres in Oxfordshire outside London.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Palazzo Sasso, Branson owns all or part of the
hotels. Several were part of an earlier venture, Virgin Hotels,
largely in Britain and Ireland, most of which were sold last year.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Necker Island rents for $14,000 to $27,000 a day, depending on
the number of guests (up to 26), except for two weeks during the
year when couples can reserve rooms for $12,000 a week without
reserving the whole island. Those prices include meals, drinks and
activities such as sailing.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest rates are at La Residencia, beginning at $150 a day
and ranging up to $750, including Continental breakfast. The other
properties fall somewhere in between: Ulusaba is $720 to $1,600 a
day per couple, with meals and activities such as game drives and
tennis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information and reservations: Resorts Management at (800)
557-4255 for Necker and Ulusaba, (800) 225-4255 for the other
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Piorko
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
