<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FORBES22-COX     02-21 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARONVILLE, Ohio _ Former presidential candidate Steve Forbes
said he did not regret his failed run for the White House and that
only by sticking to their conservative issues would Republicans win
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, the publisher of Forbes magazine, made one of his first
speeches Monday to the Butler County Republican Party's Lincoln Day
dinner since dropping out of the Republican race Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 people showed up for the $60-a-plate dinner at the
Sharonville Convention Center, northwest of Cincinnati, raising
more than $100,000 for the Butler County Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he was disappointed the GOP primaries between
Arizona Sen. John McCain and Texas Gov. George W. Bush have turned
acrimonious in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a real discussion and I don't think they much care
who threw what at whom,'' Forbes said. ``It's like kids fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes withdrew from the presidential race after finishing third
in the New Hampshire and Delaware primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes banked his White House bid on a call to restructure the
nation's tax system, and Monday he again stressed the need to dump
the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kill it, drive a stake through its heart and bury it in hopes
it never rises again to terrorize the American people,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has not ruled out another run for the presidency, and has not
endorsed McCain or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he expected Bush to win today in the Michigan
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way Senator McCain can make a comeback is to go hard
on the issues and contrast what he stands for against what his
opponent stands for,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent $66 million of his own money in his two bids for
the White House this year and in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
