<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NUKE-POWER-796(2TA     02-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-POWER-796(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY A WORRY AS COMPANIES SHOP FOR NUCLEAR REACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As nuclear families go, the Indian Point 2
reactor's is about as small as they get. It has suffered its
teething problems, growing pains, setbacks and crises pretty much
as an only child, under the tutelage of a corporate parent,
Consolidated Edison, that has little experience in the care and
feeding of a nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
   The adjacent Indian Point 3, with its checkered operational
history, is also pretty lonely, in the corporate sense. It is run
by the New York Power Authority, which has only one other reactor,
of a different design, on the shores of Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   But both may be sold soon. Would the plants operate better, or
more safely, if adopted into a company with a bigger brood?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's benefit to aggregating expertise,'' said Stephen E.
Quinn, a vice president of Con Edison. ``There's a lot of
professional things you gain there.'' His company once set out to
have three reactors, but Indian Point 1, which resembles a modern
reactor the way a Commodore 64 resembles an iMac,was shut down
before Indian Point 2 opened in 1974. Con Ed built Indian Point 3
but sold it to the Power Authority before opening it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Con Ed and the Power Authority run what experts sometimes
refer to as mom and pop reactors. Like many other utilities, Con Ed
is seeking to sell Indian Point 2 mostly because of utility
deregulation, which has sent a handful of other groups shopping for
reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Experts, including advocates and critics of nuclear power, are
ambivalent about what the effect could be. It could be management
with more experience, or it could be management with a stronger
drive to make money, which some people think may not be consistent
with safety.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances seem likely to provide a test. Power Authority
directors are scheduled to meet this month to vote on the sale of
Indian Point 3 and the James A. FitzPatrick reactor, in Oswego,
N.Y., to Entergy Nuclear, a company based in Jackson, Miss. The
company has negotiated a deal to operate Nine Mile Point 1 and 2,
in Scriba, N.Y., for Rochester Gas and Electric, although ownership
of those reactors is confused at the moment. Indian Point 3 could
go to another entity that is trying to buy reactors: Amergen, a
partnership of British Energy and the parent company of
Philadelphia Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy officials would not say if they were negotiating for
Indian Point 2, but Carl Crawford, a spokesman, said: ``We are
interested in any plant that's available in the U.S. We're building
a new fleet of reactors in the northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amergen partnership, which is interested in Indian Point 2,
would like to buy as many as 20 reactors, a spokesman, J. William
Jones, said. The group has already bought Three Mile Island 1, near
Harrisburg, Pa., and Clinton, near the southern Illinois city of
the same name, and has struck a deal to buy Oyster Creek, in Toms
River, N.J., and Vermont Yankee, near Brattleboro, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   There are factors that make it positive for safety, said David
Lochbaum, a nuclear engineer based here at the Union of Concerned
Scientists, which is generally critical of the utilities and of the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission. ``The new owner of a nuclear power
plant clearly has a commitment to a nuclear future,'' said
Lochbaum, who worked as a consultant for both Philadelphia Electric
and Entergy before moving to the Union of Concerned Scientists.
``They've made a business decision they can make money at nuclear
power. They will do whatever it takes to make that investment
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The sellers, on the other hand, ``may not have made the choice
to go nuclear,'' Lochbaum said. ``It may just be the legacy they've
inherited.'' Of course, he added, ``you can also make the
counterargument that the new owner is only trying to make a quick
buck, to recoup their investment and make some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Anne Jackson, a physicist who retired last year as
chairwoman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to become president
of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, in Troy, N.Y., also expressed
ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a strong company taking over a number of plants,
then you'd have the potential for quite a salutary effect in how
those plants are operated, in overall safety performance as well as
economic performance,'' she said. ``It's more difficult for a
single-plant utility to amass the kind of critical mass to be able
to have the kind of expertise and resources to bring to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``you can't argue that size in and of itself
gives you good performance.'' Two of the biggest operators, she
said, the Tennessee Valley Authority and Commonwealth Edison, also
had some of the worst operating experiences.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some people concerned about nuclear safety say that a buyer is
under more pressure to keep a plant running, even if it needs
maintenance, than an old-style monopoly utility with a captive
customer population. But other experts say that high reliability
and safety are likely to come hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   At Entergy Nuclear, Jerry W. Yelverton, the president and chief
executive, said that the old theory was that plants that shut down
only briefly for refueling must be skipping something important and
reducing safety. But he said that capacity factor _ the amount of
electricity produced, compared with what would have occurred if the
plant ran at full power 365 days a year _ tended to be highest when
other statistics were also favorable, like low radiation exposure
to workers, low number of hours when crucial systems were not
working, and small number of problems that had to be reported to
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy, he said, had changed its strategy, undertaking
aggressive maintenance on various systems while the plant was
running to keep them in top shape. One example is emergency diesel
generators, needed in case of a blackout in the region. Entergy
used to take the generators, which are trouble-prone, off-line for
service while the plant was shut, which lengthened refueling
shut-downs and also made them unavailable at a time when, analysis
shows, they were more likely to be needed. Now it takes them
off-line in rotation while the plant is running, keeping them in
top shape and raising their availability at important times.
</P>
<P>
   Others see a less glowing picture. The Nuclear Information and
Resource Service, a nonprofit group here that favors shutting down
reactors, is trying to block Amergen's purchase of Oyster Creek.
The partnership is expanding into too many plants, according to
Michael Mariotte, the executive director, and may be stretched too
thin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, operators are supposed to have enough cash
on hand to weather a six-month shutdown, which can amount to $75
million or more, and to help pay for a nuclear accident anywhere in
the country, which can come to $10 million a year for 7 years. It
is not clear if Amergen can do that for more than one reactor,
Mariotte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a company with essentially no assets,'' he said. ``It
didn't exist two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the Amergen spokesman, said he could not say if such
liabilities would rest with the partnership or the parent
companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, Robert S. Wood, the senior
financial policy adviser, said that Amergen was financially
qualified to handle its completed purchases.
</P>
<P>
   When companies make an agreement to buy a plant and apply to
have the operating license transferred to them, they tend to have
far more experience than the original licensee had. Between
acquisitions and mergers, another trend in the utility industry,
the agency foresees getting about 20 applications in the next few
months, representing one-fifth of the operating reactors.
</P>
<P>
   But Mariotte of the Nuclear Information and Resource Service
said it was a case-by-case problem. Recalling Northeast Utilities,
among others, he said, ``the largest utilities have often gotten
into the most trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
