</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Q&AMP;A-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 20 QUESTIONS ON MARKETING AND MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time again to ask 20 questions about advertising, marketing
and the media.
</P>
<P>
   _ Isn't it fortunate for the ABC Television Network unit of Walt
Disney Co. that virtually no one remembers an advertisement from
the 1997-98 season, promoting its lineup of Tuesday night comedies,
that asserted: ``Families need money and laughter. And we're not
about to hand out money''?
</P>
<P>
   _ What will consumers looking for contemporary attitudes from
American automakers think about a decision by the Chevrolet
division of General Motors to sign a two-year agreement to sponsor
the musical organization known since the mid-1960s as Up With
People?
</P>
<P>
   _ What did music lovers in Missouri make of postcards promoting
a ``special Valentine's concert,'' proclaiming that ``Krispy Kreme
is the official doughnut of the St. Louis Symphony Orchestra''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is a spot for Panasonic high-definition television sets
featuring a dreadful imitation of the voice of Jimmy Durante the
worst celebrity impression ever in a commercial?
</P>
<P>
   _ How much more would shares of the Omnicom Group be worth if
that agency company were to be renamed Omni.com?
</P>
<P>
   _ How did executives at Wong Doody feel when they read the Jan.
1 issue of Time magazine and learned that a mock ad the agency
created was selected to be part of a humorous article _ and the
creation was credited to ``Wang Doody''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of the WPP Group
has created a newspaper ad for Maxwell House coffee, sold by a
division of Philip Morris, in which a woman promises ``I will watch
less TV,'' will there be a complementary TV spot in which she
promises ``I will read fewer newspapers''?
</P>
<P>
   _ How embarrassed were executives at Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and
their agency, BBDO New York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of
Omnicom, when a commercial featuring the football player Cris
Carter ran briefly with his given name misspelled on screen as
``Chris''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Jeff Bezos, the chairman and chief executive at
Amazon.com, be flattered or annoyed by an ad for a company called
Addashop.com that declares ``Go from Bozo to Bezos in just five
minutes''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why was it that when DaimlerChrysler decided to discontinue
its Plymouth brand, almost no one noted that the death came four
decades after the end of a sibling automobile line, DeSoto?
</P>
<P>
   _ Are members of Generation Y puzzled when they listen to ``(I
Can't Get No) Satisfaction'' and hear Mick Jagger sing about a
television commercial for cigarettes?
</P>
<P>
   _ Does anyone reading TV Guide Celebrity Dish, a new magazine
published by TV Guide Inc., recall a similar publication named Good
Food that corporate predecessors, Triangle Publications and Murdoch
Magazines, introduced, closed, reintroduced and closed again in the
1970s and 1980s?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will those who consider Procter &AMP; Gamble hopelessly staid and
old-fashioned take heart from a Go Card postcard ad that recommends
Scope mouthwash ``when your date on Friday lasts till Saturday''?
</P>
<P>
   _ When Qwest Communications International merges with U S West,
wouldn't it be delightful if the merged company were to be named
West Qwest or Qwest West?
</P>
<P>
   _ When coupon ads for the Whitehall-Robins Health Care division
of American Home Products extend invitations to consumers to ``Join
the Advil family,'' how many reply with that venerable riposte
``Not tonight, I have a headache''?
</P>
<P>
   _ When executives at the Frito-Lay division of PepsiCo
introduced a ``honey BBQ'' version of Fritos Racerz, a line of
car-shaped corn snacks, did they consider that consumers might
perceive a barbecued race car to be morbid rather than delectable?
</P>
<P>
   _ Have readers of Fortune magazine, published by the Time Inc.
division of Time Warner, really become accustomed to reviews of
compact discs by bands like Hole, Pulp, Air and R.E.M.?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was it a coincidence that on the same Sunday, the comic strips
``For Better or For Worse'' and ``One Big Happy'' both showed their
fictitious families playing Monopoly?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did all the descriptions of Monica Lewinsky as ``the portly
pepperpot'' in The New York Post stimulate sales of Campbell's
Pepper Pot Soup?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will a purposely cheesy performing monkey, dancing to a
cha-cha tune in a garage, invite an advertising columnist to invest
online and then declare ``You ask a lot of questions for someone
from Brooklyn''?
</P>
</TEXT>
