<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CUCKOO-THEATER-REVIEW     02-21 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUCKOO-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIME OF THE CUCKOO': A LUKEWARM REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Leona Samish, the unhappily single heroine of
Arthur Laurents' ``Time of the Cuckoo,'' Debra Monk throws out her
smile as if it were a baited fishhook. Shiny and sharp, it seems to
precede her onto the stage, an invitation cast with energy but only
slim expectations of getting a nibble.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hardness in that smile, a desperation, that makes it
more than friendly. You get a strong feeling that this gregarious
American tourist in Venice could turn nasty. When she does, you can
only wonder why the people around her didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   If you are familiar with Laurents' drama, which opened Monday
night in a generally lukewarm revival at the Mitzi E. Newhouse
Theater at Lincoln Center, this description probably doesn't tally
with your idea of Leona, the very American executive secretary who
falls for a very Italian married man.
</P>
<P>
   When the play was first seen in 1952, Shirley Booth had the
role, and according to Brooks Atkinson's review in The New York
Times, ``everybody was in love with her when the final curtain
descended.'' Katharine Hepburn played the part with starched
sentimentality in a screen version that emphasized the work's
weepier side.
</P>
<P>
   Leona's latest avatar is more likely to make you cringe than
sniffle. That Monk, who gave comparable brashness to a similar role
in the 1994 revival of William Inge's ``Picnic,'' doesn't ask for
easy sympathy is the most provocative element in this latest
production of ``Cuckoo,'' which is directed by Nicholas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents, best known today for his superb book for the musical
``Gypsy'' and the screenplays for ``The Way We Were'' and ``The
Turning Point,'' has already gone on record as saying that Monk is
providing a dimension that was always meant to be. Booth, he writes
in his forthcoming ``Original Story By: A Memoir of Broadway and
Hollywood,'' worried too much about the audience's not liking her.
</P>
<P>
   Yet presented with clearer, harder eyes, in lieu of misty ones,
``The Time of the Cucardly looks timeless. In tracing
Leona's short-lived affair with a Renato Di Rossi (Olek Krupa), the
play turns on the familiar opposition of European sophistication,
especially in matters sexual, and those classic American ``isms,''
Puritanism and materialism.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of cold Anglo-Saxons melting in the Mediterranean sun
had of course already been explored extensively by novelists like
Henry James and E.M. Forster. Laurents, boldly for the early 1950s,
translates the idea into more openly sexual terms, suggesting that
monogamy and celibacy are not necessarily virtues. As Signora
Fioria (Cigdem Onat), the worldly landlady of the pensione where
Leona is staying, says of Americans, ``You have such impractical
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   This impracticality is part of a larger tendency to delay
immediate pleasures in the name of unrealistic ideals. This is
reflected not only in the main, aborted love story of ``Cuckoo,''
but also in the portraits of the other Americans at the pensione.
</P>
<P>
   There are the McIlhennys (Polly Holliday and Tom Aldredge), an
elderly couple who are finding Europe a bit of a bore, and Eddie
and June Yaeger (Adam Trese and Ana Reeder), a pair of newlyweds
with conflicting notions of romantic love.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents brings these separate lives into head-on collision with
dexterity. And occasionally, as in a speculative, teasing
conversation between June and Eddie on marital infidelity, he gives
truly organic and particular life to the play's basic arguments.
</P>
<P>
   He also, however, lends his characters, especially the Italians,
the epigrammatic eloquence of teachers in the school of life.
Renato, for example, in courting Leona, says, ``The noise in your
head is so loud, Miss Samish. Be quiet. Let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   One might offer the same advice to Martin and his ensemble. The
production never overcomes a self-consciousness that starts with
James Noone's picturesque but artificial-looking set, in which a
carved Venetian landscape looms in monochromatic relief, and
extends to the Tennessee Williams-esque siren calls of the
gondoliers.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are too often pitched high in the name of
thematic clarity and instant laughs. Monk, in particular, has been
given some ungainly comic business, including an overextended
pantomime scene in which she tries to conduct a conversation with a
non-English-speaking servant (Chiara Mangiameli). And having Leona
walk with a trembling, stiff-legged gait after first being kissed
by Renato seems cheap.
</P>
<P>
   In his revised script for ``Cuckoo,'' Laurents makes it clear
that Leona is no virgin. And he has scaled up her big moment of
drunken humiliation _ something, Laurents has written, he felt
Booth never took far enough _ by having the shockable McIlhennys in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Monk, who looks smart and crisp in Theoni V.
Aldredge's New Look-style dresses, pursues her character's harsher
side with a vengeance, a tendency that reaches its climax when
Leona flashes the McIlhennys with a view of her panties in the
party scene. Even in less demonstrative moments, Leona gives off a
strident, manic quality, and you are always aware of her
uncomfortable reliance on alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   There is a brave intelligence in Monk's performance. But as it
is, her shrillness keeps us at a wary distance. Though the other
characters keep saying how likable Leona is, you get the feeling
that underneath they're thinking of organizing an intervention to
get her on a plane to the Betty Ford Center, or whatever the 1950s
equivalent was.
</P>
<P>
   Krupa's Renato begins promisingly, all animal amorality and
bedroom eyes, but once he starts the speechifying, he turns into a
bore. More crucially, it is a cold chemistry that he and Monk
produce together.
</P>
<P>
   Trese and Reeder look appropriately young and healthy, although
they are also more wooden than their elders. A canny child actor
named Sebastian Uriarte is terrific as a tough Venetian urchin. And
the ravishing and ravaged-looking Onat, though Turkish, expertly
conveys Italian-style sensuality as Americans came to think of it
through the films of Anna Magnani.
</P>
<P>
   Aldredge and Holliday, estimable veterans both, don't have much
to do, but they make a definite impression. They could easily come
across as corn-pone innocents abroad, but there's a sobering,
understated air of disappointment about the McIlhennys.
</P>
<P>
   When Holliday murmurs, of the couple's experience of Europe, ``I
don't know what we expected, really,'' she makes the evening's most
affecting case for the dangers of inflated expectations. It's a
quiet moment, but it sets off widening ripples. This production
could use more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE TIME OF THE CUCKOO'
</P>
<P>
   By Arthur Laurents; directed by Nicholas Martin; sets by James
Noone; costumes by Theoni V. Aldredge;ng by Brian MacDevitt;
original music and sound by Mark Bennett; stage manager, Kelley
Kirkpatrick; general manager, Steven C. Callahan; production
manager, Jeff Hamlin. Presented by the Lincoln Center Theater,
under the direction of Andre Bishop and Bernard Gersten. At the
Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater, Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   With: Debra Monk (Leona Samish), Olek Krupa (Renato Di Rossi),
Cigdem Onat (Signora Fioria), Adam Trese (Eddie Yaeger), Ana Reeder
(June Yaeger), Chiara Mangiameli (Giovanna), Polly Holliday ( Edith
McIlhenny), Tom Aldredge ( Lloyd McIlhenny), Sebastian Uriarte
(Mauro) and Paola Pagliacolo (Vito).
</P>
</TEXT>
