<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-REDS22-CO     02-21 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-REDS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media swarm meets Junior
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ A black Mercedes CLK60 with Florida license
WICKID-1 rolled into the parking lot of the city of Sarasota Sports
Complex at 9:06 Monday morning and the Messiah of Cincinnati
baseball stepped out.
</P>
<P>
   The Messiah of Cincinnati baseball didn't look like a messiah in
his dark blue Nike T-shirt (what else but Nike?), his white Nike
shoes (what else but Nike?) and his blue jeans (what, Nike doesn't
make blue jeans?).
</P>
<P>
   The Ken Griffey Jr. era officially commenced as the Messiah of
Cincinnati baseball walked a gauntlet of cameras from his car to
the clubhouse before meeting 150 members of the media representing
65 outlets.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the arrival of Greg Vaughn last year ushered in a
new area of facial hair in Cincinnati, Junior's arrival ushers in a
new era of diamond earrings.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Bowden said it had nothing to do with
Junior's ear-lobe preference, that the club was adjusting to the
times, but as some folks already are saying, ``Whatever Junior
wants?'' Yes, look for players to wear their hats turned backward
during practice, something else Griffey does. In the past, Bowden
has been known to walk up to a player and turn his hat bill forward
if he catches one wearing it backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Allen (club CEO) and I discussed it over the winter and
decided some of our rules are archaic as far as society goes and
needed changing,'' Bowden said. ``Stud earrings are OK, but nothing
dangling over the lobes. If 29 other clubs can wear them, why not
ours?''
</P>
<P>
   As Bowden said, ``Cincinnati is back on the map. We were able to
trade for the best player in the game and we're very proud again to
wear Reds uniforms,'' complete with earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's clubhouse entrance was without extraordinary fanfare _
Sean Casey, his locker neighbor, stuck out his hand and said,
``What's up, Junior?'' Mostly the players sat in their chairs in
stunned awe.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Barry Larkin broke the ice by shouting, ``Hey, come
over here and clean my locker, Junior.'' Griffey ignored him.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey spent three hours at the complex, dressing in his
home-game uniform to pose for Upper Deck baseball cards, unpacking
gear and schmoozing with his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I have to do is remember names,'' he said.
``I'm glad the names are on the backs of the (spring) uniforms
until I can learn first names. The big thing is that everybody's
childhood dream is to play in your hometown and now I get to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, 30, is forever low-key and soft-spoken, a difficult
read.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as excited as I get,'' he said softly as he sat
atop the first-base dugout with a microphone in his hand, facing
the media seated in the Ed Smith Stadium stands. ``It's as excited
as I get other than sliding into home against the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't get that chance this year unless he helps the Reds work
their way into the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this attention is a surprise,'' he said. ``I just want to
be on the field. I feel no extra pressure, I just want to do what I
do, play hard and have fun and help the team win. Money is not
important. Winning a championship is what is important. A lot of
things have been said and written about me that aren't true. I just
want to forget all that and go play.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about landing in the same division as Chicago's Sammy Sosa
and St. Louis' Mark McGwire, Junior said, ``I'm not facing those
guys. And as far as catching Hank Aaron's home run record, I'm
still 350 away (357), a lot. I got to the the majors a lot sooner
than most guys, when I was 19. Of course, if you break a record,
you'd like to do it in front of the home crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin did the most talking about his friend and new teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke all my baseball records at Moeller (a high school in
Cincinnati), but he is not going to break my stolen base records
here . . . he doesn't have time,'' Larkin said. ``I'm going to bat
in front of him (second to Griffey's third) and he told me he would
take one strike, just one, to let me steal. That's cool. I want him
to hit. He is here to hit. With him in our lineup, there is not a
weak link. It's a very sound, strong lineup. All we need is one guy
to step up for the fifth spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected us to win last year, but we expected to win
and almost did,'' Larkin added. ``We expect it even more this year
with the people we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
