<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-OPENER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Junior's trade to Reds boosts teams' ticket sales
 &HT;    By Marc Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Normally at this time of the year, the Cincinnati
Reds sell tickets during the week and take off weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Not now. Not with Ken Griffey Jr. on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Even opposing National League teams are getting a boost from
Griffey, who was traded to the Reds in a 4-for-1 deal Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people have been in the last two weekends,'' a Reds
spokesperson said Monday. ``They normally don't do that. Sales have
been brisk _ with the biggest request for season tickets _ but we
don't have a good gauge on where we are on sales.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, only Opening Day is sold out, and the team is close to
selling out the three-game Cleveland series, July 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, whose per-game attendance averaged 24,774 last year,
19th best in baseball, say tickets for other games in all areas are
still available. The affect of the Griffey trade last week also has
been felt where baseball's other two most notable sluggers are
located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales are noticeably up for our two series' with the Reds,''
said Chicago Cubs (home of Sammy Sosa) director of ticket
operations Frank Maloney. ``I think all six games will be sellouts.
Four are close now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Wrigley Field, which seats 38,902, has already sold
out the outfield bleacher section for 23 games, including four of
the six games with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis (Mark McGwire's home), where the Cards' attendance
averaged 40,960 last season _ fourth best in baseball _ 10,000
tickets for games against the Reds were sold in the two days
following the trade. ``We've had sales like that for McGwire late
in the season, but not for another team,'' a Cards spokesperson
said. ``Griffey is a huge draw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are in St. Louis for two three-game series', July 4-6
and Sept. 29-Oct. 1 to end the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's standing room only for the last game, but that would
normally be the case anyway,'' the spokesperson said. ``But the
July 4 weekend is usually not big for us. Griffey made a big impact
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dayton, where the Class A Dayton Dragons will begin play this
summer as a Reds' affiliate, team president Bob Murphy said
Griffey's arrival did not impact local sales, although the Dragons
already had sold about 94 percent of their available tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Seattle, where Griffey's trade was rumored for
months, sales were not affected prior to the trade. When individual
tickets went on sale Feb. 5 _ five days before the trade _ the
Mariners sold a near team record of about 42,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
