<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COL-ATTICA-NYT &LR;      02-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-ATTICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SOLACE FOR WIDOW OF ATTICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 28 years have passed, and still Ann Valone chokes up
when she talks about what happened at the Attica state prison.
Twenty-eight years is not such a long time when the subject is the
day your life was turned upside down forever.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, 1971, Valone was a hospital nurse in Batavia, N.Y.,
east of Buffalo. She lived there then, as she does now, in a house
10 miles up the road from Attica. Her husband, Carl Valone, was a
prison guard, making about $9,000 a year. Even back then, it wasn't
much money, not with four children and the grocery and dentist
bills that go with them.
</P>
<P>
   That fateful day, Attica inmates rioted. They clubbed a guard to
death, then took several dozen prison employees hostage, beginning
a four-day siege that would become the bloodiest prison uprising in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hostages was Carl Valone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody called and said she heard on the radio that there was
a riot,'' Valone, now 70, said in a phone interview. ``It wasn't
till later that day that I learned my husband was a hostage. It's a
shocking thing. It's like you get almost into a shell or something.
You go into a fog.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a catch in her voice as she recalled how the fog
thickened when state troopers were ordered four days later to
retake the prison. They went in with guns blazing, firing at
convicts and hostages alike. When the Attica dust settled, 43 were
dead. All but 4 were killed in that trooper fusillade _ 29 inmates
and 10 hostages, including Carl Valone, 43.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who say the authorities had no choice but to end the
siege have acknowledged that the trooper assault was poorly
conceived and executed. A state investigating commission said as
much a year later. One disillusioned state prosecutor called it ``a
turkey shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' Valone said, ``you get real angry at the inmates.
Then you find out they acted more humane than the officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Attica's aftermath only deepened her bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, officials visited her and other families of
slain guards. ``New York state suits,'' her oldest daughter,
Maryann, calls them. The suits persuaded Valone to accept a
settlement no different from what she could have expected if her
husband had died in an accident in the prison machine shop.
</P>
<P>
   She got a one-shot payment of about $27,000, three times Carl
Valone's yearly pay. From then on, she has also been paid $120 in
workers' compensation every two weeks. Nearly all the families
agreed to this arrangement _ not realizing, Valone said, that they
were also signing away their right to bring wrongful-death suits
against the state.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take her long to feel she'd been had.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the things they did wrong, they just kind of said,
`Oops,' and closed the books,'' she said. ``It was an insulting
amount for a man's life, for what my children suffered. They grew
up without a father. I can't explain to you how put down we felt
over the years by the treatment we got.''
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing _ if anything about Attica can be called funny _
is that nothing prevented surviving inmates from bringing lawsuits.
They did just that, for wounds suffered in the assault and for
brutal reprisals later endured. For years, the cases dragged on.
Finally, they reached some resolution last week when a federal
judge in Rochester approved a settlement in which the state agreed,
while admitting no wrongdoing, to pay $12 million to inmates and
their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   And the families of the dead guards? As ever, they are out of
it. To Daniel Burling, that's unfair. Burling is a Republican
assemblyman from Wyoming County, which encompasses Attica. ``Most
people feel the families were taken advantage of,'' he said. ``They
placed their faith in the state, and the state was more concerned
about protecting its interests than taking care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cash is a time-honored way to acknowledge someone's pain. The
assemblyman intends to introduce a bill to give an extra $90,000 in
death benefits to each family of a slain Attica employee. There is
nothing magical about the figure. It equals 10 times the guards'
rough average salary in 1971, and was chosen, Burling said, only
because it seemed ``realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether his fellow lawmakers agree remains to be seen. For
Valone, no amount of money can buy peace of mind. She'd rather that
the state unseal all records relating to the sorry Attica affair.
But she also does not bank on ever seeing that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like some kind of justice,'' she said. ``We've never been
able to heal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
