clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SARASOTA, Fla. -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY --
Ken Griffey Jr. poses for photographs on a balcony at the
Cincinnati Reds spring training facility in Sarasota on Monday. The
former Seattle Mariner star Griffey became known to the world as a
Red after the four-for-one trade with the Mariners on Feb. 10 and
his signing of a nine-year, $116.5-million contract. (Mike Lang/The
Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- DEMS-DEBATE-4 -- New York
Congressman Charles Rangel along with former New York Mayor David
Dinkins, in background at left, at the Harlem debate on Monday
between Vice President Al Gore and Bill Bradley at the world famous
Apollo Theater. During the debate the audience was demonstrative,
sometimes raucous, alternating between applause and jeers as the
Democratic rivals argued about affirmative action, and their
records when both were senators. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- DEMS-DEBATE-3 -- Bill
Bradley and Vice President Al Gore during their Harlem debate on
Monday at the world famous Apollo Theater. During the debate, Gore
and Bradley promised Monday night to act against racial profiling
from the White House, and then tried to turn the question against
each other. Throughout, the audience was demonstrative, sometimes
raucous, alternating between applause and jeers as the Democratic
rivals argued about affirmative action, and their records when both
were senators. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- NY-DIALLO-TRIAL -- New
York City police officers who have come north to Albany to express
solemn support for the four officers charged with shooting to death
Amadou Diallo, march outside the Albany County courthouse on
Monday. Diallo, an unarmed black immigrant, was shot to death in
the Bronx last February in a hail of 41 bullets fired by the
officers. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LONDON -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- OBIT-DANIEL-2-B&AMP;W -- Clifton
Daniel at The New York Times' London bureau in a photo taken in
1951. Daniel, the courtly North Carolinian who served as managing
editor of The New York Times from 1964 to 1969 after a career as a
correspondent in wartime London, war-torn Europe and the Middle
East, died Monday at his home in Manhattan. He was 87. The cause
was complications of a stroke and heart disease, said his wife,
Margaret Truman Daniel. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MOSCOW -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- OBIT-DANIEL-1-B&AMP;W -- Clifton
Daniel at The New York Times' Moscow bureau in a photo taken in the
early 1950s. Daniel, the courtly North Carolinian who served as
managing editor of The New York Times from 1964 to 1969 after a
career as a correspondent in wartime London, war-torn Europe and
the Middle East, died Monday at his home in Manhattan. He was 87.
The cause was complications of a stroke and heart disease, said his
wife, Margaret Truman Daniel. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- CUCKOO-THEATER-REVIEW --
Debra Monk with Olek Krupa in Arthur Laurent's ``Time of the
Cuckoo'' which opened Monday night at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater
at Lincoln Center. ``Time of the Cuckoo'' turns on the familiar
opposition of European sophistication, especially in matters
sexual, and those classic American ``isms,'' Puritanism and
materialism. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Feb. 21, 2000 -- DREYFUS-TV-SEMINAR --
Richard Dreyfuss has an upcoming role as the president of the
United States in the live-for-television remake of Fail-Safe. Doing
live television represents a career first for Dreyfuss. ``I think a
lot of people are going to tune in like they tune into a car wreck
and say, ``'Hey, let's see how far out of control he can go.'''
(Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) AL MUFAQARA, West Bank -- Feb. 21, 2000 --
WESTBANK-CAVES -- Women and children part of the the Jabarin Family
try to keep warm inside a small cave near Al-Mufaqara. Evicted from
a hamlet that was cleared by Israeli soldiers in October, the
Jabarin family keep the faith that they will be permitted to return
to their original home. The caves, in an area of the Hebron hills
that the Israeli army has declared a firing zone, can be seen as
another chapter in the grinding struggle between Israel and the
Palestinians over how much land each side will control if they
finally negotiate a permanent peace. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- KOSOVO-MITROVICA-3 -- Feb. 21,
2000 -- British troops stand guard near the main bridge that
separates the Serbian and Albanian districts of the divided city of
Mitrovica, Monday. Thousands of ethnic Albanians from throughout
Kosovo marched on the divided city and clashed with a phalanx of
NATO-led troops who used tear gas and fists to keep them from
reaching the Serbian district. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 21, 2000 --
KOSOVO-MITROVICA-2 -- A Canadian soldier restrains an Albanian
demonstrator during a riot in Mitrovica that resulted from ethnic
Albanians trying to storm the main bridge that separates the
Serbian and Albanian districts of the divided city. Thousands of
ethnic Albanians from throughout Kosovo marched and clashed with a
phalanx of NATO-led troops who used tear gas, fists and guns to
keep them from reaching the Serbian district. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 21, 2000 --
KOSOVO-MITROVICA-1 -- British troops struggle to hold back Albanian
demonstrators in Mitrovica on Monday. The protesters were trying to
storm the main bridge that separates the Serbian and Albanian
districts. Thousands of ethnic Albanians from throughout Kosovo
marched on the divided city and clashed with a phalanx of NATO-led
troops who used tear gas and fists to keep them from reaching the
Serbian district. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
