u s BC-BOX-NOTES-NYT &LR;      02-21 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA AND TRINIDAD IN NEW YORK  
 CHAVEZ ON UNDERCARD  
 SCREAMING MATCH AFTER BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oscar De La Hoya plans to make the most of his visit
to New York this week, with television appearances on ``The View''
and ``Late Show With David Letterman.'' But Felix Trinidad, who
took away De La Hoya's World Boxing Council welterweight title in a
controversial decision last September, will try to steal some of
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is in town for his welterweight bout against Derrell
Coley on Saturday night at Madison Square Garden. The 12-round
match will be televised on HBO's ``Championship Boxing'' series.
Trinidad will hold a workout at the Church Street Gym in lower
Manhattan on Tuesday afternoon in preparation for his bout with
David Reid, the World Boxing Association superwelterweight
champion, on March 3 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Trinidad-Reid bout came as a result of the failure to make a
rematch between De La Hoya and Trinidad. The door is still open for
the rematch, and De La Hoya believes it will be made once Trinidad
realizes he can't make as much money fighting anyone other than De
La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Trinidad-Reid bout is less than two weeks away,
De La Hoya said he doubted it would take place. De La Hoya said the
fight, which is to be broadcast on pay-per-view by Showtime Event
Television, won't generate enough money to pay the purses of
Trinidad and Reid. Trinidad is scheduled to earn $4 million and
Reid $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make financial sense for Trinidad,'' De La Hoya
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to buy the pay-per-view for that fight. And if
he wins, so what? But if he loses, then he has nowhere to go. If he
comes back for the rematch, then everything is different.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya last fought in New York in 1995 when he stopped Jesse
James Leija in the second round of a lightweight championship bout.
The Garden has sold 11,000 of the 18,000 tickets for his fight
against Coley.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez on Undercard
</P>
<P>
   When David Reid defends his World Boxing Association title
against Felix Trinidad on March 3 at Caesars Palace, Julio Cesar
Chavez of Mexico, a former world champion in three weight classes,
will box on the undercard.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Chavez (103-4-2, 86 knockouts) will meet Bobby
Elkins (28--8, 22 knockouts) of Nashville, Tenn., according to an
announcement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Screaming Match After Bout
</P>
<P>
   The 122-pound world championship bout this past Saturday night
in Las Vegas between Erik Morales, the World Boxing Organization
title-holder, and Marco Antonio Barrera, who holds the WBC version
of the title, was explosive for all 12 rounds. But the real
fireworks started after Morales (36-0), the WBC superbantamweight
champion, won a controversial split decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum of Top Rank, Morales' promoter, got into a screaming
match with Frank Warren, the promoter for Barrera. And Barrera's
camp began screaming about a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Duane Ford scored the bout 114-113 for Barrera. Judge
Carol Castellano scored it 114-113 for Morales. Judge Dalby Shirley
scored the bout 115-112 for Morales. On Shirley's scorecard,
Morales won rounds five through 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel and know I'm the champion,'' Barrera said. ``You
can't fight two rivals, the judges and Erik Morales. The judges
know who won the fight. I'm going to ask the president of the WBO
to let me keep my title, because I didn't lose it. I'd rather have
had the guy knock me out than to have him rob me of my title like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to CompuBox punch statistics, Barrera threw 511 power
punches and connected on 272, while Morales threw 723 power punches
and landed 290. But Morales seemed worse from the wear of the fight
than Barrera did.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' face was black and blue and his body was covered with
red welts. Barrera's face was puffy and he had a small cut on his
left cheek. Morales said he felt he won the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult fight, but I feel I won most minutes of the
rounds,'' Morales said. ``Barrera was trying to steal the last
minute of the rounds. I think the judges recognized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales said he doubted that there would be a rematch. He said
he would abandon the 122-pound division and move up to 126 pounds.
He said he expected to face the winner of the Luisito Espinosa-Guty
Espanda bout for the vacant WBC featherweight championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEMOCRATS22-COX     02-21 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS SPAR IN LIVELY DEBATE ON RACIAL ISSUES
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley
squared off on the stage of the legendary Apollo Theatre on Monday
night in the most spirited debate yet of their contest for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The raucous audience that filled the 86-year-old black
entertainment landmark contributed to the lively nature of the
debate. The audience alternated between applause and jeers as the
Democratic rivals skewered each other over their records in the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a community activist in Harlem, helped set
the tone of the debate with the first question to the candidates
about what they would do to end racial profiling, the police
practice of identifying crime suspects on the basis of race.
</P>
<P>
   In posing the question, Sharpton noted that ``many in our
community have to live in fear of both the cops and the robbers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, who is trailing Gore in the polls, the debate on
racial and urban issues presented one of his last opportunities to
gain ground on the vice president before the important ``Super
Tuesday'' primaries and caucuses in 16 states March 7.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley came out swinging from the opening moments of the
90-minute nationally televised debate, which was sponsored by CNN
and Time magazine and moderated by CNN's Bernard Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger repeatedly cited votes taken by Gore as a member
of Congress from Tennessee in the 1970s and 1980s that Bradley said
revealed the vice president's ``conservative Democrat'' nature.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that Gore's support for anti-gun-control
measures in Congress had made him the ``poster boy'' for the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Bradley tried to present Gore with the record
of votes he said were in favor of tax exemptions for private
schools that discriminate on the basis of race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a copy of all five of those votes, my statement in
opposition and the Congressional Black Caucus's, saying this would
got to Bob Jones University,'' he told Gore. ``You have to face up
to this if you're going to be a strong leader.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president refused to accept the documents Bradley
held out to him. And he pointed out that nearly all the members of
the Congressional Black Caucus had endorsed his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded with a challenge to Bradley to explain one of his
committee votes against legislation providing affirmative action
for minority broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bradley was growing ``desperate'' and was trying to
``build yourself up'' with the attacks on votes the vice president
took more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the two generally agreed with each
other on substantive policy matters. Both vowed to end racial
profiling, to support increased funding for urban schools, to
continue affirmative action programs, to review abuses in the
criminal justice system, to fight AIDS in the minority community
and to expand health care coverage for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   They also repeated their opposition to the Confederate battle
flag flying over the state capitol in South Carolina and criticized
the Republicans, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, for not speaking out against the flag.
</P>
<P>
   They repeated their differences over the scope of health
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was willing to express support for economic reparations
to African Americans for centuries of slavery, though both
indicated support for greater recognition of African American
contributions to American culture.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley was the aggressor throughout, Gore took every
opening Bradley gave him.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Bradley's acknowledgement Sunday that a special
prosecutor should investigate the Democratic Party's role in the
1996 campaign finance scandal, Gore said, ``Senator Bradley, you
must be the only Democrat in America who misses Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr was the former independent counsel who investigated
President Clinton on a variety of matters, including the White
House sex scandal that led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
