<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARDON-KING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preston King pardoned after 39 years
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A black man from southwest Georgia who spent four
decades in exile after a legal battle with a draft board he claimed
was racist received a full pardon Monday from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The grant of executive clemency allows Preston King, 63, who
last touched American soil in 1961, when ``white'' and ``colored''
water fountains were still the norm in his native Albany and
throughout the South, to return home for his brother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   King was a graduate student when he was convicted of draft
evasion after refusing to respond to an all-white draft board that
began referring to him as ``Preston'' rather than ``Mr. King''
after his race became known.
</P>
<P>
   King's protest of what was a common form of disrespect in the
segregated South resulted in his conviction by an all-white jury
and an 18-month prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Then 23, King jumped bail and has been a federal fugitive ever
since. He has lived most of that time in England, where he is a
political science professor.
</P>
<P>
   During that nearly 40 years, as his family appealed to
Washington, King has mourned from overseas as his mother, father
and three brothers have been buried in the family plot in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest brother, Clennon W. King, died Feb. 12. With the
funeral scheduled Thursday in Albany, the family once again
appealed to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton signed a ``full and unconditional'' pardon
for King to be able to return freely to the United States, said
White House deputy press secretary Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the president has been considering a pardon for
several months, but the death of King's 79-year-old brother sped up
the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was certainly expedited out of humanitarian concern for
Mr. King and his family,'' Kennedy said. ``He is pardoned for the
offense for which he was convicted and also indicted.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the pardon was met with jubilation and relief by King's
family in Albany, who had been central to the civil rights movement
in southwest Georgia. Carol King, his sister-in-law and widow of
civil rights attorney C.B. King, said the family is eagerly
awaiting his return Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful thing,'' she said from her Albany home. ``It
transcends 40 years of looking for him to come home. We're just
ecstatic over it. We feel it's an answer to our prayers.
Regrettably, it comes at the time of losing one brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter E. Massey, president of Morehouse College, has explored
the possibility of Preston King accepting an academic position with
the school. But Carol King said she expects her brother-in-law to
return to his home in England after the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, he's planning to visit,'' she said. ``He'll
be leaving Saturday or Sunday. He's a professor and he has his
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge William A. Bootle, now 97 and retired in Macon,
presided over King's trial in 1961. Bootle said he never forgot
King's case because it was unusual. King was willing to report for
duty if the draft board referred to him with respect, Bootle said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, when King's family renewed their efforts to bring
him home, Bootle has been among the most outspoken figures to ask
for a pardon. He wrote a formal letter to the president. On Monday,
Bootle applauded Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted,'' Bootle said. ``I think justice has been done.
I think it's great that the president of the United States would
take time to consider a matter like that. It's democracy at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he deserved the sentence (in 1961). It's the water
that's gone under the bridge since then that's changed the
situation. He's lived a good life for 39 or 40 years. He's
established himself as a good citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drew attention to the fact that he wanted respect. He
wanted to go in the service as a man and not a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   King was a graduate student in England in 1961 and has lived
abroad ever since. He married, had two children and later divorced.
His daughter, Oona, 31, is a member of the British Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   King could not be reached for comment Monday. Chevene King Jr.,
who helped lead the effort to have his uncle return home without
the threat of prosecution, said he spoke with him over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased the president has granted my uncle a
pardon,'' Chevene King said. ``I can't express to you how elated
the family is that this matter will be brought to an end after 39
years. I'm sure to a large degree it won't actually sink in until
we see him home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
