</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-HOSTAGE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 death row inmates take guard hostage in Texas prison
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, Texas _ Two convicted killers who were part of the
Thanksgiving Day 1998 escape attempt from death row fled their
cells and took a guard hostage Monday evening in a new bid for
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations continued late into the night as prison system
director Wayne Scott personally directed attempts to get Ponchai
Wilkerson, 28, and Howard Guidry, 23, to surrender peacefully as
the tense standoff played itself out inside the Terrell Unit just
south of Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reported that the guard _ a 57-year-old woman who has
worked for the prison system 39 months _ appeared unhurt. They
would not identify her.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the episode marked the first hostage situation on
Texas' death row in years, possibly ever. Several years ago, a
guard was held hostage at an Abilene prison and, more recently, a
convict held a correctional worker hostage for a time at a prison
mental unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope this could end peacefully, but we are not
optimistic at this point,'' said Larry Todd, a spokesman for the
Texas Department of Criminal Justice. ``The most dangerous inmates
are on death row, and we consider both (Wilkerson and Guidry) to be
extremely dangerous. They have nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   While Todd refused to discuss the convicts' demands, other
officials said freedom was sought at least at one point _ and
quickly ruled out. ``No way. That's not negotiable,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials at the scene said the ordeal began just after 4
p.m. Monday as guards were preparing to serve the evening meal, or
had just finished serving it to convicts on death row, a section of
the maximum-security prison. Convicts there remain in their
solitary-confinement cells for 23 hours a day, allowed out only to
exercise or shower _ one by one and under heavy guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``How they got out of their cells, we don't know yet for sure,''
said an official at the scene who asked not to be quoted by name.
``But they probably jimmied their cell doors open.''
</P>
<P>
   Once out of their cells, authorities said Wilkerson and Guidry
grabbed the unarmed guard, handcuffed her with her own handcuffs
and forced her against a wall as other guards called for help.
Officials confirmed that Wilkerson and Guidry were armed with a
sharpened steel rod 12 to 18 inches in length and a steel tool that
resembles a wrench, usually used to open food slots in the steel
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson and Guidry were both sentenced to die by lethal
injection for Houston slayings. Officials said Wilkerson was
scheduled for execution March 15, but Guidry had no date.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after the hostage was grabbed, the other 2,800
convicts at the prison were locked in their cells. The prison's
880-plus staff includes more than 632 guards.
</P>
<P>
   After the Thanksgiving Day 1998 escape attempt by eight death
row convicts, prison officials decided to relocate death row to the
much-newer Terrell Unit. Of the 460 convicts under a death
sentence, 112 had been moved to Terrell by Monday and 339 remained
at the Ellis Unit. Eight women under death sentence are housed at
the Mountain View Unit outside Gatesville.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Scott was wounded in an escape attempt from the
historic Walls Unit in Huntsville in which two prison workers who
were taken hostage died.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
