u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-ART-615&AMP;A     02-21 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE TRADE JABS IN FIERCEST CAMPAIGN DEBATE YET
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and NYT13 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To a chorus of boos, shouts and cheers at the Apollo
Theater in Harlem, Bill Bradley and Al Gore engaged in the most
brutal presidential debate of the year, with Bradley attacking the
vice president as a ``conservative Democrat'' and Gore caustically
describing his opponent as a ``desperate'' candidate intent on
``tearing down'' his fellow Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The two men drew their swords almost as soon as the session
began, and from there on in, turned almost every question into an
attack. It was politics as spectacle, produced in an 87-year-old
theater that is better known for the music of Charlie Parker and
James Brown than debates between men seeking to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is an elaborate, what I call Gore-dance,''
Bradley said, mocking his opponent when the subject turned to the
two men's position on registering hand guns. ``It's a dance to
avoid facing up your conservative record on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By all means, Bill, get the negativity off your chest, but
when you return, let's face the real problems facing this
country,'' Gore responded. Turning to the crowd, Gore acidly
described his opponent as someone who ``questions the character of
people who disagree with him'' and ``confuses disagreement with not
being a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley, a couple of days ago, your campaign said that
you wanted to get some things off your chest. Well, since then
you've made personal attack after personal attack,'' Gore said.
``The problem is these attacks don't solve any problems. They do
divide us as Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, sponsored by Time magazine and CNN, repeatedly
seemed on the verge of running out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time, time, time,'' the moderator, CNN's Bernard Shaw, said
repeatedly as Gore, in particular, tried to respond to Bradley, who
was far more aggressive than he has ever been. At another point,
shouts from an audience member, followed by the shouts of other
members of the audience trying to quiet him, left the two
candidates standing there speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley repeatedly challenged Gore for voting, as a member of
Congress in 1981, to overturn an Internal Revenue Service ruling
that would have denied tax-exempt status to private schools whose
racial make-up did not reflect the community where they were
located. As Gore tried to brush off the challenge, Bradley
responded by attempting to hand Gore a sheaf of papers that he said
included the bills themselves. Gore ignored his opponent, leaving
Bradley standing holding the stack of papers in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was reminiscent of Gore's challenge to Bradley in a
previous television encounter to shake hands on a pledge to take
all TV advertisements off the air. Bradley refused, leaving Gore
with his hand out.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gore responded by attacking Bradley for voting in 1995
against legislation to provide more broadcast franchises to
minority owners of television stations.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was the first the two have had in a month, and came
at a particularly critical time for Bradley, whose campaign
nationally _ and in New York, a state where he had once been seen
as posing a powerful challenge to Gore _ has seemed increasingly
adrift. Bradley's supporters viewed Monday night's session as a
chance, arguably one of his last, to effectively put his campaign
back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go in burning with confidence,'' said Jacques DeGraff,
Bradley's deputy national campaign manager. ``This is going to be a
turning point in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is scheduled to deliver what his aides described as two
major speeches in New York over the next two days before heading
out to Washington state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate had barely begun when the two candidates began to
snipe at each other with unusual ferocity. The first question,
posed by the Rev. Al Sharpton, focused on what each candidate would
do to ban racial profiling and prevent police brutality while
keeping crime low.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley repeated his earlier exhortations of why Gore did not
simply stroll down the hall to ask President Clinton to issue an
executive order, immediately, banning racial profiling. Gore said
that work, indeed, had begun to move in that direction. But he
issued the first of numerous one-line zingers by firing back: ``You
know, racial profiling practically began in New Jersey, senator.''
</P>
<P>
   The nastiness permeated the next few minutes, on issues ranging
from possible reparations for slavery, to health care, to
technology and education for African-Americans. Several times, Gore
criticized Bradley for failing to support legislation that would
have expanded the number of black and minority-owned broadcasting
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   But on issues of particular importance to minority voters, the
two candidates clashed even more bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley accused Gore of seeking to end federal affirmative
action, and he was sharply critical of Gore's vote to preserve the
tax-exempt status of schools like Bob Jones University, pulling out
copies of bills and testimonials demonstrating the two candidates'
differing positions. Bradley even tried to offer the papers to
Gore, thrusting them like a frustrated student.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to face up to this if you're going to be a strong
leader,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 minutes of the debate, Bradley also began to attack
Gore as having a conservative record as a congressman, on issues
over everything from tobacco to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks made up 16 percent of the electorate in the 1992
Democratic primary in New York. Clinton won 52 percent of the black
vote, according to a survey of voters leaving the polls at the
time; that was considered the key to his winning the three-way race
with 41 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remains hugely popular with blacks in New York, as in
the rest of the country, and Gore has closely linked himself to the
president, particularly when appearing before black audiences.
</P>
<P>
   He did so again Monday night. Gore has the support of most of
the major black figures in the state, including Rep. Charles Rangel
of Harlem, H. Carl McCall, the state's controller and highest
elected black official, David Dinkins, the former mayor, and Floyd
B. Flake, the former congressman and Queens minister who endorsed
Gore from his pulpit at Sunday services a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bradley enjoys far less support among black elected
officials in New York. He has tried to compensate for that with a
show of support from black basketball players and other
celebrities, among them Spike Lee, the film director, who showed up
at the press filing center across the street from the Apollo before
the debate to tell reporters how well he thought Bradley would do.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has made race one of the touchstone issues of his
campaign; his first major campaign speech, delivered in Manhattan
last April, was devoted to the subject of racial discord.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time that Gore and Bradley had appeared at a
debate devoted to black issues . The audience Monday night was
almost entirely black, and had been invited by community and church
organizations. The first question was posed by Sharpton, who, with
Flake, suggested two weeks ago that the two Democratic candidates
hold a debate on racial issues in a black community.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations for Monday's debate turned out to be more than
a little complicated, with prolonged negotiations among the various
parties over who should be given tickets, the make-up of the debate
sponsors and the format. The result was a long-list of sponsors,
and an unusually free-form kind of debate, including an unscreened
array of questioners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
