A4183 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KIDS-ABUSE-KAN &LR;      02-21 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ABUSE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI LAWMAKERS CONSIDER REVAMPING THE WAY STATE SOCIAL WORKERS
HANDLE CHILD ABUSE REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ A far-reaching
proposal to revamp the way state social workers handle reports of
child abuse is gaining momentum among state lawmakers, supporters
say.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plan, inspired in part by last year's torture and starvation
deaths of Kansas City brothers Larry and Gary Bass, would require
social workers to contact police any time they open an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It would require each county to designate a chief investigator
who is a specialist in child abuse. It would require social service
agencies to enlist the help of schools, police, child care
providers and other resources when investigating reports of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And it would set up a state Social Services SWAT team that would
have police powers, including the authority to seek search warrants
when adults are suspected of trying to cover up abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor, Democratic Sen. Joe Maxwell of Mexico, said
the measure was an effort to harness all the resources already
available to combat child abuse. The current approach is so
fragmented among multiple agencies that serious omissions can
occur, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how badly the system can fail, he pointed to
the case of 8-year-olds Larry and Gary Bass, who died from
starvation in October. Court records say that their mother, Mary
Bass, admitted punishing them by withholding food and lowering
their legs into scalding water.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as 1995, neighbors, ministers and teachers notified
the Division of Family Services that the boys, who were part of a
set of triplets, appeared abused. Yet there is no record that the
boys were ever seen by a social worker, officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Three social workers were suspended for 20 days without pay for
failing to notice the pattern of abuse reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask, how can this kind of thing go on so long that
a child can be starved to death?'' Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's plan would centralize responsibility for such cases in
the chief investigator. That person would be required to oversee
the investigation every time social workers received more than one
complaint about the same child or the same abuser.
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigator would have to verify that social workers
actually saw the suspected victim of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell said the change could keep reports from teachers and
tips to child abuse hot lines from being ignored or lost in the
shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill requires an affirmative response in connection with
any report to the Division of Family Services,'' Maxwell said.
``They can decide to investigate or not, but I want them to make a
conscious decision in writing to determine whether a criminal
investigation is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell said he was confident the plan would pass the Senate.
The House, he said, had also made child abuse a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the death of the Bass children,'' he said, ``everyone in
the Capitol is aware of the importance of child protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reform the way child abuse cases are handled began
last year when Gov. Mel Carnahan appointed a Child Fatality Task
Force to examine patterns of enforcement at the county level.
</P>
<P>
   The effort became a priority after the Bass boys' deaths and the
case of a St. Louis girl who was beaten to death with a broom
handle because she didn't do her homework, Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which could go to the Senate floor as early as this
week, is supported by the Department of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   Social Services Director Gary Stangler said he especially liked
the cross-agency approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a good job of working with police, but we won't
routinely reach out to groups like teachers, nurses and child care
providers who could provide you with good information on what's
happening with that child,'' Stangler said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Gulino, the Jackson County deputy medical examiner who was
co-chairman of the Child Fatality Task Force, was enthusiastic
about most of the bill's reforms. He said making a chief
investigator responsible for an investigation was critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way cases are assigned is almost ridiculously variable,''
Gulino said. ``Other times, you hear of cases that are reported to
DFS, but an individual worker just didn't get it. We need a
consistent mechanism for identifying cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's plan also incorporates some of the ideas championed by
Democratic Sen. Harry Wiggins of Kansas City to open the system to
public scrutiny. Wiggins wanted to open investigation records to
temporary guardians of abuse victims and news reporters so that the
public would know when the system went awry.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas went too far for many senators. But Maxwell said the
current law, which keeps the records secret, is too stringent. So
Maxwell's bill would allow the state Social Services director to
open investigative records when disclosure would not harm other
children in the family.
</P>
<P>
   It also would make public the final report issued by each
county's Child Fatality Review Panel. The panels examine how the
system worked and whether the child's death could have been
prevented.
</P>
<P>
   And it would make investigative records produced by the new
state Social Services SWAT team open to the public after an
investigation is completed. The team, known as the State Technical
Assistance Team, would train and aid local agencies in child abuse,
neglect and exploitation cases.
</P>
<P>
   Stangler said making the agencies' records more open would
strengthen accountability, which is important to restoring public
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's damning to the whole system when we can't disclose what
services were provided and what happened in some of these cases,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gulino, however, opposes making the reports of each county's
Child Fatality Review Panel public. The panels could become a forum
for finger-pointing instead of an objective analysis of how the
system could be improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also would require the Division of Family Services
to keep most records on unsubstantiated complaints on file for 10
years instead of two. Stangler said a 10-year retention schedule
would help case workers detect patterns of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if a complaint is unsubstantiated, if you see six of them
in four years, that's a signal that something is wrong,'' he said.
``Often, that is important in helping us protect a younger
sibling.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is SB0757 and SB602.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
