<HEADLINE>
BIRCH-TELECOM  BIRCH TELECOM GETS $125 MILLION IN LOANS TO EXPAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANAS CITY, Mo. _ Birch Telecom of
Kansas City, which had only a handful of employees two years ago,
has received $125 million in loans to continue its expansion in
Kansas, Missouri and Texas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The financing, arranged by Lehman Brothers Inc., comes from a
coalition that includes eight banks and institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The loans will give the local telephone service company working
cash and capital to expand its Internet facilities and launch
service in additional cities in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With the loans announced Monday, Birch has raised about $350
million since it was formed in January 1997. The company has more
than 1,000 employees in Kansas, Missouri and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The involvement of these new financial partners coincides with
the many opportunities we will pursue during 2000,'' said David E.
Scott, Birch president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are launching additional markets in Texas, expanding to 17
by year-end. To support the increase in customers, lines and
products offered, we continue to invest heavily in our back-office
capabilities, both in information systems and through a significant
expansion of our provisioning and customer care work force.''
</P>
<P>
   The loans were made in a combination of a $25 revolving credit
line for working capital and a $100 million term loan that can be
drawn on as needed to pay for telecommunications systems and
back-office systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
