u p BC-MICH-REPUBS-1STLD-WRI     02-21 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(890)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANGELIST GOES ON THE ATTACK TO HELP BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS to update with more on Rudman reference, comment from
McCain's top aide in Michigan, phone calls accusing Bush of being
anti-Catholic; story now in two takes.) 
 (See also MICH-BUSH, ARIZ-REPUBS, MCCAIN-MOOD) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1-7, 10, 11 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNETT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ While Gov. George W. Bush tried Monday to
rally Michigan voters for Tuesday's primary here with a sunny
message of tax cutting and political reform, a second, shadow
campaign by his allies sought to sow suspicions of Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCain reported receiving automated telephone
calls in which the recorded voice of the televangelist Pat
Robertson urged them to ``protect unborn babies and restore
religious freedom'' by opposing McCain.
</P>
<P>
   As he has on his cable television program, Robertson, a
supporter of Bush, accuses McCain of having chosen as his national
chairman ``a vicious bigot who wrote that conservative Christians
in politics are anti-abortion zealots, homophobes and would-be
censors.''  &UR;  &LR;  The reference is to Warren Rudman, the former New
Hampshire senator, who used those phrases in his autobiography to
describe some in the Christian right, although he also said there
were ``some fine, sincere people in its ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, as he crossed the state on the final day of campaigning
before the primary, continued to attack Bush as a character
assassin and pretender to the mantle of Republican reformer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Robertson said Monday night that he had made the
recording for the Michigan Christian Coalition, without the
knowledge of the Bush campaign. Bush aides said they knew nothing
of the calls and that the direct calls they were making to voters
were all positive. ``All of our scripts are positive
get-out-the-vote scripts,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel campaigns here against McCain, one above the fray
and the other slashing, recalled the pattern in South Carolina,
where third parties spread damaging, exaggerated, and sometimes
false information about McCain. The votes of conservative
Christians, who were and are the focus of those messages, were
crucial to Bush's victory in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, other third-party groups were also coming to Bush's
aid with radio commercials that inflamed doubts about McCain's
commitment to ending abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As the McCain campaign revealed late Monday that it had a
recorded instance of Robertson's calls, the Bush campaign accused
McCain of ``attack phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign released transcripts of two such calls, in which an
automated voice repeated many of the same criticisms that McCain
has made publicly. One call accused Bush of increasing public
spending by a greater percentage in Texas than Bill Clinton has in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both McCain and Bush are good men,'' the caller continued,
``but John McCain has a much more conservative record on fighting
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   The second call accused Bush of a ``negative smear campaign''
and urged a vote against ``negative smear politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hudome, McCain's top aide in Michigan, said that the two
calls transcribed by the Bush campaign were consistent with calls
the McCain forces were making.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to make advocacy calls,'' Hudome said. ``It's
another thing to make push-style negative calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter, he said, was the approach of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's message Monday was largely consistent with those calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like Luke Skywalker trying to get out of the Death
Star,'' declared the senator, delighting in his new Star Wars
imagery before a rowdy crowd at Heritage High School in Saginaw,
north of here.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal to Michigan's independent-minded voters, he held
Bush's establishment support, including from Gov. John Engler,
against him. ``I'm telling you, they're shooting at me from
everywhere. Everybody's against me. Governor Engler, Governor Bush,
all the governors, all the senators. And we're going to kill them,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   As some in the crowd chanted ``No more Bush,'' McCain replied,
``I thank you. There's our secret weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to ignore his Republican rival Monday, explaining to
reporters that ``this is the time to rally the vote.'' He preferred
to direct his barbs at Vice President Al Gore, who he accused of
``politics that's so stale and so negative.''
</P>
<P>
   But when pressed, Bush once again questioned McCain's commitment
to cleaning up the political system. ``He talks about the iron
triangle in Washington, D.C,'' Bush said, referring to the
senator's complaints about the links between lobbyists, campaign
donations and legislation. ``He's been ringing that iron triangle
like a dinner bell.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Bush's simile, McCain responded, ``He's the one taking
all the money from them. Seems to me he's had a Pavlovian
reaction.'' With a laugh, he essayed a metaphor, accusing Bush of
having ``both feet in the trough.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of boutique politicking in New Hampshire and South
Carolina, the candidates, short of time to impress voters and short
of patience with each other, were counting on their national images
and a burst of appearances to make and correct impressions in what
Bush on Monday called an abbreviated ``two-day primary.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Bush was buoyant as he moved from east to west,
from the company of workers at a Detroit factory to a rally among
Grand Rapids' more conservative voters Monday evening. McCain
traveled from north to south before flying home in the evening to
Arizona, which also votes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Late into the evening Monday, the Bush and McCain campaigns
traded accusations of sinister telephone calls. Bush aides supplied
the telephone numbers of women who said they had received calls
accusing Bush of being anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Karns, who lives in the Detroit suburb of Birmingham,
said that she received a call at 5:30 p.m. that issued a ``Catholic
voters alert.'' Then, she said, the anonymous voice told her ``that
George Bush had gone to Bob Jones University, and Bob Jones
University was anti-Catholic, and George Bush was anti-Catholic.''
Then, she continued, ``It said John McCain was pro-Catholic and I
should vote for John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that
the caller ``accused Bush of calling the pope the anti-Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign denied any knowledge of the calls.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign supplied the telephone number of Sue Eaton,
a homemaker in Ypsilanti who said she had received an automated
telephone call Monday afternoon attacking McCain and ``more or less
insinuating to the fact of being a POW made him have a bad
temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton said the call suggested that McCain would have a
hair-trigger temper in dealing with an obstreperous foreign power
like Iraq, and urged her to make a ``wise choice.'' She said she
did not know the origin of the call, and the Bush campaign denied
any knowledge of it.
</P>
<P>
   Any of Michigan's 6.7 million registered voters is free to cast
a ballot Tuesday, regardless of party affiliation. Pollsters have
pronounced the race too close to call, and they say it is highly
dependent on the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Candice Miller, Michigan's secretary of state and state
elections officer, has been predicting that 950,000 voters will
turn out on Tuesday, when the weather is expected to be
unseasonably mild. Just over half a million people voted in the
primary of March 1996.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to the bigger voice that the primary's earlier date
has given them in selecting the nominee, Michigan voters are likely
to be drawn to the polls by a variety of local ballot issues, like
whether to add filters to the Internet for Holland's library or to
raise $12 million to overhaul Birmingham's sewers.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by historical patterns, as much as 20 percent of the
potential vote may already have been cast by absentee ballot.
Michigan automatically mails such ballots to its elderly citizens.
</P>
<P>
   John Schwarz, the only Republican state senator to endorse
McCain, said that he was hoping that 1.1 million voters turn out,
because he felt that that would benefit the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Higher turnout, he said, ``indicates more independents are
voting, and you know, Michigan is independent heaven.'' In 1996, 10
percent of the voters in the Republican primary were Democrats, and
28 percent were independents.
</P>
<P>
   But South Carolina had a record turnout in its primary Saturday,
and Bush won handily.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have indicated that Bush has strong support among
Republicans in Michigan. So given his hopes of rallying
independents, McCain's itinerary Monday was odd, since he did not
campaign in suburban Detroit where independents are concentrated.
``Would I have gone to Oakland county?'' asked Schwarz, speaking by
telephone before climbing back on the candidate's bus in Saginaw.
``Yeah, I would have. But I'm not making those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in two days McCain had hit ``probably six of the
nine media markets in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain began his day in the thinly populated northern reaches of
the state, campaigning in Traverse City. There, at one of his
trademark town meetings, he once again made the quality of the
campaign itself an issue, urging a crowd of more than 1,000 to
``reject this negative campaigning, reject this character
assassination, reject the low road to the presidency and support
the high road.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Detroit, Bush made stops at a Bob's Big restaurant
and an elementary school in Brighton, before giving a midday speech
in East Lansing. There, Bush portrayed himself as the true reformer
in the race. ``If you're sick and tired of the politics of
Washington, D.C., of the gridlock, there's a home for you in this
campaign,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
