<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOX-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-     02-21 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX DECIDES TO END `WHO WANTS TO MARRY A MULTIMILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to delete `Nev.' after Lake Tahoe reference in 9th graf.)   
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fox Network decided Monday to kill the potentially lucrative
franchise called ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire,'' ending
an episode almost as bizarre as the so-called reality-based
programs for which the television network has become known, like
``The World's Most Shocking Moments Caught on Tape.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Sandy Grushow, chairman of Fox Entertainment
Television, came after Fox learned that Rick Rockwell, the
bridegroom in last week's widely watched special, had been the
subject of a restraining order because of charges that he had
physically threatened a girlfriend nine years ago. Fox executives
said Rockwell had failed to disclose the information during
background checks leading up to the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the network canceled a repeat of last week's show
scheduled for Tuesday night, but left open the possibility that it
would broadcast new versions of the program in the future. Flush
with the ratings success, Darnell had announced last week his
intention to mount a special with the genders reversed, and a
female millionaire selecting a husband.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the special, which had stirred a national debate
about modern relationships and the pressures on women to marry,
raises new questions about the risks in a growing trend among the
broadcast networks to rely on programs that put real people into
challenging and life-changing situations.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months networks have plans to put people on a
desert island swarming with cameras, to lock people together into a
house filled with cameras, and even, in the case of one syndicated
show, to marry strangers off to each other every week.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Darnell, the executive vice president of Fox who invented
the marry-a-millionaire concept, said the network had decided not
to go forward with any other specials in that format because,
``It's just not worth the risk.'' He said: ``This is the end for
this show. We are not doing another one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the show broadcast a week ago, Rockwell, who billed himself
as a real estate developer and motivational speaker, selected among
50 prospective brides in a beauty-pageantlike contest. He chose
Darva Conger, an emergency room nurse.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, however, information emerged that
revealed that Rockwell was a longtime comedian with a history of
engaging in stunts like telling jokes for 30 straight hours to get
into the Guinness Book of World Records. While Fox and Next
Entertainment, the company that produced the special, continued to
vouch for his financial claim of assets exceeding $2 million,
numerous questions arose about the truthfulness of some of his
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Though Fox claimed that it had conducted a thorough check of
Rockwell, it became clear that the research was less than
exhaustive. Among Rockwell's claims called into question were that
he had not performed as a comedian in about 10 years (a comedy club
owner said he had hired him only two years ago) and that he had
opened for the ``Tonight'' show star, Jay Leno, in Lake Tahoe. A
representative for Leno said that Rockwell had never opened
anywhere for him).
</P>
<P>
   Several companies for whom Rockwell said he worked as a
motivational speaker said that they had never hired him. Nancy
Buchholz, a spokeswoman for Maritz Travel, a national travel-agency
business based in St. Louis, said that Rockwell had never performed
at a Maritz travel agency. Mary Elizabeth Gifford, a spokeswoman
for The Golden Door, a high-end California health spa, said that
Rockwell had never been a guest speaker there. Don Stanziano, the
spokesman for the Scripps Hospital system in San Diego, which
includes six hospitals, said that the company had no record of
Rockwell ever performing at any of the hospitals or corporate
retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, who returned to his San Diego home from a honeymoon
trip to the Caribbean with Conger on Sunday, told a local
television station, KFMB, in San Diego: ``As you know, this journey
began with my desire to find love on a television show. I had no
idea there would be so much interest and so much scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   About the restraining order, he said: ``Nearly ten years ago, I
was involved in a relationship that ended poorly. But I am here to
tell you tonight that at no time have I ever struck any of my
girlfriends for any reason.'' Rockwell went on to say that he
``never informed the producers of the show about this issue because
I considered it a closed chapter in my life and any contentious
feelings that existed ten years ago are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Darnell of Fox said, `'The latest information came as a shock to
me and the production company. I don't know why he didn't say
anything to us about it.`
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell had been extensively questioned about his background,
Darnell said. ``The production company did a security check and he
came up clean. It was a criminal check, a civil check and a credit
check. He was actually specifically asked if there was anything
else we should know about his past. He signed an affidavit that
everything he told us was true.''
</P>
<P>
   The saga of the special began in the fall when Darnell came up
with the idea to marry off a millionaire on a show, in an effort to
play off the mania surrounding ABC's hit game show ``Who Wants To
be A Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell has gained a reputation in television for creating some
of the most outrageous and highly rated specials of recent years,
including some with the memorable titles of ``When Animals Attack''
and `When Good Pets Go Bad,'' as well as ``Alien Autopsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The specials, which almost always generated high ratings, have
been extremely effective during the special rating periods knows as
sweep months, when advertising rates are set, helping Fox post
impressive overall ratings by replacing many of the network's least
popular programs.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, the storm over ``MultiMillionaire'' came as Fox
was beginning to distance itself from the violent specials.
Grushow, who recently took over the job running Fox's entertainment
division, called them ``ratings crack,'' and said the network
needed to break its addiction to them. Grushow argued that Fox got
only a short-term benefit from the specials, that they did not
provide any ancillary profits _ like those from syndication _ and
that they occupied time periods where Fox needed to develop
comedies and dramas that could be long-term assets.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell also developed other, entertainment-oriented specials
like ``Secrets of Magic Revealed,'' which showed how many famous
magic tricks are done. That program, which outraged many magicians,
was the highest-rated special ever on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent fiasco, Darnell said he would continue to
develop specials ``that get under people's skin and are
fascinating.'' But he added that ``there will be a level of
responsibility that goes with them.'' He called the magic special
``a perfect example of the kind of show we want to keep doing.''
Specifically, he said, ``I'll be back in May with something
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Other networks are expected to continue their plans to broadcast
reality-based shows, he said, because the audience response to them
has been so strong. CBS will have two such programs this summer _
one, ``Survivor,'' will take a group of people to an island off
Borneo and put them through various tests with the ultimate winner
taking home $1 million. The other CBS show is ``Big Brother,''
which has a similar format, set in a house with cameras.
</P>
<P>
   A company called Infinity Productions has plans for a weekly
syndicated show called ``Wed at First Sight,'' a ``Dating
Game''-type program except that the couple, strangers at the start
of the show, will be married at the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
