<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RUBIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISAAC RUBIN, 86, APPEALS COURT JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Justice Isaac Rubin, a former New York state appeals
court judge from Westchester County, died Saturday in a hospice in
the Bronx. He was 86 and lived in Rye.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the bench in 1990 after 20 years, Rubin
continued to work in the court system as a judicial hearing officer
for the state Supreme Court and its Appellate Division in
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Until mid-January, when pancreatic cancer incapacitated him,
Rubin drove to work in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   When Rubin stepped down as an appeals judge at age 77, it was
only after having unsuccessfully challenged a provision of the New
York State Constitution that requires state judges to retire at 76.
At the time, he said, ``A judge should be judged based on his own
physical condition and his competence, not solely on his age.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin began his judicial career in 1970 as a City Court judge in
Rye. He was appointed to the County Court of Westchester in 1973
and was elected to a full term as a County Court judge in 1974 and
then to the New York State Supreme Court in Westchester in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   From 1978 to 1981, he acted as the supervising judge for the
criminal division of the 9th District, which includes Westchester,
Dutchess, Orange, Rockland and Putnam counties. He developed
procedures that helped reduce court backlogs in the five counties.
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed to the Appellate Division in 1982 by Gov. Hugh
Carey and reappointed by Mario Cuomo in 1984. He was president of
the Westchester County Bar Association from 1971 to 1973. Rubin was
also a member of the New York State Commission on Judicial Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Mount Vernon, he served in the Army Air Corps
in World War II. Before becoming a judge, he was a partner in his
own law firm in Mount Vernon for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from New York University, where he also earned his
law degree. He also had a doctorate in law from St. John's
University Law School. Rubin is survived by his wife, Lucille; his
son, Charlie, of New York City; his daughter, Carol Rubin Kahn of
Chappaqua; and one granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-21-00 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000221.0456 </DOCNO>
