<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-21 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY TRAILS, 2-0, AFTER A DISASTROUS DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ On a day when blood and hope were lost
aboard the Italian yacht Luna Rossa, Team New Zealand's NZL 60
sailed to its second straight commanding victory on Tuesday and
took a 2-0 lead over the Prada Challenge in defense of the
America's Cup. The margin was two minutes 43 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After a lay day on Wednesday, Race 3 of the five-of-nine-race
series is scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For the Italians, the day started badly and then deteriorated
into utter, unchecked, complete disaster. At the five-minute gun
before the start, Luna Rossa approached from starboard, the
advantaged end, an edge it had used with stunning effectiveness in
Race 1.
</P>
<P>
   But the New Zealand helmsman Russell Coutts, coming in to the
starting area from port, almost immediately took matters into his
own hands. With remarkable maneuverability accentuated by crisp,
perfect crew work that made NZL 60 look like an Olympic sprinter in
full glide and Prada like a weekend jogger trudging through sand
dunes, Coutts cut behind Prada, gained an overlap, and took full
control of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian tactician Torben Grael had but one option: bail for
the spectator fleet in a frantic attempt to evade the Kiwi's
shadow. Coutts, on his tail, was ready for his dash, answering each
of Prada's evasive moves tit for tat.
</P>
<P>
   NZL 60 led back across the starting line, which they crossed at
full speed with Luna Rossa 18 seconds in arrears. Like a wide
receiver trying to shake a cornerback off the line of scrimmage,
Prada threw two quick tacks at the Kiwis, but they kept the clamps
on and would not be shaken.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief glimmer of hope for the Italians as they
tacked away to port and finally gasped a breath of clear air
unhindered by the exhaust off the trailing edge of the Kiwis'
sails. The day's first shift in the oscillating, 12-to 15-knot
breeze was a lefty, and for a brief moment Luna Rossa closed to
within a boat length of the New Zealanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're faster,'' said one Prada crewman, and for a moment it
appeared he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly blood was flowing aboard Luna Rossa and the race,
for all intents and purposes, was over.
</P>
<P>
   The call came from Prada that a plastic bag or tarp was caught
on its keel wings, sapping speed as well as the boat's ability to
point at an optimal angle high into the wind. A long carbon-fiber
pole was sent topsides to execute the task, but somehow the stick
caught bowman Max Sirena along the side of his head, opening a wide
gash.
</P>
<P>
   With a towel pressed to his skull in an attempt to contain the
wound, Sirena hung limply over the side as a deep red stain spread
over the aft quarter of Prada's silver hull. A launch went
alongside and Sirena was whisked aboard, where a doctor closed the
cut with stitches.
</P>
<P>
   But the Italians' problems were far from over, for the offending
plastic was still dangling from the underbody. The Italians spilled
wind from their sails, slowed down, and lowered a crewman over the
side on a halyard to swipe at the material with the pole, but to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   Luna Rossa had no choice but to stop almost completely and lower
another sailor, mainsail trimmer Piero Romeo. Adding insult to
injury, NZL 60 was flying away at around 10 knots on the wings of a
new right-hand shift. Romeo could not dive down and free the mess,
but putting on the brakes allowed the plastic to finally drift
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians' chances to tie the series had already drifted
away, for the Kiwis rounded the top mark two minutes 19 seconds
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians made some gains at the next two marks, but on leg
4, when they found themselves unable to tack for about 10 minutes
because of a broken sail track, the New Zealanders put it away. It
was the punctuation mark on a horror story.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can go wrong?'' said the Prada helmsman, Francesco
de Angelis, as the Kiwis pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight race, the score had been settled in the
first 20 minutes. But as in Race 1, the Kiwis won not because of a
decided edge in boat speed, but by error-free, efficient sailing
and faultless tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians have a day to heal and regroup. After another
brilliant piece of sailing by their hometown opponents on the
Hauraki Gulf, whether it will be time enough to make any difference
is suddenly very much in doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
