<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK AGREES TO STOP DISPUTED ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. has
agreed to stop what a competitor alleges is misleading advertising
about a refund loan program. Block, however, said it planned to
continue offering the loans until the matter was resolved in court.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Liberty Tax Service, a Virginia Beach, Va., tax-preparation
chain founded by longtime Block rival John Hewitt, sued last month
in federal court in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty alleged that Block misled consumers in certain test
markets when it offered what are known as refund-anticipation loans
without telling taxpayers about loan fees that would be deducted
from the refund.
</P>
<P>
   Block says that the advertising properly discloses the costs and
features of the loans to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Refund-anticipation loans are loans that Block, Liberty and
other tax preparers make available to clients who want refunds
faster than the Internal Revenue Service normally can provide them.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, once the preparer receives federal confirmation that
a claimed refund is likely to be paid, the preparer will arrange
for a loan to the taxpayer, within about 48 hours, of an amount of
money equal to the refund, minus a fee for the service. The
preparer then collects the full refund about a week later when the
IRS finishes processing the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Block this year is testing a plan in California and parts of
Virginia, Pennsylvania, New York, Iowa and Ohio in which the
company incorporates the refund-anticipation loan fees into what
customers pay for preparation and filing. The company then arranges
a loan equal to the full refund.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Virginia markets where the new plan is being tested
include cities served by Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who once worked for Block, previously founded and headed
Jackson Hewitt Tax Service, the nation's second-largest tax
preparation network after Block. Jackson Hewitt is now a subsidiary
of Cendant Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Norfolk
alleging that Block was unfairly advertising in the test markets
that taxpayers were getting full refunds without disclosing the
true nature of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Block disputes those allegations but signed a consent agreement
Friday in that court to end the disputed advertising ``until a
trial can be held on the merits of the claims,'' said Neil Getzlow,
a company spokesman in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Block intends to continue offering the refund loans and
collecting the fees up front because the consent agreement does not
bar those activities, Getzlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt disputed Block's contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the judge is going to be mad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side could estimate when the dispute might come to
trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
