A4213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-SCENE-NYT &LR;      02-21 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUCOUS CROWD PUTS STAMP ON DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DEMS-DEBATE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even before Monday night's Democratic debate began,
one got the feeling it would be different from the others. As the
moderator, CNN's Bernard Shaw, was laying out the ground rules forthe audience, a man who could not hear boomed out from the upper
tier, ``What about that mike, spike?''
</P>
<P>
   For the next five minutes Shaw fumbled about with his
microphone, and the feisty, vociferous, oh-so-New York role of the
audience had been firmly established for the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   As former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore jousted
from behind their lecterns, the packed house at the Apollo Theater
in Harlem hooted, howled and shouted their opinions with abandon,
prompting Shaw to ask for calm at one point and forcing a
several-minute delay at another.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the historic home of Wednesday night amateur
talent nights that have launched the careers of more than a few
black stars, where the mettle of novice performers is tested by
raucous crowds quick with their hooks, stingy with their ovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds here let you know how they feel immediately,'' said
Haja Worley, 53, a Wednesday night regular who attended Monday
night's debate. ``There was some of that going on tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous crowd in their red-velvet seats seemed perfectly
attuned to the combative mood of the candidates, who slugged it out
in their testiest meeting in five debates.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore challenged Bradley's commitment to ending racial
profiling by saying, ``Racial profiling practically began in New
Jersey'' _ a reference to Bradley's home state _ the crowd erupted
in both catcalls and cheers, making it impossible to hear Gore from
the upper tiers for a full minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to New York,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's press
secretary. ``This sure isn't Iowa or New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   They were no less generous with the noise with Bradley. When the
insurgent tried to hand Gore a packet of letters purporting to
document his opposition to legislation barring tax-exempt status to
Bob Jones University and other private colleges known for
discriminatory practices, the jeers and cheers were deafening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please restrain your outbursts so we can proceed,'' Shaw
implored the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   One woman wearing a Million Man March sweatshirt played
cheerleader to the upper-deck crowd, pounding her fist into an open
palm when Gore got in a zinger, miming a foul shot when Bradley
blasted back.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was even brought to a standstill when a man in the
audience began shouting at the candidates, who stood watching him
mutely. As his tirade continued, aggravated audience members began
chanting, ``Respect Harlem! Respect Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, particularly Gore, seemed to sense the rowdiness
of the crowd, playing to it at times. Almost every time Bradley
ripped off an attack on Gore, the vice president would mug for the
crowd, theatrically mouthing ``Not true!'' at points, shaking his
head in mock dismay at others.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also played to the crowd with his entrance, shaking the
hands of each of the three journalists on the panel and then
crossing to center stage to shake Shaw's and Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   (It was emblematic of the two candidates' contrasting styles
that Bradley had simply walked onto the stage and gone straight to
his lectern. After Gore upstaged him, however, Bradley made a point
of showing the three panelists that he would like to come over and
shake their hands, but was tethered to his microphone.)
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the raucous mood of the debate hall seemed to move
across the street to the press room, where surrogates for the two
candidates were allowed to shout their analyses through a
microphone at the crowd of reporters who were struggling to file
stories on deadline. (In most previous debates, the surrogates have
either been kept out of the press room or required to offer their
opinions in private.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley fired the African Americans who were part of his
Senate staff, and I'll name them for you,'' screamed Mayor Sharpe
James of Newark, N.J., a one-time supporter turned bitter critic of
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The debate had the potential to be even more freewheeling than
it was, as audience members were allowed to ask questions, just
like in the town meetings both candidates hold. And as the debate
got under way, the lines of people wanting to speak were 15 deep
before each of four microphones in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   But some impromptu screening by the CNN producers managed to
keep the questions respectful and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   And that left more than a few people unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disappointed they didn't let me ask my
question,'' said Barry Crumbley, who wanted to ask the candidates
about black farmers. ``That's not how it's supposed to be at the
Apollo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
