<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FIZER-IOWA-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE HIS DENIALS, FIZER IS CYCLONES' KEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iowa State junior forward Marcus Fizer insists that he would not
be a leading candidate for Big 12 Player of the Year if not for a
supporting cast of multi-talented guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be the player I am today if not for Michael Nurse,
Jamaal Tinsley, Kantrail Horton and all the guys,'' Fizer insists.
``One player can't win it all. The ball begins in their hands. They
give it to me. They deserve all the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer might pass on credit for the Cyclones' surprising run at
the Big 12 championship, but few would argue that the power forward
is the prime reason for Iowa State's success. The Cyclones (22-4,
10-2) go into tonight's battle in Ames, Iowa, with Texas (19-6,
10-2) knotted with the Longhorns and Oklahoma State atop the
conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about any of their kids you want, and there have
been some great additions,'' Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said.
``But it all started with Marcus Fizer and his mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents point to a marked improvement in Fizer's game from his
sophomore season. A more mature Fizer has displayed newfound
leadership and the dogged determination to become a dominant
player. But Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy points to the bottom
line as the area where Fizer has had the most visible effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``His impact on winning is his biggest improvement,'' Eustachy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer led the Big 12 in scoring (18.0 points per game) a season
ago and was eighth in rebounding (7.6). But he was mildly surprised
last summer when he was not one of the 12 players selected for the
USA Basketball team that won the gold medal at the World University
Games in Spain. He made the top 16, but did not survive the final
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way it was a shock,'' Fizer said. ``But among the final
16 players, everyone had been to postseason \Rplay\S except me.
Some had been to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had worked hard to get to that point and considered
it a great blessing that I had gotten that far. But I became more
mentally focused after not making the team. Actually, that
experience gave me a lot of extra confidence and made me want to
work harder to get my school recognized, gave me more drive to work
as hard as I could to be the best I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer again leads the conference in scoring (21.2) and ranks
seventh in rebounding (7.8), but teammates say he's much more
valuable than the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about what Marcus does for this team
because he does a little bit of everything,'' Iowa State senior
forward Stevie Johnson said. ``He's matured so much in every phase
of his game. He's gotten so much better, bigger and stronger. It's
so evident, everyone can see it. Not only his teammates, but people
watching in on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also evident to opponents watching game tapes. Texas
forward Gabe Muoneke, who along with Chris Owens and sometimes
Chris Mihm will be asked to take turns guarding Fizer tonight, said
no one has improved more in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as physical as he's ever been, but he's much more mobile
than he ever was,'' Muoneke said. ``He does things all over the
court that make everyone else on his team better. But this year,
he's got more help, which allows him to be a better player, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in Fizer has been most evident to Eustachy, who built
this year's team around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is a different guy, more mature,'' Eustachy said. ``He
lets the game come to him. He dictates the game. It dictated him
last year. If things went well early, fine. If it didn't, it
affected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also changed his body this summer. Fat turned to muscle. He
now benches close to 400 pounds, and there's more pop to him
because he lost some weight. He's playing above the rim a lot more.
And he's taking fewer shots, yet scoring more because he's taking
better shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the Big 12 race, Fizer said this season
has erased the memories of the past two, when the Cyclones were a
combined 17-33 and 11-21 in conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the best year of my life in basketball,'' Fizer
said. ``It's almost nullified those first two seasons. I wouldn't
trade this season or this group of guys for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer shies away from personal adulation, but accepts his role
as the team's leading player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Superman,'' he said. ``I have flaws just like anyone
else. I just try to be a leader and do the right things. I want to
help carry this team as far as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, that's been right to the top of the Big 12.
\Nsubheds:The book on Fizer \Nagatea:Class: Junior
</P>
<P>
   Position: Forward
</P>
<P>
   Height: 6-8
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 265
</P>
<P>
   High school: Earned McDonald's All-America honors at Arcadia,
La., becoming first ISU recruit so honored. ... Named ``Parade''
All-American. ... Recruited by former Cyclones coach Tim Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   College: Averaged 14.9 points and 6.7 rebounds as freshman. ...
Averaged 18.0 points and 7.6 points as a sophomore, earning AP
first-team All Big 12 honors. ... A top contender for All-American
and Big 12 Player of the Year honors this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
