<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MATEO-TEX </SLUG>
 RANGERS HAVE PLAN FOR MATEO (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Ruben Mateo's spring-training agenda has
been set. The Rangers want their center-field prodigy to:
</P>
<P>
   Learn to go back on fly balls without smashing into the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Stop trying to hit home runs every time up.
</P>
<P>
   Stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Back up his cocky attitude by focusing on playing the game right
and playing it well.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates emphasized that last point during a chat he
had with Mateo and newly acquired right-fielder Gabe Kapler at the
start of spring training Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their future is so bright, I told them I don't want them to
let it pass them by,'' Oates said yesterday. ``The window can close
so fast. No. 1, they should enjoy it, and No. 2, they should take
advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the right fielder \RKapler\S. He's going
to be fine. I wanted to make sure the center fielder walks the
talk. He talks about his girlfriend being The Ballpark in
Arlington. I just want to make sure he doesn't lose his focus
because this opportunity doesn't come along often.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo is the latest in the Rangers' trinity of Latin American
outfielders expected to be All-Stars, following the path of Ruben
Sierra and Juan Gonzalez. But those two have moved on. Now, Mateo's
time has come.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is he the minor-league prospect everybody raves about.
He is the Rangers' starting center fielder, and they want to make
sure he's ready for the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good,'' left fielder Rusty Greer said. ``But he's got to
prove himself and prove he can play. Everybody knows he has the
talent, but he's got to use that talent on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo is not shy. He good-naturedly taunted hitting coach Rudy
Jaramillo, who was pitching to him in batting practice, during the
first workout Sunday. Mateo dared Jaramillo to pitch him inside.
When he did, Mateo hit the ball over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their own style,'' Jaramillo said. ``Some
players show more confidence verbally and physically than others.
But if you're going to be cocky, you've got to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mateo, ``I just want to do the best I can for this team.
The main thing is I want to stay healthy and play in as many games
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers want to see that as well. Mateo has a combined .325
batting average over his past three minor-league seasons, but he
has also missed nearly four months of playing time in that span
because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo was called up to the Rangers on June 12 last year but
missed two weeks with a strained groin muscle. He then had his
season come to an end Aug. 4 when he got hit in the left hand with
a pitch and broke his hamate bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was hard on me,'' Mateo said. ``The team was going to the
playoffs, and I missed that. I don't like to sit out any games,
especially the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were hoping Mateo would make up for lost time with a
strong winter-ball season in his native Dominican Republic. But
more problems came up. Mateo missed much of the regular winter
season with a stomach virus that caused him to lose 15 pounds. He
tried returning for the playoffs but was 7-for-46 (.152) before
being sidelined with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin wasn't happy about what he was
hearing about Mateo and made it a point to meet with him during his
annual trip to the Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Were you really hurt or did you not want to play
winter ball?' '' Melvin said. ``I asked him, `Are you prepared for
the opportunity to play in the big leagues, or do I need to go out
and get another center fielder?' I told him about \Rbackup
outfielders\S Chad Curtis and Jason McDonald. I let him know it's
not automatic, there are no shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He responded with a smile and that inner confidence,'' Melvin
said. ``You do that with some players, and I see them scared. You
do it with him, it's a laugh. He said, `You don't have to worry
about center field.' ''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
