<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-HAMILTON-AWARD-CE     02-21 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HAMILTON-AWARD-CEREMONY-TEX </SLUG>
 GEORGIA TECH'S JOE HAMILTON BIG
ENOUGH FOR O'BRIEN AWARD (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
By WHIT CANNING c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Reflecting on the four years her son Joe
spent as the quarterback at Georgia Tech, Ginger Hamilton decided
it was almost as if he had fulfilled a destiny laid out long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing that runs through my mind now,'' she said, as
her son prepared to accept the 1999 Davey O'Brien National
Quarterback Award at the Fort Worth Club, ``is the way Joe has been
true to the principles his father (Joseph) spent all those years
instilling in him: that size doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what size you are, you can excel.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting an Atlantic Coast Conference career total offense record
(10,640 yards), Hamilton certainly excelled. And as the 23rd winner
of the annual award presented by the Davey O'Brien Foundation, the
5-foot-10 ``Little Joe'' was certainly one of the most fitting. It
was almost as if he played out a script written by the 5-7 ``Little
Davey'' long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my life listening to people tell me I'm too small
to do this,'' said Hamilton, accompanied by his parents, and his
sister, Megan. ``I've spent most of that time trying to prove them
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey O'Brien? I know he was a great quarterback who led the
nation in passing and led his team to a national championship, and
I am very proud to win the award named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew how to play the game. He was a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Hamilton, who led the Yellow Jackets to three consecutive
bowl games and set ACC career marks for touchdown passes and
passing efficiency. As a senior, he finished second in the nation
in total offense (344.9) and pass efficiency (175.0), throwing for
3,060 yards and 29 touchdowns and rushing for 734. Georgia Tech led
the nation in total offense (509.0) and was second in scoring
(40.7).
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton also became legendary for fourth-quarter comebacks,
pulling out seven victories in that fashion over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we worked on,'' Georgia Tech offensive
coordinator Ralph Friedgen said, ``but mainly it was Joe. He just
had that spirit. He never believes he's beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his dream of being a pro quarterback, Hamilton said,
``I just want to fit in somewhere. I hope someone will give me a
chance to prove myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Hamilton managed to get his hometown of
Alvin placed on the South Carolina state map for the first time in
memory. There is now a sign proclaiming it the ``Home of Joe
Hamilton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm glad about that,'' he said, laughing. ``I guess
there's about 800 people there, and I need to go back and see how
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton _ who was joined by runner-up Drew Brees of Purdue and
several past winners including Jim McMahon, Gino Torretta, Peyton
Manning, Danny Wuerffel, Michael Bishop and Don McPherson _
received a Rolex watch and became an honorary Fort Worth citizen.
Georgia Tech received a check for $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Henkes of L.D. Bell was the high school scholarship
winner, receiving a four-year, $20,000 scholarship.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
