<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AUCTION-RESIGN-1STLD-     02-21 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-RESIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATIONS AT SOTHEBY'S SHAKE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 6th and 7th grafs of background. Rewrites first
part of 10th graf, bgng In 1979...)  
(mk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As it deals with a federal anti-trust investigation,
Sotheby's, the leading worldwide auction house, announced Monday
the resignations of its major shareholder, A. Alfred Taubman, as
chairman and Diana D. Brooks, arguably the most powerful woman in
the art world, as president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sovern, the former president of Columbia University,
will replace Taubman as the company's chairman, and William
Ruprecht, managing director of Sotheby's North and South America
since 1994, will take over Brooks' job. The resignations, which
came after a board meeting conducted by telephone Monday afternoon,
rocked an art world already shaken by the criminal investigation.
They left open questions about the future direction of the company,
including the possible sale of Taubman's interests, and the
high-end auction business in general.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks the art world and Wall Street have been waiting for
Sotheby's to respond to allegations that it conspired with
archrival Christie's to fix the commissions the auction houses
charge buyers and sellers. The criminal anti-trust investigation
into the matter, which began in 1997, heated up three weeks ago
when Christie's announced that it was cooperating with federal
investigators regarding ``possible conduct'' relevant to the
investigation. A month before, Christopher M. Davidge, its chief
executive officer, abruptly resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Any illegal collusion could involve tens, if not hundreds, of
millions of dollars. Sotheby's and Christie's control about 95
percent of the $4 billion worldwide auction business. Christie's,
which was bought by the French investor Francois Pinault in 1998,
is now held privately. Sotheby's, which trades on the New York
Stock Exchange, is in a far more vulnerable position. Not only does
it not have conditional promises of leniency, which Christie's won
by coming to prosecutors first with information, but it also has
shareholders to answer to.
</P>
<P>
   Its share price has plunged from a high of 47 last spring to 17
3/4 on Friday. In Monday's announcement, Sotheby's said it had
``recently met with the Department of Justice in order to discuss a
prompt and appropriate resolution of this investigation.'' Neither
it nor Christie's has denied wrongdoing in their public statements.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the investigation are two increases in
commission fee structures. In 1992, Sotheby's announced that it was
increasing the commissions buyers pay from a flat fee of 10 percent
to 15 percent on the first $50,000 of a purchase price, with a 10
percent fee on the rest. Seven weeks later Christie's followed
suit. Neither house altered its structure for buyers after that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Christie's came first, changing fees it charges sellers
from a flat commission of 10 percent to a more complex,
nonnegotiable sliding scale ranging from 2 to 20 percent, depending
on the size of the sale. Weeks later Sotheby's did the same. Before
the auction houses changed the commission for sellers they ran the
risk of cutting into their profits by agreeing to cut or eliminate
fees to get business from many of the world's most important
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   In a staff e-mail sent Monday afternoon, Ruprecht said ``these
decisions have been very difficult ones for Alfred and Dede and
they have made them in the best interests of Sotheby's.''
</P>
<P>
   Taubman, 75, the Detroit shopping-center magnate credited with
transforming plain suburban shopping centers, known as strip malls,
into playgrounds for the rich with designer shops like Yves St.
Laurent, Ralph Lauren and Louis Vuitton, bought Sotheby's in 1983.
Taubman owns 22.5 percent of the outstanding shares of the company
and has 63 percent of the company's voting power on the board. He
used his flair for retailing to turn Sotheby's from a sleepy
auction house into a one-stop shopping center offering customers
everything from financing and insurance to storage and art
education.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he hired Ms. Brooks, an outgoing woman with a mind for
numbers, who started in the finance department and worked her way
up to president of Sotheby's in America in 1987 and its worldwide
chief executive seven years later. Brooks became president of
Sotheby's in America in 1987 and its chief executive worldwide
seven years later. Last year, Brooks, 49, decided to invest $40
million in Internet business, joining forces with Amazon.Com and
starting Sotheby's own Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Sovern, 69, has coupled his lifelong involvement with Columbia
with several high-profile assignments that have called on his
expertise as a lawyer. He was chairman of the New York State-New
York City Commission on Integrity in Government, which became known
as the Sovern Commission, after municipal scandals shook the city
in 1986. He also served as head of the New York City Charter
Commission and as a trustee of the fund established to raise money
to help pay President Clinton's anticipated legal bills in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment is evidence of the desire of Sotheby's board to
bring in a respected figure who can help the company preserve its
image and deal with whatever integrity problems arise from the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It may also signal the fact that the auction house is
positioning itself for a sale. Financial analysts involved in the
art world said that Taubman had been studying whether to sell his
shares even before the current turn in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Taubman nor Brooks could be reached for comment. Dealers
and art buyers were reluctant to respond publicly to the news of
the resignations. ``No one's rejoicing,'' said an art lawyer who
would speak only on condition of anonymity. ``We're waiting for the
other shoe to drop. At this point we don't know how seriously these
disclosures will affect confidence in the art market.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene V. Thaw, a prominent retired dealer, said, ``It's not
going to change much except that a very aggressive firm has fallen
on difficult times. People will still buy great works of art. Maybe
the dealers will feel these staunch competitors are not riding so
high anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, investigations have also been launched by the European
Union and the Australian Competition Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
