<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-21 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4221 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVS-PACERS-TEXMA     02-21 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-PACERS-TEX </SLUG>
 MAVS' MISTAKES LET WIN SLIP AWAY (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By DWAIN PRICE c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The pain was etched all over the faces of the
Mavericks after last night's gut-wrenching 94-93 loss to the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were seconds away from claiming a major victory
against the best team in the Eastern Conference _ and at Conseco
Fieldhouse, where the Pacers had strung a franchise-record 19
consecutive victories together.
</P>
<P>
   From the pedigree of these two squads, this would have been akin
to David slaying Goliath. But the Mavericks bungled too many plays
in the last 30 seconds that erased a four-point lead and led to
their demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurt,'' guard Erick Strickland said in the somber and
quiet locker room. ``It just hurts. We gave that one away.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss gave the Mavericks (22-30) a split on a two-game road
trip against Eastern teams. The Mavs' next game is Thursday, at
home against the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some questionable decisions and questionable officiating
calls down the stretch the Mavericks were still in position to win
the game. However, All-Star guard Michael Finley's 17-footer
chipped the front of the iron and bounced harmlessly away as time
expired.
</P>
<P>
   For Finley, who had about two dozen family members and friends
from Chicago in the stands, the ending was dramatically different
from when the Mavericks last played in Indianapolis. Two years ago
in this city, Finley drained a 3-pointer at the buzzer as the
Mavericks upset the Pacers, 85-82.
</P>
<P>
   But with Reggie Miller hounding him, Finley had no such good
fortune this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted was a make,'' said Finley, who finished with 22
points. ``That's the way Coach drew it up, but I didn't come
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach Don Nelson admitted he didn't come through for
his team when he inexplicably decided to let second-year forward
Dirk Nowitzki throw the ball inbounds with 21.9 seconds left and
the Mavericks up, 93-92. Instead of using a timeout as he neared a
five-second violation, Nowitzki forced a lob pass near the
Mavericks' bench that went out of bounds off Finley's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was totally my fault; I had a young player taking the
ball out,'' Nelson said. ``I did it because he's 7-feet tall, and I
thought he could see over the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bottom line is you need a veteran inbounding the ball
in that situation, and I made a cardinal error as a coach by
putting a young player in that spot, and it won't happen again. It
cost us the game, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   After Nowitzki's turnover, Miller drove past Steve Nash and into
the teeth of the Mavericks' defense. It appeared rookie Greg
Buckner had tied Miller up in a jump-ball situation.
</P>
<P>
   However, Buckner was whistled for a foul, and Miller proceeded
to bury two free throws with 14.4 seconds left to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Buckner said he's used to not getting that call in that
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a rookie, so I've been getting calls like that against me
since I've been here,'' Buckner said. ``You've just got to find a
way to fight through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't dwell on it. We still had 15 seconds to play. They
outsmarted us at the end, but that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks led for most of the game, including 93-89 after
Nowitzki (23 points) drilled a 3-point field goal with 30.3 seconds
left. But before the Mavericks could finish celebrating what looked
like a sure victory, Pacers guard Travis Best zipped downcourt and
knocked down a 3-pointer of his own in less than seven seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman grabbed a Mavericks season-high 18 rebounds and
was his usual colorful self, as he exchanged pleasantries with the
fans throughout the game. In addition, Rodman landed in the lap of
two photographers in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who won the rebound battle, 44-38, are now 6 1/2
games behind Minnesota in the battle for the final Western
Conference playoff spot. If they miss it by one game, they could
look to last night's game as the one that did them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a heck of a game,'' Nelson said. ``Too bad we didn't
get the win.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
